                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a warrant under the Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998 be made to any District Court Judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application to the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 7 of the [Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998] may be made to the District Court Judge for the District Court District wherein the place in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for,* 11.[7] (1) An application to the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 7 of the [Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/22/enacted/en/html) may be made to the District Court Judge for the District Court District wherein the place in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is the information required to apply for a warrant in the form of a sworn statement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- by sworn information.* (2) Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the Form [34.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/912b3d43-3d90-4209-9829-e6e9fb09613d/Information For Issue Of Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for the warrant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.25]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Form of warrant.* (3) A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2585d723-f60d-4eba-982b-c63e9d48db96/Search Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a member of the Garda Síochána apply for a warrant under the European Arrest Warrant Act 2003?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to a judge of the District Court by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section of the [European Arrest Warrant Act 2003]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - for purposes of the European Arrest Warrant Act 2003 (No. 45 of 2003) 15[9](1) An application to a judge of the District Court by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section of the [European Arrest Warrant Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/45) may be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district within which the dwelling concerned is situated. (2). Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the Form [34.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/62eef001-c6c3-493a-8a77-9fefdacb4823/Information For Search Warrant - European Arrest Warrant Act 2003 section No. 34.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule of the member of the Garda Síochána applying for such warrant. (3) A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ff8a8613-5fec-479d-ab1b-8eeba1a528f7/Search Warrant - European Arrest Warrant Act 2003 section No. 34.34.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant made to the judge of the district court where the premises are located?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made to the Judge of the District Court for the District Court District wherein the premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *- under the Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998* 16[10](1). An application to the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to sub-section (4) of section 50 of the [Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/29) may be made to the Judge of the District Court for the District Court District wherein the premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated. (2).Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the Form [34.35](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63344470-d644-47ee-86c6-461529e205e0/Information For Issue Of Warrant - Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998 section 50(4) No. 34.35.docx/docx/1) Schedule of an authorised officer. A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.36](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63344470-d644-47ee-86c6-461529e205e0/Information For Issue Of Warrant - Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998 section 50(4) No. 34.35.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a member of the Garda Síochána apply for a warrant under the Prevention of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 5 of the [Prevention of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under the Prevention of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001 (No. 27 of 2001) as amended by the Criminal Justice Act 2006 (No. 26 of 2006) 19.[13] An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 5 of the [Prevention of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/27)(as substituted by section 191(1) of the Criminal Justice Act 2006) may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the place in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated. Such application shall be by information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.41](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6b525d4-771f-49f9-a131-38b00cede916/Information For Search Warrant - Prevention Of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001, section 5(1) (as substituted by Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 191(1)) No. 34.41.docx/docx/1), Schedule A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.42](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b584dbb0-b910-4871-8637-4f51062bef5f/Search Warrant - Prevention Of Corruption (Amendment) Act 2001, section 5(1) (as substituted by section 191(1) of the Criminal Justice Act 2006) No. 34.42.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Consumer Protection Act 2007 referenced in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by an authorised officer (for the time being appointed or continued as such in accordance with section 30 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) (No 19 of 2007) for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 30(10) of the said Act of 2007 may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the premises in respect of which the warrant is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under the Consumer Protection Act 2007 (No.19 of 2007) 20.[14] An application by an authorised officer (for the time being appointed or continued as such in accordance with section 30 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) (No 19 of 2007) for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 30(10) of the said Act of 2007 may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the premises in respect of which the warrant is sought are situated. Such application shall be by sworn information in writing of such authorised officer in the Form [34.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/97eb138f-2653-42ab-92c1-5ad5fe8343e8/Information for search warrant - Consumer Protection Act 2007, section 30(10) No. 34.43.docx/docx/1), Schedule A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.44](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5feff534-1bd9-460d-86b5-202ae0601cd6/Search Warrant - Consumer Protection Act 2007, section 30(10) No. 34.44.docx/docx/1), Schedule 21.[15] (1) An application pursuant to section 74(7) of the [Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/7/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of inspector for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 74(8) of the said Act may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District where the place concerned is situated, by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.45](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/45736e09-2c8e-4386-a391-3ec7afb4e7c1/Information for warrant - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 74(7) No. 34.45.docx/docx/1), Schedule A warrant granted on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.46](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63d5bbb7-4820-4632-b931-835034d315cc/Search warrant - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 74(7) No. 34.46.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a member of the Garda Síochána apply for an order to enter a place and obtain evidential material?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section of the said Act of 2008 may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the evidential material is situated by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.48]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) An application under section 75(8) of the said Act of 2008 by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of inspector for an order under section 75(10)(a) of the said Act of 2008 that a person produce evidential material to a named member of the Garda Síochána so that he or she may take it away, or give such member access to it, and/or for an order under section of the said Act to require any person who appears to the Judge to be entitled to grant entry to the place to allow the member to enter it to obtain access to the material may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the evidential material is situated by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.47](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8ea7a75b-2368-42bf-85b7-a83e73c72b4a/Information - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 75(8) No. 34.47.docx/docx/1), Schedule An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section of the said Act of 2008 may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the evidential material is situated by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.48](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a7ab6e34-2902-447b-8720-696492cf19ea/Information for order under section only - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 75(8) No. 34.48.docx/docx/1), Schedule An order made under section 75(10) of the said Act of 2008 on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.49](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4b99847a-72bd-499f-bda8-23e622245eb0/Order - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 75(10) No. 34.49.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before an order can be varied or discharged under section 75(14)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order under section 75(14) of the said Act of 2008 varying or discharging an order made under section 75(10) shall, unless the Judge otherwise permits, be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form [34.50]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) An application for an order under section 75(14) of the said Act of 2008 varying or discharging an order made under section 75(10) shall, unless the Judge otherwise permits, be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form [34.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3dfe4ae4-0adf-4a1f-bc14-ebcca08da8da/Notice of application to - vary - discharge an order under section 75(10) of the Act - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 75(14) No. 34.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána named in the order or the person to whom the order relates not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original order shall be produced in court on the hearing of any application for an order varying or discharging it. Any variation ordered may be endorsed on the original or a copy of the order and dated and signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before an order can be varied or discharged?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 63(7) of the said Act for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 63(3) shall, unless the Judge otherwise permits, be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form [34.53]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) An application under section 63(7) of the said Act for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 63(3) shall, unless the Judge otherwise permits, be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form [34.53](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e36faca-9252-47ed-8409-cb91683ac51a/Notice of application to vary - discharge an order under section 63(3) of the Act - Criminal Justice Act 1994, 63(7) (as substituted by Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, No. 34.53.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána named in the order or the person to whom the order relates not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original order shall be produced in court on the hearing of any application for an order varying or discharging it. Any variation ordered may be endorsed on the original or a copy of the order and dated and signed by the Judge'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant be issued based on an application made by a Garda Síochána member under section 12(4)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 12(4) of the [Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22) may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the dwelling in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## -under section 12(4) of the Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 (No. 22 of 2010) 23. [17] An application by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 12(4) of the [Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22) may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the dwelling in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated. Such application shall be by information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99ea917b-d3f8-4022-9701-482218aa40bb/Information for Search Warrant - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 12(4) No. 34.54.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be made and heard in accordance with [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), rule 27. A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5439ad22-b5df-40ea-9a49-9f77edccada7/Search Warrant - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 12(4) No. 34.55.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a member of the Garda Síochána apply for a warrant under the Criminal Procedure Act 2010?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 18(2) of the [Criminal Procedure Act 2010] by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent for the issue of a warrant may be made to the Judge of the District Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under the Criminal Procedure Act 2010 24.[18] An application pursuant to section 18(2) of the [Criminal Procedure Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/27/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent for the issue of a warrant may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the place in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated. Such application shall be by information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.56](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d7e5b3f1-de4e-4b52-8232-fd135a44a6e1/Information - Criminal Procedure Act 2010, section 18(2) No. 34.56.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be made and heard in accordance with [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), rule 27. A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.57](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afe6a1ec-b076-4dc1-b81a-8d5fb94cef7f/Search Warrant - Criminal Procedure Act 2010, section 18(2) No. 34.57.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Was Order 34 rule 20 inserted after September 2008?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 34 rule 20 inserted by [S.I. 106 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/106/made/en/print?q 106\u0026years 2009), effective 24 April 2009"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[10] Order 34 rule 16 inserted by [S.I. 700 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/700/made/en/print?q 700&years 2004), effective 14 November 2004 [11] Order 34 rule 17 inserted by [S.I. 322 of 2008](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/322/made/en/print?q 322&years 2008), effective 8 September 2008 [12] Order 34 rule 18 inserted by [S.I. 322 of 2008](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/322/made/en/print?q 322&years 2008), effective 8 September 2008 [13] Order 34 rule 19 inserted by [S.I. 322 of 2008](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/322/made/en/print?q 322&years 2008), effective 8 September 2008 [14] Order 34 rule 20 inserted by [S.I. 106 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/106/made/en/print?q 106&years 2009), effective 24 April 2009 [15] Order 34 rule 21 inserted by [S.I. 94 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/94/made/en/print?q 94&years 2010), effective 5 April 2010 [16] Order 34 rule 22 inserted by [S.I. 94 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/94/made/en/print?q 94&years 2010), effective 5 April 2010 [17] Order 34 rule 23 inserted by [S.I. 536 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/536/made/en/print?q 536&years 2011), effective 11 November 2011 [18] Order 34 rule 24 inserted by [S.I. 585 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/585/made/en/print?q 585&years 2011), effective 10 December 2011 [19] Order 34 rule 25 inserted by [S.I. 653 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/653/made/en/print?q 653&years 2011), effective 4 January 2012'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34A - Criminal Justice (Surveillance) Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for authorization to continue surveillance required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application mentioned in subsection (10) of section 7 of the Act under subsection (4) of section 4 of the Act by the superior officer to a Judge of the District Court for an authorisation to continue the surveillance approved by the Superior Officer under subsection (3) of section 7 of the Act shall be made on oath and in writing of the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) An application mentioned in subsection (10) of section 7 of the Act under subsection (4) of section 4 of the Act by the superior officer to a Judge of the District Court for an authorisation to continue the surveillance approved by the Superior Officer under subsection (3) of section 7 of the Act shall be made on oath and in writing of the applicant and in the Form [34A.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d8f1bdd9-080a-4c02-836e-602aafe91e32/Information for an authorisation to continue surveillance - CriminalJustice (Surveillance) Act 2009, section 4(4) and section 7(10) No. 34A.13.docx/docx/1), [34A.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e13a7ec9-22da-4846-8940-100dfac28819/Information for an authorisation to continue surveillance - Criminal Justice (Surveillance) Act 2009, section 4(4) and section 7(10) No. 34A.14.docx/docx/1), or [34A.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5515aa13-dabc-4885-a9f9-3bbe7920265a/Information for an authorisation to continue surveillance - Criminal Justice (Surveillance) Act 2009, section 4(4) and section 7(10) No. 34A.15.docx/docx/1), as the case may be. (7) Applications to which this Order applies shall be made parte and otherwise than in public and may be made in chambers. [1] Order 34A inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2010), effective 22 July 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 35 - Certified Copies Of Orders And Of Other Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a District Court Clerk sign an order if it meets certain conditions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an order recording a decision of a Judge of the District Court may be signed by a Judge or (provided that it complies with the requirements of sub-rule (2)) by any District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which the order was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 35 - Certified Copies Of Orders And Of Other Documents - Court: District 1.[1] (1) To the extent that sections 14(1) and 14(2) of the [Courts Act 1971](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1971/act/36/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 23 of the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/14)) provide that an order so signed shall be evidence in any legal proceedings of the said decision, an order recording a decision of a Judge of the District Court may be signed by a Judge or (provided that it complies with the requirements of sub-rule (2)) by any District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which the order was made. (2)[2] When any order referred to in sub-rule (1) is intended to be signed by a District Court Clerk, the form of order shall: - immediately following the heading of the order, include the words “BY ORDER OF JUDGE ................................. a Judge of the District Court” and identify by name the Judge who made the order; - in the body of the order, recite the making of the order by that Judge, and - (iii) where a form of such order which may be signed by a Judge is included in any Schedule to these Rules: - (a) immediately following the place for signature, instead of the specification “Judge of the District Court” include the specification: “District Court Clerk assigned to the said District Court area”, and - contain such other modifications as are necessary. (3) To the extent that sections 14(3) and 14(4) of the Courts Act 1971 (as substituted by section 23 of the Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2008) provide that a warrant so signed shall be evidence in any legal proceedings of the matters to which the warrant relates, a warrant issued by a Judge of the District Court may be signed by a Judge or (provided that it complies with the requirements of sub-rule (4)) by any District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which the warrant was issued.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 35 - Certified Copies Of Orders And Of Other Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge direct the clerk to provide a copy of an order or document if it''s needed for legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a Judge is satisfied that a copy of an order or other document is reasonably required by any person for the purpose of any legal proceedings, such Judge may direct the Clerk to furnish a copy of such order or other document to such person upon payment by such person of the prescribed fee (if any)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Where a Judge is satisfied that a copy of an order or other document is reasonably required by any person for the purpose of any legal proceedings, such Judge may direct the Clerk to furnish a copy of such order or other document to such person upon payment by such person of the prescribed fee (if any). 4. A copy of an order or other document furnished under this Order shall be certified by the Clerk to be a true copy of the original order or document as the case may be, which is in his or her custody. [1] Order 35, rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 92 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/92/made/en/print?q 92&years 2009), effective 23 March 2009 [2] Order 25 sub rule (2) of rule 1 originally amended by [S.I. 41 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/41/made/en/print?q 41&years 1998), substituted by [S.I. 92 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/92/made/en/print?q 92&years 2009), effective 23 March 2009'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 36 - Costs And Witnesses'' Expenses', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to costs and witnesses'' expenses in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 36 - Costs And Witnesses'' Expenses - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 36 - Costs And Witnesses'' Expenses - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 36 - Costs And Witnesses'' Expenses', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order parties to pay costs and witness expenses in summary jurisdiction cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court makes an order in any case of summary jurisdiction (including an order to “strike out” for want of jurisdiction) it may make an order in accordance with law ordering any party to the proceedings to pay to the other party such costs and witnesses’ expenses as it shall think fit to award."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs in summary cases* 1.[[1]](#_ftn1) Where the Court makes an order in any case of summary jurisdiction (including an order to “strike out” for want of jurisdiction) it may make an order in accordance with law ordering any party to the proceedings to pay to the other party such costs and witnesses’ expenses as it shall think fit to award.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 36 - Costs And Witnesses'' Expenses', 'Court Rules', 'Can costs or witnesses'' expenses be recovered through a warrant of distress if there is no specific provision for their enforcement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such costs or expenses may be recovered by warrant of distress"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Enforcement of order* 4. Where there is no provision in these Rules for the enforcement of an order awarding costs or witnesses'' expenses, such costs or expenses may be recovered by warrant of distress. [1]Order 36 rule 1 substituted by 496 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/496/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Are all individuals allowed to attend the sittings of the Children Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"all persons shall be excluded from sittings of the Children Court except – - (a) officers of the court - the parents or guardian of the child concerned, - an adult relative to the child, or other adult who attends the court pursuant to section 91 (6) of the Act, - persons directly concerned in the proceedings, - bona fide representatives of the press, - such other persons (if any) as the court may at its discretion permit to remain."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. Subject to the Act and the preceding rules of this Order, the provisions of the Summary Jurisdiction Rules, 1909 (S.R. & 952) dated July 31, 1909 made under section 133(7) of the [Children Act, 1908](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1928/sro/8/made/en/print) shall, by operation of section 5 (1) of the Children Act, 2001, with any necessary modifications, apply to proceedings under the Act. 6. Notwithstanding any provision of [Order 14]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-14-District-Admission-To-Court-And-Publication-Of-Proceedings), all persons shall be excluded from sittings of the Children Court except – - (a) officers of the court - the parents or guardian of the child concerned, - an adult relative to the child, or other adult who attends the court pursuant to section 91 (6) of the Act, - persons directly concerned in the proceedings, - bona fide representatives of the press, - such other persons (if any) as the court may at its discretion permit to remain. However the order or decision of the Court (if any) in any such proceedings shall be announced in public. 7. Where the Court imposes one or more of the conditions specified in section 90(1) of the Act on the release on bail of a child, such condition shall be endorsed on the recognisance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge proceed with a summary trial if the child consents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if the accused child (inquiry having been made of him or her by the judge) consents to the case being tried summarily"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '8. Where an accused child is before the court charged with an indictable offence with which the court has jurisdiction to deal summarily if the accused does not object, the judge shall inform the accused child of his or her right to be tried by a jury and if the accused child (inquiry having been made of him or her by the judge) consents to the case being tried summarily, and, the case is not one of an offence which is required to be tried by the Central Criminal Court or manslaughter and the court is of opinion that the offence constitutes a minor offence fit to be tried summarily (or, where the child, having had the opportunity to have the assistance of his or her parent or guardian, adult spouse, an adult relative accompanying him or her, wishes to plead guilty, to be dealt with summarily), the court, having taken account of the age and level of maturity of the child concerned and any other facts that it considers relevant, may take the accused child’s plea and try him or her summarily. 9. Where an accused child is before the court charged with an offence which is required to be tried by the Central Criminal Court or with manslaughter and wishes to plead guilty and the Court is satisfied that he or she understands the nature of the offence and the facts alleged, then, if the accused child signs a plea of guilty the judge may by order (Form [37.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50df8d58-756c-4a67-9fb1-24829fc26ddb/Order Sending Forward On A Plea Of Guilty - Children Act, 2001, section 75(5) No. 37.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule and with the consent of the Director of Public Prosecutions (which consent may be conveyed as provided in rule 4 of [Order 24]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-24-District-Proceedings-Relating-to-Indictable-Offences)), or, where appropriate, of the Attorney-General, send him or her forward for sentence with that plea to the court to which, if he or she had pleaded not guilty, the accused could lawfully have been sent forward for trial.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required if a child fails to comply with a community sanction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where it appears to the court, on application in that behalf by a member of the Garda Síochána that a child has failed, without reasonable cause, to comply with an order in force imposing a community sanction or any condition to which such order is subject, there shall be issued a summons to the child to appear before it in the Form [37.19]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '10. An order imposing a community sanction shall be in the Form [37.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8035ee5b-1858-4077-96bd-a020c0eca283/Order For Community Sanction – Restriction On Movement Order - Children Act, 2001, Section 133 No. 37.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule Any application made under section 136 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service, at least four days before the date upon which the application is to be heard, on the accused, the parents or guardian of the accused, and any other person directly affected by the order, of a notice in the Form [37.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49228326-5c3c-4883-9e3f-8389fa8bbbbc/Notice Of Application For An Order On Failure To Comply With Community Sanction – Restriction On Movement Order - Children Act, 2001, section 136 No. 37.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule 11. Where it appears to the court, on application in that behalf by a member of the Garda Síochána that a child has failed, without reasonable cause, to comply with an order in force imposing a community sanction or any condition to which such order is subject, there shall be issued a summons to the child to appear before it in the Form [37.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0c5e95d9-c34f-49b4-9498-59e297190d41/Summons To Appear To Answer Non-Compliance With Order Imposing Community Sanction - Children Act, 2001, section 136 No. 37.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule Unless the Court has excused the parents and/or guardian of the child from appearing, pursuant to section 90(5) of the Act, such summons to appear shall also be addressed to the parents and/or guardian of the child. If the child shall fail to appear in answer to said summons, the Court may issue a warrant in the Form [37.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ca36544-2c76-4b52-b872-c53cfc4c7efa/Warrant To Arrest - Children Act, 2001, section 136(3) No. 37.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule for his or her arrest. The order of the Court on the hearing of the application shall be in the Form [37.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2aacaa91-4e9f-40df-9245-5ba5a7d1c745/Order On Failure To Comply With Community Sanction – Restriction On Movement Order No. 37.21.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for the notice of application required under section 83 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application in the Form [37.29]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '14. [4] An order of the Court pursuant to section or section 82(2)(a) of the Act in respect of an action plan ordering that the child concerned comply with it and be supervised by a probation and welfare officer while it is in operation shall be in the Form [37.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e032dec5-d9bb-4e32-ab04-d37183aedfbc/Order Approving And Applying Action Plan - Children Act, 2001, section 82 No. 37.28.docx/docx/1) Schedule On such order being made, the proceedings shall be adjourned to a date fixed by the Court for review of compliance with the action plan in accordance with Section 84 of the Act. The probation and welfare officer who convened the relevant family conference shall be at liberty in such case to apply to the Court for the purposes of section 83 of the Act. Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application in the Form [37.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2e20bf3-0469-4cd1-98ea-a048bc6a6d6e/Notice Of Application For Resumption Of Proceedings - Children Act, 2001, section 83 No. 37.29.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be served not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of such application on (a) the prosecuting Garda; the child and the parent(s) or guardian of the child or if the whereabouts of the parent(s) or guardian are unknown, on any adult relative of the child or other adult who has, under section 91(6) of the Act of 2001, accompanied the child during the proceedings'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an order authorizing the taking of an intimate sample from a child made to the Children''s Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order authorising the taking of an intimate sample from a child in the circumstances mentioned in section 17(1) of the Act of 2014 may be made to the Children Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008 and the Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014* 15.[5] (1) In this rule: the “**Act of 2008**” means the [Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/7/enacted/en/html) (No. 7 of 2008); the “**Act of 2014**” means the [Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/11) (No. 11 of 2014); the expression “**intimate sample**” has the same meaning as in section 2(1) of the Act of 2014. (2) An application for an order authorising the taking of an intimate sample from a child in the circumstances mentioned in section 17(1) of the Act of 2014 may be made to the Children Court by information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the Form [37.41](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de32a3d5-2397-491a-a811-337bb5b9ef63/Information - Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014 (No. 11 of 2014) (the “Act of 2014”), section 17 - Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008 (No. 7 of 2008) No. 37.41.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) Where the person to whom the application relates is a child (including a child who is a protected person), an application for any other order under the Act of 2014, for an order under section of the Act of 2008 (inserted by section 134 of the Act of 2014) or for an order under section 50A(6) of the International Criminal Court Act 2006 (inserted by section 140 of the Act of 2014) may be made to the Children Court by information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the Form [31.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a4ab50b2-9cf8-40f8-be9e-aa7b45de32d4/Information - Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014 (No. 11 of 2014) (the “Act of 2014”) No. 31.12.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications, and the procedure set out in Order 31 shall apply, with such modifications as are necessary. (4) An information sworn for the purposes of section 17(1) of the Act of 2014 shall include details of (as the case may be): - the facts grounding the matters mentioned in section 17(4)(a) to of the Act of 2014;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 37 - Proceedings Involving Children Or Young Persons', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application under section 17(3) of the Act of 2014 be made orally during the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any application under section 17(3) of the Act of 2014 may be made viva voce at the hearing and shall be determined before consideration of the application under section 17(1) of the Act of 2014."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the facts which establish that one of the conditions specified in section 17(1) of the Act of 2014 is satisfied, and - (iii) the means by which and time at which, the child concerned and any parent or guardian of that child (other than a parent or guardian to whom section 15(2) of the Act of 2014 applies), was informed of the intention to make the application (including the time and place at which it was intended to make the application), and - the rank of the applicant. (5) Any application under section 17(3) of the Act of 2014 may be made viva voce at the hearing and shall be determined before consideration of the application under section 17(1) of the Act of 2014. (6) Any application under section 17(7) of the Act of 2014 may be made viva voce at the hearing of the application under section 17(1) of the Act of 2014 and a warrant issued on foot of such application shall be in the Form 37.42, Schedule (7) Where the Court considers it necessary, it may adjourn the hearing of the application and direct a further notification to a parent or guardian of the child concerned. (8) Where the person to whom the appeal relates is a child (including a child who is a protected person), an appeal under section 81(11) or section 83(9) of the Act of 2014 may be made to the Children Court by notice of appeal in the Form [31.1A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cb54cac8-f457-4df9-bad9-76e32625da5f/Notice of Appeal against an Authorisation - Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014, section 81(11) No. 31.1A.docx/docx/1) or [31.1B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2831d9a5-1e62-4ad5-a400-19486fc9ce2a/Notice of appeal against a determination - Criminal Justice (Forensic Evidence and DNA Database System) Act 2014, section 83(9) No. 31.1B.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with the necessary modifications, and the procedure set out in Order 31 shall apply, with such modifications as are necessary.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a specific named court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters - Court: District # **Order 38: Miscellaneous Matters******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court exercise power in cases where there is no apparent offense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"cases of ... no offence disclosed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## ***Power of Court in cases of variance, defects, omissions, no offence disclosed or no appearance***'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court amend the summons or warrant if there is a variance between the complaint and the evidence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may amend the summons, warrant or other document by which the proceedings were originated and proceed to hear and determine the matter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### **Variance between evidence and complaint** 1.(1) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (3), in cases of summary jurisdiction no variance between the complaint and the evidence adduced in support thereof, as to the time at which the offence or cause of complaint is stated to have been committed or to have arisen, shall be deemed material, provided that such information or complaint was in fact made within the time limited by law for making the same; nor shall any variance between the complaint and the evidence adduced in support thereof, as to the place in which the offence or cause of complaint is stated to have been committed or to have arisen, be deemed material, provided that the said offence or cause of complaint was committed or arose within the jurisdiction of the Judge by whom the case is being heard, or that, the accused resides or in the case of an offence was arrested within such jurisdiction. In any such case the Court may amend the summons, warrant or other document by which the proceedings were originated and proceed to hear and determine the matter.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court amend documents if there are defects or omissions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may amend any such summons, warrant or other document"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Defects* (2) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (3), no objection shall be taken or allowed on the ground of a defect in substance or in form or an omission in the summons, warrant or other document by which the proceedings were originated, or of any variance between any such document and the evidence adduced on the part of the prosecutor at the hearing of the case in summary proceedings or in proceedings in the Court relating to an indictable offence, but the Court may amend any such summons, warrant or other document, or proceed in the matter as though no such defect, omission or variance had existed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss the complaint without prejudice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"it may refuse to make any such amendment and may dismiss the complaint either without prejudice to its being again made, or on the merits, as the Court thinks fit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Court’s discretion* (3) Provided, however, that if in the opinion of the Court the variance, defect or omission is one which has misled or prejudiced the accused or which might affect the merits of the case, it may refuse to make any such amendment and may dismiss the complaint either without prejudice to its being again made, or on the merits, as the Court thinks fit; or if it makes such amendment, it may upon such terms as it thinks fit adjourn the proceedings to any future day at the same time or at any other place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court dismiss a case if the complaint does not disclose any legal offense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court is of opinion that the complaint before it discloses no offence at law"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *No offence disclosed / No appearance* (4) Where the Court is of opinion that the complaint before it discloses no offence at law, or if neither the prosecutor nor accused appears, it may if it or thinks fit strike out the complaint with or without awarding costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there an order mentioned for inspecting and copying entries in banker''s books?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order to inspect and copy entries in Banker''s Books"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Order to inspect and copy entries in Banker''s Books**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 7 of the Bankers'' Books Evidence Act 1879 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a party to proceedings before the Court for an order under section 7 of the [Bankers'' Books Evidence Act 1879] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district wherein the proceedings have been brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for - venue* 2.(1) An application by a party to proceedings before the Court for an order under section 7 of the [Bankers'' Books Evidence Act 1879](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1879/act/11/enacted/en/print.html) (42 & 43 Vict. 11) authorising that party to inspect and take copies of entries in a banker''s books for any of the purposes of such proceedings may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district wherein the proceedings have been brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice in the Form [38.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28dec6c1-bed1-461d-aa0f-b8ffc8fb4a07/Notice Of Application For An Order To Inspect And Copy Entries In Books - Bankers'' Books Evidence Act, 1879 section 7 No. 38.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be lodged with the Clerk prior to the making of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the order granting the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.2]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Order of court* (3) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0a875f41-bd60-4d54-9c31-cda7954ff181/Order To Inspect And Copy Entries In Books - Bankers'' Books Evidence Act, 1879 section 7 No. 38.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be served upon the relevant bank three clear days before the order is to be obeyed. Service may be effected by delivering a copy of the order to the office of the bank wherein the relevant records are kept.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application under Section 7A be made at any sitting of the Court within the relevant Court district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Superintendent under the provisions of section 7A ... may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district wherein the offence in question is alleged to have been committed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Section 7A application- venue* (4) An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Superintendent under the provisions of section 7A of the [Bankers'' Books Evidence Act 1879](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1879/act/11/enacted/en/print.html) (42 & 43 Vict. as inserted by section 131 [Central Bank Act 1989](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/16/enacted/en/html), and as amended by section 14 of the [Disclosure of Certain Information for Taxation and Other Purposes Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/25/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district wherein the offence in question is alleged to have been committed and may be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Notice of* (5) application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice in the Form [38.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/626ef0ec-5ccd-4a40-974a-f6cc1834ac21/Notice Of Application For An Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books - Bankers’ Books Evidence Act, 1979 section 7 No. 38.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be lodged with the Clerk prior to the making of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application under section 908A of the Taxes Consolidation Act required to be made in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by an authorised officer of the Revenue Commissioners under the provisions of section 908A of the [Taxes Consolidation Act 1997] shall be by information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Section 908A application- venue* (7) An application by an authorised officer of the Revenue Commissioners under the provisions of section 908A of the [Taxes Consolidation Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/39/enacted/en/html), as inserted by section 207 of the [Finance Act 1999](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1999/act/2/enacted/en/html), and as amended by section 68 of the [Finance Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/3/enacted/en/html) and by section 132 of the [Finance Act 2002](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2002/act/5/enacted/en/html) shall be by information on oath and in writing, in the Form [38.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f445692b-51bf-420d-bf63-4f233f110f3e/Information In Support Of Application For Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books Or Records - Taxes Consolidation Act, 1997 section 908a Amended No. 38.12.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the Judge for the Court district wherein the offence in question is alleged is being, has been or is about to be committed or where the financial institution in respect of which the order is sought is located, and may be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that the court order must follow?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.13]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Order* (8) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c87e56e1-1d64-4d4d-b54e-8c6d237e94aa/Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books Or Records - Taxes Consolidation Act 1997 section 908a as amended No. 38.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be served upon the relevant financial institution three clear days before the order is to be obeyed. Service may be effected by delivering a copy of the order to the office of the financial institution wherein the relevant books or records are kept.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to inform the coroner about the outcome of criminal proceedings related to a death?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"inform (in the Form [38.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b809481e-be19-47cf-ad38-22b1c14ae8ac/Notice To Coroner - Coroners Act, 1962 section 25 (3) No. 38.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule the coroner holding an inquest in relation to the death of the result of the proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice under 1962 Act* 3. At the conclusion of criminal proceedings in the Court in relation to the death of a person the Clerk shall, pursuant to section 25(3) of the [Coroners Act 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/9) (No. 9 of 1962), inform (in the Form [38.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b809481e-be19-47cf-ad38-22b1c14ae8ac/Notice To Coroner - Coroners Act, 1962 section 25 (3) No. 38.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule the coroner holding an inquest in relation to the death of the result of the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for extending the detention of seized cash be made orally?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána or an officer of Customs and Excise under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act for an order authorising the detention beyond 48 hours of cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made by the information on oath and in writing of the applicant, in the Form [38.4]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for order authorising detention of cash* 5.(1) An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána or an officer of Customs and Excise under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act for an order authorising the detention beyond 48 hours of cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made by the information on oath and in writing of the applicant, in the Form [38.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05cc38a8-2b3b-4ee5-a373-05698fc20c95/Information - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule Such application shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district wherein the cash was seized. Where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the case so requires, such application may be heard and determined on the evidence viva voce and on oath of the applicant. In such case, a written note of the evidence given shall be prepared by the applicant and signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Interpretation of terms - Interpretation of terms', 'Court Rules', 'Is a small claim proceeding only defined under Order 53A?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"a small claim proceeding under [Order 53A] and a European small claim proceeding under [Order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '“**return date**”, unless otherwise provided in these Rules, means the date first fixed for the hearing by the Court of an application in civil proceedings by notice of motion, by notice of application, by summons or by other document by which the application or matter is listed before the Court, and includes any date to which the hearing is adjourned; the “**Schedule of Costs**” means the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any other similar Schedule for the time being in force; “**small claim**”, or “**small claim proceeding**”, unless the context otherwise requires, includes a small claim proceeding under [Order 53A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53A-District-Small-Claims-Procedure) and a European small claim proceeding under [Order 53B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53B-District-European-Small-Claims-Procedure-(For-Cross-Border-Small-Claims-Within-The-European-Union)); “**solicitor**” includes: - (a) a practising solicitor on record for a party (including such a solicitor who is a member of a firm of solicitors or who is employed by a firm or by another solicitor), and including a firm of solicitors; or - a visiting lawyer, having the same right of audience as a lawyer established in the State by virtue of Regulation 3 of the European Communities (Freedom To Provide Services)(Lawyers) Regulations 1979 ( S.I. No. 58 of 1979 ), who is acting for a party; or - a registered lawyer, entitled to pursue the professional activities of a solicitor by virtue of Regulation 10 of the European Communities (Lawyers Establishment) Regulations 2003 (S.I. No. 732 of 2003), who is acting for a party. Additional expressions are defined for the purposes of particular Orders or rules within those Orders or rules respectively. [1] District Court Rules 1997 “Interpretation of Terms” provisions substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014) of 2014, effective 3 February 2014.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a plenary summons used for proceedings that require oral evidence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An originating summons for the commencement of plenary proceedings with pleadings and to be heard on oral evidence (in these Rules called a plenary summons)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 1 - Commencement of Proceedings - Court: Superior 1. Save as otherwise provided in these Rules, civil proceedings in the High Court shall be instituted by a summons of the Court to be called an originating summons. 2.[[1]](#_ftn1) An originating summons for the commencement of plenary proceedings with pleadings and to be heard on oral evidence (in these Rules called a plenary summons) shall, save in admiralty proceedings, and save in personal injuries actions as defined in [Order 1A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-1A-Superior-Procedure-by-Personal-Injuries-Summons), be in the [Form No 1 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_ftn1). 3. An originating summons for the commencement of summary proceedings without pleadings and to be heard on affidavit with or without oral evidence (in these Rules called a summary summons) shall, in the case of any claim mentioned in [Order 2]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-2-Superior-Procedure-by-Summary-Summons), rule 1, be in the [Form No 2 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon4). 4. An originating summons for the commencement of summary proceedings without pleadings and to be heard on affidavit with or without oral evidence (in these Rules called a special summons) shall, in the case of any claim mentioned in [Order 3]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-3-Superior-Procedure-By-Special-Summons) (other than in admiralty proceedings) be in the [Form No 3 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_ftn3). 5. Any costs occasioned by the use of any forms of summonses or of indorsements thereon, other or more prolix than the forms in these Rules prescribed shall be borne by the party using the same, unless the Court shall otherwise direct. 6. In all proceedings (other than to take a minor into wardship) commenced by originating summons, procedure by plenary summons shall be obligatory except where procedure by summary summons or by special summons is required or authorised by these Rules. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 1 rule 2 substituted by 248 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0248.html), effective 2 June 2005.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 2 - Venue', 'Court Rules', 'Was Order 2 rule amended in 2023?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 2 rule amended by 201 of 2023] effective 27 April 2023."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 2 rule substituted by 618 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/618/made/en/print), effective 30 December 2015. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 2 rule substituted by 597 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/597/made/en/print), effective 19 December 2014. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 2 rule substituted by 618 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/618/made/en/print), effective 30 December 2015. [[6]](#_ftnref6) Order 2 rule inserted by 618 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/618/made/en/print), effective 30 December 2015. [[7]](#_ftnref7) Order 2 rule inserted by 618 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/618/made/en/print), effective 30 December 2015. [8]Order 2 rule amended by 201 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/201/made/en/pdf) effective 27 April 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 23 - Trial Of Summary Offences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order immediate payment of a fine if the accused has no fixed address within the jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court is satisfied that the accused person is possessed of sufficient means to enable him or her to pay the penalty forthwith, or that the accused has no fixed abode within the jurisdiction"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Time for payment* 7. (1) The Court may, subject to the availability to the accused person of the option under section 6(1)(a)(ii) of the 2014 Act, order that a fine shall be paid within such period, not less than 14 clear days, as it thinks fit to fix for the purpose, and if it fixes no period, the fine shall be paid within the period of 14 clear days from the date of the order, and on subsequent application by or on behalf of the accused, it may allow such further time for payment as it thinks fit. (2) Where the Court is satisfied that the accused person is possessed of sufficient means to enable him or her to pay the penalty forthwith, or that the accused has no fixed abode within the jurisdiction, or if the accused, on being asked if he or she desires time for payment, does not express any such desire, or if for any special reason the Court expressly directs that no time shall be allowed for payment, it may in accordance with [section 1](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1914/en/act/pub/0058/sec0001.html#sec1) of the [Criminal Justice Administration Act 1914](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1914/en/act/pub/0058/index.html) order that the penalty shall be paid forthwith, and where no time is allowed the reason therefor shall be stated in the warrant of committal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 23 - Trial Of Summary Offences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order immediate payment of a fine if the accused is deemed to have sufficient means?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court is satisfied that the accused person is possessed of sufficient means to enable him or her to pay the penalty forthwith..."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Time for payment* 7. (1) The Court may, subject to the availability to the accused person of the option under section 6(1)(a)(ii) of the 2014 Act, order that a fine shall be paid within such period, not less than 14 clear days, as it thinks fit to fix for the purpose, and if it fixes no period, the fine shall be paid within the period of 14 clear days from the date of the order, and on subsequent application by or on behalf of the accused, it may allow such further time for payment as it thinks fit. (2) Where the Court is satisfied that the accused person is possessed of sufficient means to enable him or her to pay the penalty forthwith, or that the accused has no fixed abode within the jurisdiction, or if the accused, on being asked if he or she desires time for payment, does not express any such desire, or if for any special reason the Court expressly directs that no time shall be allowed for payment, it may in accordance with [section 1](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1914/en/act/pub/0058/sec0001.html#sec1) of the [Criminal Justice Administration Act 1914](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1914/en/act/pub/0058/index.html) order that the penalty shall be paid forthwith, and where no time is allowed the reason therefor shall be stated in the warrant of committal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 27 - Estreatment Of Recognisances Forfeiture Of Money Lodged', 'Court Rules', 'Can a superintendent apply for a warrant to commit someone to prison after issuing a warrant of distress?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"At any time after the issue of such warrant of distress the said superintendent may, having first given at least seven days'' notice of the application (in the [Form 27.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4810d0ff-c67c-4f1b-980a-14812343dd1c/Notice of application for warrant of execution (to enforce by committal an order to estreat) No. 27.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the person against whom the warrant of distress was issued (the respondent)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by committal* [5](2)[6] At any time after the issue of such warrant of distress the said superintendent may, having first given at least seven days'' notice of the application (in the [Form 27.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4810d0ff-c67c-4f1b-980a-14812343dd1c/Notice of application for warrant of execution (to enforce by committal an order to estreat) No. 27.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the person against whom the warrant of distress was issued (the respondent) and having lodged the original of that Form with the Clerk, apply to the Court for the issue of a warrant to commit the respondent to prison, and the Court may, if satisfied on hearing the applicant that it was found impossible to execute that warrant of distress, issue a warrant ([Form 27.8, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a40eb5d3-b960-4ee8-bcbd-762f9895f1cd/Warrant Of Execution (To Enforce By Committal An Order To Estreat) No. 27.8.docx/docx/1)) to commit the respondent to prison for a term not exceeding the appropriate period specified in the scale set out in the Table to section 2 of the [Courts (No 2) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html) , and thereupon the applicant shall return the warrant of distress to the Court for cancellation (3)[7]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 25 - Issue Of Warrants In Execution Of Court Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant of committal be issued if there is a default in paying a penalty?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In all cases of summary jurisdiction whenever an order has been made upon the conviction of any person of an offence under section 2(1) of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986 or section 1 of the Criminal Justice Administration Act 1914 committing a person to prison, the Court may issue a warrant of committal to imprisonment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- in default of payment of penalty* 2.[2] (1) In all cases of summary jurisdiction whenever an order has been made upon the conviction of any person of an offence under section 2(1) of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986 or section 1 of the Criminal Justice Administration Act 1914 committing a person to prison, the Court may issue a warrant of committal to imprisonment (Form [25.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/da048fa9-e9be-40ab-a484-3d6ba771b0fe/Warrant of Execution (to commit in default of payment of fine) - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986, section 2(1) No. 25.5.docx/docx/1) or [25.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49f0a535-5660-41c7-abdf-39012d10b6ed/Warrant Of Execution (Summary Jurisdiction) (To commit in default of payment of penalty - Time not allowed) No. 25.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule forthwith or at any time not later than six months from the date on which the said order was made. (2) In all cases of summary jurisdiction whenever an order has been made upon the conviction of any person of an offence for the performance of a condition and that condition has not been performed, the Court may, upon the application of the prosecutor, issue a warrant of committal to imprisonment for the non-performance of the condition ([Form 25.7,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3afb6d47-ce77-44e7-aaff-9f3a93b45d18/Warrant Of Execution (Non-Performance Of Condition) No. 25.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule at any time not later than six months from the expiration of the time fixed by the said order for the performance thereof.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a member of the Garda Síochána apply for an order to obtain material or access to it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 63(1) of the Criminal Justice Act 1994 by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 63(3) of the said Act that a person produce material to a named member of the Garda Síochána so that he or she may take it away, or give such member access to it, may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the material is situated, by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form 34.51"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under section 63 of the Criminal Justice Act 1994 (No. 15 of 1994)(as substituted by section of the [Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/7/enacted/en/html) 22.[16] (1) An application under section 63(1) of the [Criminal Justice Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/15) by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 63(3) of the said Act that a person produce material to a named member of the Garda Síochána so that he or she may take it away, or give such member access to it, may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the material is situated, by the information on oath and in writing of such member in the Form [34.51](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2dd3b073-dd91-4a99-baf7-ab451a9ca82e/Information - Criminal Justice Act 1994, 63(1) (as substituted by Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 105) No. 34.51.docx/docx/1), Schedule An order made on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bb97df40-af32-4e2d-b8a9-a91f9ea06db3/Order - Criminal Justice Act 1994, 63(3) ( as substituted by Criminal Justice (Mutual Assistance) Act 2008, 105) No. 34.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of application required to be served on the person from whom the cash was seized?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the person from whom the cash was seized and upon any other person directly affected by the order previously made under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for order authorising further detention of cash* 6.(1) An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána or an officer of Customs and Excise under section 38(3) of the 1994 Act for an order authorising the further detention in accordance with section 38(3) of the 1994 Act of cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the cash was seized. Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the person from whom the cash was seized and upon any other person directly affected by the order previously made under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c1a1fe0f-1295-4a10-9a1b-946d89878d79/Notice Of Application For An Order Authorising The Further Detention Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds Of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the original notice of application to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of such notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of application* (2) Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Such notice may be served in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings). The original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of such notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for releasing cash required to be served on specific members of law enforcement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the member(s) of the Garda Síochána or officer(s) of Customs and Excise who applied for any order previously made under section 38(2) or section 38(3) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for order releasing cash* 7.(1) An application to the Court under section 38(5) of the 1994 Act for an order releasing cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the cash was seized. Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the member(s) of the Garda Síochána or officer(s) of Customs and Excise who applied for any order previously made under section 38(2) or section 38(3) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fe876c2c-2e37-4ee5-8a75-a25057d8a7fd/Notice Of Application For An Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for serving the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of application* (2) Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Such notice may be served in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings). The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that the order of the court should follow?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.9]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Form of order* (3) The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab17f375-ede1-4b91-b635-f776d7cd7994/Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can applications under the 1994 Act be heard in any sitting of the court within the judge''s district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Applications to the Court under the 1994 Act may be brought, heard and determined before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 8.(1) Applications to the Court under the 1994 Act may be brought, heard and determined before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district wherein the cash was seized at any sitting of the Court within such Judge’s district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any mention of specific certificates or applications related to the Sex Offenders Act 2001 in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Certificates and applications under Sex Offenders Act 2001 (as amended)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for orders imposing post-release supervision under the Sex Offenders Act 2001?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order imposing post-release supervision pursuant to section 29 of the Sex Offenders Act 2001 may be in the Form [38.15]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order imposing post-release supervision* (2) An order imposing post-release supervision pursuant to section 29 of the Sex Offenders Act 2001 may be in the Form [38.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3697915-fed8-4d22-9b07-7f4f1f8b8f1f/Order For Imprisonment And Post-Release Supervision - Sex Offenders Act, 2001 section 29 No. 38.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such Order shall be transmitted to the Governor of the Prison to which the accused is committed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served on the sex offender before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served on the sex offender concerned at least seven days before the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application under section 30A* (3) An application to the Court pursuant to section 30A of the Sex Offenders Act 2001 (inserted by section 51 of the Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Act 2017) for an order amending any condition attached to, or for the inclusion of any new condition in, any order of the Court providing for post-release supervision may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the order providing for post-release supervision was made. Notice of the application shall be served on the sex offender concerned at least seven days before the date of hearing. A copy of the notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can changes to post-release supervision conditions be added to the original order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the terms of any such change may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the order and re-signed by the Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Indorsement of new terms* (4) Where the Court amends a condition or includes any new condition attached to, or includes any new condition in, the order providing for post-release supervision, the terms of any such change may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the order and re-signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the topic about types of parole or conditional release?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"### Variation of conditional release"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Variation of conditional release'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when making an application to vary, revoke, or add a condition to a person''s release?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application in the Form [38.18] may be made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - application - service - order 13. Where a person has been released from detention on conditions in accordance with section of the 2015 Act, an application in the Form [38.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/93ec30f7-670e-4445-9605-f01609039818/Application to Vary Revoke Add a Condition of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(5) sect 20(10) No 38.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule may be made pursuant to section 20(5) or section 20(10) of the 2015 Act, to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the person’s dwelling place is situated, by the person, an immigration officer, or a member of the Garda Síochána to vary, revoke or add a condition to the person’s release. Such application shall be served in the manner provided by section 5 of the 2015 Act and shall be served at least four clear days before the date for hearing the application. The original of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing. The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ffa8ea69-7288-4df6-ab27-8790d4fbc9a3/Order Varying Revoking Adding a Condition of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(5) sect 20(10) No 38.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for ordering the release of a person detained under sections 20(4) or 20(10) of the 2015 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order of release shall be in the Form [38.20]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Order of release 14. Where a person who has been detained pursuant to the provisions of section 20 of the 2015 Act is brought, under the provisions of section 20(4) or section 20(10) of the 2015 Act before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district where the person is being detained and the Court orders the release of that person, the order of release shall be in the Form [38.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/10b22ec9-be2b-4e64-b26f-0d9805aae3c3/Order of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(4) sect 20(11) No 38.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010 referred to in rule 16?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“the Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010”"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interpretation – rules 16 to 18* 16. In this rule and rules 17 and 18, “**the 2010 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 2010).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for an order under section 17(2) of the 2010 Act required to be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 17(2) of the 2010 Act ordering a person not to carry out a specified service or transaction shall be made parte"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applications under section 17* 17. An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 17(2) of the 2010 Act ordering a person not to carry out a specified service or transaction shall be made parte and otherwise than in public to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order is proposed to be served. Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing of the applicant, in the Form [38.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0906e9a4-b703-4680-90a0-7507c8ca6612/Information - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 17 No. 38.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule Where the application is for a second or subsequent order in relation to a particular service or transaction, there shall be produced with the information a copy of any previous order of the Court in relation to that service or transaction. An order of the Court under section 17(2) of the Act shall be in the Form [38.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/96cae89f-a5b5-4aca-9535-e4b6886cb9e3/Order - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 17 No. 38.23.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before making an application under sections 19 or 20 of the 2010 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application, in the Form [38.24]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applications under section 19 or 20* 18.(1) An application to a Judge of the Court under section 19 of the 2010 Act to revoke an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act, or an application under section 20 of the 2010 Act for an order in relation to any of the property concerned in an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order or direction was made. Such application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application, in the Form [38.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bafe0aa8-9a13-4e9f-8fcc-572e873f7cf0/Notice of Application - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 19 - section 20 No. 38.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule and service of a copy of that notice, in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings), upon the member of the Garda Síochána on whose application the order under section 17 of the 2010 Act was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served at least four days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Unless the Court permits otherwise, notice of such application shall be served at least four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of applications under section 19 or 20* (2) Unless the Court permits otherwise, notice of such application shall be served at least four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of the notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court join additional parties to an application under sections 19 or 20 of the 2010 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may direct that any person affected by the direction or order who was not given notice of the application be joined in, or put on notice of, the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Service of applications under section 19 or 20* (3) Where it seems appropriate to the Court to so direct, in any application under section 19 or section 20 of the 2010 Act, the Court may direct that any person affected by the direction or order who was not given notice of the application be joined in, or put on notice of, the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for an order made under section 20 of the 2010 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order of the Court under section 20 of the 2010 Act shall be in the Form [38.25]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Order under section 19 or 20* (4) An order of the Court under section 20 of the 2010 Act shall be in the Form [38.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/41c0df42-fe72-4b01-a988-adabb2fe9bd4/Order - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 20 No. 38.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified in Order 39?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 39 - General Rules - Court: District # **Order 39: General Rules******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific procedure mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"WHERE NO PROCEDURE PROVIDED FOR"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1- WHERE NO PROCEDURE PROVIDED FOR'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Can a bureau officer apply for a warrant under the Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a bureau officer who is a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 14(1) of the [Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under the Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996 (No. 31 of 1996) as amended by the Criminal Justice Act 2006 (No. 26 of 2006) 18.[12] An application by a bureau officer who is a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 14(1) of the [Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/31/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 190(1) of the [Criminal Justice Act 2006](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html)) may be made to the Judge of the District Court assigned to the District Court District wherein the place in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated. Such application shall be by information on oath and in writing of such bureau officer in the Form [34.39](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1a2857ba-9fd7-4209-b3fc-3e2661a8b9a7/Information For Search Warrant - Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996, section 14(1) (as substituted by Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 190(1)) No. 34.39.docx/docx/1), Schedule A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.40](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ef1ce8ff-3a86-4918-99bf-b293765e8399/Search Warrant - Criminal Assets Bureau Act 1996, section 14(1) (as substituted by Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 190(1)) No. 34.40.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when committing a person to a place of detention under certain sections of the 2015 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order of detention shall be in the Form [38.16], [38.16A], or as the case may be, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Commitment to detention 11. Where a person who has been detained pursuant to section 20(1) or section 20(9) of the 2015 Act is brought before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the person is being detained and is committed by the Court to a place of detention as provided for in section 20(3)(a), section 20(10), or as the case may be, section 20(12) of the 2015 Act, the order of detention shall be in the Form [38.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b74d51c7-7456-4bf7-b2ba-f26d5d38683a/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(3)(a) No 38.16.docx/docx/1), [38.16A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/817becce-c3ed-4dbc-99d8-97150f97fbf3/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(10) No 38.16A.docx/docx/1), or as the case may be, [38.16B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4c105597-77b0-4b67-a37d-65a088a9d970/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(12) No 38.16B.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court determine its own procedure if one is not specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the procedure for the conduct of civil proceedings is not prescribed by these Rules or by an enactment, or for any other reason there is doubt about the manner or form of the procedure, the Court may determine what procedure is to be adopted and may give directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Where no procedure provided for* 1. (1) If the procedure for the conduct of civil proceedings is not prescribed by these Rules or by an enactment, or for any other reason there is doubt about the manner or form of the procedure, the Court may determine what procedure is to be adopted and may give directions. (2) Subject to [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), rule 9(4), where no form for use in the Court in respect of a step, notification or other action in a civil proceeding is for the time being prescribed, any form for the time being in use in the Circuit Court or the High Court for the corresponding step, notification or other action in civil proceedings may be used in civil proceedings in the Court with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court set aside a proceeding due to non-compliance with the rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may— - (a) set aside the proceeding, either wholly or in part;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Effect of non-compliance* 2. (1) Subject to any provision of an enactment, a failure to comply with these Rules is an irregularity and does not render a civil proceeding or a step taken, or any document or order in the proceeding void. (2) If there has been a failure to comply with these Rules, the Court may— - (a) set aside the proceeding, either wholly or in part; - set aside any step taken in the proceeding, or any document or order therein; - exercise its powers under these Rules to allow amendments and to make orders dealing with the proceeding generally.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about time?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## 3 - TIME"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - TIME'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court list a civil proceeding to explain a lack of activity?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may cause the civil proceeding to be listed before the Court to explain the failure to proceed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Dormant proceedings* 4. (1) Where no step by a party requiring the filing of a document with the Clerk or notification to the Court under these Rules has been taken in a civil proceeding for twelve months or more since the last such step, the Court may cause the civil proceeding to be listed before the Court to explain the failure to proceed. (2) The Clerk must notify the parties of any listing in accordance with sub-rule (1). The notification may be in [Form 39.02, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce279976-c45b-4654-b033-db71d3483461/Notice of listing of proceedings No. 39.02.docx/docx/1). (3) A party may file a written explanation of the failure to proceed with the Clerk and if the Court is satisfied that there were sufficient reasons for the failure to proceed, may direct that the civil proceeding be removed from the list to explain the failure to proceed and direct that the Clerk notify the parties accordingly. (4) On the listing of a civil proceeding in accordance with sub-rule (1), the Court may make such orders and give such directions as are in the opinion of the Court likely to ensure the civil proceedings are prepared for trial in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court extend or shorten time periods set by Acts of the Oireachtas?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Sub-rules (1) and (2) do not apply: ... to any period of time fixed by an Act of the Oireachtas, or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Enlargement or abridgement of time* 5. (1) Subject to sub-rules (3) and (4), the Court may, on any terms it considers reasonable, enlarge or abridge any of the times fixed by these Rules, or by a prior order of the Court, for taking any step or doing any act in any civil proceedings. (2) Subject to sub-rules (3) and (4), the Court may also, on any terms as to costs or otherwise as it considers just, declare any step taken or act done in any civil proceedings to be sufficient, even though not taken or done within the time or in the manner prescribed by these Rules. (3)[2] Sub-rules (1) and (2) do not apply: - (a) to any period of time fixed by an Act of the Oireachtas, or - to any period of time fixed by a statute which was in force in Saorstát Éireann immediately before the date of the coming into operation of the Constitution and which continued in force by virtue of Article 50 of the Constitution, or - to any application to which rule 10(2) of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) applies. (4) Without limiting the generality of sub-rule (3), any application to state a case under section 2 of the Summary Jurisdiction Act 1857 must be made within the time prescribed by that Act. (5) Unless otherwise directed or permitted by the Court, an application to enlarge or abridge time must be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties who would be affected by the enlargement or abridgement of time.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for the statutory declaration under the Mediation Act 2017?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 39.02, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Statutory declaration required by section 14(2) or 15(2) of Mediation Act 2017* 6.[3] The statutory declaration required by section 14(2) or 15(2) of Mediation Act 2017 may be in the [Form 39.02, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce279976-c45b-4654-b033-db71d3483461/Notice of listing of proceedings No. 39.02.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 39 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 39 sub-rule (3) of rule 5 substituted by [S.I. 423 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/423/made/en/print?q 423&years 2019), effective 2 September 2019 [3] Order 39 rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an electronic signature satisfy the requirement for a physical signature on a court document sent digitally?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such requirement shall be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents - Court: Circuit # Order 4: Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents [1] 1[2] [3] [4] [5] (1). The Court shall have for use in each County an embossing Seal or, in circumstances in which the Office has multiple locations, embossing Seals with an appropriate inscription, as directed by the Minister, specifying the name of the Circuit in connection with which it is to be used. Such Seal shall be placed and retained in the custody of the County Registrar. It shall not be necessary that any Decree, Order, Warrant or other document shall be signed by the Judge. (2) Every document requiring under any provision of statute or statutory instrument, rule of law or any other Order of these Rules to be issued under Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the Seal of the Court impressed thereon and the signature of a person mentioned in sub-rule (4). (2A)[6] Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement shall be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of [that Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or that Regulation. Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be sealed, such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic seal in accordance with [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng) (3) Every document requiring authentication other than one referred to in sub-rule (2), and every Decree, Order and Warrant, shall be authenticated by the signature of a person mentioned in sub-rule (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a combined court office manager authenticate the Seal of the Court on certain documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the combined court office manager appointed under section 19 of [that Act] for that combined court office, or such member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in that combined court office under section 21 of the [Courts and Court Officers Act 2009] as may, for such period as may be specified, be nominated in writing for that purpose by the combined court office manager concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The persons who may authenticate the impression of the Seal of the Court on a document mentioned in sub-rule (2) or a document mentioned in sub-rule (3) are: - (a) the County Registrar, or - such person, or one of such persons, as may, for such period as may be specified, be nominated in writing for that purpose by the County Registrar, or - where any business of the office of the Court in a county is specified in accordance with section 14 of the [Courts and Court Officers Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) as business that shall be transacted in a combined court office established under that section, and for the purposes of such business: - the combined court office manager appointed under section 19 of [that Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) for that combined court office, or - such member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in that combined court office under section 21 of the [Courts and Court Officers Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) as may, for such period as may be specified, be nominated in writing for that purpose by the combined court office manager concerned. (5)[8] The proper officer may certify any printed version of the legible content of any original document which was transmitted to or by the proper officer by digital delivery as a certified copy of the original. 2.[9] Where by reason of the re-arrangement of Circuits an embossing Seal is not available for a particular Circuit Court area then until such time as an embossing Seal becomes available, all documents required by Rule 1 of this Order to be authenticated by the Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the signatures of both the Circuit Court Judge and - (a) the County Registrar for the said area or - where paragraph of rule 1(4)of this Order applies, the combined court office manager concerned or member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in the combined court office nominated in writing for that purpose by that combined court office manager.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'Was Order 4 rule 1(2A) added after 2019?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 4 rule 1(2A) inserted by 217 of 2025]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[1] Title amended by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019. [2] Order 4 rule 1 substituted by 409 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/409/made/en/print), effective 28 August 2006. [3] Order 4 rule 1(2) and 1(3) substituted by 583 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/583/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2010. [4] Order 4 rule 1(4) inserted by 583 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/583/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2010. [5] Order 4 rule 1(4) substituted by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019. [6] Order 4 rule 1(2A) inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [7] Order 4 rule inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [8] Order 4 rule 1(5) inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [9] Order 4 rule 2 inserted by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 4 - Mode of Address', 'Court Rules', 'Is a judge addressed as ''A Bhreithimh'' in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge shall be addressed in court as \"**A Bhreithimh**\" or as \"**Judge**\"."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 4 - Mode of Address - Court: District # Order 4: Mode of Address [1] A Judge shall be addressed in court as "**A Bhreithimh**" or as "**Judge**". [1] Order 3 inserted by[S.I. No. 93/1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93)- District Court Rules, 1997'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to specify the exact grounds of complaint in the endorsement of claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"it shall not be essential to set forth the precise ground of complaint or the precise remedy or relief to which the plaintiff considers himself entitled."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '2.[[5]](#_ftn5) Save in the case of a personal injuries summons as defined in [Order 1A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-1A-Superior-Procedure-by-Personal-Injuries-Summons), the indorsement of claim on a plenary summons shall be entitled “**General Indorsement of Claim**” and there shall be an indorsement of the relief claimed and the grounds thereof expressed in general terms in such one of the forms in [Appendix Part II](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#weds2) as shall be applicable to the case, or, if none be found applicable, then such other similarly concise form as the nature of the case may require. The indorsement of claim on a personal injuries summons shall be as provided by [Order 1A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-1A-Superior-Procedure-by-Personal-Injuries-Summons). 3. In the indorsement required by rule 2 it shall not be essential to set forth the precise ground of complaint or the precise remedy or relief to which the plaintiff considers himself entitled. 3A.[[6]](#_ftn6) In the case of proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003, the indorsement of claim shall contain a statement - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, - specifying the section of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003 or the rule made under section 46(3) of that Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation. 4. The indorsement of claim on a summary summons and on a special summons shall be entitled “**SPECIAL INDORSEMENT OF CLAIM,**” and shall state specifically and with all necessary particulars the relief claimed and the grounds thereof. The indorsement of claim on a summary summons or a special summons shall be in such one of the forms in [Appendix Part III](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#weds2), as shall be applicable to the case, or, if none be found applicable, then such other similarly concise form as the nature of the case may require.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that the statement about costs must follow?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The statement shall be in the form incorporated in the [Form No 2 in Appendix A, Part"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. (1) Whenever a claim indorsed on a summary summons is for a liquidated sum only, the indorsement, besides stating the amount claimed in respect of the demand, shall state the amount claimed for costs, and shall further state that on payment of such amounts for demand and costs within six days after service, or in the case of a summons not for service within the jurisdiction, within the time limited for appearance, further proceedings will be stayed. (2)[[7]](#_ftn7) [[8]](#_ftn8) The amount claimed for costs shall be: - (a) If the demand does not exceed €15,000: Such sum as would be appropriate to a proceeding for a like amount in the District Court. - If the demand exceeds €15,000 but does not exceed €75,000: Such sum as would be appropriate to a proceeding for a like amount in the Circuit Court. - If the demand exceeds €75,000: €70 with €7 for each additional service after the first, and the costs of any order for issue and service, or service of the summons or notice in lieu thereof outside the jurisdiction, or for substituted or other service, or for the substitution of notice for service, or for declaring service effected sufficient, or for notice by advertisement of the issue of the summons, and this amount shall be exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. (3) The statement shall be in the form incorporated in the [Form No 2 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon4). In any case within this rule the defendant may, notwithstanding payment, have the costs taxed, and if more than one-sixth of the amount paid shall be disallowed the amount disallowed shall be refunded and the plaintiff’s solicitor shall pay the costs of taxation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the indorsement to specify the date when the loan was made in actions by a moneylender?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the date on which the loan was made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '9. If the plaintiff sues or the defendant is sued in a representative capacity, the indorsement shall show in manner appearing in such of the forms in [Appendix Part I](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#Weds1), as shall be applicable to the case, or by any other statement to the like effect, in what capacity the plaintiff or defendant sues or is sued. 10. In probate actions the indorsement shall show whether the plaintiff claims as creditor, executor, administrator, residuary legatee, legatee, next-of-kin, heir-at-law, devisee, or in any and what other capacity. 11. In all cases in which the plaintiff, in the first instance, desires to have an account taken, the summons shall be indorsed with the claim that such account be taken. 12. In actions by a moneylender or an assignee or by the personal representative or personal representatives of a deceased moneylender for the recovery of money lent by a moneylender or any interest thereon or the enforcement of any agreement or security relating to any such money or interest, the indorsement on the summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, the fact that the plaintiff is a licensed moneylender, or (in an action by an assignee or by the personal representative or personal representatives of a deceased moneylender) that the original assignor, or the testator or intestate, as the case may be, was at the time of the loan a licensed moneylender, and if the action be commenced by summary summons or special summons, shall also state, in addition to any other particulars: - (a) the date on which the loan was made; - the amount actually lent to the borrower; - the rate per cent. per annum of interest charged; - the date when the contract for repayment was made; - the fact that a note or memorandum of the contract was made, and was signed by the borrower; - the date when a copy of the note or memorandum was delivered or sent to the borrower; - the amount repaid; - the amount due but unpaid;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'Is the electronic mail address mentioned as an alternative to the registered place of business for receiving documents in legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the date upon which such unpaid sum or sums became due; - the amount of interest accrued due and unpaid on every such sum. 13. In actions to recover a debt or liquidated demand in money arising under a hire-purchase agreement or credit-sale agreement (as defined by the Hire-Purchase Act 1946) or any contract of guarantee relating to such an agreement, the special indorsement of claim on a summary summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, that the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Hire-Purchase Act 1946, have been complied with. # Indorsement of address** 14.[[9]](#_ftn9) The solicitor of a plaintiff shall indorse upon the summons and notice in lieu of service of a summons, the address and occupation or description of the plaintiff and also his own name or that of his firm and: - the registered place of business where documents may be left for him, and - where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form. 15.[[10]](#_ftn10) A plaintiff suing in person shall indorse upon the summons and notice in lieu of service of a summons his occupation or description and: - an address for service, where documents may be left for him, and - where the plaintiff consents to the receipt of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of an address for service) to which documents may be sent in electronic form. 16. In all cases where proceedings are commenced otherwise than by summons, rules 14 and 15 shall apply to the document by which such proceedings originate as if it were a summons. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 4 rule 1A inserted by 14 of 1989](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1989/en/si/0014.html), effective 1 February 1989. [[2]](#_ftnref2) Order 4 rule 1A substituted by 506 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0506.html), effective 10 August 2005.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'Was Order 4 rule 15 substituted more than once?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 4 rule 15 originally substituted by 307 of 2013], effective 26 August 2013, but re-substituted by 475 of 2017], effective 27 November 2017."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 4 rule 1A substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 4 rule 1A(3) deleted by 307 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2013/en.si.2013.0307.pdf), effective 26 August 2013. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 4 rule 2 substituted by 248 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0248.html), effective 2 June 2005. [[6]](#_ftnref6) Order 4 rule 3A substituted by 186 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/186/made/en/print), effective 1 June 2017. [[7]](#_ftnref7) Order 4 rule 5(2) substituted by 16 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2014/en.si.2014.0016.pdf), effective 3 February 2014. [[8]](#_ftnref8) Superseded amendment: Order 4 rule amended by 585 of 2001](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2001/en/si/0585.html), effective 1 January 2002. This replaced “**£55**” with “**€70**” and “**£5**” with “**€7**”. This replaced some amounts in pounds in the RSC with convenient euro equivalents. Unless specifically adjusted by 585 of 2001, other references to “**£**” in the RSC were converted to euro at the rate of €1 £0.787564, effective 1 January 2002. [[9]](#_ftnref9) Order 4 rules 14 and 15 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017. [[10]](#_ftnref10) Order 4 rule 15 originally substituted by 307 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2013/en.si.2013.0307.pdf), effective 26 August 2013, but re-substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a specific type of court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court - Court: District # Order 40:Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it forbidden for a claimant to split their claim into multiple parts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claimant must not divide a claim for the purpose of making the claim the subject of two or more claim notices."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Claim not to be divided* 2. (1) A claimant must not divide a claim for the purpose of making the claim the subject of two or more claim notices. (2) A claimant who has a claim for more than the amount for which a claim may be made in the Court may abandon the excess by so stating in the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must a claim notice include the name and address of the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"state the name and address of the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Names, addresses and representation of parties* 3. (1) A claim notice must— - (a) state the full name and address of the claimant and an address for service of documents on the claimant; and - if the claimant sues in person, state an address for service of documents on the claimant; and - if the claimant sues or the respondent is sued in a representative capacity, state the capacity in which the claimant sues or the respondent is sued in a representative capacity; and - state the name and address of the respondent; and - if the claimant sues by a solicitor, state the name or firm and business address of the solicitor and also, if the solicitor is the agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal. (2) Where a solicitor’s name is given on a claim notice as solicitor for a claimant— - (a) the solicitor must, on request in writing by a respondent, confirm in writing whether the claim notice was filed by or with the authority of the solicitor on behalf of that claimant; and - if the solicitor confirms in writing that the claim notice was not filed by or with the authority of that solicitor, the Court must stay the civil proceedings and no further step may be taken in the civil proceedings without the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a civil proceeding required to be initiated through the filing and service of a claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Subject to the provisions of these Rules which apply to particular categories of claims or cases, a civil proceeding must be commenced by the filing for issue and service of a claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Commencement of civil proceedings* 4. (1) Subject to the provisions of these Rules which apply to particular categories of claims or cases, a civil proceeding must be commenced by the filing for issue and service of a claim notice. (2) Save where otherwise provided by these Rules or by an Act and subject to [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) and the Conventions to which it relates, a claim notice must be filed with and issued by the Clerk for the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or at the election of the claimant, - in proceedings founded on contract, (except proceedings arising from an agreement under the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24) or the [European Communities (Consumer Credit Agreements) Regulations 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/281) (S.I. 281 of 2010)) in which the contract is alleged to have been made, or - in proceedings founded on tort, in which the tort is alleged to have been committed, or - in ejectment proceedings, in which the lands the subject of the proceedings are situated. (3) Filing must be effected by filing with the Clerk assigned to the Court area referred to in sub-rule (2), in person or by post. (4) Unless otherwise provided by law, civil proceedings in the Court must be heard and determined at a sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the civil proceeding was brought. (5)[2] Except in a case to which section 7(6)(a)(ii) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html) applies, a claim notice which has been issued by a Clerk is deemed to have been issued on the date on which it was filed with the Clerk for issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claim notice required to contain a statement of claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claim notice must contain a statement of claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Form of claim notice* 5. (1) Unless sub-rule (2) applies, a claim notice must be in , Schedule or in [Form 40.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/95a3c20f-d07f-4dc8-a4dd-ba53f8c3672c/Claim notice - debt claim not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule in a debt claim. (2) If a claim notice is to be served out of the State, the claim notice must be in the form required by [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) (service out of the State with the permission of the Court) or, as the case may be, Order (service out of the State without the permission of the Court). (3) A claim notice must contain a statement of claim. (4) A statement of claim must— - (a) contain, in a summary form, a statement of all material facts on which the claimant relies, but not evidence by which those facts are to be proved; - contain the necessary particulars of every fact; - if the claim arises by or under any enactment, identify the specific provision of the enactment that is relied on; - state specifically the amount or other relief or remedy sought; state the place where and the date when the claim arose. (5) A statement of claim in a debt claim must state that the claim is for debt or liquidated damages, must specify the amount claimed by way of debt or liquidated damages and must include particulars of the claimant’s demand for payment. (6) A statement of claim must be divided into paragraphs numbered consecutively, and each fact or matter stated, so far as practicable, must be contained in a separate paragraph. (7) Where the claim is founded on any written document, the statement of claim must state the date of the document and the parties to the document and: - (a) if the claim is for the payment of money, the amount claimed, or - if the claim is for breach of contract, the alleged breach or breaches of the contract.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for a claimant to state the reasons if they were unable to include certain information in their initial claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a claimant alleges that he or she was unable, at the time at which a claim notice was issued, to include in the claim notice any of the information required by this rule to be specified in the claim notice, he or she must include in the claim notice a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A statement of claim must contain a list of all correspondence and other documents on which the claimant will rely at the trial including the date if any and a brief description of each document. (9) Any claim notice in which damages are claimed is assumed to include a claim for interest from the date of judgment, where permitted by law, and for the costs of the civil proceedings, whether or not expressly claimed. (10) Where a claimant alleges that he or she was unable, at the time at which a claim notice was issued, to include in the claim notice any of the information required by this rule to be specified in the claim notice, he or she must include in the claim notice a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the claim notice. The claimant must, when the claim notice is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific timeframe mentioned for the respondent to pay the claimed amounts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"within ten days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Costs to be specified* 6. (1) In a debt claim, the claim notice must be indorsed with a statement as follows— "If you pay the amount of €...... and costs of €....... to the claimant or the claimant''s solicitor within ten days and without filing and serving an appearance and defence you may avoid further costs.". (2) The amount of costs in the indorsement must be the appropriate amount set out in the Schedule of Costs. (3) If a claim notice is indorsed in accordance with sub-rule (1), and the respondent pays the amounts claimed within the time limited for filing and serving an appearance and defence, then the civil proceeding is concluded. (4) The claimant must notify the Clerk in writing when civil proceedings are concluded in accordance with sub-rule (3).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the consent form required to be in Form 40.03 when the amount claimed exceeds €15,000?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the consent must be in the [Form 40.03]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Consent proceedings* 7. (1) Where civil proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the [1924 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/10/enacted/en/html) are brought before the District Court and the amount claimed in such proceedings is in excess of €15,000 and, pursuant to the proviso (inserted by section of the 1991 Act) to paragraph A of section 77, the necessary parties to the proceedings sign a form of consent either before or at any time during the hearing, the consent must be in the [Form 40.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d66c6fe2-a616-46f0-82d7-752450a2eed5/Consent No. 40.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) When completed, the consent must be attached to and filed together with the original claim notice or other originating document or, as appropriate, must be produced to the Court during the hearing. (3) Every consent so filed or produced must be retained by the Clerk with the original claim notice or other originating document and must be noted on the court record and on any order issued in relation to the civil proceedings. (4) Costs, where allowed in any such civil proceedings, must be in accordance with the relevant provisions of the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time frame given for the respondent to file documents if the claimant fails to do so?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the claimant omits or refuses to file the documents within the 14 day period mentioned in sub-rule (1), the respondent must do so as soon as may be after the expiration of the 14 day period."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Proceedings transferred from the High Court or Circuit Court* 8. (1) Where civil proceedings are remitted or transferred to the District Court by the High Court under section 25 of the [1924 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/10/enacted/en/html) or by the Circuit Court under section 15 of the [1991 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/20/enacted/en/html), the claimant must, within 14 days from the date of perfection of the order for remittal or transfer, file with the Clerk a certified copy of the order and the summons, civil bill or other originating document (or a copy thereof) and copies of all documents already delivered and orders made in the proceedings. (2) Where the claimant omits or refuses to file the documents within the 14 day period mentioned in sub-rule (1), the respondent must do so as soon as may be after the expiration of the 14 day period. (3) The party filing the documents must give notice to every other party to the proceedings of such filing. (4) After filing of the order and documents, the civil proceedings must continue as if they had been commenced in the Court and any respondent who has not served a defence and filed an appearance must do so within the 21 days of service of the notice referred to in sub-rule (3). (5) The civil proceedings must be heard and determined by the Court as if they had originally been commenced in the Court. (6) A note of the remittal or transfer must be entered on the court record and on any order issued in relation to the proceedings. (7) Costs, where allowed in any such civil proceedings, must be in accordance with the provisions of the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for claims under section 74 of the Consumer Protection Act 2007?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any claim by a consumer for damages under section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007] must be commenced by the issue and service in accordance with this Order of a claim notice, entitled in the matter of section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007] and otherwise in the [Form 40.01, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Proceedings under section 74 of the Consumer Protection Act 2007* 9. (1) Any claim by a consumer for damages under section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) (No. 19 of 2007) must be commenced by the issue and service in accordance with this Order of a claim notice, entitled in the matter of section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) and otherwise in the [Form 40.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1) with such modifications as are appropriate. (2) Any consent under section 74(4) of the Consumer Protection Act 2007 must be in the [Form 40.03, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d66c6fe2-a616-46f0-82d7-752450a2eed5/Consent No. 40.03.docx/docx/1) but, instead of reciting that it is given under section 77A of The Courts of Justice Act 1924, must recite that it is given under section 74(4) of the Consumer Protection Act 2007, and must be lodged with the Clerk either before or at any time during the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court extend the validity of a claim notice beyond its initial one-year period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may extend the validity of the claim notice for three months from the day of the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Duration* 10.[3] (1) A claim notice is valid for service for one year after the day it is filed. (2) If a claim notice has not been served on a respondent, the Court may extend the validity of the claim notice for three months from the day of the order. (3) An order may be made under sub-rule (2) before or after expiry of the claim notice. (4) The Court may on an application made under sub-rule (2) before the expiry of the claim notice make an order extending the validity of the claim notice if it is satisfied that reasonable efforts have been made to serve the respondent, or for other good reason. (5) The Court may on an application made under sub-rule (2) after the expiry of the claim notice make an order extending the validity of the claim notice if it is satisfied that there are special circumstances which justify an extension, such circumstances to be stated in the order. (6) The claimant may apply under sub-rule (2) without notice to the respondent, but if the Court considers that the respondent ought to be heard, the Court may adjourn the further hearing and direct the claimant to give written notice to the respondent of the place and time to which the application was adjourned. (7) If a witness summons has not been served on a witness, the Court may from time to time extend the validity of the witness summons for such period from the day of the order as the Court directs, not being more than six months from that day. (8) An order may be made under sub-rule (7) before or after expiry of the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a data protection action required to be brought in the court area where the data subject resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the court area in which— (a) the controller or processor against whom the data protection action is taken has an establishment, or the data subject has his or her habitual residence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Data Protection Actions* 11[4].(1) In this rule: the “**2018 Act**” means the [Data Protection Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/7/enacted/en/html) (No. 7 of 2018); “**data protection action**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 117 of the 2018 Act; “**GDPR**” means [Regulation 2016/679](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/679/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 27 April 2016 on the protection of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data and on the free movement of such data, and repealing Directive (General Data Protection Regulation); each of the expressions “**controller**”, “**data subject**” and “**processor**” has the same meaning as in the GDPR or the 2018 Act as the context requires. (2) A data protection action must be brought in the court area in which— - (a) the controller or processor against whom the data protection action is taken has an establishment, or - the data subject has his or her habitual residence. (3) Where a data protection action is brought on behalf of a data subject by a not-for-profit body, organisation or association to which section 117(7) of the 2018 Act applies that has been mandated by the data subject to do so, the claim notice must: - include a statement to that effect, and - confirm that the claimant satisfies each relevant requirement of Article 80 of the GDPR, and must otherwise be in the Form [40.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such further modifications as are appropriate. (4) The Court may, of its own motion or on the application of another party to a data protection action, direct the provision to it of such additional information as is necessary in order to confirm that the claimant is such a body, organisation or association.” [1] Order 40 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 40 sub-rule (5) of rule 4 substituted by [S.I. 513 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/513/made/en/print?q 513&years 2016), effective 8 November 2016 [3] Order 40 rule 10 substituted by [S.I. 423 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/423/made/en/print?q 423&years 2019), effective 2 September 2019 [4] Order 40 rule 11 inserted by 13 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/13/made/en/print#:~:text Minister for Justice.&text 1.,the time being in force.), effective 20 January 2024.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section titled ''DEFINITIONS'' in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## 1 - DEFINITIONS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - DEFINITIONS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about personal injuries proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"PERSONAL INJURIES PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE 2004 ACT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - PERSONAL INJURIES PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE 2004 ACT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for where personal injury proceedings must be heard and determined?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Unless otherwise provided by law, personal injuries proceedings in the Court must be heard and determined at a sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the personal injuries proceedings were brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Venue* 3.(1) Save where otherwise provided by these Rules or by an Act and subject to [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) and the Conventions to which it relates, a personal injuries summons must be filed with and issued by the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - at the election of the claimant, in which any tort alleged in the personal injuries summons is alleged to have been committed. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by filing an originating document, to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons, with the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent has his or her principal office, or - at the election of the claimant, in which any malicious incident alleged in the Garda compensation personal injuries summons is alleged to have occurred, and by the issuing of that Garda compensation personal injuries summons by the Clerk concerned. (2) Unless otherwise provided by law, personal injuries proceedings in the Court must be heard and determined at a sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the personal injuries proceedings were brought. (3) Except in a case to which section 7(6)(a)(ii) of the Courts Act 1964 applies, a personal injuries summons which has been issued by a Clerk is deemed to have been issued on the date on which it was filed with the Clerk for issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Does a personal injuries summons require the claimant''s Personal Public Service Number?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant’s Personal Public Service Number (and where a claimant has not been issued with a PPSN, this must be stated in the personal injuries summons)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Content of personal injuries summons* 5.(1) A personal injuries summons must specify: - the claimant’s name, the address at which he or she ordinarily resides and his or her occupation; - the claimant’s Personal Public Service Number (and where a claimant has not been issued with a PPSN, this must be stated in the personal injuries summons); - (iii) the respondent’s name, the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (if known to the claimant) and the respondent’s occupation (if known to the claimant). (2) In any proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the 2003 Act, the personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons must contain a statement: - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, - specifying the section of the 2003 Act or the rule made under section 46(3) of the 2003 Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Must a personal injuries summons include details of each instance of negligence by the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"each instance of negligence by the respondent, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Particulars of claim in personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 6. (1) A personal injuries summons must: - (a) set out full and detailed particulars of- - the nature of the claim and of each allegation, assertion or plea comprising that claim; - the injuries to the claimant alleged to have been occasioned by the wrong of the respondent; - (iii) the acts of the respondent constituting the wrong and the circumstances relating to the commission of the wrong; - each instance of negligence by the respondent, and - contain a schedule of full particulars of all items of special damage in respect of which the claimant is making a claim. (2) A Garda compensation personal injuries summons must: - (a) set out full and detailed particulars of-: - the injuries or death alleged to have been occasioned by the malicious incident concerned; - the malicious incident, and - (iii) in the case of proceedings brought by one or more persons to whom section of the 2022 Act refers, the applicability of that section to each person by whom or for whose benefit the proceedings are brought, and. - contain a schedule of full particulars of all items of special damage in respect of which the claimant is making a claim. (3) Where a claimant who has not served the notice required by section 8(1) of the 2004 Act within the time prescribed for service of that notice alleges that there was a reasonable cause for failing to do so within that time, the personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summon must include details of the cause of that failure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claimant required to provide additional information after serving a summons if they were unable to include all necessary details initially?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he or she must include in the summons a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the summons. The claimant must, when the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide and verify such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where a claimant alleges that he or she was unable, at the time at which a personal injuries summons Garda compensation personal injuries summon was issued, to include in the summons any of the information required by this rule to be specified therein, he or she must include in the summons a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the summons. The claimant must, when the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide and verify such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that respondents must use when they intend to defend personal injuries proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Each respondent who intends to defend personal injuries proceedings must deliver to the claimant (or his solicitor) an appearance and defence in the Form [40A.02]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Form of personal injuries defence* 7.(1) Each respondent who intends to defend personal injuries proceedings must deliver to the claimant (or his solicitor) an appearance and defence in the Form [40A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/816a97df-5fe3-41bd-9871-ad64dbe48558/Personal injuries defence No. 40A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule and file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk within 28 days after the service on him or her of the personal injuries summons. (2) Where any respondent makes a counterclaim, the counterclaim must be in the Form [40A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab6c0721-b772-42f9-af8f-64a7c1de36eb/Personal injuries counterclaim No. 40A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be appended to the defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of motion required when making certain applications in personal injury cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The following applications in personal injuries proceedings must be made by application to the Court by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Applications by notice of motion in personal injuries proceedings* 9.(1) The following applications in personal injuries proceedings must be made by application to the Court by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties. The notice of motion must be in the Form [40A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b48ee3d-2e7c-4a96-9208-96acdcf26ccb/Notice of motion (personal injuries action) No. 40A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be supported by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application under section 9(2) of the 2004 Act (in the absence of agreement between or among the parties) for the extension of the period provided for in this Order or otherwise in these Rules, within which any document may be served or thing may be done; - an application by a respondent under section 10(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay or dismissal of proceedings by reason of a claimant’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 10 of the 2004 Act; - (iii) an application by a respondent under section 11(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay or dismissal of proceedings by reason of a claimant’s failure to provide further information requested under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the 2004 Act; - an application by a claimant under section 12(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay of proceedings or for judgment by reason of a respondent’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 12 of the 2004 Act; - an application by a party for a direction of the Court under section 15 of the 2004 Act that a mediation hearing be held; - an application to the Court to order delivery by the opposing party of further and better particulars of any pleading delivered by that opposing party; - (vii) an application by a party wishing to have evidence given by affidavit, under section 19 of the 2004 Act;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that the notices of settlement offers must be in?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be in the Form [40A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cc9350a5-acea-4ab4-8aaa-e6830d61a3bf/Notice as to terms No. 40A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Offer of settlement* 11.(1) Copies of the claimant’s notice of an offer of terms of settlement required by section 17(1) of the 2004 Act and of the respondent’s notice required by section 17(2) of the 2004 Act must be filed in Court. (2) Copies of the notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be filed by being delivered, together with an affidavit or statutory declaration of service of the notice on the opposing party, to the Clerk as soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period referred to in section 17(3) of the 2004 Act. (3) The notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be in the Form [40A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cc9350a5-acea-4ab4-8aaa-e6830d61a3bf/Notice as to terms No. 40A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4) The notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must not be given or produced to the Judge before the determination of the personal injuries proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a pre-trial hearing mandatory in personal injuries proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A pre-trial hearing as provided for in section 18 of the 2004 Act must be held in personal injuries proceedings where the Court, on the application by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties by the party wishing to apply for a pre-trial hearing, considers that a pre-trial hearing is appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Pre-trial hearing* 12.(1) A pre-trial hearing as provided for in section 18 of the 2004 Act must be held in personal injuries proceedings where the Court, on the application by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties by the party wishing to apply for a pre-trial hearing, considers that a pre-trial hearing is appropriate. (2) A Judge presiding over a pre-trial hearing may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as he or she considers necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the proceedings are in dispute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 28 - Recognisances Under The Probation Of Offenders Act, 1907', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued when a Probation Officer applies to discharge a recognisance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue of notice of the application in the [Form 28.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7.[2] An application by a Probation Officer to discharge a recognisance entered in accordance with rule 1 may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the offender is bound by the recognisance to appear. Such application shall be preceded by the issue of notice of the application in the [Form 28.7, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8b7cd0b5-88c5-4446-8668-6f8d0a3abbad/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Recogisance - (Probation Of Offenders Act 1907, As Amended By Criminal Justice Administration Act 1914) No. 28.7.docx/docx/1), which shall be served upon the person bound by the recognisance and each surety (if any) at least four days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where the Court considers it appropriate, it may dispense with the requirement to give such notice. 8.[3] On any application to vary the terms or conditions of the recognisance, or to discharge a recognisance, the original recognisance shall be produced in Court. Where the Court varies the terms or conditions of the recognisance, the persons bound shall re-acknowledge the recognisance as so varied before the Court on the making of such variation. Where the Court discharges the recognisance, the discharge shall be endorsed on the recognisance by the Judge. [1] Order 28 rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 544 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/544/made/en/print?q 544&years 2006), effective 20 November 2006 [2] Order 28 rule 7 inserted by [S.I. 544 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/544/made/en/print?q 544&years 2006), effective 20 November 2006 [3] Order 28 rule 8 inserted by [S.I. 544 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/544/made/en/print?q 544&years 2006), effective 20 November 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 3 - Procedure By Special Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Was 149 of 2010 implemented on May 10, 2010?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"149 of 2010 is effective 10 May 2010"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[[7]](#_ftnref7) Order 3 rule 15 substituted by rules 15, 15A and by 149 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2010/en.si.2010.0149.pdf). 149 of 2010 is effective 10 May 2010, subject to paragraph 2 which reads: “Any application for registration of a lis pendens containing the particulars required by law before 1 December 2009 for such registration which is received after 1 December 2009 and prior to the date mentioned in paragraph 1 shall be deemed to comply with the requirements for registration of a lis pendens in accordance with section 121 of the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009.” [[8]](#_ftnref8) Order 3 rule 21 substituted by 269 of 2001](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2001/en/si/0269.html), effective 16 July 2001. [[9]](#_ftnref9) Order 3 rule 21 amended by 14 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2007/en/si/0014.html). 14 of 2007 is effective 13 February 2007, subject to paragraph 3 which states: “Nothing in these Rules shall affect the validity of any step taken or any other thing done in any proceedings on any relevant application or in any proceedings on any appeal referred to in [Order 84C](full-court-rule?id c218bd79-5889-4992-b1f0-cbfe0cd08b06), rule 1(2) initiated before the commencement of these Rules. Any such proceedings shall, save where the court in those proceedings otherwise orders, be continued and completed as if these Rules had not been made.”'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for personal injury proceedings involving the Garda Síochána Compensation Act 2022?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"personal injuries proceedings in the Court which are proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the Form No. 40A.09"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form of personal injuries summons and Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 4.(1) Personal injuries proceedings in the Court must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the Form No. [40A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/940afe85-406e-40fc-8b09-0cc375ed14cf/Personal injuries summons No. 40A.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), personal injuries proceedings in the Court which are proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the [Form No. 40A.09](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a201467f-8689-419e-897b-ba29c9f98fb3/Garda compensation personal injuries summons - Garda Síochána Compensation Act 2022 - No 40A.09.docx/doc/1), Schedule to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons. (3) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, the provisions of these Rules which apply to a claim notice apply, with appropriate modifications, to a personal injuries summons and to Garda compensation personal injuries summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of motion required to be served on the respondent at least seven days before the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of motion must be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Application for approval of an assessment* 13. (1) An application for the approval by the Court of an assessment under section 35(2) of the 2003 Act must be made by notice of motion in the Form [40A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1cb50a26-3393-4963-ad8c-22bce14cf860/Notice of application for approval of Injuries Board assessment No. 40A.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The notice of motion must be filed with and issued by the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - at the election of the applicant, in which any tort to which the relevant claim mentioned in section 35 of the 2003 Act relates is alleged to have been committed (3) The notice of motion must be supported by an affidavit entitled “IN THE MATTER OF THE PERSONAL INJURIES ASSESSMENT BOARD ACT 2003 and IN THE MATTER OF AN APPLICATION RELATING TO A.B., A [WARD, CHILD OR PERSON WHO IS THE SUBJECT OF A DECISION-MAKING REPRESENTATION ORDER], OF [ADDRESS] BY C.D., ACTING AS [STATE CAPACITY] ON BEHALF OF THE SAID A.B.” (4) The notice of motion must be addressed to the respondent by name and must be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the return date. (5) The notice of motion must be served - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (or in the case of a company, its registered office) or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished by the respondent, at that address, or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (or in the case of a company, its registered office) or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court direct investment if an order to pay issues according to section 38 of the 2003 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may direct investment in accordance with Order 43, rule 12."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) When considering an application concerning such an assessment the Court may appoint a person of full age to act as guardian litem of the child. (7) Where applicable, the provisions of [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment), rule 7 (concerning lodgments) apply mutatis mutandis to assessments made in favour of children, wards or persons the subjects of Decision-Making Representation Orders which are approved in accordance with this rule in respect of the amount recoverable in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act. (8) The Clerk must send by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail to the Personal Injuries Assessment Board a certified copy of any order made pursuant to this rule. (9) If an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy of the order to pay must be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or in electronic form. (10) If an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, the Court may direct investment in accordance with [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), rule 12.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application by an assessor required to be made within the Court area where the respondent resides or conducts business?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by an assessor for an order under section 27(2) of the 2003 Act must be made at a sitting of the District Court in the Court area within which the person against whom the order concerned is sought resides or carries on business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Application to Court by assessors* 14.(1) An application by an assessor for an order under section 27(2) of the 2003 Act must be made at a sitting of the District Court in the Court area within which the person against whom the order concerned is sought resides or carries on business. (2) Such an application must be by notice of application in the Form [40A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ebc937f0-fe1e-4b15-9e27-cfb59be03be5/Notice of application by assessors No. 40A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be addressed to the respondent by name. (3) Notice of the application must be served by the applicant not later than seven days before the return date. The notice must be served: - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, at that address; or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address. [1] Order 40A originally inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014; substituted in entirety by 231 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/231/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,Compensation) Act 2022) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of May, 2024.), effective 31 May 2024. [2] Order 40A Rule 10 subsection (4) inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018 Superseded amendments: Order 40A sub-rule (1) of rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 599 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/599/made/en/print?q 599&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014 Order 40A sub-rule (3) of rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 513 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/513/made/en/print?q 513&years 2016), effective 8 November 2016 Order 40A sub-rule (2) of rule 5 substituted by [S.I. 102 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/102/made/en/print?q 102&years 2017), effective 24 April 2017 Order 40A rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 327 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/327/made/en/print?q 327&years 2019), effective 1 August 2019 Order 40A sub-rule (4) of rule 10 inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 2 January 2018 Order 40A sub-rule (2) of rule 13 substituted by [S.I. 599 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/599/made/en/print?q 599&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) : - Court: District # *Order 40B:*Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) *[1]*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''ejectment'' used in the context of legal proceedings for recovering possession of premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any reference in an enactment to “ejectment” must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to recovery of the possession of premises by a landlord or other person claiming to be entitled to possession of premises"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— the “**1860 Act”** means the [Landlord and Tenant Law Amendment Act Ireland 1860](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1860/act/154/enacted/en/print.html); any reference in an enactment to “**ejectment**” must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to recovery of the possession of premises by a landlord or other person claiming to be entitled to possession of premises; “**landlord and tenant claim notice**” means a claim notice beginning landlord and tenant proceedings in the District Court in accordance with these Rules, and any reference in an enactment to an ejectment civil summons must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to a landlord and tenant claim notice; “**landlord and tenant proceedings**” means any civil proceedings which may be brought in the District Court between a landlord and a tenant, and any reference in an enactment to proceedings for ejectment or for the recovery of possession of premises in the District Court must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to landlord and tenant proceedings; any reference to an “**order**” must, for the purposes of this Order, unless the context otherwise requires, be taken to include a reference to a judgment, decree or dismiss.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is this order only applicable to landlord and tenant proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of this Order apply to landlord and tenant proceedings in the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Requirements of this Order additional to Order 40* 2. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to landlord and tenant proceedings in the Court. (2) The requirements of this Order are additional to the requirements of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) as regards claim notices.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claim notice required to specify the names of both the landlord and the tenant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"specify the names of the landlord and the tenant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional particulars required in landlord and tenant claim notice* 3. (1) A landlord and tenant claim notice must: - (a) specify the names of the landlord and the tenant; - specify the nature of the tenancy and state whether the tenancy is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register maintained under section 127 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and where the tenancy is required to be so registered, either give particulars of registration or confirm that it is not so registered; - contain a description of the premises to which the claim relates, including the full address and any other details necessary to establish the Court area in which the premises are situated; - specify the rent under the tenancy; - where it is part of the claim that the tenancy has determined, the facts of the determination of the tenancy and the means by which it was determined; - where non-payment of rent is part of the claim, specify the amount of rent due after all fair and just allowances, and the date up to which that rent was due; - explain why the claimant is not precluded from bringing civil proceedings in the Court in respect of the tenancy by section 182 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html); - set out the appropriate costs in the Schedule of Costs payable if the claimant’s claim is settled before appearance and defence. (2) A claim notice claiming for the recovery of possession of premises from a tenant at will, a permissive occupant, or a caretaker or servant must also: - (a) state that a demand for possession was made by or on behalf of the owner of the premises; - specify the date of the demand for possession; - confirm the respondent’s refusal or omission to quit and deliver up possession. (3) The Court may stay proceedings in respect of any tenancy which is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register maintained under section 127 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) but is not so registered.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when issuing a claim notice for recovery of possession of premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claim notice in a claim for: ... recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent must be in accordance with [Form Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Form of claim notice* 4. A claim notice in a claim for: - (a) recovery of possession of premises for overholding, - recovery of possession of premises from a tenant at will, a permissive occupant, a caretaker or a servant or, - recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent must be in accordance with [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e0dcf0a-82cc-49e3-8416-3760171832de/Landlord and tenant claim notice, recovery of possession of premises No. 40B.01.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claim notice required to be served on the immediate tenant if they are not in actual possession of the premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the immediate tenant of the claimant in landlord and tenant proceedings is not in actual possession of the premises, the claim notice must be served on that immediate tenant in addition to any person on whom service is required under sub-rule (1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Service of claim notice* 5. (1) A landlord and tenant claim notice must be served on every person in actual possession of the premises specified in the claim notice, whether as tenant, sub-tenant, or otherwise. (2) The claim notice must be served in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (3) Where the immediate tenant of the claimant in landlord and tenant proceedings is not in actual possession of the premises, the claim notice must be served on that immediate tenant in addition to any person on whom service is required under sub-rule (1). (4) Where no person is in actual possession of the premises, a copy of the claim notice must be affixed to the door or some other conspicuous part of the premises claimed. In such a case, the affixing of a copy of the claim notice must be taken to be sufficient service of the claim notice. (5) Where the person who was last in actual possession of the premises was a sub-tenant, and no person is in actual possession, the claim notice must also be served on the immediate tenant of the claimant, as provided by sub-rule (3).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court grant a stay of execution when making an order based on a landlord and tenant claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may grant a stay of execution on such conditions as it thinks reasonable in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Stay of execution* 7. On making an order on foot of any landlord and tenant claim notice claiming recovery of possession of premises, the Court may grant a stay of execution on such conditions as it thinks reasonable in the circumstances.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent stop further proceedings by paying the rent and costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may order that all further proceedings be stayed on payment to the claimant of the money deposited, and such further amount, if any, for costs up to the date of tender as the Court thinks reasonable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Payment or tender in claims for recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent* 8. (1) At any time before an order on a claim for recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent has been delivered to the County Registrar or Sheriff for execution, the respondent or any person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy may pay to the claimant: - (a) all rent and arrears of rent due at the time of the service of the claim notice, and - a sum sufficient to cover the claimant’s costs, or may tender those amounts to the claimant. (2) If tender of the amounts mentioned in sub-rule (1) is refused, the respondent or other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy may deposit those amounts with the Clerk. (3) The Clerk must give a receipt for any amounts deposited under sub-rule (2) and give notice to the claimant of receipt of the amounts deposited. (4) In such a case, the Court may order that all further proceedings be stayed on payment to the claimant of the money deposited, and such further amount, if any, for costs up to the date of tender as the Court thinks reasonable. (5) A decision of the Court under sub-rule (4) is subject to appeal as if it were a final order on foot of a claim notice in ejectment for non-payment of rent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Can a writ of restitution be granted if the rent, arrears, and costs are paid within six months?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A writ of restitution may be awarded in accordance with sub-rule (1) on the payment to the claimant or the deposit with the Clerk of the amount due for rent, arrears of rent and costs within six months after the execution of the judgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Writ of restitution* 9. (1) When an order for possession for non-payment of rent has been executed, the Court may award a writ of restitution on the application of the respondent or any other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy. (2) A writ of restitution may be awarded in accordance with sub-rule (1) on the payment to the claimant or the deposit with the Clerk of the amount due for rent, arrears of rent and costs within six months after the execution of the judgment, as provided by sections 70 and 71 of the 1860 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant for possession be issued more than six months after the date of the order without an application to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"After the expiration of six months from the date of the order a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant by motion on notice to the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Warrant for possession* 10. (1) A warrant for possession under section 86 of the 1860 Act may be issued at any time not exceeding six months after the date of the order. (2) After the expiration of six months from the date of the order a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant by motion on notice to the respondent. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about procedures for statutory applications in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application - Court: District # Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for the enforcement of a decision made by a relevant authority considered a relevant application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application to the Court by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court, for an order of the Court directing, requiring or compelling a person to perform, comply with, carry out or implement, or for the enforcement of, a decision, determination, notice or order of a relevant authority (in the remainder of this Order, referred as an “enforcement application”)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. (1) In this Order - “**relevant authority**” means any agency, board, authority, commission, council, ombudsman, tribunal, or other body (not including a company formed under the Companies Acts) established by or under an enactment, which is authorised by an enactment: - (a) to exercise powers under an enactment to determine or decide, any complaint or issue, or - to issue any notice or order addressed to a person requiring the taking or ceasing of any action, and includes, where the context so requires, any committee, officer or member of the staff of such a body who has been authorised by an enactment or by such a body to exercise those powers; “**relevant application**” means any of the following applications– - (a) an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court for an order directing, requiring or compelling a person to take any step or do any thing (including, without limitation, to provide information or to produce a document or thing) or prohibiting or restraining a person from, or directing a person to cease or refrain from, taking a step or doing a thing (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “**direction application**”), - an application to the Court by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court, for an order of the Court directing, requiring or compelling a person to perform, comply with, carry out or implement, or for the enforcement of, a decision, determination, notice or order of a relevant authority (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as an “**enforcement application**”) but does not include: - any application for the issue by the Court or the Clerk of any order for execution of any such decision, determination, recommendation, or settlement which an enactment provides may be enforced or executed as, or in the like manner to, a judgment of the Court; or - any application for the issue of a summons; or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claim for damages considered a ''licence application''?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by that enactment to apply to the Court, for any licence, certificate, authority or permission or, as the case may be, for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding or restriction on holding any licence, certificate, authority or permission (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “licence application”),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) any claim for damages (which must be commenced by claim notice); - except where a particular procedure for such an application is specified in another Order of these Rules, an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by that enactment to apply to the Court, for any licence, certificate, authority or permission or, as the case may be, for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding or restriction on holding any licence, certificate, authority or permission (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “licence application”), - except where a particular procedure for such an application is specified in another Order of these Rules, any other application to the Court for relief under an enactment (other than relief by way of damages, liquidated or unliquidated) which is, required, authorised or permitted by these Rules to be brought or made in accordance with this Order. (2) Where an enactment provides for or permits a relevant application to be made to the Court or to a Judge and no other provision is made for the applicable procedure either by the enactment concerned or by these Rules, the procedure set out in the following rules applies. (3) Sub-rule (2) is subject to any requirement of the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is a direction application required to be brought in the Court area where the person against whom an order is sought resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in the case of a direction application or an enforcement application, in the Court area where the person or one of the persons against whom an order or other relief is sought resides or carries on any trade, profession or business"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Venue for relevant application* 2. (1) A relevant application must be brought: - (a) in the case of a direction application or an enforcement application, in the Court area where the person or one of the persons against whom an order or other relief is sought resides or carries on any trade, profession or business; - in the case of a licence application: - in the Court area where the applicant intends, in reliance on the licence, certificate, authority or permission sought (or, as the case may be, sought to be restored) to carry on any trade, profession or business; or - where the licence, certificate, authority or permission is not sought for the purpose of a trade, profession or business, in the Court area where the activity permitted by the licence, certificate, authority or permission is intended to be conducted; or - (iii) where the application is for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding, any licence, certificate, authority or permission, in the Court area where the disqualification or restriction concerned was imposed; or otherwise - in the Court area where the applicant resides. (2) Sub-rule (1) is subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of application required to be in Form No.', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Commencement of relevant application* 3. (1) The relevant application must be made by notice of application (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as “**the notice of application**”). (2) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of the provision of the enactment under which the application is made. (4) Where any order, direction or other relief is sought against any person, the notice of application must also be entitled as between the applicant as applicant and such person as respondent, and must contain the names and addresses of the applicant and of each respondent. (5) Where the application is authorised by an enactment to be made parte, or where no order, direction or other relief is sought as against any person or persons, the notice of application must be entitled in the matter of the provision of the enactment pursuant to which the application is made and on the application of the applicant, and must contain the name and address of the applicant. (6) The notice of application must specify the particular relief sought against each respondent and the particular provision of the relevant enactment authorising the granting of each such relief.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is a true copy of the decision required to be attached to the notice of application for an enforcement application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a true copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing, must be attached to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on any respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Documents to be attached to the notice of application* 4. Where the relevant application is an enforcement application, a true copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing, must be attached to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on any respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is the applicant required to provide evidence of their standing and authority during the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"evidence of the standing and authority of the applicant to make the application under the relevant provision of the enactment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Evidence required at hearing in every case* 5. (1) The applicant must adduce at the hearing of every relevant application: - (a) evidence of the standing and authority of the applicant to make the application under the relevant provision of the enactment; - if the applicant is acting in a representative capacity, or relief is sought against any respondent in a representative capacity, evidence of the capacity of the applicant or, as the case may be, the respondent; - evidence of the facts or circumstances which it is alleged authorise or entitle the applicant to make, or justify the applicant in making, the application and which support the granting of the relief sought; and - all correspondence and documents passing between the applicant and each respondent (if any), or otherwise issuing from any of them, relevant to the matter or matters in respect of which relief is sought, but not including any correspondence or document which, by law, a person is obliged or entitled to refuse to produce. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not operate to limit the evidence which the applicant is required to adduce at the hearing of the relevant application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific period of notice required for an application to be made to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Not less than 21 days’ notice of an application by notice of application must be given to the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Period of notice* 6. (1) Not less than 21 days’ notice of an application by notice of application must be given to the Court. (2) Each respondent must be served, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), with a copy of the notice of application (and copies of any documents required to be attached) not later than seven days before the return date. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date. (4) Where the relevant enactment requires prior publication of notice of the intended application, a print of the newspaper or other publication in which notice was published must also be lodged with the Clerk within the time specified in sub-rule (3). (5) Sub-rules (1) and (2) are subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court provide directions and orders for the conduct of proceedings on the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may: [...] give directions and make orders for the conduct of the proceedings as appear convenient for determining the application in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Orders which may be made by Court on return date* 7. (1) On the return date, the Court may: - (a) hear the application; or - give directions and make orders for the conduct of the proceedings as appear convenient for determining the application in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings. (2) Directions and orders under sub-rule may, where appropriate, include: - (a) directions that notice of the application be served on any other person, including mode of service and the time allowed for such service; - directions that the parties furnish written submissions to the Court and deliver those written submissions to one another; - an order directing the delivery and filing of any affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required when applying to vary or discharge an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A notice of motion to vary or discharge must be in [Form No. 44.02]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Application to vary or discharge an order* 8. (1) Where the relevant enactment permits any subsequent application to vary or discharge an order made by the Court on the relevant application, the application to vary or discharge the order must be made by notice of motion to vary or discharge (as the case may be). (2) A notice of motion to vary or discharge must be in [Form No. 44.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case. The notice must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) Not less than 21 days’ notice of an application to vary or discharge must be given to the Court. (4) The applicant for the original order and every respondent served with that application must be served, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), with a copy of the notice of motion to vary or discharge not later than seven days before the return date. (5) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of motion on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date. (6) Sub-rules (3), (4) and (5) are subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment. # [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified as District in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court - Court: District # Order Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific content mentioned in section 2 - GENERAL?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - GENERAL'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the appellant to attach copies of documents related to the notice, decision or direction being appealed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The appellant must also attach to the notice of appeal and to any copy of the notice of appeal served a copy of the notice, decision or direction appealed from and, where appropriate, copies of any other documents or exhibits used in relation to the notice, decision or direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Copy documents to be attached* 4. The appellant must also attach to the notice of appeal and to any copy of the notice of appeal served a copy of the notice, decision or direction appealed from and, where appropriate, copies of any other documents or exhibits used in relation to the notice, decision or direction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the notice of appeal to be served on additional individuals?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court hearing the appeal may, if it considers it proper, direct that the notice of appeal be served on any person not already served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Court may direct service of the notice of appeal* 5. The Court hearing the appeal may, if it considers it proper, direct that the notice of appeal be served on any person not already served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about specific legal appeals?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order specifically about criminal matters?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters - Court: District # **Order Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters****\*[**[1]**](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1)** ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a civil summons be made to the Clerk for the Court area where the defendant resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application to sign and issue the summons may, unless otherwise provided by an enactment or these Rules, be made to the Clerk for the Court area wherein that person ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application for summons* 1. (1) In any case where these Rules provide that an application to the Court is to be made or civil proceedings in the Court are to be begun by a civil summons, then the applicant, moving party or claimant may apply to the Clerk for the Court area in which the application is to be made or the proceedings are to be begun for the issue of a civil summons for service. (2) When it is intended to begin proceedings (which are not proceedings to which the [Courts (No. 3) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/33/enacted/en/html) relates) in the District Court against a person, and the issue of a summons requiring the appearance of that person before the Court is necessary, on a matter or issue which the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine by summons, an application to sign and issue the summons may, unless otherwise provided by an enactment or these Rules, be made to the Clerk for the Court area wherein that person ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to provide a copy or copies of the summons for service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a copy or copies for service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Form, signing and issue of summons* 2. (1) The applicant for the issue of the summons must lodge with the Clerk a duly completed summons, which may be in the [Form 40E.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/33195e4d-431e-492f-bf24-df0861589d33/Summons issued by a Clerk in a matter other than a criminal matter No. 40E.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (with such modifications as are appropriate to the case), together with a copy or copies for service. (2) The summons must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) The Clerk must unless otherwise provided by an enactment or these Rules, list the matter or issue for hearing at a sitting of the Court, record the place, date and time of hearing on the summons and copies and, having signed and dated the summons and copies, issue them to the applicant for service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court to which the summons is returnable required to have jurisdiction over the matter mentioned in the summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"having jurisdiction to deal with the matter or issue set out in the summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Court to which the summons is returnable* 3. Every summons issued under this Order must require the appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Court: - (a) having jurisdiction to deal with the matter or issue set out in the summons; - for the Court area to which the Clerk issuing the summons is assigned; - within the Court district in which a Judge of the District Court has jurisdiction in relation to the matter or issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 41 applicable to summonses signed and issued in proceedings covered by this Order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the provisions of [Order 41]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Service and filing* 4. Save where otherwise provided, the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) (Service of Documents) apply to summonses signed and issued in proceedings to which this Order relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Are the provisions of rules 4 through 9 of Order 15 applied with necessary modifications?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of rules 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9 (with any necessary modifications) of [Order 15]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Order 15 (in part) to apply* 5. The provisions of rules 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9 (with any necessary modifications) of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) apply to summonses signed and issued in proceedings to which this Order relates. \* Note: Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of offences are contained in [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to intellectual property?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order - Intellectual Property"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Intellectual Property - Court: District # **Order Intellectual Property******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Copyright and Related Rights Act 2000 mentioned in the definitions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “2000 Act” means the [Copyright and Related Rights Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) (No. 28 of 2000);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— the “**1992 Act**” means the [Patents Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1992); the “**1996 Act**” means the [Trade Marks Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6) (No. 6 of 1996); the “**2000 Act**” means the [Copyright and Related Rights Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) (No. 28 of 2000); the “**2001 Act**” means the [Industrial Designs Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) (No. 39 of 2001). the “**2019 Act**” means the [Copyright and Other Intellectual Property Law Provisions Act 2019](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/19/enacted/en/html) (No. 19 of 2019); “**intellectual property claim**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is this order applicable only to intellectual property claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of this Order apply to intellectual property claims in the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 Requirements of this Order additional to Order 40** 2. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to intellectual property claims in the Court. (2) The requirements of this Order are additional to the requirements of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) as regards claim notices.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Does a claim notice in an intellectual property case need to specify the legal provisions under which relief is sought?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"state specifically the relief sought against each respondent and every provision or rule of law relied on in support of each such relief"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 Additional particulars required in claim notice in intellectual property claim** 3. (1) An intellectual property claim notice must: - state the registered number of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates; - set out full particulars of the ownership of any unregistered intellectual property right concerned in the proceedings, or of the right of the claimant to claim infringement; - (iii) include particulars of the nature and extent of any intellectual property right relied upon by the claimant (including the capacity in which the claimant sues if not the registered proprietor or proprietor of the intellectual property right concerned); - include particulars of the nature and extent of the alleged infringement of any intellectual property right relied on by the claimant; - set out the material facts relied on in support of the intellectual property claim; - state specifically the relief sought against each respondent and every provision or rule of law relied on in support of each such relief and, where relief under the [1992 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/1/enacted/en/html), [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6), [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) and/or [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) is sought, the particular provisions under which relief is sought and the grounds for each such relief; - (vii) set out clearly the basis upon which the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine the intellectual property claim; - (viii) set out the appropriate costs in the Schedule of Costs payable if the claimant’s claim is settled before appearance and defence. (2) A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must be in accordance with [Form 40.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the modifications necessitated by this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to name and serve a claim notice on every person against whom relief is sought in an intellectual property claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must name as respondent, and must be served on, every person against whom relief is sought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4 Service of claim notice** 4. A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must name as respondent, and must be served on, every person against whom relief is sought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for delivery up be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court in or by way of a civil proceeding for the delivery up of: ... may be made parte to any sitting of the Court for the Court District wherein it is believed that the infringing matter concerned is or are in the possession, custody of control of any person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **5 Civil application for delivery up** 5. (1) An application to the Court in or by way of a civil proceeding for the delivery up of: - infringing goods, material or articles under section 20 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6); or - an infringing article, copy, or device under section 131 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or - (iii) an illicit recording, article or device under section 255 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or - an infringing product or article under section 61 of the [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) may be made parte to any sitting of the Court for the Court District wherein it is believed that the infringing matter concerned is or are in the possession, custody of control of any person. (2) The application may be grounded upon an information on oath and in writing by or on behalf of the proprietor of the registered trade mark concerned, or the copyright owner or a person having rights conferred by Part III of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) or the registered proprietor or his or its authorised representative, as the case may be. (3) Where an application has been made, and remains undetermined, in a criminal proceeding, for the delivery up of some or all of the same article(s), copies, devices or products, an application under this rule shall not be determined until the determination of the application in the criminal proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form recommended for orders made on applications under rule 5?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order made on an application under rule 5, whether parte or inter partes, may be in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **7 Form of order for delivery up** 7. An order made on an application under rule 5, whether parte or inter partes, may be in the [Form 40F.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c56c1a04-8de6-4002-b292-d1d0ea028372/Order for delivery up No. 40F.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when making an application for the erasure, removal, or obliteration of an offending sign?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must be in the Form Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **8 Civil application for erasure etc of offending sign or for forfeiture or disposal** 8. (1) Subject to sub-rule (4), an application to the Court in or by way of a civil proceeding for: - an order to cause an offending sign to be erased, removed or obliterated from any infringing goods, material or articles, or to secure the destruction of infringing goods, materials or articles under section 19 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6), or - an order for the destruction or forfeiture of infringing goods, material or articles under section 23 of the 1996 Act, or - (iii) an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an infringing copy, article or, device under section 145 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html), or - an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an illicit recording, article or device under section 264 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html), or - an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an infringing product or article under section 72 of the [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html), must be in the [Form 40F.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c7da7f4-09cf-476f-bb28-4fd68b03f69d/Notice of Application for Erasure Forfeiture Disposal No. 40F.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be served by the applicant, by personal service or by prepaid registered post: - (a) on the respondent thereto, - on any other person appearing to have an interest in the goods, materials, articles, copies, devices or products concerned, and - on any other person directed by the Court to be served. (2) If served personally, the notice must be served at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable; if served by prepaid registered post, the notice must be served at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (3) Where an application has been made, and remains undetermined, in a criminal proceeding, for the delivery up of some or all of the same article(s), copies, recordings, devices or products, an application under this rule shall not be determined until the determination of the application in the criminal proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court decide on an application under section 19 of the 1996 Act after determining an intellectual property claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, where it has determined an intellectual property claim, determine an application under section 19 of the [1996 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Notwithstanding sub-rules (1), (2) and (3), the Court may, where it has determined an intellectual property claim, determine an application under section 19 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6) made orally to the Court concerning infringing goods, material or articles which were the subject of that intellectual property claim, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that all persons having an interest in the infringing goods, material or articles are before the Court and have had an opportunity to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing service of documents in civil proceedings within the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State - Court: District # **Order 41: Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is a ''document'' in this context specifically defined as a ''District Court document''?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a “document” means a “District Court document”"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Definitions* 1. In this Order- a “**document**” means a “**District Court document**” within the meaning of section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons-server required to serve documents in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"a document may be served by: a summons-server standing assigned to the Court area concerned; or any person authorised to do so by the party or person on whose behalf the document is served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Persons authorised to serve documents* 2. (1) In civil proceedings, a document may be served by: - (a) a summons-server standing assigned to the Court area concerned; or - any person authorised to do so by the party or person on whose behalf the document is served, unless these Rules or statute otherwise provide or unless the Court otherwise directs. (2) The fee to be paid to a summons-server for the service of any document is the sum as determined by the County Registrar from time to time, payable on proof of each separate service effected. Where the fee to be paid for the service of any document is for the time being prescribed by rule of court or otherwise, the fee becomes payable on proof of each separate service effected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be served via registered prepaid post according to the Courts Act 1964?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A document in proceedings to which section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964] relates may, subject to and in accordance with the provisions of, section 7 of the [Courts Act 1964], be served by sending a copy of the document by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his or her last known residence or place of business in the State."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3. Mode of service - registered post* 3. (1) A document in proceedings to which section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html) relates may, subject to and in accordance with the provisions of, section 7 of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html), be served by sending a copy of the document by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his or her last known residence or place of business in the State. (2) The document may be posted by the person on whose behalf it purports to be issued or by a person authorised by him in that behalf.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be served on a company by sending it to the last known registered office according to the Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"For the purposes of this rule, any document left at or sent by post to the place for the time being recorded by the Registrar of Companies as the situation of the registered office of a company must be deemed to have been left at or sent by post to the registered office of the company notwithstanding that the situation of its registered office may have been changed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5. Service on a company* 5.(1) A document may be served on a company by leaving a copy of the document at or sending a copy of the document by post to the registered office of the company or, if the company has not given notice to the Registrar of Companies of the situation of its registered office, by registering the document at the office of the Registrar of Companies. (2) For the purposes of this rule, any document left at or sent by post to the place for the time being recorded by the Registrar of Companies as the situation of the registered office of a company must be deemed to have been left at or sent by post to the registered office of the company notwithstanding that the situation of its registered office may have been changed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be served to a local authority by sending it via prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by sending a copy of the document by prepaid registered post to its principal office."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6. Service on a local authority or an unincorporated body* 6. A document may be served on a local authority, statutory board or body, or an unincorporated society or club by leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the authority, board, body, society or club at its principal office or by sending a copy of the document by prepaid registered post to its principal office.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claim notice be served on a partnership without court permission if some partners are in the state and others are outside?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The permission of the Court is not necessary for the issue and service on a partnership of a claim notice or other originating document where one or more of the partners is in the State and one or more outside the State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7. Service on a partnership* 7.(1) Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, a copy of the document must be served either: - (a) on any one or more of the partners; or - at the principal place within the State at which the business of the partnership is carried on, on any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there; and such service must be deemed good service on the firm sued, whether any of the members of the partnership are outside the State or not. (2) The permission of the Court is not necessary for the issue and service on a partnership of a claim notice or other originating document where one or more of the partners is in the State and one or more outside the State, provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the claimant before the civil proceedings are begun, the claim notice or other originating document must be served on every person within the State sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be served on a child''s solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"on the child’s solicitor unless the Court otherwise decides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8. Service on a child* 8. Where the person to be served is a child, a document is effectively served if served: - (a) on the father, mother or other guardian having actual custody of the child or with whom the child resides; or - if the child has no father, mother or other guardian, on the person with whom the child resides or under whose care the child is; or - on the child’s solicitor unless the Court otherwise decides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can service be considered valid if it''s delivered to the governor or director of a prison instead of the prisoner?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service on the governor, director or other person in charge of the prison or place of detention is, unless the Court otherwise decides, good service on the prisoner or person detained."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10. Service on a prisoner* 10. Where the person to be served is a prisoner or a person detained in a place of detention under the order of any court or tribunal, service on the governor, director or other person in charge of the prison or place of detention is, unless the Court otherwise decides, good service on the prisoner or person detained.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can service on a solicitor be considered good service if the solicitor has accepted it through a document exchange service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service on the solicitor for a party may be effected: ... by sending a copy of the document to a document exchange service designated by that solicitor in accordance with sub-rule (3) through which that solicitor accepts documents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11. Acceptance of service* 11. (1) Service of a document must be deemed good service if the Court is satisfied that a solicitor acting on behalf of the person to be served has accepted service of the document. (2) Service on the solicitor for a party may be effected: - (a) by delivering a copy of the document to the solicitor; or - by leaving a copy of the document at the solicitor’s office; or - by sending a copy of the document by post in an envelope to, the solicitor; or - by sending a copy of the document to a document exchange service designated by that solicitor in accordance with sub-rule (3) through which that solicitor accepts documents. (3) Delivery or service through a document exchange service under sub-rule (2): - (a) is effective provided that the solicitor concerned has confirmed in writing to the party serving the document or copy (or that party’s solicitor) that he or she will accept service of documents in the civil proceedings through the document exchange service designated by him or her; - ceases to be effective where, prior to delivery or service, the solicitor concerned has in writing revoked such confirmation. (4) Any statutory declaration verifying delivery or service through a document exchange service must exhibit the written confirmation referred to in sub-rule (3) and contain a statement that the confirmation had not, at the time of the delivery or service concerned, been revoked in accordance with this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court allow for substituted service if there''s a good reason?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court is satisfied that, for good cause shown, service of a document cannot be effected in a manner or in any manner prescribed by these Rules, the Court may make an order:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12. Substituted service* 12.(1) Where the Court is satisfied that, for good cause shown, service of a document cannot be effected in a manner or in any manner prescribed by these Rules, the Court may make an order: - (a) for substituted or other service; or - for the substitution for service of notice by advertisement or otherwise. (2) Particulars of any order for substituted or other service must be endorsed on the original and on each copy of the document to be served. (3) An application for an order for substituted or other service may be made parte. (4) Where the Court is satisfied that any particular mode of service prescribed is at any time not then available, the Court may by order in writing direct that the service of documents or of any particular class of documents be effected in such other manner as it thinks proper. (5) A direction under sub-rule (4) must be retained by the Clerk and remains in force until the mode of service concerned is again available or until the direction is revoked by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court declare service of documents as valid even if they were not served according to the rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, if it considers it just to do so, deem the service of any document actually effected in any civil proceedings to be good and effected service, even though the service was not effected in a manner prescribed by these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13. Service deemed good* 13. The Court may, if it considers it just to do so, deem the service of any document actually effected in any civil proceedings to be good and effected service, even though the service was not effected in a manner prescribed by these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration of service required when serving documents by registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A statutory declaration of service, which must be in the Form 41.01, Schedule must be made not earlier than ten days after the day on which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service was posted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14. Proof of service* 14. (1) A person who serves a document may prove the service: - (a) by evidence given orally before the Court; or - by statutory declaration as to service made in accordance with the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html). (2) A statutory declaration as to service must be in the [Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), [41.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1ce8e29-61fe-41d6-b1e4-0be6fe055224/Declaration as to service by ordinary post No. 41.02.docx/docx/1) or [41.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d590fd61-c2f8-49d3-9efa-e869eb833fc7/Statutory declaration as to personal service No. 41.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be. (3) When service of a document on a person has been effected by registered prepaid post, a statutory declaration of service, which must be in the [Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made not earlier than ten days after the day on which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service was posted. (4) A statutory declaration of service by registered post must: - (a) be made by the person who posted the envelope; and - exhibit the certificate of posting; and - state, where appropriate, that the original document was duly stamped at the time of posting, and - state that the envelope has not been returned undelivered to the sender.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is it mandatory for the person who served the document to appear in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"it is not necessary for the person who effected service to attend in person at the Court to prove service on oral evidence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15. Person proving service by statutory declaration need not attend Court* 15. Where a statutory declaration is made, and filed with the Clerk under rule 19: - (a) the statutory declaration is prima facie evidence of the mode, time and place of service as set out in the statutory declaration; and - it is not necessary for the person who effected service to attend in person at the Court to prove service on oral evidence, but the Court may, if it considers it necessary, require the person who effected service to attend before it and give evidence concerning the service notwithstanding the making of a statutory declaration.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is the service of a document considered complete when the envelope is delivered according to normal postal procedures?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the document must be deemed to be served on the person to whom it was directed at the time at which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service would be delivered in the ordinary course of post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16. Deemed time of service* 16. Where service of a document is effected by registered prepaid post or by ordinary prepaid post, the document must be deemed to be served on the person to whom it was directed at the time at which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service would be delivered in the ordinary course of post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is service of a document that requires stamping valid if the document is not stamped at the time of service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"service of the document has no effect or validity unless, at the time of service, the original document was so stamped"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17. Service invalid unless document stamped, where required* 17. Where a document is required by law to be stamped (or payment of a Court fee on the document otherwise recorded), service of the document has no effect or validity unless, at the time of service, the original document was so stamped (or payment of the appropriate Court fee on the document otherwise recorded).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a minimum time requirement for serving documents before a hearing in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a document which must be served before a hearing in the Court must be served at least seven days or, in the case of service by registered prepaid post, at least 21 days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18. Time for service before hearing* 18. Save where otherwise provided by another enactment or by these Rules, a document which must be served before a hearing in the Court must be served at least seven days or, in the case of service by registered prepaid post, at least 21 days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for filing documents before a hearing in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a document which must be filed with the Clerk before a hearing in the Court, including any statutory declaration of service, must be filed at least four days or, in the case of filing by prepaid post, at least seven days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *19. Time for filing before hearing* 19. Subject to any order or direction of the Court, a document which must be filed with the Clerk before a hearing in the Court, including any statutory declaration of service, must be filed at least four days or, in the case of filing by prepaid post, at least seven days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is the delivery of a notice under sections 8 or 17 of the Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004 required to follow a specific method?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The delivery or service of any notice for the purposes of section 8 or section 17 of the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004] must be in the manner prescribed in section 4 of that Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *20. Service under Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004* 20. The delivery or service of any notice for the purposes of section 8 or section 17 of the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) must be in the manner prescribed in section 4 of that Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor act as a permitted user to deliver applications electronically?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a solicitor acting for such party or person) may be designated as a permitted user and when so designated is thereby permitted: to deliver to or file or lodge with the Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system any application which may be made to the Court and any document which may be delivered, filed or lodged in any such application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *21. Electronic service in licensing matters**[4]* 21. (1) This rule applies to licensing matters within the original jurisdiction of the Court. (2) In this rule: “e**lectronic system**” means an electronic system for the time being made available by the Courts Service which enables permitted users, officers of the Court and members of the staff of the Courts Service to transmit and receive documents and information concerning applications before the Court; “**p****ermitted user**” means a person who is for the time being permitted to use the electronic system; “**terms and conditions of use of the electronic system**” means any terms and conditions of use of the electronic system for the time being published, on a website maintained by it or otherwise, by the Courts Service or notified by the Courts Service to permitted users. (3) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, and subject to compliance by the permitted user with the terms and conditions of use of the electronic system, a party to or person interested in any licensing matter before the Court or intended to be brought before the Court (or a solicitor acting for such party or person) may be designated as a permitted user and when so designated is thereby permitted: - to deliver to or file or lodge with the Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system any application which may be made to the Court and any document which may be delivered, filed or lodged in any such application, - to serve by electronic means through the electronic system any document or notice concerning such application upon any person required by statute or these Rules to be served with, or put on notice of, any such application, document or notice, provided that: - (a) such service may be effected by the Clerk (or by a member of the staff of the Courts Service acting with the authority of the Clerk) on behalf of the person serving such document or notice, and - such service is deemed not to be effective unless the person to be served is a permitted user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents transmitted electronically through the system be authenticated without a physical signature?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A document transmitted by electronic means through the electronic system may be authenticated, and the identity of the person in whose name it has issued may be verified, by being—transmitted from an information system or e-mail address of a permitted user, accepted for the purpose of this rule by the Courts Service, or transmitted to or created within the electronic system by or on behalf of the Clerk or by a permitted user, without the need for the incorporation in the document of a manuscript signature of the person in whose name it has issued."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Any other document or information concerning such application may be transmitted to a permitted user by or on behalf of the Court or Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system. (5) A document transmitted by electronic means through the electronic system may be authenticated, and the identity of the person in whose name it has issued may be verified, by being— - (a) transmitted from an information system or e-mail address of a permitted user, accepted for the purpose of this rule by the Courts Service, or - transmitted to or created within the electronic system by or on behalf of the Clerk or by a permitted user, without the need for the incorporation in the document of a manuscript signature of the person in whose name it has issued. (6) If a permitted user is not complying with the terms and conditions (or any of them), permission to use the electronic system may be withdrawn in respect of that user. (7) An originating notice of application submitted for issue by electronic means in accordance with this rule is deemed to be issued when it has been assigned a record number and/or a return date. (8) Where an originating notice of application or a notice of motion is issued in accordance with the preceding provisions of this rule, - (a) a print or copy of the originating notice of application or notice of motion as transmitted for issue shall, when issued, be treated as the original of that document, and - the Clerk may certify any printed version of such document as a certified copy of the original. [1] Order 41 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 41 Rule 4A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025 [3] Order 41 rule 9 substituted by [S.I. 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [4] Order 41, rule 21 inserted by [S.I. 498 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/498/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing service of documents outside the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court - Court: District # **Order 41A: Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Central Authority defined as the Master of the High Court in relation to the State?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"when used in relation to the State, means the Master of the High Court;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order - “**Central Authority**”: - (a) when used in relation to the State, means the Master of the High Court; and - when used in relation to another State which is a party to the Hague Convention means the authority or authorities designated by that State under Article 2 of the Hague Convention to receive requests for the service of documents; “**document**” includes an extrajudicial document; the “**Hague Convention**” means the [Hague Convention of 15 November 1965](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 17) on the Service Abroad of Judicial and Extrajudicial Documents in Civil or Commercial Matters; “**Receiving Agency**”, for the purposes of the Service Regulation: - (a) when used in relation to the State means any County Registrar; and - when used in relation to another State in which the Service Regulation applies, means the authority or authorities designated by that State under Article 2 of the Service Regulation to receive requests for the service of documents; “**Service Regulation**” means [Regulation No. 1393/2007](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 13 November 2007 on the service in the Member States of judicial and extra-judicial documents in civil or commercial matters (service of documents) and repealing [Council Regulation No. 1348/2000](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2000/1348/oj/eng) (O.J. 324/79); “**Transmitting Agency**”, for the purposes of the Service Regulation: - (a) when used in relation to the State means any County Registrar; and - when used in relation to another State in which the Service Regulation applies, means the public officers, authorities or other persons designated by the relevant State under Article 2 of the Service Regulation to transmit requests for the service of documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is service outside the State allowed in proceedings for ejectment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in proceedings for ejectment where the premises sought to be recovered are within the State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Cases in which service outside the State may be allowed* 2. Service outside the State of a claim notice or other originating document (or of notice of an originating document), may be allowed by the Court in the following cases- - (a) in proceedings for ejectment where the premises sought to be recovered are within the State; - in proceedings in contract, where the contract is - made in the State, or - made by or through an agent trading or residing in the State on behalf of a principal trading or residing out of the State, or - (iii) by its terms or implications to be governed by Irish law; - in proceedings for a breach committed in the State of a contract wherever made (even if such breach was preceded or accompanied by a breach outside of the State which rendered impossible the performance of the part of the contract which ought to have been performed in the State); - in proceedings in tort, where the tort was committed in the State; where any relief is sought against a person domiciled or ordinarily resident in the State; - where any person outside the State is a necessary or proper party to an action properly brought against another person duly served in the State; in proceedings relating to a child or a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) who is domiciled in or a citizen of the State; - where necessary, in proceedings brought under section 38(3) of the [Criminal Justice Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/15) (and in accordance with [Order 38]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-38-District-Miscellaneous-Matters), rule 6) for an order authorising the further detention of cash seized.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for serving documents outside the State required to be supported by an affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for permission to serve a claim notice or other originating document, (or notice thereof), on a person outside the State must be made parte and must be supported by an affidavit, or other evidence, which shows:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 How an application for permission to serve outside the State is made* 3. (1) An application for permission to serve a claim notice or other originating document, (or notice thereof), on a person outside the State must be made parte and must be supported by an affidavit, or other evidence, which shows: - (a) that in the belief of the deponent, the claimant has a good cause of action; and - where the respondent is or probably may be found; and - whether the respondent (or, as the case may be, the relevant respondent) is or is not a citizen of Ireland; and - the grounds on which the application is made. (2) Permission must not be granted unless it sufficiently appears to the Court that the case is a proper one for service out of the State under this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a copy of the order granting permission always served with the claim notice or other originating document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"a copy of the order granting permission must also be served on the respondent with the documents required by sub-rules (1) and (2)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Documents to be served on the respondent (or relevant respondent)* 4. When an order is made granting permission to serve outside the State under the provisions of this Order, (1) if the respondent to be served is a citizen of Ireland, the claim notice or other originating document must be served on that respondent, together with any other document required in any particular case to be served; (2) if the respondent to be served is not, or is not known or believed to be, a citizen of Ireland, notice of the claim notice or other originating document (instead of the document itself) must be served on that respondent, together with any other document required in any particular case to be served; (3) a copy of the order granting permission must also be served on the respondent with the documents required by sub-rules (1) and (2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is service by registered post considered effective once the envelope is delivered according to the usual postal schedule?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service under this rule by registered post must be taken to have been effected on the day on which the envelope containing the documents would be delivered in the ordinary course of post or on such other day as may be proved."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Mode of service on the respondent (or relevant respondent)* 5. (1) When permission is granted to serve outside the State under this Order, service must be by registered post or by insured post, as appropriate, or by such other method as the Court directs. (2) When service under this rule is by registered post, application for an advice of delivery must be made to the postal authorities at the time of posting. Proof of service by post must be by the production of a statutory declaration of service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned). These documents must be lodged with the Clerk with the originals of the documents of which copies were posted. (3) Service under this rule by registered post must be taken to have been effected on the day on which the envelope containing the documents would be delivered in the ordinary course of post or on such other day as may be proved.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is diplomatic or consular service allowed if the member state has not communicated opposition?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service by diplomatic or consular agents, in accordance with Article 13 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated, in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation, that it is opposed to the service of documents in its territory by diplomatic or consular agents)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Where the Service Regulation applies (service in the European Union outside the State)* 6.[3] Where the person to be served is in another State in which the Service Regulation applies, service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation which, in addition to lodgment for service with the Transmitting Agency in accordance with rule 11(2), may include: - (a) service by diplomatic or consular agents, in accordance with Article 13 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated, in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation, that it is opposed to the service of documents in its territory by diplomatic or consular agents), or - direct service, in accordance with Article 15 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation that it is opposed to direct service of documents in its territory).”.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can service be done by post according to the Hague Convention if the destination state has not objected?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service by post under rule 5 provided the destination State has not objected to postal service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Where the Hague Convention applies (outside the European Union)* 7. Where the person to be served is in another State which is a party to the Hague Convention (and in which the Service Regulation does not apply), service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention, which may include service by post under rule 5 provided the destination State has not objected to postal service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a counterclaim or third party notice be served out of the state without permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A counterclaim or third party notice may be served out of the State without permission where the claim made by the respondent in the counterclaim or third party notice is of such a kind that, if the claim were made by claim notice, the claim notice could be served out of the State without permission of the Court under Order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Service of counterclaim or third party notice* 9. (1) This rule applies to - - (a) a counterclaim against the claimant and another person joined as respondent in accordance with [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties) if the person joined is not already a party to the proceeding; and - a third party notice filed in accordance with [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure). (2) A counterclaim or third party notice may be served out of the State without permission where the claim made by the respondent in the counterclaim or third party notice is of such a kind that, if the claim were made by claim notice, the claim notice could be served out of the State without permission of the Court under [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific procedure mentioned for serving documents on persons in states that are parties to the Hague Convention?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a document for use in civil or commercial proceedings in the Court is to be served on a person in another State in which the Service Regulation does not apply but which is a party to the Hague Convention, that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Procedure* 10. (1) Where a document for use in civil or commercial proceedings in the Court is to be served on a person in another State in which the Service Regulation applies, that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation. (2) Where a document for use in civil or commercial proceedings in the Court is to be served on a person in another State in which the Service Regulation does not apply but which is a party to the Hague Convention, that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk make a request for service of documents outside the State in civil proceedings in the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Lodgment of documents for service* 11.(1) A request for service of documents outside the State in civil proceedings in the District Court may be made by: - (a) a party; - a solicitor acting for a party; or - a Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a translation of each document required when requesting service of a document abroad?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service Regulation* (2) A person requesting service of a document abroad under the Service Regulation must lodge with the Transmitting Agency as appropriate: - a request for service of the document in the form specified in the Annex to the Service Regulation, and a copy thereof; - two copies of the document to be served, and an additional copy for each person to be served; - (iii) a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept, unless that document is already in one of those languages; - an undertaking to pay the costs of service, payment or reimbursement of which these may be sought by the Receiving Agency of the State addressed; and the relevant provisions of [Order 11D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-11D-Superior-Service-of-Documents-Outside-of-the-Jurisdiction-but-within-the-EU-Regulation-No-1393-2007) of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a translation of the documents required when serving them abroad under the Hague Convention?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Hague Convention* (3) A person requesting service of a document abroad under the Hague Convention must lodge with the Central Authority (Master of the High Court): - a request for the service of the document in the form specified in the Annex to the Hague Convention, and a copy thereof; - two copies of the document to be served, and an additional copy for each person to be served; - (iii) a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept, unless that document is already in one of those languages; - an undertaking to pay the costs of service, payment or reimbursement of which these may be sought by the Central Authority of the State addressed; and the relevant provisions of [Order 11E]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-11E-Superior-Service-of-Documents-Outside-of-the-Jurisdiction-(Hague-Convention)) of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate of service considered as prima facie evidence of the facts stated in it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A certificate of service completed and forwarded under: ... must be taken to be prima facie evidence of the facts stated in that certificate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Certificate of service* 12. (1) A certificate of service completed and forwarded under: - (a) Article 10 of the Service Regulation by the Receiving Agency; or - Article 6 of the Hague Convention by the Central Authority addressed or any authority which it may have designated for that purpose must be taken to be prima facie evidence of the facts stated in that certificate. (2) A document purporting to be such a certificate must, until the contrary is proved, be deemed to be such a certificate. (3) On receipt of a certificate mentioned in sub-rule (1), the claimant (or the claimant’s solicitor) must lodge the certificate with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment be given if the respondent has not appeared or defended the claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"judgment must not be given until it is established that: ... the document or notice was actually delivered to the respondent or to the respondent’s residence by another method provided for by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Procedure on non-appearance of the respondent* 13. (1) Where a claim notice or other document instituting proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and the respondent has not filed and served an appearance and defence or otherwise given notice of intention to defend the claim, judgment must not be given until it is established that: - (a) the originating document or notice was served by a method prescribed by the internal law of the State addressed for service of documents in domestic civil proceedings on persons within its territory, or - the document or notice was actually delivered to the respondent or to the respondent’s residence by another method provided for by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, and, in either of these cases, the service or the delivery was in sufficient time to enable the respondent to defend. (2) An application for judgment in default of appearance and defence in a case mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be made by filing an affidavit with the Clerk, but the Clerk may in any such case list the application before the Court for hearing and notify the claimant of the return date of the application. (3) At the hearing of any application in the proceedings the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court issue a judgment without receiving a certificate of service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention has been received"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Judgment may be given despite absence of certificate of service* 14. Despite rule 10, the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention has been received, if all of the following conditions are fulfilled- - (a) the document or notice thereof was transmitted by a method provided for in the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, - a period of not less than six months, considered adequate by the Court in the particular case, has elapsed since the transmission of the document or notice, - no certificate of any kind has been received, even though every reasonable effort has been made to obtain it through the competent authorities of the State addressed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent apply to extend the time for appealing a judgment if they did not appear?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a claim notice or other document instituting civil proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and judgment has been given against a respondent who has not appeared, the respondent may apply to extend the time for appealing from the judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Time for appeal may be extended* 15. (1) Where a claim notice or other document instituting civil proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and judgment has been given against a respondent who has not appeared, the respondent may apply to extend the time for appealing from the judgment. (2) An application by a respondent under sub-rule (1) must be made by motion on notice and must be grounded on the affidavit of the moving party. (3) On hearing the application, if the Court is satisfied that- - (a) the application was made within a reasonable time after the respondent had knowledge of the judgment and - without any fault on his or her part, the respondent did not have knowledge of the documents in sufficient time to defend or, as the case may be, knowledge of the judgment in sufficient time to appeal, and - the respondent has a prima facie defence to the claim on the merits, the Court may extend the time for appealing from the judgment on such terms and conditions as the Court considers just. [1] Order 41A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 41A, rule substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [3] Order 41A rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 471 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/471/made/en/print?q 471&years 2018), effective 10 December 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order related to serving documents outside the state without court permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court - Court: District # **Order Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court******[1]** **[2]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the topic about serving documents in a different state without court approval?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"SERVICE OF DOCUMENTS OUTSIDE THE STATE WITHOUT THE PERMISSION OF THE COURT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **SERVICE OF DOCUMENTS OUTSIDE THE STATE WITHOUT THE PERMISSION OF THE COURT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document focused on judgments given in other countries?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT IN THE STATE OF CERTAIN JUDGMENTS GIVEN IN OTHER MEMBER STATES AND CERTAIN OTHER STATES"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT IN THE STATE OF CERTAIN JUDGMENTS GIVEN IN OTHER MEMBER STATES AND CERTAIN OTHER STATES**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is Regulation No 1215/2012 about jurisdiction and the recognition and enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"ON JURISDICTION AND THE RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[REGULATION NO 1215/2012](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2012/1215/oj/eng) ON JURISDICTION AND THE RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS (RECAST) (the “Jurisdiction Regulation”)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Is service on a relevant person under the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 required to follow Order 7, rule 8?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) must be in accordance with [Order 7]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9. Service on a relevant person* 9[3].(1) Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) must be in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8. (2) Where the person to be served is a ward of court, a document is effectively served if served: - (a) on the person’s solicitor; or - on the committee of the ward of court, unless the Court otherwise decides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Brussels Convention related to civil and commercial matters?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"JURISDICTION AND THE ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE BRUSSELS CONVENTION OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES ON JURISDICTION AND THE ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS, 1968](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri CELEX:41968A0927(01)) (the “Brussels Convention”)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Lugano Convention related to civil and commercial matters between member states?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"JURISDICTION AND THE ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS BETWEEN MEMBER STATES OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES AND THE EUROPEAN FREE TRADE ASSOCIATION"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE LUGANO CONVENTION ON JURISDICTION AND THE ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS BETWEEN MEMBER STATES OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES AND THE EUROPEAN FREE TRADE ASSOCIATION, 2007](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/convention/2007/712/oj/eng) (the “Lugano Convention”)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the regulation related to maintenance obligations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"MAINTENANCE OBLIGATIONS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[REGULATION 4/2009](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng) OF 18 DECEMBER 2008 ON JURISDICTION, APPLICABLE LAW, RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF DECISIONS AND COOPERATION IN MATTERS RELATING TO MAINTENANCE OBLIGATIONS (the “Maintenance Regulation”)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Rome Convention related to simplifying procedures for recovering maintenance payments between European Community member states?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"on the simplification of procedures for the recovery of maintenance payments"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **THE ROME CONVENTION BETWEEN THE MEMBER STATES OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES ON THE SIMPLIFICATION OF PROCEDURES FOR THE RECOVERY OF MAINTENANCE PAYMENTS (the “Rome Convention”) AND T[HE MAINTENANCE ACT 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the New York Convention related to the recovery of maintenance abroad?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the New York Convention on the Recovery Abroad of Maintenance"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE NEW YORK CONVENTION ON THE RECOVERY ABROAD OF MAINTENANCE](https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetailsIII.aspx?src TREATY&mtdsg_no XX-1&chapter 20&Temp mtdsg3&clang (the “New York Convention”) AND THE [MAINTENANCE ACT 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Hague Child Convention focused on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition, enforcement and cooperation in respect of parental responsibility and measures for the protection of children?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “Hague Child Convention”"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE HAGUE CONVENTION ON JURISDICTION, APPLICABLE LAW, RECOGNITION, ENFORCEMENT AND CO-OPERATION IN RESPECT OF PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY AND MEASURES FOR THE PROTECTION OF CHILDREN 1996](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 70) (the “Hague Child Convention”)** # **1 - DEFINITIONS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claimant defined as someone who resides in a Member State and claims entitlement to maintenance from a person in another state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a person residing in a Member State (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) the central authority of such a jurisdiction which has been designated pursuant to paragraph 1 or, where appropriate, paragraph 2 of Article 2 of the Rome Convention, or - an authority of such a jurisdiction with functions corresponding to those exercisable by the Central Authority within the State; “**central authority of a designated jurisdiction**” means:- - (a) a transmitting or receiving agency in a state which is a contracting party to the New York Convention, or - an authority of a designated jurisdiction with functions corresponding to those exercisable by the Central Authority within the State; “**claimant**” means, according to the context, either:- - (a) a person residing in a Member State (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in a designated jurisdiction (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a Member State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the [Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a designated jurisdiction; “**Contracting State**”, - (a) when used in the context of proceedings under the Brussels Convention, has the meaning assigned to it in section 4(1) of the 1998 Act,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a Member State in the context of maintenance proceedings limited to states within the European Union where the Maintenance Regulation applies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**Member State**”, when used in relation to maintenance proceedings, means a member state of the European Union in which the relevant provision of the Maintenance Regulation applies;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- when used in the context of proceedings under the Lugano Convention, means a State in respect of which that Convention has entered into force or taken effect in accordance with Article 69 or 72 thereof; “**designated jurisdiction**” means:- - (a) any state which is a contracting party to the New York Convention, or - any other state or jurisdiction which is declared by order of the Minister for Foreign Affairs to be a designated jurisdiction for the purposes of Part III of the 1994 Act; “**domiciled**” and “**habitually resident**”, when used in relation to maintenance proceedings, must be construed in accordance with the Maintenance Regulation; [5] “**the terms “2007 Hague Protocol**” and “**enforcement order**”, have the meanings assigned to them respectively in Regulation 2 of the 2011 Regulations; “the terms “**decision**”, “**enforceable maintenance order**” and “**maintenance debtor**” each have the meaning assigned to them respectively in Regulation 2 of the 2011 Regulations or, as the context requires, Regulation 2 of the 2019 Regulations; “**Hague Maintenance Convention**” means the Convention on the International Recovery of Child Support and Other Forms of Family Maintenance done at The Hague on 23 November 2007; “**maintenance creditor**” includes any body which, under the law of a reciprocating jurisdiction, is entitled to exercise their rights of redress of, or to represent, the creditor, and references in these Rules to a maintenance creditor or to a claimant (as defined herein) must be construed as including references to the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention; the “**Maintenance Regulation**” means Council Regulation 4/2009 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1); “**Member State**”, when used in relation to maintenance proceedings, means a member state of the European Union in which the relevant provision of the Maintenance Regulation applies;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings be brought against an insurer domiciled in another country if the policy-holder is domiciled in the same country as the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"against an insurer domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State and the policy-holder is domiciled in the State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Venue in cross-border insurance matters* 2.[6] When it is proposed to bring proceedings before the District Court by virtue of: - (a) Article 11 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, or - Article 9 of the Lugano Convention, or - Article 8.2 of the Brussels Convention, (all of which relate to insurance matters) against an insurer domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State and the policy-holder is domiciled in the State, the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a consumer bring proceedings against another party domiciled in a different country under certain regulations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the consumer is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Venue in cross-border consumer contract claims* 3.[7] When a consumer who is domiciled in the State proposes to bring proceedings before the District Court by virtue of: - (a) Article 18 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, or - Article 16 of the Lugano Convention, or - Article 14 of the Brussels Convention (all of which relate to consumer contracts) against the other party to a contract and that other party is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the consumer is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is permission from the court required before serving proceedings against a person domiciled in another member state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"service of proceedings begun in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 of this Order and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention) without prior permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Beginning proceedings against a person domiciled abroad* 5. (1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), service of proceedings begun in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 of this Order and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention) without prior permission of the Court. (2) When proceedings are instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or the Lugano Convention against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State and that person is not or is not known or believed to be a citizen of Ireland, notice of the document commencing the proceedings in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and not the document itself must be served on that person. (3) A claimant or claimant’s solicitor may begin such proceedings by completing, signing, stamping (if so required) the claim notice or other document beginning the proceedings and filing it, together with duly completed originals and copies of the notice ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and of a certificate in the [Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the Clerk for the Court area for which the proceedings are to be issued. (4) The Clerk must stamp them with the official stamp showing the date of issue and return the documents to the claimant or claimant’s solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for the time allowed for filing and entering an appearance and defense when serving documents in a non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State, the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least six weeks from the date of service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) A notice and certificate returned under sub-rule (3) must be served on the respondent as indicated in rule 4 (which may include service by post provided that if such service is into a Contracting State in which the Hague Convention applies, the State of destination has not made an objection to such service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention) or, where appropriate, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court). (6) Where the documents are to be served in the European territory of another Member State or Contracting State the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least five weeks from the date of service. Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State, the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least six weeks from the date of service. (7) On receipt of the certificate of service prescribed in Article 10 and the Annex of the Service Regulation or Article 6 of the Hague Convention, the claimant (or solicitor for the claimant) must lodge with the Clerk the originals of: - the claim notice, civil summons or other document instituting the proceedings, - (where appropriate) the notice of commencement of proceedings ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1)) which was served, - the certificate ([Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1)) which was served, and - the certificate of service, at least four days before the date on which the proceedings are first listed before the Court. (8) Where service has been effected by registered post or insured post the following provisions must apply- - (a) the claimant or claimant’s solicitor must, not earlier than ten days after the date of posting, lodge with the Clerk the relevant documents listed in sub-rule (7), together with a statutory declaration as to service of the documents posted, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned);'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time mentioned when documents are considered served if sent by regular mail?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the documents issued for service must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, Article 15 of the Hague Convention, be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post; - the statutory declaration as to service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the said Article 15 of the Hague Convention, together be deemed to be sufficient evidence of service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claim notice be served directly to an Irish citizen domiciled in another member state when proceedings begin under certain regulations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claim notice or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice of the document)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Where the respondent is a citizen of Ireland* 6. (1) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or the Lugano Convention against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, and that person is a citizen of Ireland, the claim notice or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice of the document). (2) Subject to sub-rule (1), the requirements of rule 5 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a respondent to file an appearance if they intend to defend the proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, in proceedings to which rule 5 or rule 6 relates, a respondent intends to appear or to be represented at the hearing for the purpose of: defending the proceedings and/or, by virtue of Article 26 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 24 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 18 of the Brussels Convention for the purpose of contesting the jurisdiction of the Court, the respondent or respondent’s solicitor must file:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Appearance and defence* 7.[8] Where, in proceedings to which rule 5 or rule 6 relates, a respondent intends to appear or to be represented at the hearing for the purpose of: - (a) defending the proceedings and/or, - by virtue of Article 26 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 24 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 18 of the Brussels Convention for the purpose of contesting the jurisdiction of the Court, the respondent or respondent’s solicitor must file: - in proceedings begun by claim notice, an appearance; or - in proceedings begun by civil summons or other document, a notice of appearance and intention to defend so soon as to reach the Clerk within the period of five weeks or, as the case may be, six weeks, prescribed by rule 5(6) and within the same period serve a copy on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor (together with a defence, where required). Where the respondent contests the jurisdiction of the Court, the appearance must include a statement to that effect.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must the Clerk present all communications received from the respondent at the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Hearing of proceedings* 8. (1) The provisions of [Order 47A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47A-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Non-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default in Non-Debt Claims) apply to proceedings to which this Part relates with the modifications identified in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims). (2) At the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 5 or 6, the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court give judgment by default if the respondent has not filed an appearance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the respondent has not filed an appearance, the claimant must, if applying for judgment by default, show to the satisfaction of the Court..."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Where the respondent does not appear (3) Where the respondent fails to appear and is not represented at the hearing, the Court may, if it considers it necessary to do so, require the production of the advice of delivery form confirming delivery to the respondent or to the respondent’s address of the envelope containing the copy documents for service referred to in rule 5(5). (4) Where the respondent has not filed an appearance, the claimant must, if applying for judgment by default, show to the satisfaction of the Court- - (a) that each claim made in the document instituting the proceedings is one which, by virtue of the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine, - that no other Court has exclusive jurisdiction within the meaning of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention to hear and determine any such claim, - that no proceedings involving the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State or, as the case may be, in another Contracting State, - that the respondent was duly served with the document beginning the proceedings or notice of that document, and - [9] that the respondent has been able to receive the document beginning the proceedings or notice in sufficient time to enable him or her to arrange for his or her defence, or all necessary steps have been taken to this end, as required by Article 28 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 26 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 20 of the Brussels Convention (5) Where the respondent has filed an appearance or otherwise given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment must not be given until the requirements of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, Article 15 of the Hague Convention (as set out in [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 10) have been complied with.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court allowed to give judgment without receiving a certificate of service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided for by the Service Regulation or by the Hague Convention has been received"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Notwithstanding sub-rule (5), the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided for by the Service Regulation or by the Hague Convention has been received, if all the conditions listed in Article 19 of the Service Regulation or Article 15 of the Hague Convention (as set out in [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 14) are fulfilled. (7) Where the Court gives judgment against a respondent in proceedings to which this rule relates, the claimant, (or claimant’s solicitor) must immediately notify the respondent of having obtained the judgment. (8) Where judgment has been given in such proceedings against a respondent who has not appeared and the respondent wishes to apply for an extension of time for appeal from the judgment, the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 15 apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate in Form required when requesting the provision of documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a certificate in duplicate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Enforcement of judgments abroad: provision of documents* 9.[10] (1) An interested party who, for the purposes of Articles 53 and 54 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 46 and 47 of the Brussels Convention, requests the provision of the documents mentioned in section 14 of the 1998 Act in respect of a judgment given in the District Court, must lodge with the Clerk for the Court area in which the judgment was given - - (a) an original and two copies of the judgment duly completed, - a certificate in duplicate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and - where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent. (2) When the judgment has been signed by the Judge and served in accordance with the provisions of rule 10, the Clerk must give to the party requesting them a duly authenticated copy of the judgment, a certificate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a certified true copy or copies of the document or documents referred to in sub-rule and must retain the other documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the claimant to serve a judgment on a respondent according to specific regulations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, for the purposes of Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 53 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 47 of the Brussels Convention, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a judgment given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Service of judgment and proof of service* 10.[11] (1) Where, for the purposes of Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 53 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 47 of the Brussels Convention, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a judgment given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part. (2) When service has been effected and duly certified, the certificate of service or, where appropriate, the certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service and the advice of delivery form, must be lodged with the Clerk for retention with the original judgment. (3) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the documents referred to in Article 47.1 of the Brussels Convention, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the [Form 41B.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e30f0b06-b26a-4e7b-b6f1-2ea34fd31f4b/Certificate that a judgment is enforceable No. 41B.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule (with any necessary modifications) and a certified copy or copies of the relevant document or documents lodged under sub-rule (2). (4) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the certificate referred to in Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the form in Annex to the Jurisdiction Regulation; (5) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the certificate referred to in Article 54 of the Lugano Convention, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the form in Annex to the Lugano Convention 339/3 of 21 December 2007). # **3 - CROSS-BORDER MAINTENANCE PROCEEDINGS IN THE STATE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section specifically titled ''Maintenance Regulation''?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Maintenance Regulation*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Maintenance Regulation*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Hague Convention applicable when serving documents in states where the Service Regulation does not apply?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another State which is a state in which the Service Regulation does not apply but in which the Hague Convention applies, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 8 to 11) of the Hague Convention and this Part."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Application of the Hague Convention or Service Regulation* 12. (1) The provisions of the Service Regulation or of the Hague Convention apply, where relevant, to proceedings brought in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation. (2) When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another Member State, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 7 to 10) of the Service Regulation and this Part. (3) When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another State which is a state in which the Service Regulation does not apply but in which the Hague Convention applies, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 8 to 11) of the Hague Convention and this Part.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings against a person domiciled abroad be initiated in the District Court without prior court permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service of proceedings which may be instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention), without prior permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Beginning proceedings against a person domiciled abroad* 13. (1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), service of proceedings which may be instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention), without prior permission of the Court. (2) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, and that person is not or is not known or believed to be a citizen of Ireland, notice of the document beginning the proceedings (in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule and not the document itself must be served on that person. (3) A claimant or claimant’s solicitor may begin proceedings mentioned in sub-rule (2) by completing, signing, stamping (if so required) the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings and filing it, together with duly completed originals and copies of the notice ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule and of a certificate in the [Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the Clerk for the Court area for which the proceedings are to be issued. (4) The Clerk must stamp the documents showing the date of filing and must, having regard to the provisions of sub-rule (6), list the proceedings for hearing before the Court. (5) Having recorded the place, date and time of hearing on the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings and the notices, the Clerk must return all documents to the claimant or claimant’s solicitor. (6) A notice and certificate returned under sub-rule (5) must be served as indicated in rule 12 or, where appropriate, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), on the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a difference in the required time for serving documents in European versus non-European territories of another member state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the documents are to be served in the European territory of another Member State they must be served at least five weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing. Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State, they must be served at least six weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(7) Where the documents are to be served in the European territory of another Member State they must be served at least five weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing. (8) Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State, they must be served at least six weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing. (9) On receipt of the certificate of service prescribed in Article 10 and the Annex of the Service Regulation, the claimant (or claimant’s solicitor) must lodge with the Clerk the originals of: - the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, - (where appropriate) the notice that proceedings have been begun ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule which was served, - the certificate ([Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule which was served, and - the certificate of service, at least four days before the date of the sitting of the Court. (10) Where service has been effected by registered post or insured post the following provisions apply- - (a) the claimant or claimant''s solicitor must, not earlier than ten days after the date of posting, lodge with the Clerk the relevant documents listed in sub-rule (9), together with a statutory declaration as to service of the documents posted, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned); - the documents issued for service must be deemed to have been issued at the time at which the envelope containing the copies for service was posted; - the documents must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation, be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post; - the statutory declaration as to service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation together be deemed to be sufficient evidence of service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a maintenance summons be served directly to an Irish citizen who is not domiciled or habitually resident in the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice thereof)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Where the respondent is a citizen of Ireland* 14. (1) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, and that person is a citizen of Ireland, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice thereof). (2) Subject to sub-rule (1), the requirements of rule 13 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly. Two notices of appearance and intention to defend must be served in each case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific deadline mentioned for sending the notice of appearance and intention to defend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Notice of appearance and intention to defend* 15. Where, in proceedings to which rule 13 or rule 14 relates, a respondent intends to appear or to be represented at the hearing: - (a) for the purpose of defending the proceedings and/or, - by virtue of Article 5 of the Maintenance Regulation for the purpose of contesting the jurisdiction of the Court, the respondent or his or her solicitor must complete, detach and send by post to the Clerk one of the notices of appearance and intention to defend which were received so soon as to reach the Clerk not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing, and must at the same time complete, detach and send by post to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant the other such Notice received.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Hearing of Proceedings section subject to Order 54 for maintenance cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the provisions of [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) apply to proceedings to which this Part relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Hearing of proceedings* 16. (1) Subject to this rule, the provisions of [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) apply to proceedings to which this Part relates. (2) The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default) and [Order 47A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47A-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Non-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default in Non-Debt Claims) do not apply to proceedings to which this Part relates. (3) At the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 13 or rule 14, the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for a party to provide the Clerk with additional information beyond the original order and relevant documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must provide the Clerk with any additional information required by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Enforcement of judgments abroad: provision of documents* 17. (1) A party who requests the provision of the documents mentioned in Article 20 or, as the case may be, Article 28, of the Maintenance Regulation- - (a) must file with the Clerk for the Court area in which the decision was given an original and two copies of the order recording the decision and, where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent, and - must provide the Clerk with any additional information required by the Clerk. (2) When the order has been signed and served in accordance with the provisions of rule 18, the Clerk must give to the party requesting them a duly authenticated copy of the order recording the decision, the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the Maintenance Regulation and a certified true copy or copies of the other documents referred to in sub-rule 1(a), and must retain the other original documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the claimant or their representative to serve a decision given at a sitting of the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Service of decision and proof of service* 18. (1) Where, for the purposes of enforcing a decision under the Maintenance Regulation, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a decision given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant and in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation (or, where applicable, the Hague Convention) and this Part. (2) When service has been effected and duly certified, the certificate of service or, where appropriate, the certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service and the advice of delivery form, must be filed with the Clerk for retention with the original judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is service of process required before an application under Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation can be made to the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the District Court being brought- ... must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of the appropriate summons or notice of application mentioned in [Order 54]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Application for variation or revocation by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation* 19. (1) An application to the District Court being brought- - (a) by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation, by a maintenance creditor domiciled in the State against a maintenance debtor outside the State, or - by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation, by a maintenance creditor outside the State against a maintenance debtor habitually resident or domiciled in the State must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of the appropriate summons or notice of application mentioned in [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) or, where appropriate, notice thereof in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is outside the State, and the provisions of this Part apply to any such application. (2) An order of the Court granting any such application must be served on a party within the State by registered post and on a party outside the State in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation (or, where applicable, the Hague Convention) and this Part.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Clerk to forward specific documents when a maintenance debtor changes their residence within the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a maintenance debtor ceases to reside in the Court area in which the proceedings have been registered and commences to reside elsewhere in the State, the Clerk for the first Court area must forward to the Clerk for the Court area in which the maintenance debtor is for the time being residing the following documents-"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Transmission of documents on change of address by maintenance debtor* 20. (1) Where a maintenance debtor ceases to reside in the Court area in which the proceedings have been registered and commences to reside elsewhere in the State, the Clerk for the first Court area must forward to the Clerk for the Court area in which the maintenance debtor is for the time being residing the following documents- - (a) a copy of the maintenance order and a copy of the relevant enforcement order or, as the case may be, a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the Maintenance Regulation, of the decision issued by the court of origin, - a certificate of arrears in the [Form 41B.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/795a1a10-42a3-486a-966b-ab7e17fa3a97/Certificate of arrears No. 41B.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule - a copy of the variation order (if any), - any other relevant document. (2) The Clerk receiving the documents must proceed as if the copy of the maintenance order and the copy of the enforcement order had been received from the Master of the High Court. # **4 - ENFORCEMENT OF MAINTENANCE ORDERS UNDER THE MAINTENANCE REGULATION AND THE 2011 REGULATIONS: DECISIONS GIVEN IN A MEMBER STATE BOUND BY THE 2007 HAGUE PROTOCOL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk responsible for registering the details of the decision after receiving the necessary documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"On receipt of the documents, the Clerk must - (a) register particulars of the decision concerned, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Appropriate Clerk to register decisions* 21. (1) Where a maintenance creditor or the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation wishes to seek the enforcement in the State of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation, the party or the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation must send to the Clerk for the appropriate Court area for the district referred to in Regulation 3, 4 or 6 (as the case may be) of the 2011 Regulations (in this Part, the “appropriate Clerk”) the documents referred to in Article 20 of the Maintenance Regulation. (2) Where the Central Authority makes a request under Regulation 17(6) of the 2011 Regulations that payments of maintenance be made directly to the maintenance creditor, the Clerk must enter the matter before the Court. (3) On receipt of the documents, the Clerk must - - (a) register particulars of the decision concerned, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice informing the maintenance debtor about the registration of the decision required to be sent by registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice must be sent by registered prepaid post and a copy must also be sent by registered prepaid post to the person on whose behalf registration was sought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice to maintenance debtor* - by notice in the [Form 41B.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a5caee07-b1a3-4ad1-aca2-9bff1c1e104f/Notice of registration No. 41B.05.docx/docx/1) Schedule inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the decision. (4) The notice must be sent by registered prepaid post and a copy must also be sent by registered prepaid post to the person on whose behalf registration was sought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must the appropriate Clerk register particulars when a decision is varied or revoked by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he or she must register particulars thereof and must by notice inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the variation or revocation order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Appropriate Clerk to register particulars of variation etc.* (5) Where a decision referred to in sub-rule (1) has been varied or revoked by the court which made the decision and the appropriate Clerk has received the documents referred to in Article 20 of the Maintenance Regulation in respect of the variation or revocation, he or she must register particulars thereof and must by notice inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the variation or revocation order. (6) This rule does not limit the ability of a party who has not complied with sub-rule (1) to invoke in the State a decision recognised within the meaning of Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation otherwise than for the purpose of enforcement of the decision.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must the District Court Clerk send a notice to both the maintenance creditor and debtor when registering an enforcement or recognition order related to a maintenance order or its variation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must send by registered post to the maintenance creditor and the maintenance debtor a notice in the [Form or as the case may be, [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Registration of orders [13]* 23.(1) Where a copy of a maintenance order or a copy of an order varying or revoking such an order, in respect of which an enforcement order has been made under the 2011 Regulations or a recognition order has been made under the 2019 Regulations, is received together with a copy of the relevant enforcement order or recognition order by a District Court Clerk from the Master of the High Court or the Central Authority, the Clerk must register particulars of each document received. (2) If the enforcement order or, as the case may be, recognition order, referred to in sub-rule (1) has been made in respect of a maintenance order or an order varying a maintenance order, the Clerk must send by registered post to the maintenance creditor and the maintenance debtor a notice in the [Form 41B.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f2fd74b9-1423-42da-9391-aa5ddad30330/Notice of registration No. 41B.06.docx/docx/1) or as the case may be, [Form 41B.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1a74011e-939f-4a0a-bf4e-157899a22307/Notice of Registration District Court Maintenance Rules 202 of 2021 No 41B.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) If the enforcement order or, as the case may be, recognition order, referred to in sub-rule (1) has been made in respect of an order revoking a maintenance order, the Clerk must send by registered prepaid post to the maintenance debtor a copy of the revocation order and a statement of any amounts still due and payable under the maintenance order, which statement must contain, or be sent together with, an endorsement to the like effect as the endorsement on a notice under sub-rule (2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a District Court Clerk proceed with enforcing unpaid sums without receiving a written request?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"When a District Court Clerk receives a request in writing from a maintenance creditor under Regulation 10(9) of the 2011 Regulations in relation to any sum payable by virtue of an enforceable maintenance order but not duly paid, the Clerk may proceed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 56]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Request from maintenance creditor* 24. (1) When a District Court Clerk receives a request in writing from a maintenance creditor under Regulation 10(9) of the 2011 Regulations in relation to any sum payable by virtue of an enforceable maintenance order but not duly paid, the Clerk may proceed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 56]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-56-District-Attachment-Of-Earnings) (Attachment of Earnings) or rules 3 and 4 (but not rules 7 and 8) of [Order 57]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url proceedings-under--section-8-of-the-enforcement-of-court-orders-act-1940-etc) (Proceedings under section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940). (2) Where it appears to a District Court Clerk that any sums payable to him or her under an enforceable maintenance order for transmission to the maintenance creditor are in arrears and he or she has received no request in writing under the said Regulation 10(9) in relation thereto, the Clerk may in his or her discretion, having considered the extent of the arrears and any other relevant matter, notify the maintenance creditor of the means of enforcement available in respect of the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons in Form required before an application can be made to the District Court under Articles 2 or 5.2 of the Brussels or Lugano Conventions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the District Court being brought- ... must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of a summons in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Application by virtue of Articles 2 and 5.2 of Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention* 25. (1) An application to the District Court being brought- - (a) by virtue of Article 5.2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance creditor domiciled or habitually resident in the State against a maintenance debtor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State for the variation of a maintenance order, - by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance creditor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State against a maintenance debtor domiciled in the State for the variation of a maintenance order, or - by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance debtor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State against a maintenance creditor domiciled in the State for the variation or revocation of a maintenance order, must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of a summons in the [Form 41B.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/27ef99e9-cbbb-48f4-9513-47aea508db73/Summons to vary or revoke a maintenance order No. 41B.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule or, where appropriate, notice of summons in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, and the provisions of this Order apply. (2) The order of the Court granting the application must be served on a party within the State by registered post and on a party domiciled in another Member State or Contracting State in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, the Hague Convention (including Articles 8 to 11 thereof) and this Order. # **6 - RECOVERY OF MAINTENANCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the enforcement order applicable only to the parts of a judgment that relate to maintenance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"these Rules apply only to those parts that relate to maintenance"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Enforcement Order* 26. If a judgment or an instrument or settlement referred to in Articles 50 or 51 of the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 57 or 58 of the Lugano Convention does not relate solely to maintenance, these Rules apply only to those parts that relate to maintenance, and on receipt of an enforcement order made by the High Court, in relation thereto, the Clerk must proceed as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Master of the High Court responsible for making an enforcement order in certain circumstances?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Master, having made an enforcement order in respect of the maintenance order, sends those orders to the appropriate District Court Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Enforcement Order* 28. Where: - (a) the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request from a central authority of a designated jurisdiction on behalf of a claimant for the recovery of maintenance from a person for the time being residing in the State (the “respondent”), and - the request is accompanied by an order of a Court in a Contracting State (within the meaning of the 1998 Act), and - the Central Authority under the 1994 Act transmits the request pursuant to section 14(1)(a) of the 1994 Act to the Master of the High Court for determination in accordance with section 7 of the 1998 Act, and - the Master, having made an enforcement order in respect of the maintenance order, sends those orders to the appropriate District Court Clerk, the Clerk must proceed as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form required before applying for enforcement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application mentioned in sub-rule (1) must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Application for enforcement under section 14 of the 1994 Act* 29. (1) Where the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request referred to in rule 28 and the request is accompanied by an order made by any other Court and the Central Authority under the 1994 Act is of opinion that the order may be enforceable in the State, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act may apply pursuant to section of the 1994 Act at any sitting of the District Court for the relevant Court district (as set out in section 14(11) of the 1994 Act) for the enforcement of the order. (2) An application mentioned in sub-rule (1) must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form 41B.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1decda26-498d-444e-a953-675ca98283b9/Notice of application for enforcement No. 41B.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the respondent. The notice must be accompanied by a copy of the documents mentioned in section 14(6) of the 1994 Act. Service must be effected by registered post at least 21 days prior to the return date. (3) When service has been effected, the applicant must lodge with the Clerk the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, at least four days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it the responsibility of the Clerk to send copies of the enforcement order to the Central Authority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"copies of the order of the Court must be sent by the Clerk to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Clerk to send copy orders (4) Where, on hearing the application, the Court makes an order for the enforcement of the order of the court in the designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance, copies of the order of the Court must be sent by the Clerk to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk responsible for enforcing the enforceable maintenance order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Clerk to enforce order (5) When the Court makes such an order the Clerk must proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Central Authority enforce a request without an accompanying order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Where the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request referred to in rule 27 and either:-(a) the request is not accompanied by an order referred to in rule 27 or in rule 28, or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 Enforcement procedure where not accompanied by order* 30. (1) Where the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request referred to in rule 27 and either:- - (a) the request is not accompanied by an order referred to in rule 27 or in rule 28, or - enforcement of the order is refused,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application be made to the District Court at any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - application to District Court and the Central Authority under the 1994 Act intends to make an application to the District Court under section 14(1)(c)(ii) of the 1994 Act, for the recovery of maintenance in accordance with the request, the application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district (as set out in section 14(11) of the 1994 Act) and must be deemed (as provided in section 14(3) of that Act) to be an application for a maintenance order under section 5, 5A or 21A of the 1976 Act, as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - on notice (2) The application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form 41B.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dec35386-f2e6-407c-9959-03ac62b7eaa1/Notice of application for the recovery of maintenance No. 41B.10.docx/docx/1) , Schedule on the respondent. The notice must be accompanied by copies of the documents mentioned in section 14(6) of the 1994 Act. Service must be effected by registered post at least 21 days before the return date of the application. (3) When service has been effected, the applicant must lodge with the Clerk the original of the notice, together with the certificate of posting, at least four days prior to the return date. (4) Where, on hearing the application, the court makes a maintenance order, the Clerk must proceed in accordance with the relevant provisions of [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) and this Order, and the forms therein provided (with any necessary modifications) may be used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk required to send documents related to the proceedings when a videolink transfer order is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must forward a copy of the order together with any other documents in his or her possession relating to the proceedings, to the appropriate District Court Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *32 Transfer to facilitate videolink evidence* 32. Where, at the hearing of an application under section of the 1994 Act, the Court makes an order pursuant to section 14(7) of that Act transferring the proceedings to a Court district where facilities are available for taking the evidence of the claimant or of any witness through a live television link, the Clerk must forward a copy of the order together with any other documents in his or her possession relating to the proceedings, to the appropriate District Court Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant request to give evidence by deposition at any sitting of the court where they reside or work?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A request by the claimant to give evidence on sworn deposition before the District Court under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the claimant resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Request to give evidence by deposition* 33. (1) A request by the claimant to give evidence on sworn deposition before the District Court under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the claimant resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) A deposition, taken under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act must be in the [Form 41B.12,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/71a24723-8cd7-4f98-932c-7a5d584cc5d0/Deposition of claimant No. 41B.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule and must include the certificate of the Court required under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act at the foot of the deposition. A certified copy of the deposition and certificate must be given by the Clerk to the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for serving notice at least 21 days before taking evidence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice must be served by registered post at least 21 days prior to the date fixed for taking the evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *35 Procedure under section 19 of the 1994 Act or Regulation 16 of the 2019 Regulations [14]* 35.(1) Subject to the provisions of section 19(8) of the 1994 Act, where on request from the Master of the High Court, pursuant to section 19(2) of the 1994 Act, a Judge of the District Court proposes to take the evidence of a person for the purposes of proceedings in a designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance, the Clerk must issue and serve notice, in the [Form 41B.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f8e2a05-8cb5-4bc8-8eed-db4e2ef730f6/Notice that evidence will be taken - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(3) No. 41B.14.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the person concerned, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act, the Master of the High Court and on such other persons as the Court thinks fit. The notice must be served by registered post at least 21 days prior to the date fixed for taking the evidence. (2) Where such evidence is taken on sworn deposition, the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/72e39e2d-457f-4f23-b474-c663331d540f/Deposition - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(4) No. 41B.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk must send a certified copy thereof to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the requesting authority. (3) Where, as provided for in section 19(9) of the 1994 Act, the requesting authority makes a request for the taking of evidence directly to the District Court, the provisions of this rule must, with any necessary modifications, apply in relation to such a request. (4) If it is not possible to take the evidence within four months of the receipt of the request by the Central Authority under the 1994 Act, the Judge must certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and the Clerk must send the same to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the requesting authority.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Clerk to send a certified copy of the deposition to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk must send a certified copy thereof to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention for transmission to the requesting Central Authority concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Subject to the provisions of Regulation 16 of the 2019 Regulations, where on request from the Master of the High Court, pursuant to Regulation 16(3) of the 2019 Regulations, a Judge of the Court proposes to take the evidence of a person of a person residing in the State on foot of such request, the Clerk must issue and serve notice, in the [Form 41B.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f8e2a05-8cb5-4bc8-8eed-db4e2ef730f6/Notice that evidence will be taken - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(3) No. 41B.14.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the person concerned, the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention, the Master of the High Court and on such other persons as the Court thinks fit. The notice must be served by registered post at least 21 days prior to the date fixed for taking the evidence. (6) Where such evidence is taken on sworn deposition, the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/72e39e2d-457f-4f23-b474-c663331d540f/Deposition - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(4) No. 41B.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk must send a certified copy thereof to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention for transmission to the requesting Central Authority concerned. (7) If it is not possible to take the evidence within three months of the receipt of the request by the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention, the Judge must certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and the Clerk must send the same to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention for transmission to the requesting Central Authority concerned. # **8 - MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS APPLICABLE TO PROCEEDINGS TO WHICH PARTS 3 TO 7 REFER**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the payment required to be made in euro?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must be paid in euro"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *36. Currency of payments* 36. An amount payable in the State under:- - (a) a decision recognised within the meaning of Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation; - an enforceable maintenance order by virtue of an enforcement order as provided for in the 2011 Regulations, or - an order for recovery of maintenance which is made by a Court in a jurisdiction other than the State and is enforceable in the State as provided for in the 1994 Act, must be paid in euro and if the amount is stated in the decision, enforceable maintenance order or order for recovery, as the case may be, in a currency other than euro, the payment must be made on the basis of the exchange rate prevailing on the date of the making of the enforcement order or of the order of a court in the State for the enforcement of the decision for the recovery of maintenance between that other currency and euro.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Does the clerk need to follow exchange control regulations when sending payments abroad?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before transmitting any such payment abroad the Clerk must comply with any Exchange Control regulations for the time being in force governing the transmission of such payments"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *37 Clerk to give receipt for and transmit payments* 37. (1) The Clerk must give, or send by ordinary post, to the maintenance debtor a receipt for each payment made by him or her under an order referred to in rule 36 and must transmit such payment forthwith by registered post, by insured post or by any other appropriate method to the person entitled to receive it, having due regard to the provisions of subsections 2(a) and of section 4 of the 1994 Act, where applicable. (2) Before transmitting any such payment abroad the Clerk must comply with any Exchange Control regulations for the time being in force governing the transmission of such payments and must, where necessary for that purpose, produce the order referred to in rule 36 to an authorised dealer, (i.e. a licensed bank) for inspection.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings by a maintenance creditor be held in a court district where the debtor''s employer is located within the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in case the maintenance debtor does not reside in the State but is in the employment either of a person residing or having a place of business in the State or of a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which that person resides or, as the case may be, the body has its seat, in accordance with Regulation of the 2011 Regulations."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *38 Venue for proceedings by creditor* 38. (1) Proceedings by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor being brought in the District Court under the 2011 Regulations and the Maintenance Regulation for the enforcement of an enforceable maintenance order, may be brought, heard and determined: - (a) in case the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State or is deemed under Regulation 6 of the 2011 Regulations to be habitually resident in the Dublin Metropolitan District, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the maintenance debtor habitually resides or, as the case may be, is deemed to be habitually resident, in accordance with Regulation 10(7)(a) of the 2011 Regulations; - in case the maintenance debtor does not reside in the State but is in the employment either of a person residing or having a place of business in the State or of a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which that person resides or, as the case may be, the body has its seat, in accordance with Regulation of the 2011 Regulations. (2) Proceedings being brought by the maintenance creditor by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention for the variation of a maintenance order made in a Contracting State other than the State may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the maintenance debtor is domiciled. # **9 - MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS APPLICABLE TO PROCEEDINGS TO WHICH PARTS 2, 5 AND 6 REFER**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice required to be filed with the Clerk before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application in the [Form must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *39 Application for order to provide information under Regulation 19(2) of the 2011 Regulations* 39. (1) An application by the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation to the Court under Regulation 19(2) of the 2011 Regulations for an order requiring a person or body (not being a person or body mentioned in Regulation 19(1) of the 2011 Regulations) to provide to the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation information as to the whereabouts, place of work, or location and extent of the assets, of a maintenance creditor or debtor (within the meaning of the 2011 Regulations) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the person or body to whom the order sought is to be directed resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. Notice of the application in the [Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing. (2) Where the Court grants the application and makes the order sought, the Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice required to be filed before the hearing of an application under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application in the [Form must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *40 Application for order to provide information under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act* 40. (1) An application by the Central Authority under the 1994 Act to the Court under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act for an order requiring a person or body (not being a person or body mentioned in section 20(1) of that Act) to provide to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act information as to the whereabouts, place of work, or location and extent of the assets of a maintenance debtor (within the meaning of the 1998 Act) or respondent may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the person or body to whom the order sought is to be directed resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. Notice of the application in the [Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing. (2) Where the Court grants the application and makes the order sought, the Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned. # **10 - PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE HAGUE CONVENTION 1996**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 referred to as the ''2000 Act'' in the definitions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “2000 Act” means the [Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *41 Definitions (this Part)* 41. In this Part (rules 41 to 52 inclusive), unless the context otherwise requires: the “**2000 Act**” means the [Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/37/enacted/en/html) (No. 37 of 2000); the “**Clerk**” means the Clerk for the Court area in which the original application was or is to be heard and decided or in which the original order was made; each of the expressions “**another contracting state**”, “**Central Authority**”, “**contracting state**”, “**the Convention**”, “**decision**”, “**judgment**”, and “**measure**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 1 of the 2000 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the 2000 Act or the Convention be brought at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"proceedings before the Court under the 2000 Act or under the Convention by virtue of the 2000 Act may be brought, heard or determined"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *42 Venue for proceedings under the 2000 Act or the Convention* 42. Subject to section 4(2) and section 4(3) of the 2000 Act, proceedings before the Court under the 2000 Act or under the Convention by virtue of the 2000 Act may be brought, heard or determined: - (a) in the case of proceedings to which section or section of the 2000 Act applies, at any sitting of the Court for any Court area in the Court district determined in accordance with section or, as the case may be, section of the 2000 Act; - in the case of any other proceedings under the 2000 Act or under the Convention by virtue of that Act, at such sitting of the Court or otherwise as is prescribed by these Rules or by statute for proceedings seeking the relief concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court stay the proceedings when it believes another contracting state is better suited to assess the best interests of the child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may stay the proceedings before it for a period specified by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *43 Stay of proceedings* 43. (1) Where the Court has jurisdiction in any proceedings to which the Convention applies, under Article 5 or 6 of the Convention but, on application of a party to the proceedings or of its own motion, considers in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention that the authority of another contracting state would be better placed in the particular case to assess the best interests of the child, the Court may stay the proceedings before it for a period specified by the Court and, as the Court considers appropriate, either: - (a) direct the Central Authority to make a request on its behalf to the proper authority of the other contracting state concerned to assume jurisdiction to take such measures of protection as it considers necessary in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention, or - invite the parties to introduce such a request before the proper authority of the other contracting state concerned in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention, and the Court may, for those purposes, limit the period of any stay to a period specified by the Court, and adjourn the matter for further consideration. (2) The Court may discharge a stay ordered in accordance with sub-rule (1) and direct the withdrawal of any request made under paragraph (a) of that sub-rule if the authority in the other contracting state concerned does not assume jurisdiction within the period for which the Court granted the stay. (3) The Court may discharge a stay ordered in accordance with sub-rule (1) if the parties do not, within the period specified by the court, request the authority in the other contracting state concerned to assume jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to append a copy of any relevant written request made by the competent authority of another contracting state when the Court is asked to exercise jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must additionally have appended a copy of any relevant request in writing made by the competent authority of another contracting state"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *44 Application for court to exercise jurisdiction as appropriate court of a contracting state* 44. Where the Court is asked in accordance with the Convention to exercise a jurisdiction conferred on it to take any measures by virtue of being the appropriate court of a contracting state, the document commencing the appropriate proceedings in accordance with these Rules: - must additionally be entitled in the matter of the provision of the Convention in accordance with which the Court is asked to exercise jurisdiction, and - must additionally have appended a copy of any relevant request in writing made by the competent authority of another contracting state, together with a certified translation, where necessary, into Irish or English, or - (iii) must otherwise set out the basis on which the request to exercise jurisdiction is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court provide directions to the Central Authority to facilitate exchanges of views?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may give such directions to the Central Authority as are appropriate to facilitate participation in any exchange of views"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *45 Exchange of views* 45. The Court may give such directions to the Central Authority as are appropriate to facilitate participation in any exchange of views referred to manner and by such means as the Court considers most suitable to meet the purposes of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court instruct the Central Authority to inform another country''s Central Authority about an order made under Article 11?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may direct the Central Authority to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *46 Orders under Article 11 and Article 12 of the Convention* 46. (1) In any case where the Court has made an order under Article 11 of the Convention, the Court may direct the Central Authority to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order and may direct the first-mentioned Central Authority to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether measures referred to in paragraph 2 of Article 11 of the Convention have been taken and, if so, as to the content of those measures. (2) In any case where the Court has been asked to make an order under Article 12 of the Convention, the Court may direct the Central Authority: - (a) to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether any measures have been taken by the authorities having jurisdiction under Articles 5 to 10 of the Convention and, if so, as to the content of those measures; - to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether a decision (in respect of the measures of protection which may be required by the situation) referred to in paragraph 2 of Article 12 of the Convention has been taken and, if so, as to the content of that decision; or - to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making by the Court of an order under Article 12 of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court adjourn proceedings to make a request under Article 34 of the Convention?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may adjourn proceedings under the 2000 Act for the purpose of making a request under Article 34 of the Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *47 Adjournment to make request under Article 34* 47. Without limiting any other power of the Court, the Court may adjourn proceedings under the 2000 Act for the purpose of making a request under Article 34 of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for recognition and/or enforcement be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may at the election of the applicant, be made parte in the first instance"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *48 Request under Article 24* 48. (1) A request to the Court by an interested party (in accordance with section 3(2) of the 2000 Act) pursuant to Article 24 of the Convention to decide on the recognition or non-recognition of a measure taken in another contracting state and/or pursuant to Article 26 of the Convention that a measure be declared enforceable or registered for the purpose of enforcement in the State may at the election of the applicant, be made parte in the first instance subject to the prior filing with the Clerk of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule or otherwise must be made on notice to the respondent by the issue and service on the respondent at least 4 days prior to the date fixed for the hearing of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An application for such recognition and/or enforcement must be grounded on an affidavit which: - (a) exhibits the judgment or decision (in this rule referred to as the “decision”) constituting or recording the measure concerned or a certified or otherwise duly authenticated copy thereof (together with a certified translation, where necessary, into Irish or English) and - where necessary, states the name of the authority in the contracting state concerned and the date on which and place at which the measure was given or ordered, and - explains concisely the nature and effect of the measure and - sets out or verifies (or which exhibits and verifies documents which set out): - the full name, address and date and place of birth (where available) of each child to whom the measure relates; - the full name, address and date and place of birth (where available) of each person who has, in relation to each such child, rights and/or obligations of a kind mentioned in Article 3 of the Convention;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn the application if the required evidence is not initially provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"adjourn the application to allow the applicant an opportunity to produce that evidence or those documents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *49 Where evidence not produced* 49. Where the party applying under rule 48 does not produce the evidence or documents referred to in rule 48, the Court may: - (a) adjourn the application to allow the applicant an opportunity to produce that evidence or those documents, or - accept equivalent evidence or documents, including by way of oral evidence, or - dispense with the production of such evidence or documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required when applying to set aside or discharge an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any application consistent with the requirements of the Convention to set aside or discharge such an order must, unless the Court otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service on the original applicant of a notice (or, as the case may be, on every person on whom the Court’s order has been served) in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *50 Enforcement, setting aside and discharge of order* 50. (1) The order of the Court granting a request to decide on the recognition of a measure taken in another contracting state and/or that a measure be declared enforceable or registered for the purpose of enforcement in the State is, subject to sub-rule (2), enforceable for all purposes in accordance with these Rules. (2) The Court may direct the service by such means as it directs of the order on any person who it appears to the Court may be affected by the making of the order and may stay the operation of the order for a specified period. (3) Any application consistent with the requirements of the Convention to set aside or discharge such an order must, unless the Court otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service on the original applicant of a notice (or, as the case may be, on every person on whom the Court’s order has been served) in the [Form 41B.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1324e26-e5b3-41b8-9b64-3306023c8f11/Notice of Application to vary or revoke an order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the original notice must, unless the Court otherwise allows, be filed with the Clerk at least two days before the return date of the application. (4) An application under sub-rule (3) must, unless the Court otherwise permits, be brought: - (a) by a person served with the order in the State, within one month of such service, or - by a person served with the order in another contracting state, within two months of such service. (5) The Court may stay the enforcement of the order, on such terms as it sees fit, where such an application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate required by the court for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A certificate of the Court for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act (in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *51 Certificate under section 6 of 2000 Act* 51. (1) A certificate of the Court for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act (in the [Form 41B.19,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22ac957e-0cad-4f76-b6bd-eca8f0be6d4d/Certificate - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be provided on application in writing to the Clerk for that purpose. Where appropriate, certified copies of any relevant order of the Court in the proceedings and of any document filed as proof of service in the proceedings may be appended to the certificate. (2) Where the applicant (or an authority of another contracting state) requests further particulars of the proceedings to which the certificate relates, the Clerk, having consulted with the Judge, and subject to Article 37 of the Convention, may certify such further particulars.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document related to a legal proceeding in a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim - Court: District # **Order 42: Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about appearance and defence the first section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a digital user file and serve an appearance and defence through digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A digital user (within the meaning of Order 39A) may file and/or serve an appearance and defence by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with Order 39A and, in the case of service, where the claimant or claimant’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Appearance and defence* 1. (1) A respondent who intends to defend civil proceedings must give, or send by post, to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant an appearance and defence, in the [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule not later than 28 days after the service on him or her of the claim notice, and must at the same time file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk. (1A)[2] A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court)) may file and/or serve an appearance and defence by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with Order 39A and, in the case of service, where the claimant or claimant’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user. (2) Where a claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) is served outside the State in accordance with these Rules and any order of the Court, the time within which a respondent served outside the State must serve his or her appearance and defence on the claimant and file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk is: - (a) five weeks after the service of the claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) exclusive of the day of service where the claim notice, other originating document or notice is served in the European territory of another Member State of the European Union, or - six weeks after the service of the claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) exclusive of the day of service where the claim notice, other originating document or notice is served in any non-European territory of a Member State of the European Union. (3) A defence must - - (a) contain a statement that the respondent intends to defend the claim notice; and - state the name and address of the respondent and an address for service in the European Union at which documents required to be served on the respondent may be left; and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is a respondent required to serve or file an appearance when a civil summons that doesn''t need a written defense is served within the State?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A respondent on whom a civil summons which does not require the delivery of a written defence is served within the State is not required to serve or file such an appearance."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- if the respondent defends by a solicitor, state the name or firm and business address within the European Union of the solicitor and also, if the solicitor is an agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal. (4) Where a civil summons which does not require the delivery of a written defence (or notice thereof) is served outside the State in accordance with these Rules and any order of the Court, the respondent may notify his or her intention to appear and contest the claim by serving an appearance in [Form 42.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b8cdf3dc-212d-4fd5-9579-4961fe689f1c/Notice of appearance and intention to defend a claim notice or civil summons served outside Ireland which requires an appearance No. 42.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the claimant and filing a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk within the period specified in sub-rule (2). A respondent on whom a civil summons which does not require the delivery of a written defence is served within the State is not required to serve or file such an appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for an appearance and defense in a debt claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appearance and defence in a debt claim must be in [Form 42.03]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Appearance and defence to debt claim* 2. (1) An appearance and defence in a debt claim must be in [Form 42.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/613a061f-1571-42a9-95fc-15790472b3df/Appearance and defence - debt claim No. 42.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule A respondent who intends to defend a debt claim must give, or send by post, to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant his or her appearance and defence not later than 28 days after the service on him or her of the claim notice, and must at the same time file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk. (2) A defence in a debt claim must state whether the claim is: - (a) disputed as to both liability and amount; - disputed only as to amount and if so, what amount is admitted to be due; - admitted in full and if so, whether the respondent proposes to pay immediately or requires time for payment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Must a respondent provide reasons for denying a fact in their defence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent who states that a fact stated in statement of claim is denied must— - (a) give reasons for denying the fact;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Appearance and defence in claims other than debt claims* 3. (1) Unless the respondent requires further particulars of statement of claim, a respondent to a claim other than a debt claim who contests or disputes all or part of a claimant’s claim must serve an appearance and defence in [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the claimant at the address for service stated in the claim notice and must file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk. (2) A defence must state which of the facts stated in statement of claim are— - (a) admitted; - denied; - not admitted. (3) A respondent who, in the defence, does not state whether a fact stated in statement of claim is— - (a) admitted; - denied; - not admitted— must be taken to admit the fact. (4) A respondent who states that a fact stated in statement of claim is denied must— - (a) give reasons for denying the fact; and - if the respondent intends to prove a fact different from that stated in the statement of claim, state, with necessary particulars, the fact that the respondent intends to prove. (5) The respondent must state specifically, with particulars, any fact or matter which— - (a) makes the claim of the claimant not maintainable; or - if not stated specifically, might take the claimant by surprise; or - raises questions of fact not arising out of the statement of claim. (6) If the defence arises by or under any enactment, the defence must identify the specific provision relied on. (7) A defence must be divided into paragraphs numbered consecutively, and each fact or matter stated, so far as is practicable, must be contained in a separate paragraph. (8) A defence must contain a list of all correspondence and other documents (other than any documents already identified in the statement of claim) on which the respondent will rely at the trial including the date if any and a brief description of each document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent serve an appearance and defence without the court''s permission if the claimant has already obtained a judgment in default of appearance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"an appearance and defence may not be served, except by permission of the Court, if the claimant has obtained judgment in default of appearance."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Late filing and service of appearance and defence* 4. A respondent may serve an appearance and defence and file an appearance at any time after the service of a claim notice with the written consent of the claimant, but an appearance and defence may not be served, except by permission of the Court, if the claimant has obtained judgment in default of appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent amend their defense after receiving further particulars from the claimant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim may serve and file an amended defence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Amendment of defence where particulars given* 5. Despite rules 2 and 3, a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim may serve and file an amended defence: - (a) not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim; or - at any other time with the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about change of solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**2 - CHANGE OF SOLICITOR**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 - CHANGE OF SOLICITOR**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party who is defending a case in person hire a solicitor without needing an order from the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A party suing or defending in person may appoint a solicitor without an order for the purpose."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Notice of change, appointment or discharge of solicitor* 6. (1) A party suing or defending by a solicitor may change his or her solicitor, or discharge his or her solicitor and sue or defend in person. (2) A party suing or defending in person may appoint a solicitor without an order for the purpose. (3) Notice of any change, discharge or appointment of a solicitor ([Form 42.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c30cd90d-8359-4aec-8bfc-71d65892d4cc/Notice of change - appointment of solicitor No. 42.04.docx/docx/1) or [42.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f1f07705-50c6-4788-9e8c-c86cba3d5e38/Notice of discharge of solicitor No. 42.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate) must be filed with the Clerk, and served on the opposite party, or his solicitor (if any), and on the solicitor discharged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about notice requiring copy documents or further particulars?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**3 - NOTICE REQUIRING COPY DOCUMENTS OR FURTHER PARTICULARS**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - NOTICE REQUIRING COPY DOCUMENTS OR FURTHER PARTICULARS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent request copies of documents mentioned in the statement of claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the statement of claim on which the claimant relies or referred to in the statement of claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Copy documents or further particulars from claimant* 8. A respondent may at any time before or at the time of delivery of a defence apply to the claimant in writing: - (a) for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the statement of claim on which the claimant relies or referred to in the statement of claim ([Form 42.06,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e6f835-a2eb-4f86-8cf7-396bc2c735cd/Notice requiring copy documents No. 42.06.docx/docx/1) Schedule - requiring the claimant to provide further particulars which the respondent asserts are reasonably necessary as to specified matters in the statement of claim ([Form 42.07,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f51331f-49b2-4f93-8dcc-6804bb812c27/Notice requiring further particulars No. 42.07.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant request copies of documents listed in the defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the defence on which the respondent relies or referred to in the defence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Copy documents or further particulars from respondent* 9. A claimant may within 28 days after delivery of a defence apply to the respondent in writing: - (a) for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the defence on which the respondent relies or referred to in the defence ([Form 42.06,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e6f835-a2eb-4f86-8cf7-396bc2c735cd/Notice requiring copy documents No. 42.06.docx/docx/1) Schedule - requiring the respondent to provide further particulars which the claimant asserts are reasonably necessary ([Form 42.07,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f51331f-49b2-4f93-8dcc-6804bb812c27/Notice requiring further particulars No. 42.07.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss a claim notice if the claimant fails to provide required documents or particulars?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if the party is a claimant, that the claim notice be dismissed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Failure to give copies or particulars* 10. (1) If a party fails to comply with a notice requiring copies of listed documents or requiring further particulars within 21 days of service of the notice, the Court may make an order requiring the party to provide the copies or the necessary particulars within a time specified by the Court. (2) Such an order may provide that on failure to do so - - if the party is a claimant, that the claim notice be dismissed; or - if the party is a respondent, that the party''s defence, if any, be struck out. (3) An application for an order under sub-rule (1) must be made before a date is fixed for hearing of the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party amend their pleading after receiving further particulars without court permission if they do so within 28 days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A party who has required further particulars of another party’s pleading may serve and file an amended statement of claim or other pleading: ... not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Amendment of pleading where particulars given* 11. A party who has required further particulars of another party’s pleading may serve and file an amended statement of claim or other pleading: - (a) not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars; or - at any other time with the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Does the order apply to counterclaims and third-party claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"This Order applies, with any necessary modification, to a counterclaim and to a claim by third party notice as if the counterclaim or the third party claim were a civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Application to counterclaims and third party claims* 12. This Order applies, with any necessary modification, to a counterclaim and to a claim by third party notice as if the counterclaim or the third party claim were a civil proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can the costs of requesting particulars be included in the successful party''s costs if they are not certified as necessary by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the costs of requesting particulars may only be allowed as part of the successful party’s costs against the unsuccessful party where, and only where, the particulars are certified as necessary by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Costs of particulars* 13. Unless otherwise ordered by the Court: - (a) the costs of requesting particulars may only be allowed as part of the successful party’s costs against the unsuccessful party where, and only where, the particulars are certified as necessary by the Court; and - the costs of replying to particulars may be recovered by the unsuccessful party against the successful party where the particulars are not certified as necessary by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about a counterclaim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**4 - COUNTERCLAIM**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4 - COUNTERCLAIM**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent file a counterclaim after the initial defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A respondent who counterclaims must file and serve the counterclaim with his or her defence, unless the Court otherwise permits."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 When counterclaim permitted* 14. (1) A respondent may set off or set up any right or claim the respondent alleges he or she has against the claimant as a counterclaim against the claim of the claimant, whether the respondent’s claim is a claim in damages or not. (2) A set off or counterclaim has the same effect as a cross action, so as to enable the Court to determine both the claim and the counterclaim at the same trial. (3) The Court may, on the application of the claimant before the trial, refuse permission to the respondent to avail himself or herself of the counterclaim if in the opinion of the Court, the set off or counterclaim cannot be conveniently disposed of in the trial of the claimant’s claim, or ought not to be allowed. (4) These Rules apply to a counterclaim as if the claimant were the respondent and the respondent were the claimant. (5) A respondent who counterclaims must file and serve the counterclaim with his or her defence, unless the Court otherwise permits. (6) A counterclaim must be in [Form 42.08,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/269d5e24-5305-463b-82e4-58181471951b/Statement of counterclaim No. 42.08.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss a frivolous or vexatious claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in case of the claim or defence being shown by the pleadings to be frivolous or vexatious, the Court may order the claim to be stayed or dismissed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Stay or order in proceeding* 15. (1) The Court may at any stage of the civil proceedings order to be struck out or amended any matter in any pleading which is unnecessary or scandalous, or which may tend to prejudice, embarrass, or delay the fair trial of the civil proceedings. (2) The Court may in any such case, if it thinks fit, order the costs of the application to be paid as between solicitor and client. (3) The Court may order any pleading to be struck out, on the ground that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or answer and in any such case or in case of the claim or defence being shown by the pleadings to be frivolous or vexatious, the Court may order the claim to be stayed or dismissed, or judgement to be entered accordingly, as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court strike out a statement of claim if it is considered prejudicial to the fair hearing of the case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may prejudice, embarrass or delay the fair hearing of the proceeding"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Striking out a pleading* 16. (1) If a statement of claim or defence or any part of a statement of claim or defence - - (a) does not disclose a cause of action or defence; is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious; - may prejudice, embarrass or delay the fair hearing of the proceeding; or - is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court— the Court may order that the whole or part of the statement of claim or defence be struck out or amended. (2) This rule, with any necessary modification, applies where the respondent counterclaims or claims against a third party. [1] Order 42 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 42 Rule 1 Sub-rule 1A inserted by 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent issue a third party notice within ten days after receiving a claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent may within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) issue and serve on the third party a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claim against a person not already a party* 1. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent - (a) claims any contribution or indemnity against any person not already a party (in this Order, a “**third party**”), or - claims against a third party any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the claimant, or - requires that any question or issue relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings should be determined not only as between the claimant and the respondent but also as between either or both of them and a third party, the respondent may within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) issue and serve on the third party a notice (in this Order, a “**third party notice**”) (in [Form 42A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7a463659-45c6-4aec-855b-ecf3e1f36b4b/Third party notice (indemnity or contribution) No. 42A.01.docx/docx/1) or [42A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/35cae99e-6a23-43ee-8e95-4da4d4ae63cf/Third party notice (issue) No. 42A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be), containing a statement of the nature of the claim against the respondent and the nature and grounds of the respondent''s claim against the third party or of the question or issue to be determined. 1A.[2] Notwithstanding rule 4, a digital user (within the meaning of [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court)) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court) and, in the case of service, where the third party or third party’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the respondent to provide a copy of the claim notice to the third party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The respondent must serve a copy of the claim notice or notice of application on the third party with the third party notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Copy of claim notice to be served* 2. The respondent must serve a copy of the claim notice or notice of application on the third party with the third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time frame mentioned for serving a copy of the third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The respondent must within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Copy to be filed* 3. The respondent must within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) serve a copy of the third party notice on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor and file a copy of the third party notice with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 41 relevant to the service of a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of [Order 41] relating to the service of documents apply to the service of a third party notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Service* 4. The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) relating to the service of documents apply to the service of a third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is a third party considered a party to the civil proceeding after being served a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a third party notice is served on the third party, the third party is, as from the time of service, a party to the civil proceeding with the same rights as if he or she had been sued in the ordinary way by the respondent by whom the third party notice was issued or by the claimant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Third party becomes a party on service* 5. Where a third party notice is served on the third party, the third party is, as from the time of service, a party to the civil proceeding with the same rights as if he or she had been sued in the ordinary way by the respondent by whom the third party notice was issued or by the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Does a third party have to appear and defend themselves within 28 days after receiving a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The third party must, within 28 days of the service of the third party notice, give or send by post to the respondent or respondent’s solicitor and to the Clerk notice of appearance and defence to the third party notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Appearance and defence to third party notice* 6. (1) Where a third party disputes the claim by the respondent against him or her or the claim by the claimant against the respondent, [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) applies as if the third party notice were a claim notice served by the respondent on the third party. (2) The third party must, within 28 days of the service of the third party notice, give or send by post to the respondent or respondent’s solicitor and to the Clerk notice of appearance and defence to the third party notice (in the [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1) or [42.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/613a061f-1571-42a9-95fc-15790472b3df/Appearance and defence - debt claim No. 42.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications) or an appearance and notice requiring particulars, and the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)(relating to defence and counterclaim) and [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment) (relating to lodgment) apply mutatis mutandis to the proceedings on the third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court grant a judgment or order after the trial in civil proceedings where a third party notice has been served?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may at or after the trial, or if the proceedings are decided otherwise than by trial, on an application by motion grant such judgment or order to or against any party or parties as the nature of the case requires."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Court may grant judgment or order* 9. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent has served a third party notice, the Court may at or after the trial, or if the proceedings are decided otherwise than by trial, on an application by motion grant such judgment or order to or against any party or parties as the nature of the case requires.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is court permission required before executing a third party in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"execution may not issue against the third party without the leave of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Execution not to issue without leave* 10. Where in civil proceedings judgment is given or an order is made against a respondent and judgment is given or an order is made in favour of that respondent against a third party, execution may not issue against the third party without the leave of the Court until the judgment or order against the respondent has been satisfied.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent make a claim for indemnity against another party already involved in the proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any contribution or indemnity"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Claim against person already a party* 11. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent claims against any person already a party: - (a) any contribution or indemnity, or - any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the claimant, or - that any question or issue relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings should be determined not only as between the claimant and the respondent but also as between either or both of them and that person, the respondent may, within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) issue and serve on that other party a notice in the prescribed form ([Form 42A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/464596fe-19cb-4aac-b882-3438e8c4fcdf/Notice of indemnity, contribution or issue against a party No. 42A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule containing a statement of the nature and grounds of the respondent’s claim or of the question or issue to be determined. This rule does not apply to any claim which could be made by counterclaim. [1] Order 42A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 42A Rule 1A inserted [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) by effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing a court order related to joining claims and parties in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties - Court: District # Order 43: Joining Claims And Parties [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is a child considered a vulnerable person according to the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a vulnerable person includes a child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order— “**birth certificate**” means a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of a person’s birth; [2]“**vulnerable person**” includes a child, a ward of court, and a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing how to join claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"## 2 - JOINING CLAIMS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - JOINING CLAIMS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 15 - Issue Of Summonses Alleging Offences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge issue a summons instead of a warrant for the arrest of a person charged with an indictable offense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where under [Order 16], rule 1(1) of these Rules a warrant is sought for the arrest of a person charging that person with having committed an indictable offence a Judge may, if he or she thinks fit, instead of issuing a warrant issue a summons requiring the appearance of that person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons in lieu of a warrant* 10. Where under [Order 16]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-16-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-Charging-Offences), rule 1(1) of these Rules a warrant is sought for the arrest of a person charging that person with having committed an indictable offence a Judge may, if he or she thinks fit, instead of issuing a warrant issue a summons requiring the appearance of that person, notwithstanding that the complaint had been made by information on oath and in writing. A Judge who has issued such summons may at any time (the complaint having been made by information) issue a warrant for the arrest of that person. *\* Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in matters other than criminal matters are contained in* *[Order 40E]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40E-District-Proceedings-Begun-By-The-Issue-Of-A-Summons-In-Matters-Other-Than-Criminal-Matters)**of these Rules* [1] Order 15 substituted by [S.I. 167 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/167/made/en/print?q 167&years 2005), effective 12 April 2005 [2] Order 15 rule 6 re-substituted by [S.I. 557 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/557/made/en/print?q 557&years 2010), effective 23 December 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order separate trials for claims that cannot be conveniently tried together?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if it appears to the Court that claims joined in a civil proceeding cannot be conveniently tried together, the Court may order separate trials or may exclude any claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Joining claims* 2. (1) Two or more claims may be made in one originating document, either alternatively or otherwise, so long as the claims are not mutually inconsistent or based on inconsistent allegations of fact. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), if it appears to the Court that claims joined in a civil proceeding cannot be conveniently tried together, the Court may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the necessary amendments, and may make such order as to costs as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can numerous individuals with the same interest in one claim be represented by one or more of them in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"one or more of those persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Court to defend, in the civil proceedings, on behalf of or for the benefit of all of the interested persons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Joining claimants* 3. (1) All persons may join as claimants in one civil proceeding in whom any right to relief arising out of the same transactions is claimed to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if all of those persons brought separate civil proceedings, a common question of law or fact would arise, but the total amount awarded in a civil proceeding on any single claim form may not exceed the maximum amount which the Court has jurisdiction to award in a civil proceeding, regardless of the number of claimants who may share in, or be awarded a portion of, that amount. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), if the Court is satisfied on an application by a respondent by notice of motion, that joining all of those persons may embarrass or delay the trial, the Court may order separate trials, or make such other order as it considers just. (3) When numerous persons have the same interest in one claim (whether as claimants or as respondents), one or more of those persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Court to defend, in the civil proceedings, on behalf of or for the benefit of all of the interested persons. (4) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to claims in tort. (5) No person may be made a claimant without his or her consent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant join multiple respondents when they are unsure about who should provide redress?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When the claimant is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more respondents, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the respondents is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Joining respondents* 4.(1) All persons may be joined as respondents in one civil proceeding against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. (2) When the claimant is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more respondents, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the respondents is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. (3) When a person residing outside the Court district within which the civil proceedings must be begun under any enactment or these Rules, but within the State, is a necessary and proper party to a civil proceeding properly begun in the Court against a person within the Court district, the first mentioned person may be served with the claim notice or other document without special permission of the Court. (4) It is not necessary that every respondent be interested in resisting all or every relief sought, or in defending every cause of action included in a civil proceeding in which he or she is a respondent; but the Court may make any order which it considers just, to prevent any respondent from being embarrassed, or put to unnecessary expense, by being required to attend any hearing or application in which he or she has no interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant include multiple respondents in a single civil proceeding related to a contract?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Respondents to a claim in contract* 5. The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court add a new respondent on its own motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Court may join necessary parties* 6.(1) No claim or cause of action may be defeated by reason of the failure to join particular persons as parties. (2) The Court may in every civil proceeding deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before the Court. (3) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings, either on or without the application of any party, and on such terms as the Court considers just, make an order: - (a) striking out the name of any party, whether claimant or respondent, who has been improperly joined, or - adding as a claimant or as a respondent the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Court to adjudicate on and settle all the questions involved in the civil proceeding. (4)[3] A person may only be added as a claimant: - (a) with his or her consent in writing, if he or she is not a vulnerable person, or - if the person is a child, following the appointment of a guardian litem or next friend, who must give his or her consent in writing to act in that capacity, or - if the person is a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8, or - if the person is a ward of court, by his or her committee. (5) Every person whose name is added as a respondent must be served with the claim notice in the manner prescribed by an order of the Court or otherwise in a manner permitted by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (6) A civil proceeding must be taken to have been begun against a person added as a respondent: - (a) on the date of the filing by a claimant of an application to join the party or - where the Court does so of its own motion on the making of the order by the Court adding that person as a respondent. (7) The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section discussing parties who may have a legal disability?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"PARTIES UNDER A DISABILITY"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 4 - PARTIES UNDER A DISABILITY'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court replace a next friend or guardian litem?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Court may appoint next friend or guardian litem* 7.[4] (1) When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the child. (2) The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a child''s guardian litem conduct the defense of a civil proceeding?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a child defends by his or her guardian litem, a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Child may defend by guardian litem* 9. (1) A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose. (2) Where a child defends by his or her guardian litem, a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a relevant person as defined by the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 sue or defend in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015] may sue or defend in accordance with [Order 7], rule 8."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10**Relevant person* 10.[5] A relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) may sue or defend in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is court approval required for a compromise involving a child or a person under a decision-making representation order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If in a civil proceeding a claim is made by or on behalf of or against a child or a person in respect of whom a decision-making representation order has been made under section of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015] and is in force, no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11**Compromise of claim by a vulnerable person* 11.*[6]*(1) If in a civil proceeding a claim is made by or on behalf of or against a child or a person in respect of whom a decision-making representation order has been made under section of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) and is in force, no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court. (2) Application for approval must be by notice of motion (which may be in the [Form 43.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications) filed not later than 28 days after the compromise, payment or acceptance. (3) No affidavit is required in support of the notice of motion. (4) The Court may dispense with the requirement of a notice of motion if the application for approval is made at the hearing of the civil proceeding. (5) On the application, evidence must be given of the date of the compromise, payment or acceptance and the date of birth of the child or person, and the dates must be stated in any order approving the compromise, payment or acceptance. (6) If the acceptance of an offer of compromise is approved, the child or person must be taken to have made or accepted the offer at the time of approval.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court direct the investment of an award for a child''s benefit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A], direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003, be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Court may direct investment of an award to a child* 12. (1) The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable. (2) A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an interim payment required to be made through a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an interim payment may be made by motion (which may be in the [Form 43.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Interim payments* 13.(1) Unless the Court otherwise decides, no interim payment out of any money secured or invested on behalf of a child may be made except under an order of the Court made on the application of the child''s next friend or guardian litem. (2) An application for an interim payment may be made by motion (which may be in the [Form 43.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the civil proceedings were heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor apply parte for a child who has attained majority to continue proceedings in their own name?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application may be made parte by the former child''s solicitor, next friend or guardian litem at any sitting of the Court for the Court area in which the proceedings are being heard for an order that the claimant or respondent, formerly a child, may proceed or defend in his or her own name."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Proceeding in own name on attaining majority* 14. When a child attains majority while proceedings to which this Order relate are still before the Court, an application may be made parte by the former child''s solicitor, next friend or guardian litem at any sitting of the Court for the Court area in which the proceedings are being heard for an order that the claimant or respondent, formerly a child, may proceed or defend in his or her own name.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person receive payment from investments made on their behalf when they turn majority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person who, on attaining majority, seeks the payment of any money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit while the person was a child, may, where the order directing investment of the award to the child so provides, apply for payment out by request in writing to the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Payment out of sums invested on attaining majority* 15. (1) A person who, on attaining majority, seeks the payment of any money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit while the person was a child, may, where the order directing investment of the award to the child so provides, apply for payment out by request in writing to the Clerk (which may be in the [Form 43.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/40212e5e-3420-483b-8d18-b875e0c8be7d/Notice of application for payment out of Court of money secured or invested for the benefit of a child No. 43.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and: - (a) producing to the Clerk his or her birth certificate and a form of identifying document including a photograph of the person sufficient to identify the person as the person entitled to payment, and - filing with the Clerk a certified copy of his or her birth certificate. (2) If satisfied by the production of the person’s birth certificate and other identifying document, and any other information the Clerk in his or her discretion requires, the Clerk may authorise payment out of the balance of any money remaining to the credit of the person. (3) In any case of doubt, the Clerk may list the request for payment out before the Court. (4) In any other case, an application for payment out may be made parte to the Court. (5) On hearing a request or application under this rule, the Court may by order direct the payment out to the person of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to him or her, together with any accrued interest or investment gain, or may make any other order the Court considers just on the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for serving documents on a vulnerable person according to the given rule?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Service of documents* 16.[7] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about legal roles such as trustees, executors, and administrators?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can trustees, executors, and administrators be sued without including all the beneficiaries in the lawsuit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Trustees, executors and administrators* 17. (1) Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and must be taken to represent the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate. (2) The Court may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can partners be sued under the name of their firm?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Two or more persons claiming or being liable as partners and carrying on business in the State may sue or be sued in the name of the firm of which those persons were partners when the cause of action accrued and in the names of those persons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Partners may sue or be sued in firm name* 18. Two or more persons claiming or being liable as partners and carrying on business in the State may sue or be sued in the name of the firm of which those persons were partners when the cause of action accrued and in the names of those persons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court order the disclosure of partner details in a civil case involving a firm?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any party to a civil proceeding by or against partners suing in the name of a firm may apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time the cause of action accrued, partners in the firm, to be provided and verified as the Court directs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1**9 Court may direct provision of particulars of all partners* 19. Any party to a civil proceeding by or against partners suing in the name of a firm may apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time the cause of action accrued, partners in the firm, to be provided and verified as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Do claimants need to provide details about all partners when a claim notice is issued?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When a claim notice is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the claimants or their solicitors must, on receipt of a written demand by any respondent, immediately confirm in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Claimants must provide particulars of all partners* 20. (1) When a claim notice is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the claimants or their solicitors must, on receipt of a written demand by any respondent, immediately confirm in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. (2) If the claimants or their solicitors fail to comply with a demand under sub-rule (1), all proceedings on the claim may, on an application for that purpose, be stayed on such terms as the Court directs. (3) When the particulars of the partners are provided, the claim may proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects follow, as if each of the partners had been named as claimants in the claim notice, but the civil proceedings must nevertheless continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claim notice for partners sued in the name of their firm required to be served according to Order 41?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claim notice must be served in accordance with [Order 41]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Service on partners* 21. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, the claim notice must be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defense be filed in the name of the firm when individuals are being sued as partners?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the defence may be in the name of the firm and all subsequent proceedings may nevertheless continue in the name of the firm"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *22 Appearance and defence* 22. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, the appearance must show individually the names of the persons on whose behalf it is filed; but the defence may be in the name of the firm and all subsequent proceedings may nevertheless continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is court permission required for issuing execution in proceedings between a firm and one of its partners?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No execution may be issued in proceedings mentioned in sub-rule (1) without the permission of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Application to proceedings between a firm and a partner* 23. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to civil proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and to civil proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State. (2) No execution may be issued in proceedings mentioned in sub-rule (1) without the permission of the Court, which must be sought by motion on notice to the party to be affected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about individuals operating under business names as part of a club?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"PERSONS USING BUSINESS NAMES AND CARRYING ON ACTIVITIES AS A CLUB"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 7 - PERSONS USING BUSINESS NAMES AND CARRYING ON ACTIVITIES AS A CLUB'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person be sued under a business name if it''s not registered?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Person trading under a business name* 24. (1) A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business. (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing the business to provide and verify as the Court directs the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time the cause of action accrued was carrying on the business concerned. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)on the person carrying on business or on the person who at the time of service appears to have control or to be managing the business, at the place where the business is carried on. (4) Service in accordance with sub-rule (3) must be taken to be effective service on the person sued whether or not that person is in or outside the State, and the permission of the Court to issue the claim notice or other document is not necessary.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a club be sued even if it is not registered under the Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Persons carrying on any activity in the State as a club may, in addition to any other manner in which they may be sued, be sued in the name of the club, whether or not the club is registered under the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Person carrying on activity as a club* 25. (1) Persons carrying on any activity in the State as a club may, in addition to any other manner in which they may be sued, be sued in the name of the club, whether or not the club is registered under the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the persons who appear to have control or to be managing the activity to provide and verify as the Court directs the names, description and places of residence of the persons who at the time the cause of action accrued were the officers or trustees of the club or the persons otherwise in control of the activity carried on by the club. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) on one of the persons who at the time of service appears to be an officer or trustee of the club, or to have control of the activity carried on by the club, at a place where the activity is carried on.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Do the provisions for firms also apply to cases involving a person trading under a business name or a club?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply to all cases to which rule 24 or rule 25 applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Provisions concerning firms to apply in a claim against a person trading under a business name or against a club* 26. In so far as the nature of the case permits, the provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply to all cases to which rule 24 or rule 25 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about change of parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## 8 - CHANGE OF PARTIES"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 8 - CHANGE OF PARTIES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claim continue even after a party''s death or bankruptcy?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claim does not abate by reason of the death or bankruptcy of a party, if the cause of action survives or continues."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Claim does not abate on death or bankruptcy* 27. (1) A claim does not abate by reason of the death or bankruptcy of a party, if the cause of action survives or continues. (2) A claim or civil proceeding does not become defective by the assignment, creation, or devolution of any estate or title pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate). (3) Whether the cause of action survives or not, a claim does not abate by reason of the death of any party between the verdict or the finding of the issues of fact and the judgment, or between the announcement and recording of the judgment or order. (4) In any such case, the judgment or order of the Court may be recorded or entered notwithstanding the death.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court add a personal representative to ongoing civil proceedings if a party dies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: be made a party to the civil proceedings;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Court may join personal representative* 28. (1) This rule applies where a party to civil proceedings dies or is adjudicated bankrupt, or the estate of a party to civil proceedings devolves by operation of law. (2) In a case to which this rule applies, the Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: - (a) be made a party to the civil proceedings; or - be served with notice of the civil proceedings, on such terms as the Court thinks just, and the Court may make such orders for the disposal of the civil proceedings as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can civil proceedings continue after the assignment of an estate?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a civil, proceeding may be continued by or against the person to, or on whom, the estate or title has come or devolved"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Continuation of civil proceedings pending administration of an estate* 29. Where any estate or title to any property is assigned, created or devolved pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate), a civil, proceeding may be continued by or against the person to, or on whom, the estate or title has come or devolved.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make an parte order to add a new party when there''s a change in legal interest due to death or bankruptcy?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, in a case to which sub-rule (1) applies, it becomes necessary or desirable that: ... the Court may, by order made parte, order that the proceedings be carried on between the continuing parties, and a new party or parties, where the Court is satisfied that there has been a change or transmission of a legal interest or liability as specified in sub-rule (1)(a)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 Change of parties on death or bankruptcy or other event* 30. (1) This rule applies where: - (a) the death or bankruptcy of a party or another event which occurred after the civil proceeding was begun causes a change or transmission of the legal interest or liability; or - a person interested in the claim or civil proceeding has come into existence after the civil proceeding was begun. (2) Where, in a case to which sub-rule (1) applies, it becomes necessary or desirable that: - (a) a person who is not already a party should be made a party; or - a person who is already a party should be made a party in another capacity, the Court may, by order made parte, order that the proceedings be carried on between the continuing parties, and a new party or parties, where the Court is satisfied that there has been a change or transmission of a legal interest or liability as specified in sub-rule (1)(a), or that a person interested has come into existence as specified in sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is an order obtained under rule 30 automatically binding on the person served without any further action?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Subject to rules 32 and 33, an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served, and every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *31 Service of an order under rule 30* 31. (1) Unless the Court otherwise directs, an order obtained under rule 30 must be served on each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is himself or herself the only new party). (2) Subject to rules 32 and 33, an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served, and every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person under a disability whose case has been assigned a guardian litem still challenge an order made under rule 30 within ten days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Service of an order under rule 30 on a person under a disability* 33. Where a person under a disability who does not have a guardian litem in the civil proceeding is served with an order under rule 30, the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person and, until the period of ten days has expired, the order under rule 30 has no force or effect against the person under a disability.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the respondent apply to compel the claimant to proceed if the original claimant dies but the cause of action survives?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent (or the person against whom the action, proceeding or matter, may be continued) may apply by motion on notice to compel the claimant (or the person entitled to proceed), to proceed within a period to be fixed by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *34 Order on failure to proceed following death of a party* 34. (1) Where: - (a) a claimant in a civil proceeding dies, and - the cause of action survives, but the person entitled to proceed fails to proceed, the respondent (or the person against whom the action, proceeding or matter, may be continued) may apply by motion on notice to compel the claimant (or the person entitled to proceed), to proceed within a period to be fixed by the Court. (2) Where the Court makes an order on an application under sub-rule (1), the court may make an order that, in default of proceeding within the time fixed by the Court, the claim be dismissed with costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about consolidation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## 9 - CONSOLIDATION"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 9 - CONSOLIDATION'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific application mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - PRE-TRIAL APPLICATIONS: GENERAL [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make interlocutory orders without a notice of motion in certain cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Nothing in this Order limits the power of the Court to make any interlocutory order or give a direction (whether in the presence of some only or all of the parties) without the issue of a notice of motion in an appropriate case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application of this Order* 1. (1) Unless otherwise provided by these Rules, this Order applies to any interlocutory or other application in a civil proceeding. (2) Nothing in this Order limits the power of the Court to make any interlocutory order or give a direction (whether in the presence of some only or all of the parties) without the issue of a notice of motion in an appropriate case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is written notice required for applications made on notice to any person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Form and timing of application* 2. (1) An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit. (2) An application by notice of motion is made when the notice of motion is filed in accordance with rule 4. (3) Unless any statute or rule otherwise provides, the moving party in any application to the Court other than an parte application or an application for an adjournment must give at least 48 hours’ notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court at which such application is to be made. This filing of a notice of motion or notice of application for issue is deemed to be notice to the Clerk of intention to make the application contained in the notice on the return date assigned to it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the applicant to notify others about their application on the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Notice of application to other parties or persons* 3. On the return date of a notice of motion the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for a notice of motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form and filing* 4. (1) A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case and must include particulars of the order, direction or other relief sought as appropriate to the case, a summary of the grounds of the application and, where relevant, a statement of the provisions of law including the provisions of any enactment or these Rules relied on in making the application. (2) A notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk assigned to the Court area in which the proceedings concerned have been issued and assigned a return date by the Clerk. (3) Where the grounds for the order, direction or other relief sought include the failure or refusal of the opposing party to agree a matter, copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached to the original notice of motion. (4) Where more than one order, direction or other relief is sought against the same party in the same civil proceeding: - (a) so far as practicable, all such orders, directions or other reliefs must be sought in the same notice of motion and a party must not suffer any adverse consequence in the costs to which the party is found to be entitled by reason of having sought several orders, directions or other reliefs in the same notice of motion; and - where practicable, a party must seek all of the interlocutory orders, directions or other reliefs which the party seeks in the civil proceeding on the same return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to serve copies of notices of motion and affidavits on all relevant parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant must serve a copy of a notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit in support of the notice of motion on every person to whom notice of the motion is to be given"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Service* 5. (1) The applicant must serve a copy of a notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit in support of the notice of motion on every person to whom notice of the motion is to be given unless otherwise provided by these Rules or by an order of the Court. (2) Every notice of motion must be served on every other party against whom any relief is sought in the motion not less than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk amend a notice of motion more than once under sub-rule (1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A notice of motion must not be amended under sub-rule (1) more than once."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Return date* 6. (1) If a notice of motion has not been served a Clerk may, at the request of the party who filed it, amend the notice of motion on or before the return date named in the notice of motion to name another return date. (2) In any other case, a notice of motion may only be amended by the Court. (3) A notice of motion must not be amended under sub-rule (1) more than once.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the claimant to bring copies of notices of motion and affidavits to court on the return date of a motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Copies for Court* 7. (1) The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: - (a) any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and - any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any affidavit or document at the hearing of an application by motion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn the hearing of an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may adjourn the hearing of an application by notice of motion on such terms as it thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Adjournment* 8. The Court may adjourn the hearing of an application by notice of motion on such terms as it thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court proceed with the application if the person served with the notice of motion does not attend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Absence of party served with notice of motion* 9. (1) If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served. (2) If on an application by notice of motion the applicant fails to attend, the Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about applications to set aside or vary?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## 2 - APPLICATIONS TO SET ASIDE OR VARY"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - APPLICATIONS TO SET ASIDE OR VARY'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court discharge, set aside, or vary an order if the original application was made without notice to the affected person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"was not made on notice to that person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Application to discharge, set aside or vary an order* 10. (1) The Court may, on an application by notice of motion ( [Form 44.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate to the case) by the person affected, on notice to the applicant for the original order, discharge, set aside or vary an order which affects a person where the application for the order— - (a) was made on notice to that person, but the person did not attend the hearing of the application; or - was not made on notice to that person. (2) An order under sub-rule (1) may be subject to such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just. [1] Order 44 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified in the order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment - Court: District # **ORDER 45: LODGMENTS AND TENDERS IN LIEU OF LODGMENT****[**[1]**](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on disclosing the details of a lodgment to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Neither the Clerk nor any other person may disclose the fact (or the amount) of any lodgment to the Court until all issues between the parties concerned have been decided."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application* 2. (1) The respondent may in respect of any claim in a civil proceeding, at any time up to the time prescribed for filing and service of the respondent’s appearance and defence, lodge in Court a sum of money which he or she alleges is sufficient to satisfy the claim. (2) A lodgment in respect of a claim may be on terms that take into account any other claim between the claimant and the respondent made in the proceeding. (3) A notice of the making of the lodgment ( [Form 45.01,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/316453b8-eaa8-459b-b446-26f94604972d/Notice of lodgment No. 45.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be made in writing in a document other than the appearance and defence. (4) The notice of lodgment must contain a statement to the effect that it is served in accordance with this Order. (5) A copy of the notice of lodgment must be served on the party whose claim the lodgment is intended to meet when the appearance and defence to the claim is served on that party. (6) The original of the notice of lodgment must be filed with the Clerk who must keep it in a separate file. (7) Neither the Clerk nor any other person may disclose the fact (or the amount) of any lodgment to the Court until all issues between the parties concerned have been decided. (8) Neither the fact nor the amount of a lodgment may be intimated in a defence or other pleading or document filed in Court (other than the notice of lodgment or any notice of acceptance of a lodgment).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party accept a lodgment outside of the 28-day period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Time for accepting a lodgment* 3. (1) The party whose claim a lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged ( [Form 45.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ccf352c0-e18f-4d6c-aa65-52d5ea012416/Notice of acceptance of lodgment No. 45.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule within 28 days after the notice of lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment. (2) Where a late lodgment or an increase to a lodgment is made in accordance with rule 6, the party whose claim the lodgment or increased lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged within 28 days after the notice of lodgment or notice of increased lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment or increased lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party receive the amount lodged without a court''s judgment after accepting it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Consequences of accepting a lodgment* 4. (1) On acceptance of a lodgment, the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court, provided that the party accepting the lodgment has lodged with the Clerk or with the Accountant a signed notice of acceptance of the lodgment in full satisfaction of the claim, save as to costs and, where acceptance of the lodgment requires the consent of the party who made the lodgment, the written consent of that party to late acceptance of the lodgment. (2) If the amount of costs to which a party who has accepted a lodgment is entitled cannot be agreed between the parties concerned, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party make a late lodgment if they have the permission of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"with the permission of the Court, within such further period as is permitted in the Court’s order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Permission to make a late lodgment* 6. (1) Despite rule 2(1), a party may make a lodgment, or may make a further payment into court to increase an existing lodgment— - (a) in any case where an amendment has been made to the statement of claim in the claim notice (or, as the case may be, the counterclaim or third party notice) in which the claim is made, within 28 days after the amended pleading is served on the party making the lodgment; or - with the written consent of the party whose claim is intended to be met by the lodgment, within such further period as is permitted in that party’s consent, the original of which must be lodged with the Clerk; or - with the permission of the Court, within such further period as is permitted in the Court’s order. (2) A party who makes or increases a lodgment in accordance with sub-rule (1) must serve a notice of lodgment (or notice of increased lodgment) on the party whose claim is intended to be met.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is a party who does not accept the amount lodged responsible for all subsequent costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the Court may, due to the special circumstances of the case specifically identified by the Court, order that the party who did not accept the lodgment ... is not liable for any, or a specified amount of the costs incurred after lodgment of the party who made the lodgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Liability for costs where a lodgment is not accepted* 7. (1) Where a party does not accept the amount lodged within the time prescribed, that party is liable for all costs incurred after the lodgment (or increased lodgment) in respect of the proceeding unless the Court decides that the amount due in respect of the claim is greater than the amount lodged in respect of the claim. (2) Where a Court decides that the amount to which a party is entitled in respect of a claim is less than the amount lodged to meet that claim, the Court must give judgment for the party making the claim for the amount the Court finds to be due, but must award to the party who made the lodgment the costs incurred in respect of the proceedings after the lodgment. (3) The Court may make an order as to the disposal of the amount lodged in court as the Court thinks just. (4) Despite sub-rules (1) and (2), the Court may, due to the special circumstances of the case specifically identified by the Court, order that the party who did not accept the lodgment - - (a) is not liable for any, or a specified amount of the costs incurred after lodgment of the party who made the lodgment; or - may recover a specified amount of that party’s costs incurred after lodgment from the party who made the lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing a tender offer by a qualified party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"TENDER OFFER BY QUALIFIED PARTY IN LIEU OF LODGMENT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - TENDER OFFER BY QUALIFIED PARTY IN LIEU OF LODGMENT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a qualified party use a tender offer instead of lodging money in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a qualified party is entitled to make or increase a lodgment on the qualified party’s own behalf or on behalf of any other party under Part 2 of this Order or by order of the Court, then the qualified party may, in lieu of lodging money in Court, make an offer of tender of payment to the party whose claim is intended to be met."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Qualified parties* 9. (1) A party is as a qualified party for the purposes of this rule if the party is: - (a) a Minister of Government; or - the Attorney General; or - the Government; or - the State; or - any party in respect of whom the State is providing an indemnity; or - an indemnifier of any party authorised to carry on business in the State as an insurance undertaking under the law for the time being in force; or - the Motor Insurers Bureau; or - the Visiting Motor Insurers Bureau. (2) Where a qualified party is entitled to make or increase a lodgment on the qualified party’s own behalf or on behalf of any other party under Part 2 of this Order or by order of the Court, then the qualified party may, in lieu of lodging money in Court, make an offer of tender of payment to the party whose claim is intended to be met. (3) A tender offer made under this rule is deemed to be a lodgment and to have the same effect as a lodgment. (4) The provisions of Part 2 of this Order apply mutatis mutandis to tender offers as regards time for making and accepting them as they apply to a lodgment. (5) A tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c615f98-b1cb-4e49-8de0-893c7e83d3ed/Notice of tender offer No. 45.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must state whether liability is admitted or denied and, subject to rule 2, is to be taken to be part of the pleadings. (6) Notice of acceptance of a tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9d5e1b73-6967-49af-9b94-71cb34a75358/Notice of acceptance of tender offer No. 45.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the provisions of rules 4 and 5 apply to such acceptance. (7) Where a tender offer has been accepted, the qualified party who made the tender offer must pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a consequence for not paying the specified sum within 28 days after accepting a tender offer?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid. (9) Any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer and the Court may make any order or give any directions on that application as the Court considers just and proper. [1] Order 45 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can an applicant for security for costs go directly to the court if the other party does not agree to provide security?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant for security may apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application for security* 1. (1) A party who requires security for costs from another party may apply in writing to that other party for security for costs. (2) Where the party from whom security has been sought does not undertake in writing to provide security, the applicant for security may apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided. (3) On hearing the application, the Court may order the claimant to lodge in Court the costs of an order dismissing the claim, or may make such other order as it thinks appropriate. (4) If an order is made requiring a party to give security for costs, security must be given in the manner and at the time the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a respondent allowed to obtain an order for security for costs based solely on the fact that the claimant is a foreign national?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"No order for security for costs may be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union or against a party who applies, under the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation or the 1968 Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 If the claimant is outside the State or is a foreign national* 2. (1) A respondent is not entitled to an order compelling a claimant to give security for costs solely on the ground that the claimant resides outside the State unless the respondent shows to the satisfaction of the Court that he or she has a defence on the merits. (2) No order for security for costs may be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union or against a party who applies, under the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation or the 1968 Convention (each as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court)), for enforcement of a judgment given in another Member State or Contracting State, solely on the ground that the claimant is a foreign national or that the claimant is not domiciled or resident in the State.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss a claimant''s claim notice if they fail to provide the required security?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Failure to give security* 3. If a claimant fails to give the security required by an order, the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court modify an order related to security for costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may set aside or vary any order requiring a claimant to give security for costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Variation or setting aside* 4. The Court may set aside or vary any order requiring a claimant to give security for costs. [1] Order 45A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents - Court: District # **Order Discovery and Inspection of Documents******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is this Order applicable to debt claims without an order granting permission to defend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"This Order does not apply to debt claims (unless an order has been made giving leave to defend)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application of this Order* 1. This Order does not apply to debt claims (unless an order has been made giving leave to defend) or to small claims.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent request copies of documents listed in the claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Request for inspection or copies of documents listed in claim notice or defence* 2. (1) A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the statement of claim; - any other document referred to in the statement of claim. (2) A claimant may, at any time after service of an appearance and defence on him or her make a request to the respondent in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the appearance and defence; - any other document mentioned in the appearance and defence. (3) The party to whom a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) is made must within seven days after receipt of the request: - (a) provide copies of such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement on payment of the reasonable charges for copying them; or - produce such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement for inspection by the party who made the request, or by his or her solicitor, and permit him or her to take copies. (4) If so agreed by the parties: - (a) copies of documents may be provided in electronic form or such other form as is agreed or directed; and - inspection may be permitted of electronic copies of documents or of documents in electronic form. (5) A party who fails to comply with a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) may not afterwards put any such document in evidence on his or her behalf, unless the Court is satisfied that there was a sufficient reason for not complying with the request, in which case the Court may allow the document to be put in evidence on such terms as to costs and otherwise as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party apply to the court for an order directing discovery if the other party does not respond to a written request?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Application for discovery following request* 3. (1) Where a party wishes to have discovery of documents in addition to those which may be produced under rule 2, the party must first make a request in writing for voluntary discovery within a period of 21 days from the date of the request. (2) The request must specify the precise documents or categories of documents in respect of which discovery is sought; provide the reasons why each category of documents is required to be discovered and explain why discovery of the documents sought is necessary for disposing fairly of the claim or for saving costs. (3) If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding. (4) The notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit must be served not less than four clear days before the return date. (5) On hearing the application, the Court may, having regard to the value of the claim: - (a) refuse or adjourn the application, if satisfied that discovery is not necessary, or not necessary at that stage of the proceeding; or - make such order on such terms as to the security for the costs of discovery or otherwise, and either generally or limited to certain classes of documents, as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Does the affidavit need to specify which documents the party objects to producing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The affidavit to be made by a party against whom an order for discovery has been made must specify which, if any, of the documents scheduled in the affidavit he or she objects to produce"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Affidavit* 5. The affidavit to be made by a party against whom an order for discovery has been made must specify which, if any, of the documents scheduled in the affidavit he or she objects to produce, and must be in accordance with [Form 45B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c207105-72a0-418f-a30c-45d618b1f461/Affidavit as to documents No. 45B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the production of documents during civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may at any time while civil proceedings are pending order the production by any party to the civil proceedings, on oath, of such of the documents in his possession or power, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceedings, as the Court thinks right;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Order to produce documents for inspection* 6. (1) The Court may at any time while civil proceedings are pending order the production by any party to the civil proceedings, on oath, of such of the documents in his possession or power, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceedings, as the Court thinks right; and the Court may deal with such documents, when produced, in the manner the Court considers just. (2) If a party served with a request under rule 2(1) or (2) omits to provide copies or notify a time for inspection, or objects to allowing inspection, the Court may, on the application of the party desiring it, make an order for inspection at such time and in such place and in such manner as the Court directs. (3) An application under sub-rule (2) must be made by motion on notice to be served not later than four clear days before the return date and supported by an affidavit showing of what documents inspection is sought and that they are in the possession or power of procurement of the other party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant''s case be dismissed if they do not follow an order for discovery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Failure to comply with order for discovery* 7. (1) If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution. (2) If a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her appearance and defence, if any, struck out, and to be placed in the same position as if he or she had not defended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the responsibility for the costs of discovery typically borne by the party requesting it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the costs of discovery are part of the costs of the party seeking discovery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Costs of discovery* 8. In every civil proceeding, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, the costs of discovery are part of the costs of the party seeking discovery, either as between party and party or between solicitor and client, where, and only where, discovery is certified as necessary by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can this order be applied to children?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"This Order applies to any claimant or respondent who is a child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Application to children* 9. This Order applies to any claimant or respondent who is a child, and to the next friend or guardian litem of any such party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on serving additional discovery requests after court directions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Discovery after directions* 11. If the Court gives directions concerning discovery or inspection of documents, no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or the High Court made by a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court under section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961] (inserted by section 21 of the [Courts Act 1971]), must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Form of application* 1. An application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court under section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [Courts Act 1971](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1971/act/36/enacted/en/html)), must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), modified as appropriate).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration of service to be lodged with the Clerk after serving the notice of motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When the copy of the notice of motion has been served, a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Service of application* 2. (1) The original notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk and a copy of the notice of motion must be served on the other party to the proceeding in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least seven days before the return date. (2) When the copy of the notice of motion has been served, a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified in the order as District?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Admissions - Court: District # **Order Admissions******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form for admitting documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An admission may be in the [Form 45D.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68a4075d-1d23-407e-8c24-401cabe3d3e4/Notice of admission of documents No. 45D.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Admission of documents* 1. (1) Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c17f7252-bdbe-4880-8f53-f156167a0029/Notice to admit documents No. 45D.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule call on any other party to admit the authenticity of any document. An admission may be in the [Form 45D.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68a4075d-1d23-407e-8c24-401cabe3d3e4/Notice of admission of documents No. 45D.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a document, after written notice to admit has been served, the costs of proving the document must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable. (3) No costs of proving a document may be allowed unless: - (a) the party seeking to prove the document served notice to admit; or - the Court certifies that the omission to serve notice to admit was a saving of expense.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party admit facts only for the purposes of the current trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any admission made in response to a notice under this rule must be taken to be made only for the purposes of the particular civil proceedings, and not as an admission that may be used against the party on any other occasion or in favour of any person other than the party giving the notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Admission of facts* 2. (1) Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b7097e4-d07c-4788-a691-ccf66f7bfe0a/Notice to admit facts No. 45D.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any time not later than ten days before the date fixed for the trial, call on any other party to admit, for the purposes of the trial only, any specific fact mentioned in the notice. An admission may be in the [Form 45D.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64f44eba-4bed-49da-b3a0-d1f03dc0c354/Notice of admission of facts No. 45D.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a fact within seven days after written notice to admit has been served, or within such further time as is allowed by the Court, the costs of proving the fact must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable, or unless the Court at any time otherwise orders or directs. (3) Any admission made in response to a notice under this rule must be taken to be made only for the purposes of the particular civil proceedings, and not as an admission that may be used against the party on any other occasion or in favour of any person other than the party giving the notice. (4) The Court may at any time allow any party to amend or withdraw any admission made under this rule on such terms as the Court considers just. (5) Unless the Court orders otherwise, all costs and expenses as in the opinion of the Court have been caused by the failure of a party to serve a notice to admit documents or a notice to admit facts must, regardless of the result, be paid by the party who failed to serve the notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for admissions not made during the hearing to be in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any admission, if not made during the hearing, must be in writing, and must be signed by the party making the admission, or by his solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Admissions in writing* 3. Any admission, if not made during the hearing, must be in writing, and must be signed by the party making the admission, or by his solicitor. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order being discussed in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Amendment - Court: District # **Order Amendment******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court allow a party to change their statement of claim during civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: ... permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Court’s power to permit amendment* 1. (1) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: - (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just; - disallow any amendment already made; or - amend any defect or error in any proceeding. (2) All amendments must be permitted as are necessary for the purpose of determining the real questions in controversy between the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Must all amendments to a document be underlined?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Manner of amendment* 2. (1) A pleading or other document may be amended by written alterations in the copy which has been served, and in the copy which has been filed. Where necessary, extensive amendments may be set out on additional sheets of paper to be inserted into the pleading at a place indicated in the pleading. (2) When an amendment has been made, the amended document must be indorsed as follows: "Amended on the ..... day of ..... 20.... pursuant to Order dated the ...... day of ....... 20....". (3) All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk make corrections to a judgment or order with the approval of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Clerical errors* 3.[2] (1) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a judgment or order, or any error arising in a judgment or order from any accidental slip or omission, at any time on the application by notice of motion of the party seeking the correction on notice to the party sought to be affected by the correction. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), on application in writing of any party, the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk. (3) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a warrant issued in civil proceedings, or any error arising in a warrant issued in civil proceedings from any accidental slip or omission, at any time before execution of the warrant on the application parte by the party seeking the correction. [1] Order inserted by [S.I.17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 598 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/598/made/en/print?q 598&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in Order 46 related to a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents - Court: District # Order 46: Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any information about witness attendance in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - ATTENDANCE OF WITNESSES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is a witness required to attend court or an officer of the court if summoned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any party desiring the attendance of a person (in this Order, a “witness”) to give evidence or produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court, in any civil proceedings must apply for, and the Clerk may issue, a witness summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application to Clerk to issue witness summons* 1. Any party desiring the attendance of a person (in this Order, a “**w****itness**”) to give evidence or produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court, in any civil proceedings must apply for, and the Clerk may issue, a witness summons ( [Form 46.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3398e73-d381-42d7-a057-6b46c8eb5657/Witness summons No. 46.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule requiring the witness to whom the summons is directed to comply with the requirements of the witness summons at the time and place stated in the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a witness summons be issued without a court order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons duces tecum) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application to Court to issue witness summons* 2. (1) An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte. (2) In any case of difficulty as regards the issue of any other witness summons, the party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons. (3) On an application under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the issue of a witness summons, with or without conditions as it considers appropriate, or may make such other order as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court set aside or disregard the service of a witness summons if the witness did not receive reasonable notice or expenses were not provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may set aside or disregard service of the witness summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Service of witness summons* 3. (1) A witness summons must be served personally or by registered post on the witness named in the witness summons, unless the Court orders otherwise. (2) If it appears to the Court that a witness served with a witness summons was not given reasonable time to enable him or her to appear as directed in the witness summons, or that his or her reasonable expenses of attending have not been paid or offered to him or her, the Court may set aside or disregard service of the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an officer of the court ask for expenses when attending a sitting outside their district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the officer may require that the party requiring his or her attendance (or that party’s solicitor) must: deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance, and undertake to pay any further reasonable charges and expenses which may not be fully met by the deposit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Officer of the Court may require expenses* 5. If any officer of the Court is required by a witness summons to attend with any record or document at any sitting or place outside the Court district in which he or she is serving, the officer may require that the party requiring his or her attendance (or that party’s solicitor) must: - (a) deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance, and - undertake to pay any further reasonable charges and expenses which may not be fully met by the deposit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the claimant include multiple respondents in a single civil proceeding related to a contract?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Respondents to a claim in contract* 5. The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court add a new respondent without the consent of all claimants?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Court may join necessary parties* 6.(1) No claim or cause of action may be defeated by reason of the failure to join particular persons as parties. (2) The Court may in every civil proceeding deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before the Court. (3) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings, either on or without the application of any party, and on such terms as the Court considers just, make an order: - (a) striking out the name of any party, whether claimant or respondent, who has been improperly joined, or - adding as a claimant or as a respondent the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Court to adjudicate on and settle all the questions involved in the civil proceeding. (4)[3] A person may only be added as a claimant: - (a) with his or her consent in writing, if he or she is not a vulnerable person, or - if the person is a child, following the appointment of a guardian litem or next friend, who must give his or her consent in writing to act in that capacity, or - if the person is a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8, or - if the person is a ward of court, by his or her committee. (5) Every person whose name is added as a respondent must be served with the claim notice in the manner prescribed by an order of the Court or otherwise in a manner permitted by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (6) A civil proceeding must be taken to have been begun against a person added as a respondent: - (a) on the date of the filing by a claimant of an application to join the party or - where the Court does so of its own motion on the making of the order by the Court adding that person as a respondent. (7) The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court replace a next friend or guardian litem?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Court may appoint next friend or guardian litem* 7.[4] (1) When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the child. (2) The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a guardian litem represent a child in legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Child may defend by guardian litem* 9. (1) A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose. (2) Where a child defends by his or her guardian litem, a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is court approval required for a compromise involving a child or a person with a decision-making representation order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If in a civil proceeding a claim is made by or on behalf of or against a child or a person in respect of whom a decision-making representation order has been made under section of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 and is in force, no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11**Compromise of claim by a vulnerable person* 11.*[6]*(1) If in a civil proceeding a claim is made by or on behalf of or against a child or a person in respect of whom a decision-making representation order has been made under section of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) and is in force, no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court. (2) Application for approval must be by notice of motion (which may be in the [Form 43.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications) filed not later than 28 days after the compromise, payment or acceptance. (3) No affidavit is required in support of the notice of motion. (4) The Court may dispense with the requirement of a notice of motion if the application for approval is made at the hearing of the civil proceeding. (5) On the application, evidence must be given of the date of the compromise, payment or acceptance and the date of birth of the child or person, and the dates must be stated in any order approving the compromise, payment or acceptance. (6) If the acceptance of an offer of compromise is approved, the child or person must be taken to have made or accepted the offer at the time of approval.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court direct the investment of an award to a child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A], direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003, be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Court may direct investment of an award to a child* 12. (1) The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable. (2) A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person apply for payment of money invested for their benefit upon reaching majority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person who, on attaining majority, seeks the payment of any money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit while the person was a child, may, where the order directing investment of the award to the child so provides, apply for payment out by request in writing to the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Payment out of sums invested on attaining majority* 15. (1) A person who, on attaining majority, seeks the payment of any money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit while the person was a child, may, where the order directing investment of the award to the child so provides, apply for payment out by request in writing to the Clerk (which may be in the [Form 43.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/40212e5e-3420-483b-8d18-b875e0c8be7d/Notice of application for payment out of Court of money secured or invested for the benefit of a child No. 43.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and: - (a) producing to the Clerk his or her birth certificate and a form of identifying document including a photograph of the person sufficient to identify the person as the person entitled to payment, and - filing with the Clerk a certified copy of his or her birth certificate. (2) If satisfied by the production of the person’s birth certificate and other identifying document, and any other information the Clerk in his or her discretion requires, the Clerk may authorise payment out of the balance of any money remaining to the credit of the person. (3) In any case of doubt, the Clerk may list the request for payment out before the Court. (4) In any other case, an application for payment out may be made parte to the Court. (5) On hearing a request or application under this rule, the Court may by order direct the payment out to the person of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to him or her, together with any accrued interest or investment gain, or may make any other order the Court considers just on the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for serving documents to a vulnerable person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Service of documents* 16.[7] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about legal roles such as trustees, executors and administrators?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can trustees, executors, or administrators be sued without including all the beneficiaries in the lawsuit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Trustees, executors and administrators* 17. (1) Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and must be taken to represent the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate. (2) The Court may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person be sued under a business name that is not registered?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Person trading under a business name* 24. (1) A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business. (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing the business to provide and verify as the Court directs the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time the cause of action accrued was carrying on the business concerned. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)on the person carrying on business or on the person who at the time of service appears to have control or to be managing the business, at the place where the business is carried on. (4) Service in accordance with sub-rule (3) must be taken to be effective service on the person sued whether or not that person is in or outside the State, and the permission of the Court to issue the claim notice or other document is not necessary.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claim continue even after the death of one of the parties involved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claim does not abate by reason of the death or bankruptcy of a party, if the cause of action survives or continues."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Claim does not abate on death or bankruptcy* 27. (1) A claim does not abate by reason of the death or bankruptcy of a party, if the cause of action survives or continues. (2) A claim or civil proceeding does not become defective by the assignment, creation, or devolution of any estate or title pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate). (3) Whether the cause of action survives or not, a claim does not abate by reason of the death of any party between the verdict or the finding of the issues of fact and the judgment, or between the announcement and recording of the judgment or order. (4) In any such case, the judgment or order of the Court may be recorded or entered notwithstanding the death.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court add a personal representative to civil proceedings if a party dies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: be made a party to the civil proceedings;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Court may join personal representative* 28. (1) This rule applies where a party to civil proceedings dies or is adjudicated bankrupt, or the estate of a party to civil proceedings devolves by operation of law. (2) In a case to which this rule applies, the Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: - (a) be made a party to the civil proceedings; or - be served with notice of the civil proceedings, on such terms as the Court thinks just, and the Court may make such orders for the disposal of the civil proceedings as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make an parte order to add a new party or change the capacity of an existing party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, by order made parte, order that the proceedings be carried on between the continuing parties, and a new party or parties, where the Court is satisfied that there has been a change or transmission of a legal interest or liability as specified in sub-rule (1)(a), or that a person interested has come into existence as specified in sub-rule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 Change of parties on death or bankruptcy or other event* 30. (1) This rule applies where: - (a) the death or bankruptcy of a party or another event which occurred after the civil proceeding was begun causes a change or transmission of the legal interest or liability; or - a person interested in the claim or civil proceeding has come into existence after the civil proceeding was begun. (2) Where, in a case to which sub-rule (1) applies, it becomes necessary or desirable that: - (a) a person who is not already a party should be made a party; or - a person who is already a party should be made a party in another capacity, the Court may, by order made parte, order that the proceedings be carried on between the continuing parties, and a new party or parties, where the Court is satisfied that there has been a change or transmission of a legal interest or liability as specified in sub-rule (1)(a), or that a person interested has come into existence as specified in sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is an order obtained under rule 30 binding on the person served immediately after service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *31 Service of an order under rule 30* 31. (1) Unless the Court otherwise directs, an order obtained under rule 30 must be served on each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is himself or herself the only new party). (2) Subject to rules 32 and 33, an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served, and every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person under a disability whose case hasn''t been assigned a guardian litem yet, request the court to modify or cancel an order received under rule 30?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Service of an order under rule 30 on a person under a disability* 33. Where a person under a disability who does not have a guardian litem in the civil proceeding is served with an order under rule 30, the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person and, until the period of ten days has expired, the order under rule 30 has no force or effect against the person under a disability.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent apply to the court to compel the person entitled to proceed to continue the case if the original claimant dies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent (or the person against whom the action, proceeding or matter, may be continued) may apply by motion on notice to compel the claimant (or the person entitled to proceed), to proceed within a period to be fixed by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *34 Order on failure to proceed following death of a party* 34. (1) Where: - (a) a claimant in a civil proceeding dies, and - the cause of action survives, but the person entitled to proceed fails to proceed, the respondent (or the person against whom the action, proceeding or matter, may be continued) may apply by motion on notice to compel the claimant (or the person entitled to proceed), to proceed within a period to be fixed by the Court. (2) Where the Court makes an order on an application under sub-rule (1), the court may make an order that, in default of proceeding within the time fixed by the Court, the claim be dismissed with costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific information about pre-trial applications in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - PRE-TRIAL APPLICATIONS: GENERAL [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application in a proceeding that requires notice to a person typically required to be in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Form and timing of application* 2. (1) An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit. (2) An application by notice of motion is made when the notice of motion is filed in accordance with rule 4. (3) Unless any statute or rule otherwise provides, the moving party in any application to the Court other than an parte application or an application for an adjournment must give at least 48 hours’ notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court at which such application is to be made. This filing of a notice of motion or notice of application for issue is deemed to be notice to the Clerk of intention to make the application contained in the notice on the return date assigned to it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court require the applicant to notify others about their application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Notice of application to other parties or persons* 3. On the return date of a notice of motion the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of motion required to be filed with a specific clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk assigned to the Court area in which the proceedings concerned have been issued and assigned a return date by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form and filing* 4. (1) A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case and must include particulars of the order, direction or other relief sought as appropriate to the case, a summary of the grounds of the application and, where relevant, a statement of the provisions of law including the provisions of any enactment or these Rules relied on in making the application. (2) A notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk assigned to the Court area in which the proceedings concerned have been issued and assigned a return date by the Clerk. (3) Where the grounds for the order, direction or other relief sought include the failure or refusal of the opposing party to agree a matter, copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached to the original notice of motion. (4) Where more than one order, direction or other relief is sought against the same party in the same civil proceeding: - (a) so far as practicable, all such orders, directions or other reliefs must be sought in the same notice of motion and a party must not suffer any adverse consequence in the costs to which the party is found to be entitled by reason of having sought several orders, directions or other reliefs in the same notice of motion; and - where practicable, a party must seek all of the interlocutory orders, directions or other reliefs which the party seeks in the civil proceeding on the same return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the claimant to bring copies of notices of motion and affidavits to court on the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Copies for Court* 7. (1) The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: - (a) any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and - any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any affidavit or document at the hearing of an application by motion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court proceed with hearing an application if the person served with the notice of motion does not attend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Absence of party served with notice of motion* 9. (1) If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served. (2) If on an application by notice of motion the applicant fails to attend, the Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court discharge, set aside, or vary an order if the person affected was not notified about the original application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"was not made on notice to that person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Application to discharge, set aside or vary an order* 10. (1) The Court may, on an application by notice of motion ( [Form 44.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate to the case) by the person affected, on notice to the applicant for the original order, discharge, set aside or vary an order which affects a person where the application for the order— - (a) was made on notice to that person, but the person did not attend the hearing of the application; or - was not made on notice to that person. (2) An order under sub-rule (1) may be subject to such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just. [1] Order 44 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment - Court: District # **ORDER 45: LODGMENTS AND TENDERS IN LIEU OF LODGMENT****[**[1]**](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific interpretation mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - INTERPRETATION'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about lodging?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"LODGMENT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - LODGMENT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of lodgment required to be served in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A notice of the making of the lodgment ( [Form 45.01,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/316453b8-eaa8-459b-b446-26f94604972d/Notice of lodgment No. 45.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be made in writing in a document other than the appearance and defence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application* 2. (1) The respondent may in respect of any claim in a civil proceeding, at any time up to the time prescribed for filing and service of the respondent’s appearance and defence, lodge in Court a sum of money which he or she alleges is sufficient to satisfy the claim. (2) A lodgment in respect of a claim may be on terms that take into account any other claim between the claimant and the respondent made in the proceeding. (3) A notice of the making of the lodgment ( [Form 45.01,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/316453b8-eaa8-459b-b446-26f94604972d/Notice of lodgment No. 45.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be made in writing in a document other than the appearance and defence. (4) The notice of lodgment must contain a statement to the effect that it is served in accordance with this Order. (5) A copy of the notice of lodgment must be served on the party whose claim the lodgment is intended to meet when the appearance and defence to the claim is served on that party. (6) The original of the notice of lodgment must be filed with the Clerk who must keep it in a separate file. (7) Neither the Clerk nor any other person may disclose the fact (or the amount) of any lodgment to the Court until all issues between the parties concerned have been decided. (8) Neither the fact nor the amount of a lodgment may be intimated in a defence or other pleading or document filed in Court (other than the notice of lodgment or any notice of acceptance of a lodgment).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party accept a lodgment after the initial 28-day period if they have written consent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Time for accepting a lodgment* 3. (1) The party whose claim a lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged ( [Form 45.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ccf352c0-e18f-4d6c-aa65-52d5ea012416/Notice of acceptance of lodgment No. 45.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule within 28 days after the notice of lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment. (2) Where a late lodgment or an increase to a lodgment is made in accordance with rule 6, the party whose claim the lodgment or increased lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged within 28 days after the notice of lodgment or notice of increased lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment or increased lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can the party accepting a lodgment receive the amount lodged without a court''s judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Consequences of accepting a lodgment* 4. (1) On acceptance of a lodgment, the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court, provided that the party accepting the lodgment has lodged with the Clerk or with the Accountant a signed notice of acceptance of the lodgment in full satisfaction of the claim, save as to costs and, where acceptance of the lodgment requires the consent of the party who made the lodgment, the written consent of that party to late acceptance of the lodgment. (2) If the amount of costs to which a party who has accepted a lodgment is entitled cannot be agreed between the parties concerned, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is a party who does not accept the amount lodged responsible for all subsequent costs if the court determines the claim amount is higher?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the Court decides that the amount due in respect of the claim is greater than the amount lodged in respect of the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Liability for costs where a lodgment is not accepted* 7. (1) Where a party does not accept the amount lodged within the time prescribed, that party is liable for all costs incurred after the lodgment (or increased lodgment) in respect of the proceeding unless the Court decides that the amount due in respect of the claim is greater than the amount lodged in respect of the claim. (2) Where a Court decides that the amount to which a party is entitled in respect of a claim is less than the amount lodged to meet that claim, the Court must give judgment for the party making the claim for the amount the Court finds to be due, but must award to the party who made the lodgment the costs incurred in respect of the proceedings after the lodgment. (3) The Court may make an order as to the disposal of the amount lodged in court as the Court thinks just. (4) Despite sub-rules (1) and (2), the Court may, due to the special circumstances of the case specifically identified by the Court, order that the party who did not accept the lodgment - - (a) is not liable for any, or a specified amount of the costs incurred after lodgment of the party who made the lodgment; or - may recover a specified amount of that party’s costs incurred after lodgment from the party who made the lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a qualified party use a tender offer instead of making a cash deposit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a qualified party is entitled to make or increase a lodgment on the qualified party’s own behalf or on behalf of any other party under Part 2 of this Order or by order of the Court, then the qualified party may, in lieu of lodging money in Court, make an offer of tender of payment to the party whose claim is intended to be met."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Qualified parties* 9. (1) A party is as a qualified party for the purposes of this rule if the party is: - (a) a Minister of Government; or - the Attorney General; or - the Government; or - the State; or - any party in respect of whom the State is providing an indemnity; or - an indemnifier of any party authorised to carry on business in the State as an insurance undertaking under the law for the time being in force; or - the Motor Insurers Bureau; or - the Visiting Motor Insurers Bureau. (2) Where a qualified party is entitled to make or increase a lodgment on the qualified party’s own behalf or on behalf of any other party under Part 2 of this Order or by order of the Court, then the qualified party may, in lieu of lodging money in Court, make an offer of tender of payment to the party whose claim is intended to be met. (3) A tender offer made under this rule is deemed to be a lodgment and to have the same effect as a lodgment. (4) The provisions of Part 2 of this Order apply mutatis mutandis to tender offers as regards time for making and accepting them as they apply to a lodgment. (5) A tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c615f98-b1cb-4e49-8de0-893c7e83d3ed/Notice of tender offer No. 45.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must state whether liability is admitted or denied and, subject to rule 2, is to be taken to be part of the pleadings. (6) Notice of acceptance of a tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9d5e1b73-6967-49af-9b94-71cb34a75358/Notice of acceptance of tender offer No. 45.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the provisions of rules 4 and 5 apply to such acceptance. (7) Where a tender offer has been accepted, the qualified party who made the tender offer must pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a consequence for a qualified party who fails to pay the specified sum within 28 days after their tender offer is accepted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid. (9) Any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer and the Court may make any order or give any directions on that application as the Court considers just and proper. [1] Order 45 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a respondent allowed to get an order for security for costs just because the claimant lives outside the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A respondent is not entitled to an order compelling a claimant to give security for costs solely on the ground that the claimant resides outside the State unless the respondent shows to the satisfaction of the Court that he or she has a defence on the merits."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 If the claimant is outside the State or is a foreign national* 2. (1) A respondent is not entitled to an order compelling a claimant to give security for costs solely on the ground that the claimant resides outside the State unless the respondent shows to the satisfaction of the Court that he or she has a defence on the merits. (2) No order for security for costs may be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union or against a party who applies, under the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation or the 1968 Convention (each as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court)), for enforcement of a judgment given in another Member State or Contracting State, solely on the ground that the claimant is a foreign national or that the claimant is not domiciled or resident in the State.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent request copies of documents listed in the statement of claim after receiving a claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Request for inspection or copies of documents listed in claim notice or defence* 2. (1) A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the statement of claim; - any other document referred to in the statement of claim. (2) A claimant may, at any time after service of an appearance and defence on him or her make a request to the respondent in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the appearance and defence; - any other document mentioned in the appearance and defence. (3) The party to whom a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) is made must within seven days after receipt of the request: - (a) provide copies of such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement on payment of the reasonable charges for copying them; or - produce such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement for inspection by the party who made the request, or by his or her solicitor, and permit him or her to take copies. (4) If so agreed by the parties: - (a) copies of documents may be provided in electronic form or such other form as is agreed or directed; and - inspection may be permitted of electronic copies of documents or of documents in electronic form. (5) A party who fails to comply with a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) may not afterwards put any such document in evidence on his or her behalf, unless the Court is satisfied that there was a sufficient reason for not complying with the request, in which case the Court may allow the document to be put in evidence on such terms as to costs and otherwise as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party apply to the court for discovery if the other party does not respond to their written request?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Application for discovery following request* 3. (1) Where a party wishes to have discovery of documents in addition to those which may be produced under rule 2, the party must first make a request in writing for voluntary discovery within a period of 21 days from the date of the request. (2) The request must specify the precise documents or categories of documents in respect of which discovery is sought; provide the reasons why each category of documents is required to be discovered and explain why discovery of the documents sought is necessary for disposing fairly of the claim or for saving costs. (3) If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding. (4) The notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit must be served not less than four clear days before the return date. (5) On hearing the application, the Court may, having regard to the value of the claim: - (a) refuse or adjourn the application, if satisfied that discovery is not necessary, or not necessary at that stage of the proceeding; or - make such order on such terms as to the security for the costs of discovery or otherwise, and either generally or limited to certain classes of documents, as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant''s case be dismissed if they do not comply with an order for discovery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Failure to comply with order for discovery* 7. (1) If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution. (2) If a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her appearance and defence, if any, struck out, and to be placed in the same position as if he or she had not defended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on serving additional discovery requests without further court order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Discovery after directions* 11. If the Court gives directions concerning discovery or inspection of documents, no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for forwarding a claim to the Circuit Court or High Court made through a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court under section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961] must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Form of application* 1. An application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court under section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [Courts Act 1971](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1971/act/36/enacted/en/html)), must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), modified as appropriate).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the order specified as District?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Admissions - Court: District # **Order Admissions******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party admit facts for the trial only?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b7097e4-d07c-4788-a691-ccf66f7bfe0a/Notice to admit facts No. 45D.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any time not later than ten days before the date fixed for the trial, call on any other party to admit, for the purposes of the trial only, any specific fact mentioned in the notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Admission of facts* 2. (1) Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b7097e4-d07c-4788-a691-ccf66f7bfe0a/Notice to admit facts No. 45D.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any time not later than ten days before the date fixed for the trial, call on any other party to admit, for the purposes of the trial only, any specific fact mentioned in the notice. An admission may be in the [Form 45D.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64f44eba-4bed-49da-b3a0-d1f03dc0c354/Notice of admission of facts No. 45D.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a fact within seven days after written notice to admit has been served, or within such further time as is allowed by the Court, the costs of proving the fact must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable, or unless the Court at any time otherwise orders or directs. (3) Any admission made in response to a notice under this rule must be taken to be made only for the purposes of the particular civil proceedings, and not as an admission that may be used against the party on any other occasion or in favour of any person other than the party giving the notice. (4) The Court may at any time allow any party to amend or withdraw any admission made under this rule on such terms as the Court considers just. (5) Unless the Court orders otherwise, all costs and expenses as in the opinion of the Court have been caused by the failure of a party to serve a notice to admit documents or a notice to admit facts must, regardless of the result, be paid by the party who failed to serve the notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court amend a pleading if it deems it just?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: ... (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Court’s power to permit amendment* 1. (1) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: - (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just; - disallow any amendment already made; or - amend any defect or error in any proceeding. (2) All amendments must be permitted as are necessary for the purpose of determining the real questions in controversy between the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Should all amendments to a pleading or document be underlined?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Manner of amendment* 2. (1) A pleading or other document may be amended by written alterations in the copy which has been served, and in the copy which has been filed. Where necessary, extensive amendments may be set out on additional sheets of paper to be inserted into the pleading at a place indicated in the pleading. (2) When an amendment has been made, the amended document must be indorsed as follows: "Amended on the ..... day of ..... 20.... pursuant to Order dated the ...... day of ....... 20....". (3) All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court correct a clerical mistake in a warrant before it is executed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a warrant issued in civil proceedings, or any error arising in a warrant issued in civil proceedings from any accidental slip or omission, at any time before execution of the warrant on the application parte by the party seeking the correction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Clerical errors* 3.[2] (1) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a judgment or order, or any error arising in a judgment or order from any accidental slip or omission, at any time on the application by notice of motion of the party seeking the correction on notice to the party sought to be affected by the correction. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), on application in writing of any party, the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk. (3) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a warrant issued in civil proceedings, or any error arising in a warrant issued in civil proceedings from any accidental slip or omission, at any time before execution of the warrant on the application parte by the party seeking the correction. [1] Order inserted by [S.I.17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 598 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/598/made/en/print?q 598&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a specific type of court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents - Court: District # Order 46: Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a clerk issue a witness summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk may issue, a witness summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application to Clerk to issue witness summons* 1. Any party desiring the attendance of a person (in this Order, a “**w****itness**”) to give evidence or produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court, in any civil proceedings must apply for, and the Clerk may issue, a witness summons ( [Form 46.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3398e73-d381-42d7-a057-6b46c8eb5657/Witness summons No. 46.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule requiring the witness to whom the summons is directed to comply with the requirements of the witness summons at the time and place stated in the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend court only allowed if made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons duces tecum) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application to Court to issue witness summons* 2. (1) An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte. (2) In any case of difficulty as regards the issue of any other witness summons, the party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons. (3) On an application under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the issue of a witness summons, with or without conditions as it considers appropriate, or may make such other order as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court set aside or disregard service of a witness summons if the witness was not given enough time to attend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may set aside or disregard service of the witness summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Service of witness summons* 3. (1) A witness summons must be served personally or by registered post on the witness named in the witness summons, unless the Court orders otherwise. (2) If it appears to the Court that a witness served with a witness summons was not given reasonable time to enable him or her to appear as directed in the witness summons, or that his or her reasonable expenses of attending have not been paid or offered to him or her, the Court may set aside or disregard service of the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an officer of the court request payment for expenses when attending a sitting outside their district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the officer may require that the party requiring his or her attendance (or that party’s solicitor) must: ... deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Officer of the Court may require expenses* 5. If any officer of the Court is required by a witness summons to attend with any record or document at any sitting or place outside the Court district in which he or she is serving, the officer may require that the party requiring his or her attendance (or that party’s solicitor) must: - (a) deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance, and - undertake to pay any further reasonable charges and expenses which may not be fully met by the deposit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court impose a fine on a witness who fails to attend after being duly summoned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Consequences of failure to comply with a witness summons* 6. If a witness who has been duly summoned: - (a) fails without lawful excuse to attend or to give evidence or to produce the books, papers or documents according to the witness summons; or - unless duly excused, fails to remain in attendance throughout the hearing, the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default, or may make such other order as is just in the circumstances.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is videoconference mentioned as a method for presenting evidence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"EVIDENCE BY VIDEOCONFERENCE"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - EVIDENCE BY VIDEOCONFERENCE'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a live television link be made without prior notice of motion if the court is already considering case management directions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be heard and decided without the prior issue of a notice of motion by the Court on any occasion when the Court is considering case management directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Application for use of live television link* 8. An application for a direction that a party may participate in a hearing in the proceedings, or that a witness give evidence in any such hearing, from a location other than the Court itself, by means of a live television link in accordance with section 26 of the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/14/enacted/en/html): - (a) may be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties; - may be heard and decided without the prior issue of a notice of motion by the Court on any occasion when the Court is considering case management directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an affidavit be taken outside of Ireland by a notary public in the European Union?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - FOREIGN PUBLIC DOCUMENTS AND FOREIGN LANGUAGE DOCUMENTS 9.[2] Any affidavit for use in proceedings in the Court may be taken outside Ireland: - before any Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent exercising such functions in the country concerned, or - before any notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or - (iii) in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place; and judicial notice shall be taken of the seal or signature, as the case may be, of any such diplomatic or consular representative or agent, notary public or other person attached, appended or subscribed to any such affidavit, or to any document exhibited to any such affidavit. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is a document that claims to be covered by the 2016 Regulation considered authentic without proof of certification procedures if it would otherwise be admissible?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A document which purports to be a public document to which the 2016 Regulation applies (or a certified copy, within the meaning of Article 3(7) of the 2016 Regulation, thereof) is, without proof of: ... admissible in evidence as such if otherwise admissible."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Proof of Foreign Public, Diplomatic and Consular Documents of Member States of the European Union 10.[3] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfil functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation; the “**2016 Regulation**” means [Regulation 2016/1191](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/1191/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 6 July 2016 on promoting the free movement of citizens by simplifying the requirements for presenting certain public documents in the European Union and amending [Regulation No 1024/2012](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2012/1024/oj/eng); “**public documents**” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation. (2) A document which purports to be a public document to which the 2016 Regulation applies (or a certified copy, within the meaning of Article 3(7) of the 2016 Regulation, thereof) is, without proof of: - any formal procedure for certifying the authenticity of a signature, - the capacity in which the person signing the document has acted, or - (iii) where appropriate, the identity of the seal or stamp which it bears, admissible in evidence as such if otherwise admissible. (3) In any case in which the Court has a reasonable doubt as to the authenticity of a public document or certified copy produced in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the taking of any step permitted by Article 14 of the 2016 Regulation to dispel such doubt. In any such case the Court must in its directions set out the grounds upon which the directions are based. 11.[4] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Contracting State designated in accordance with Article 5 of the 1987 Convention; the “**1987 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Legalisation of Documents in the Member States of the European Communities](https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/documents/treaties-agreements/agreement/?id 1987011) done at Brussels on the May, 1987;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is an apostille recognized without further proof if issued according to the 1961 Convention?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proof of Foreign Public Documents (Hague Convention 1961)* 13.[6] (1) In this rule: an “**apostille**” means an apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention; the “**1961 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Requirement of Legalisation for Foreign Public Documents done at The Hague on the October, 1961](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 41); a “**Contracting State**” means a State, other than Ireland, which is a party to the 1961 Convention other. (2) A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown. (3) This rule does not apply to any document to which rule 10, rule 11, or rule 12 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing a specific court case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47: Judgment In Default In Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant request a default judgment if the respondent fails to respond within the specified period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance or defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a debt claim does not serve and file an appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a certificate under seal be filed instead of an affidavit when the claim is verified by a Minister of a Government Department?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim. (3) Where a respondent has executed a consent to judgment which has been duly witnessed, the applicant may file an affidavit ([Form 47.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36e14c1b-9b52-4447-958f-03255d2d12a7/Affidavit exhibiting consent No. 47.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule verifying the consent instead of an affidavit of debt; and where the consent is to judgment by instalments, the form of judgment (decree) in [Form 47.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ac82b1bc-3683-4311-9494-5fb6e362b178/Instalment judgment (decree) by consent No. 47.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be used. (4) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) must be given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. Judgment may not be given where the affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim was not sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) was not given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (5) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can judgment in default be given if the claim notice was sent abroad under the Service Regulation and the Hague Convention without ensuring compliance with specific articles?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 3. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Service Regulation and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge decide on an application without a court sitting if they believe an order should be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 A Judge may issue a default judgment or refer to the Court* 4.(1) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court, and may fix the amount of costs and interest as is appropriate in the circumstances in accordance with the Schedule of Costs. (2) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is not satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may, or if the claimant so requests, the Judge must, refer the matter to the Court for decision. (3) An application to which rule 3 applies must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (4) If the Judge refers an application to the Court or an application is assigned a return date, the Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) make the order sought in the application; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed; - give directions as to the application; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (5) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (6) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant continue legal proceedings against other respondents after obtaining a default judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 5. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent, further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss civil proceedings if a party does not comply with an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Default of compliance* 8. If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded. [1] Order 47 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order specifically about non-debt claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47A: Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant apply for judgment in default if the respondent fails to appear or defend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance and defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a claim other than a debt claim does not serve and file and appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant apply for judgment immediately after the respondent''s default without prior notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and at the same time consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence within 14 days from the date of that letter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application by motion on notice* 2. (1) In any case in which this Order applies, the claimant may, subject to the provisions of this rule, at any time after the respondent’s default in serving and filing an appearance or serving a defence, by motion on notice to the respondent served on the respondent not less than four clear days before the return date of the motion, apply to the Court for judgment. (2) Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and at the same time consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence within 14 days from the date of that letter. (3) If an appearance and defence is not served within 14 days from the date of that letter, the claimant may issue (by filing with the Clerk to obtain a return date) and serve a notice of motion for judgment in default which must be returnable to a return date not less than 14 days from the date of the service of the notice of motion. (4) An application under this rule must be supported— - by an affidavit or statutory declaration ([Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), [41.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1ce8e29-61fe-41d6-b1e4-0be6fe055224/Declaration as to service by ordinary post No. 41.02.docx/docx/1) or [41.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d590fd61-c2f8-49d3-9efa-e869eb833fc7/Statutory declaration as to personal service No. 41.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate) of service of the claim notice; and - by a certificate ([Form 47.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5d865ffc-a14c-473b-b3a1-7326645c45cd/Certificate of no appearance - defence No. 47.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule which may be endorsed on the verifying affidavit signed by the claimant’s solicitor or by the claimant (if acting in person) that no appearance, notice requiring particulars or defence has been received from the respondent; and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is a further affidavit required in a personal injuries action if the personal injuries summons has already been verified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"if the personal injuries summons has previously been verified"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) by an affidavit verifying the claim notice (provided that in a personal injuries action, a further affidavit is not required if the personal injuries summons has previously been verified); and - by a form of judgment (decree) ([Form 49.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae2bca29-5e13-446e-a4da-d9c458134623/Judgment (decree) following trial - damages No. 49.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications). (5) A copy of the affidavit verifying the claim notice must (unless previously served) be served on the respondent with the notice of motion. The remaining documents mentioned in sub-rule (4) must be produced on the hearing of the motion but, where permitted by the Court, the form of judgment (decree) may be filed with the Clerk subsequently. (6) If the claimant can establish special reasons making it necessary to serve a notice of motion for judgment under this rule with greater urgency than in accordance with the notice periods provided, he or she may apply parte to the Court for an order giving the claimant permission to serve a notice of motion for judgment in default giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent, or in the alternative the Court may deem good the service of a notice of motion actually served giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a motion for judgment be struck out if a defense is delivered within the specified time frame?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If, after the service of a notice of motion for judgment, the respondent delivers a defence to the claimant and not less than six days before the return date files a copy of the defence with the Clerk, with a certified copy of the notice of motion attached, the motion for judgment will stand struck out"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Motion struck out with costs if defence filed not less than 6 days before return date* 3. If, after the service of a notice of motion for judgment, the respondent delivers a defence to the claimant and not less than six days before the return date files a copy of the defence with the Clerk, with a certified copy of the notice of motion attached, the motion for judgment will stand struck out and the respondent will be liable to pay to the claimant the costs of the motion for judgment in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for an affidavit when a claim includes value-added tax?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Affidavit verifying claim* 4. (1) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply where the claimant relies on an affidavit of verification of a personal injuries summons made more than one month before the date of the application. (3) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can judgment in default be given if the claim notice was sent abroad under the Service Regulation and the respondent hasn''t served or filed an appearance and defence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 5. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the [Service Regulation](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of [Article 15 of the Hague Convention](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 77) have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit and may be included in the affidavit verifying the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific step mentioned where the court can make a peremptory order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Return date* 6. (1) All applications by motion for judgment under this Order must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (2) The Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) give judgment on the claimant’s claim contained in the claim notice in such amount as the Court is satisfied is just; - give permission to the respondent to defend the whole or part of the claim on such terms as the Court considers just; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed, or adjourn the application for the hearing of further evidence; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (3) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (4) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court. (5) On the hearing of an application for judgment under this Order, the Court may make an Order for costs in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant continue legal proceedings against other respondents after obtaining a default judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 7. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claimant treated as the respondent when considering their appearance in relation to the counterclaim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant were the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Default of appearance and defence to counterclaim* 8. If a respondent serves a counterclaim, rules 1 to 6 apply as if— - (a) the respondent were the claimant; - a reference to the appearance in those rules were a reference to the appearance to the counterclaim; and - the claimant were the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss civil proceedings if a party does not comply with an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Default of compliance* 10. If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded. [1] Order 47A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Discontinuance And Withdrawal - Court: District # **Order Discontinuance And Withdrawal******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant withdraw their case after receiving the respondent''s defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Discontinuance or withdrawal of claim or part of claim* 1. (1) The claimant may: - (a) before receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence; or - after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application), - wholly discontinue his claim against all or any of the respondents by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk; or - withdraw any part or parts of his alleged cause of action by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk. (2) Where a claimant serves a notice under sub-rule (1), the claimant must pay the respondent’s costs of the proceedings or, if the claim is not wholly discontinued, the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn. (3) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to small claims. (4) If not agreed, the applicable scale or amount of costs may be determined by the Court. (5) Discontinuance or withdrawal under sub-rule (1) is not a defence to any subsequent claim. (6) Save as provided in this Order, a claimant may not withdraw or discontinue a claim without the permission of the Court. (7) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the claimant’s application, order or permit the claim to be discontinued, or any part of the alleged cause of action to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent withdraw their defence without court permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A party who has filed an appearance and defence in a proceeding may not withdraw the defence or any part of it without the permission of the Court in accordance with sub-rule (1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Withdrawal of defence* 2. (1) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the respondent’s application, order or permit all or any part of the respondent’s grounds of defence to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just. (2) A party who has filed an appearance and defence in a proceeding may not withdraw the defence or any part of it without the permission of the Court in accordance with sub-rule (1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Is a respondent entitled to receive costs when proceedings are wholly discontinued against them?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Judgment for costs of discontinuance* 4. A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her, or for the costs occasioned by the matter withdrawn, if the action be not wholly discontinued, if the costs concerned are not paid within four days after their amount is agreed or fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for using a live television link during a hearing be made without issuing a formal notice of motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be heard and decided without the prior issue of a notice of motion by the Court on any occasion when the Court is considering case management directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Application for use of live television link* 8. An application for a direction that a party may participate in a hearing in the proceedings, or that a witness give evidence in any such hearing, from a location other than the Court itself, by means of a live television link in accordance with section 26 of the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/14/enacted/en/html): - (a) may be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties; - may be heard and decided without the prior issue of a notice of motion by the Court on any occasion when the Court is considering case management directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can affidavits be taken outside of Ireland by a notary public in the European Union?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - FOREIGN PUBLIC DOCUMENTS AND FOREIGN LANGUAGE DOCUMENTS 9.[2] Any affidavit for use in proceedings in the Court may be taken outside Ireland: - before any Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent exercising such functions in the country concerned, or - before any notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or - (iii) in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place; and judicial notice shall be taken of the seal or signature, as the case may be, of any such diplomatic or consular representative or agent, notary public or other person attached, appended or subscribed to any such affidavit, or to any document exhibited to any such affidavit. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''public documents'' defined in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“public documents” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Proof of Foreign Public, Diplomatic and Consular Documents of Member States of the European Union 10.[3] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfil functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation; the “**2016 Regulation**” means [Regulation 2016/1191](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/1191/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 6 July 2016 on promoting the free movement of citizens by simplifying the requirements for presenting certain public documents in the European Union and amending [Regulation No 1024/2012](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2012/1024/oj/eng); “**public documents**” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation. (2) A document which purports to be a public document to which the 2016 Regulation applies (or a certified copy, within the meaning of Article 3(7) of the 2016 Regulation, thereof) is, without proof of: - any formal procedure for certifying the authenticity of a signature, - the capacity in which the person signing the document has acted, or - (iii) where appropriate, the identity of the seal or stamp which it bears, admissible in evidence as such if otherwise admissible. (3) In any case in which the Court has a reasonable doubt as to the authenticity of a public document or certified copy produced in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the taking of any step permitted by Article 14 of the 2016 Regulation to dispel such doubt. In any such case the Court must in its directions set out the grounds upon which the directions are based. 11.[4] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Contracting State designated in accordance with Article 5 of the 1987 Convention; the “**1987 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Legalisation of Documents in the Member States of the European Communities](https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/documents/treaties-agreements/agreement/?id 1987011) done at Brussels on the May, 1987;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is an apostille recognized without further proof when issued by a Contracting State?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proof of Foreign Public Documents (Hague Convention 1961)* 13.[6] (1) In this rule: an “**apostille**” means an apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention; the “**1961 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Requirement of Legalisation for Foreign Public Documents done at The Hague on the October, 1961](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 41); a “**Contracting State**” means a State, other than Ireland, which is a party to the 1961 Convention other. (2) A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown. (3) This rule does not apply to any document to which rule 10, rule 11, or rule 12 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about a specific court case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47: Judgment In Default In Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a certificate under seal be filed instead of an affidavit when the claim is verified by a Minister or a statutory body?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim. (3) Where a respondent has executed a consent to judgment which has been duly witnessed, the applicant may file an affidavit ([Form 47.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36e14c1b-9b52-4447-958f-03255d2d12a7/Affidavit exhibiting consent No. 47.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule verifying the consent instead of an affidavit of debt; and where the consent is to judgment by instalments, the form of judgment (decree) in [Form 47.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ac82b1bc-3683-4311-9494-5fb6e362b178/Instalment judgment (decree) by consent No. 47.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be used. (4) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) must be given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. Judgment may not be given where the affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim was not sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) was not given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (5) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can judgment in default be given if the claim notice was sent abroad under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention without ensuring compliance with specific articles?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 3. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Service Regulation and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge directly make an order without a court sitting if they believe one is necessary?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 A Judge may issue a default judgment or refer to the Court* 4.(1) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court, and may fix the amount of costs and interest as is appropriate in the circumstances in accordance with the Schedule of Costs. (2) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is not satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may, or if the claimant so requests, the Judge must, refer the matter to the Court for decision. (3) An application to which rule 3 applies must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (4) If the Judge refers an application to the Court or an application is assigned a return date, the Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) make the order sought in the application; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed; - give directions as to the application; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (5) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (6) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant apply for judgment in default if the respondent fails to serve and file an appearance or defence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance and defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a claim other than a debt claim does not serve and file and appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claimant required to give the respondent notice before applying for judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application by motion on notice* 2. (1) In any case in which this Order applies, the claimant may, subject to the provisions of this rule, at any time after the respondent’s default in serving and filing an appearance or serving a defence, by motion on notice to the respondent served on the respondent not less than four clear days before the return date of the motion, apply to the Court for judgment. (2) Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and at the same time consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence within 14 days from the date of that letter. (3) If an appearance and defence is not served within 14 days from the date of that letter, the claimant may issue (by filing with the Clerk to obtain a return date) and serve a notice of motion for judgment in default which must be returnable to a return date not less than 14 days from the date of the service of the notice of motion. (4) An application under this rule must be supported— - by an affidavit or statutory declaration ([Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), [41.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1ce8e29-61fe-41d6-b1e4-0be6fe055224/Declaration as to service by ordinary post No. 41.02.docx/docx/1) or [41.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d590fd61-c2f8-49d3-9efa-e869eb833fc7/Statutory declaration as to personal service No. 41.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate) of service of the claim notice; and - by a certificate ([Form 47.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5d865ffc-a14c-473b-b3a1-7326645c45cd/Certificate of no appearance - defence No. 47.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule which may be endorsed on the verifying affidavit signed by the claimant’s solicitor or by the claimant (if acting in person) that no appearance, notice requiring particulars or defence has been received from the respondent; and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for an affidavit when the claim includes value-added tax?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Affidavit verifying claim* 4. (1) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply where the claimant relies on an affidavit of verification of a personal injuries summons made more than one month before the date of the application. (3) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can judgment in default be given if the claim notice was sent abroad under the Service Regulation and the respondent hasn''t served or filed an appearance and defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 5. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the [Service Regulation](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of [Article 15 of the Hague Convention](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 77) have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit and may be included in the affidavit verifying the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific procedure for notifying the claimant about orders or decisions made by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Return date* 6. (1) All applications by motion for judgment under this Order must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (2) The Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) give judgment on the claimant’s claim contained in the claim notice in such amount as the Court is satisfied is just; - give permission to the respondent to defend the whole or part of the claim on such terms as the Court considers just; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed, or adjourn the application for the hearing of further evidence; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (3) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (4) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court. (5) On the hearing of an application for judgment under this Order, the Court may make an Order for costs in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant continue legal action against other respondents after obtaining a default judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 7. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claimant treated as the respondent when considering their appearance to the counterclaim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant were the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Default of appearance and defence to counterclaim* 8. If a respondent serves a counterclaim, rules 1 to 6 apply as if— - (a) the respondent were the claimant; - a reference to the appearance in those rules were a reference to the appearance to the counterclaim; and - the claimant were the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant withdraw a part of their claim after receiving the respondent''s defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application), ... withdraw any part or parts of his alleged cause of action by written notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Discontinuance or withdrawal of claim or part of claim* 1. (1) The claimant may: - (a) before receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence; or - after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application), - wholly discontinue his claim against all or any of the respondents by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk; or - withdraw any part or parts of his alleged cause of action by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk. (2) Where a claimant serves a notice under sub-rule (1), the claimant must pay the respondent’s costs of the proceedings or, if the claim is not wholly discontinued, the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn. (3) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to small claims. (4) If not agreed, the applicable scale or amount of costs may be determined by the Court. (5) Discontinuance or withdrawal under sub-rule (1) is not a defence to any subsequent claim. (6) Save as provided in this Order, a claimant may not withdraw or discontinue a claim without the permission of the Court. (7) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the claimant’s application, order or permit the claim to be discontinued, or any part of the alleged cause of action to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Is the respondent entitled to judgment for costs if the proceedings are wholly discontinued against them?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Judgment for costs of discontinuance* 4. A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her, or for the costs occasioned by the matter withdrawn, if the action be not wholly discontinued, if the costs concerned are not paid within four days after their amount is agreed or fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court determine the scale of costs if it''s not specified or agreed upon?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Costs* 6. If the amount of costs referred to in this Order is not specified in the Schedule of Costs or is not agreed by the parties, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply, and if there is no such appropriate scale the Court may determine the amount of such costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant discontinue a small claim proceeding before it is referred to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a claimant may discontinue a small claim proceeding or withdraw any part of a small claim at any time before the small claim proceeding has been referred to the Court without the permission of the Court or the consent of the other parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claims—discontinuance or withdrawal of proceeding or claim* 7. Despite rule 1, a claimant may discontinue a small claim proceeding or withdraw any part of a small claim at any time before the small claim proceeding has been referred to the Court without the permission of the Court or the consent of the other parties. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents - Court: District # **Order 48: Authentication And Filing Of Documents****[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claim notice valid without being stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice is valid for all purposes if it has, where necessary, been stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Validity of claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice* 2. A claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice is valid for all purposes if it has, where necessary, been stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee, and bears the allocated Court number and the date of filing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk authenticate a document issued by the Court in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The signature of the Clerk for the time being assigned to the Court area in which the civil proceedings were brought is sufficient– to authenticate any order or document issued by the Court in civil proceedings other than an order which requires to bear the signature of the Judge"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Authentication of documents in civil proceedings* 3. (1) The signature of the Clerk for the time being assigned to the Court area in which the civil proceedings were brought is sufficient– - (a) to authenticate any order or document issued by the Court in civil proceedings other than an order which requires to bear the signature of the Judge; or - to certify as a copy- - any copy of a document issued by the Court in civil proceedings; or - any copy of a document filed in civil proceedings or sent to the Court by a party or other person. (2) A certified copy of a document mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be provided on payment of any applicable charges to: - (a) a party or party’s solicitor; - another person on the direction of the Court. 3A.[2] The Clerk may certify any printed version of the legible content of any original document which was transmitted to or by the Clerk as a certified copy of the original.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Must orders or warrants for attachment or committal be signed by a Judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any order or warrant for attachment or committal must be signed by a Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Orders signed by Judge* 4. Any order or warrant for attachment or committal must be signed by a Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the word ''Duplicate'' to be written or stamped on the duplicate document issued by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court permits the issue of a duplicate judgment, order or warrant, as the case may be, the word \"Duplicate\" must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Issue of duplicates* 5. (1) Where it appears to the Court that an original judgment, order or warrant in civil proceedings has been lost or destroyed or is unavailable to the parties, or to the party entitled to it, the Court may issue a duplicate of the judgment, order or warrant. (2) An application for a duplicate must be made on 48 hours'' notice to the opposite party and to the Clerk. (3) Where the Court permits the issue of a duplicate judgment, order or warrant, as the case may be, the word "Duplicate" must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document. [1] Order 48 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 48 Rule 3A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings - Court: District # Order 49: Hearing Of Civil Proceedings**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there evidence presented in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 - EVIDENCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court allow evidence to be provided through affidavits?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Oral evidence* 1. (1) Unless otherwise agreed in writing by all of the parties to the proceeding, and subject to these Rules and the law of evidence, witnesses at the trial of any claim must be examined orally on oath in open Court. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable. (3) An order may not be made authorising the evidence of a witness to be given by affidavit where it appears to the Court that another party bona fide requires the production of the witness for cross-examination, and that the witness can be produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court allow deposition evidence in certain cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a Court may order that a witness or other person be examined on oath and the order may permit a party to the proceedings to give the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Deposition evidence* 3. In any case where it appears necessary in the interests of justice, a Court may order that a witness or other person be examined on oath and the order may permit a party to the proceedings to give the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings on such terms, if any, as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a minimum notice period required when serving notice of trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Not less than ten days’ notice of trial must be given to the respondent and all other necessary parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Notice of trial* 4. (1) When an appearance and defence have been served and filed, the claimant may serve notice of trial ([Form 49.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/422a0eab-8d63-4467-acfe-66f7f11335c7/Notice of trial No. 49.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Not less than ten days’ notice of trial must be given to the respondent and all other necessary parties, save that the parties may agree that a shorter notice period must apply. (3) Notice of trial must be filed with the Clerk promptly following service, and a separate copy of the notice must be filed for each additional party. (4) Unless otherwise requested by the party giving notice of trial, or otherwise directed by the Court, notice of trial operates to set the claim (including any counterclaim) down for hearing at the next available time following the expiry of the period mentioned in the notice of trial as is assigned by the Clerk. (5) Unless the Court directs the Clerk otherwise, the next available time is at the next available sitting of the Court for civil business for the Court area in which the claim must be heard, at such time at which the claim comes on in its order in the list. (6) In any case in which the parties are agreed that the claim (and any counterclaim) is ready for hearing, the notice of trial may include any request agreed between the parties for the hearing to be specially fixed (and any reasons for such request), provided that the notice of trial is accompanied by a letter from the opposing party consenting to the request. (7) The Clerk may set down a claim (including any counterclaim) to which sub-rule (6) applies for hearing in accordance with any request, or may request the Court to give a direction in accordance with such request.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for issuing a notice of motion seeking discovery after serving notice of trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) The Clerk must notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed, and may do so by returning to that party a copy of the notice of trial with those details inserted. The party who has served notice of trial must promptly notify all other parties of the time and place at which the trial is listed. (9) No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the respondent serve the notice of trial if the claimant fails to do so within ten days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent''s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Service of notice of trial by respondent* 5. Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent apply to have a claim dismissed if the claimant does not serve notice of trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent may, instead of serving notice of trial in accordance with rule 5, apply to the Court by notice of motion to dismiss the claim for want of prosecution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Application to dismiss* 6. (1) If the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may, instead of serving notice of trial in accordance with rule 5, apply to the Court by notice of motion to dismiss the claim for want of prosecution. (2) On the hearing of an application under sub-rule (1), the Court may order the claim to be dismissed, and/or may make such other order, on such terms, as he or she considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**3 - TRIAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - TRIAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a counterclaim be pursued independently of the original claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Hearing of counterclaim* 9. (1) A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately. (2) If a counterclaim is proceeded with separately, it must be treated as a claim, irrespective of whether the original claim in which the counterclaim was made is withdrawn, stayed, discontinued or dismissed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a witness who is not a party be ordered to remain in court after giving evidence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Directions to witnesses* 10. A witness who is not a party may be ordered by the Court: - (a) to leave the Court until his evidence is required; or - to leave the Court after his or her evidence has been given; or - to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment be given in favor of one or more respondents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"judgment may be given for one or more claimants, and against or in favour of one or more respondents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Judgment* 11. Judgment (which may be recorded in one of the [Forms 49.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae2bca29-5e13-446e-a4da-d9c458134623/Judgment (decree) following trial - damages No. 49.03.docx/docx/1) to [49.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c73e68ac-3fad-49b0-a864-50126316776f/Judgment (decree) following trial for recovery of possession of premises (ejectment) No. 49.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary) may be given for one or more claimants, and against or in favour of one or more respondents (which may be recorded in [Form 49.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/95dc5b1c-1e17-4262-855d-018ff2f61e52/Judgment in favour of respondent (dismiss) following trial No. 49.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge adjourn a trial if they believe it is necessary for the sake of justice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Judge may, if he or she thinks it expedient in the interests of justice, postpone or adjourn a trial for such time, and on such terms, if any, as he or she thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Adjournment* 12. (1) The Judge may, if he or she thinks it expedient in the interests of justice, postpone or adjourn a trial for such time, and on such terms, if any, as he or she thinks just. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit any other power of the Court to adjourn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent get a dismissal judgment if they appear while the claimant does not?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Non-appearance at trial* 13. (1) If, when a case is called in Court, the claimant appears, and the respondent does not appear, the claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her. (2) If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim, but if he or she has a counterclaim, then he or she may prove the counterclaim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make an order regarding the payment schedule of a debt or damages?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Ancillary orders as to payment* 14. (1) When the Court has pronounced a judgment or made an order (or at any later time on notice being given to the opposite party), the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid. (2) If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order. (3) The Court may stay execution on foot of any judgment or order for such period and on such terms as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court dismiss a case without prejudice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to dismiss the claim either on the merits or without prejudice to the claimant’s right to proceed by a new claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Jurisdiction to give judgment or dismiss on the merits or without prejudice* 15. The Court has full jurisdiction in all cases to give judgment on the claim, or to dismiss the claim either on the merits or without prejudice to the claimant’s right to proceed by a new claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant continue with their case immediately after a ''without prejudice'' dismissal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Where a dismiss without prejudice is produced* 16. If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent produces an order of the Court dismissing the same cause of action by the claimant against the respondent without prejudice, the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order judgments to be set off against each other if they are of unequal amounts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Cross judgments may be set off* 17. (1) If: - (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or - there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties, the Court may, on the application of either party, order that the judgments be set off against each other. (2) If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the sale of a respondent''s goods if they fail to pay the ordered sum?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the amount not paid be levied by distress and sale of the goods of the respondent against whom the order was made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Order for recovery of rates and execution against goods in default of payment* 19. (1) Where the Court makes an order for the recovery of rates, the Court may direct that the sum be paid either at once or by instalments. (2) In an order to which sub-rule (1) applies, the Court may order that, in default of the sum being paid at the time and in the manner directed, the amount not paid be levied by distress and sale of the goods of the respondent against whom the order was made and by taking the money of the respondent against whom the order was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Is the case management order specified for a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49A - Case Management - Court: District # **Order 49A: Case Management******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court give directions to minimize the costs of proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"as appears convenient for the determination of the proceedings in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the cost of those proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Case management directions* 1. (1) The Court may, at any time and from time to time, of its own motion and having heard the parties, give such directions and make such orders, including the fixing of time limits, for the conduct of civil proceedings, as appears convenient for the determination of the proceedings in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the cost of those proceedings. (2) Except where these Rules provide otherwise, the Court may: - (a) ensure that the issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely, as possible; - give case management directions as to the steps which remain to be taken to prepare the case for trial, and the timetable for the completion of preparations of the case for trial, and for that purpose may adopt any timetable proposed by the parties if satisfied that it is reasonable; - make orders or give directions with respect to pleadings, the exchange between the parties of statements of issues, the identifying of issues in dispute between the parties, particulars, discovery, inspection of documents, or otherwise, which may be necessary or expedient; - make inquiries of the parties so as to ascertain the likely length of the trial and the arrangements, if any, for witnesses, information and communications technology (including video conferencing) and any other arrangements which require to be made for the trial; - fix the time and mode of trial, and may fix a date for trial and may also give directions as to the service of a notice of trial; - make any orders and give any directions in respect of arrangements for the trial as the Court considers necessary; - direct any expert witnesses to consult with each other within such time as the Court specifies for the purposes of— - identifying the issues in respect of which they intend to give evidence, - where possible, reaching agreement on the evidence that they intend to give in respect of those issues, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn a case to encourage alternative dispute resolution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court when considering case management directions, may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with Order to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Adjournment to facilitate ADR* 2. The Court when considering case management directions, may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution) to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to keep a record of all case management directions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk must maintain a record, which may be in electronic form, of all case management directions given."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Case management records* 3. (1) The Clerk must maintain a record, which may be in electronic form, of all case management directions given. (2) A copy of the case management directions must be placed on the Court file and a further copy of the case management directions must be made available to a party to the civil proceedings at the party’s request.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge who conducts a case management hearing decide not to preside over the trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge before whom a case management hearing has been conducted may determine that the trial of the civil proceeding should be before another Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Judge taking case management hearing may decline to hear trial* 5. A Judge before whom a case management hearing has been conducted may determine that the trial of the civil proceeding should be before another Judge. [1] Order 49A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to mediation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution - Court: District # Order Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn proceedings to facilitate mediation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, in accordance with section 16(2) of the 2017 Act—make an order adjourning the proceedings to such date as the Court considers just and convenient in all the circumstances"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Invitation to mediate; application for adjournment to facilitate mediation* 2. (1) The Court may, in civil proceedings to which the 2017 Act applies, in accordance with section 16(1) of the 2017 Act, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, where it considers it appropriate having regard to all the circumstances of the case: - (a) invite the parties to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings, and - provide the parties to the proceedings with information about the benefits of mediation to settle the dispute the subject of the proceedings. (2) Where, following an invitation by the Court, the parties decide to engage in mediation, the Court may, in accordance with section 16(2) of the 2017 Act— - (a) make an order adjourning the proceedings to such date as the Court considers just and convenient in all the circumstances, - make an order extending the time for compliance by a party with any relevant provision of these Rules or with any order of the Court in the proceedings, or - make such other order or give such direction as the Court considers necessary to facilitate the effective use of mediation. (3) An application by a party to civil proceedings under section 19(1) of the 2017 Act for an order adjourning the proceedings must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with Order 44, but need not be grounded on any affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application to dispense with the requirement for an affidavit be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by such a party under section 16(4) of the 2017 Act to dispense with the requirement for an affidavit may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Application for invitation to mediate* 3. An application by a party under section 16(1) of the 2017 Act must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with [Order 44]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-44-District-Applications-By-Notice-Of-Motion) within the period mentioned in section 16(4) of the 2017 Act. An application by such a party under section 16(4) of the 2017 Act to dispense with the requirement for an affidavit may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required regarding the service of the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceedings to enforce mediation settlement* 5. (1) An application under section 11(3) of the 2017 Act to enforce the terms of a mediation settlement must be made by notice of application in the [Form 49B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/145c6bab-3e2c-4867-b298-8368aa94e86d/Notice of application to enforce mediation settlement No. 49B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule grounded on an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party which must exhibit and verify the mediation settlement. (2) Copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits must be served, in accordance with Order 41, on each other party to the mediation settlement not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application to dispense with the requirement of giving a copy of the report to the parties be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 17(2) of the 2017 Act for a direction to dispense with the requirement that a copy of the report be given to the parties at least seven days prior to its submission to the Court may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Mediator’s report to Court* 6. (1) A mediator’s report required by section 17 of the Act must be entitled as in the proceedings to which it relates and must be submitted to the Court by the lodgment by the mediator with the Clerk of an affidavit verifying and exhibiting the report. (2) An application under section 17(2) of the 2017 Act for a direction to dispense with the requirement that a copy of the report be given to the parties at least seven days prior to its submission to the Court may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn proceedings to encourage alternative dispute resolution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and -"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 7. (1) The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or - where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process, and may, for the purposes of such invitation or reference, invite the parties to attend such information session on the use of such other ADR process, if any, as the Court may specify. (2) Where the parties decide to use another ADR process, the Court may make an order extending the time for compliance by any party with any pro vision of these Rules or any order of the Court in the proceedings, and may make such further or other orders or give such directions as the Court considers will facilitate the effective use of that process.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for adjournment be made without a motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made without such motion at any other time when the proceedings are before the Court, including at a case management hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Application for adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 8. An application by a party for an order under rule 7 may be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, or may be made without such motion at any other time when the proceedings are before the Court, including at a case management hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court allow evidence to be presented through affidavits instead of oral testimony?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Oral evidence* 1. (1) Unless otherwise agreed in writing by all of the parties to the proceeding, and subject to these Rules and the law of evidence, witnesses at the trial of any claim must be examined orally on oath in open Court. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable. (3) An order may not be made authorising the evidence of a witness to be given by affidavit where it appears to the Court that another party bona fide requires the production of the witness for cross-examination, and that the witness can be produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time limit for issuing a notice of motion seeking discovery after serving notice of trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) The Clerk must notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed, and may do so by returning to that party a copy of the notice of trial with those details inserted. The party who has served notice of trial must promptly notify all other parties of the time and place at which the trial is listed. (9) No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a counterclaim be handled independently of the original claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Hearing of counterclaim* 9. (1) A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately. (2) If a counterclaim is proceeded with separately, it must be treated as a claim, irrespective of whether the original claim in which the counterclaim was made is withdrawn, stayed, discontinued or dismissed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a witness be ordered to stay in court after giving evidence until the trial ends?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Directions to witnesses* 10. A witness who is not a party may be ordered by the Court: - (a) to leave the Court until his evidence is required; or - to leave the Court after his or her evidence has been given; or - to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can judgment be given in favor of one or more respondents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"judgment may be given for one or more claimants, and against or in favour of one or more respondents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Judgment* 11. Judgment (which may be recorded in one of the [Forms 49.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae2bca29-5e13-446e-a4da-d9c458134623/Judgment (decree) following trial - damages No. 49.03.docx/docx/1) to [49.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c73e68ac-3fad-49b0-a864-50126316776f/Judgment (decree) following trial for recovery of possession of premises (ejectment) No. 49.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary) may be given for one or more claimants, and against or in favour of one or more respondents (which may be recorded in [Form 49.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/95dc5b1c-1e17-4262-855d-018ff2f61e52/Judgment in favour of respondent (dismiss) following trial No. 49.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent be granted judgment dismissing the claim if they appear while the claimant does not?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Non-appearance at trial* 13. (1) If, when a case is called in Court, the claimant appears, and the respondent does not appear, the claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her. (2) If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim, but if he or she has a counterclaim, then he or she may prove the counterclaim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court delay the issuance of an execution order if instalment payments are ordered?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Ancillary orders as to payment* 14. (1) When the Court has pronounced a judgment or made an order (or at any later time on notice being given to the opposite party), the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid. (2) If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order. (3) The Court may stay execution on foot of any judgment or order for such period and on such terms as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claimant prohibited from proceeding with their case if they have previously been dismissed without prejudice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Where a dismiss without prejudice is produced* 16. If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent produces an order of the Court dismissing the same cause of action by the claimant against the respondent without prejudice, the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order that judgments be set off against each other if there are unexecuted or partially executed judgments between the same parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If: (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties, the Court may, on the application of either party, order that the judgments be set off against each other."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Cross judgments may be set off* 17. (1) If: - (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or - there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties, the Court may, on the application of either party, order that the judgments be set off against each other. (2) If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Is the case management order associated with a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49A - Case Management - Court: District # **Order 49A: Case Management******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court give directions on the steps remaining to prepare a case for trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"give case management directions as to the steps which remain to be taken to prepare the case for trial, and the timetable for the completion of preparations of the case for trial"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Case management directions* 1. (1) The Court may, at any time and from time to time, of its own motion and having heard the parties, give such directions and make such orders, including the fixing of time limits, for the conduct of civil proceedings, as appears convenient for the determination of the proceedings in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the cost of those proceedings. (2) Except where these Rules provide otherwise, the Court may: - (a) ensure that the issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely, as possible; - give case management directions as to the steps which remain to be taken to prepare the case for trial, and the timetable for the completion of preparations of the case for trial, and for that purpose may adopt any timetable proposed by the parties if satisfied that it is reasonable; - make orders or give directions with respect to pleadings, the exchange between the parties of statements of issues, the identifying of issues in dispute between the parties, particulars, discovery, inspection of documents, or otherwise, which may be necessary or expedient; - make inquiries of the parties so as to ascertain the likely length of the trial and the arrangements, if any, for witnesses, information and communications technology (including video conferencing) and any other arrangements which require to be made for the trial; - fix the time and mode of trial, and may fix a date for trial and may also give directions as to the service of a notice of trial; - make any orders and give any directions in respect of arrangements for the trial as the Court considers necessary; - direct any expert witnesses to consult with each other within such time as the Court specifies for the purposes of— - identifying the issues in respect of which they intend to give evidence, - where possible, reaching agreement on the evidence that they intend to give in respect of those issues, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court suggest alternative dispute resolution methods to the parties involved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court when considering case management directions, may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with Order to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Adjournment to facilitate ADR* 2. The Court when considering case management directions, may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution) to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to mediation and alternative dispute resolution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution - Court: District # Order Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''mediation'' defined in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"each of the expressions “mediation”, “mediation settlement” and “mediator” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the 2017 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order: the “**2017 Act**” means the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No 27 of 2017); each of the expressions “**mediation**”, “**mediation settlement**” and “**mediator**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the 2017 Act; “**another ADR process**” means conciliation or another dispute resolution pro cess approved by the Court, but does not include mediation or arbitration.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required to be lodged with the Clerk regarding the service of the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceedings to enforce mediation settlement* 5. (1) An application under section 11(3) of the 2017 Act to enforce the terms of a mediation settlement must be made by notice of application in the [Form 49B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/145c6bab-3e2c-4867-b298-8368aa94e86d/Notice of application to enforce mediation settlement No. 49B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule grounded on an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party which must exhibit and verify the mediation settlement. (2) Copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits must be served, in accordance with Order 41, on each other party to the mediation settlement not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can a mediator apply parte for dispensing with the requirement of giving parties a copy of the report at least seven days before submitting it to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 17(2) of the 2017 Act for a direction to dispense with the requirement that a copy of the report be given to the parties at least seven days prior to its submission to the Court may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Mediator’s report to Court* 6. (1) A mediator’s report required by section 17 of the Act must be entitled as in the proceedings to which it relates and must be submitted to the Court by the lodgment by the mediator with the Clerk of an affidavit verifying and exhibiting the report. (2) An application under section 17(2) of the 2017 Act for a direction to dispense with the requirement that a copy of the report be given to the parties at least seven days prior to its submission to the Court may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adjourn proceedings to encourage the use of alternative dispute resolution methods?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 7. (1) The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or - where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process, and may, for the purposes of such invitation or reference, invite the parties to attend such information session on the use of such other ADR process, if any, as the Court may specify. (2) Where the parties decide to use another ADR process, the Court may make an order extending the time for compliance by any party with any pro vision of these Rules or any order of the Court in the proceedings, and may make such further or other orders or give such directions as the Court considers will facilitate the effective use of that process.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the time limit extended when a case goes into mediation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the time for taking any step in a proceeding under any of those Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be calculated as if time did not run during the period of any adjournment to facilitate the mediation or other ADR process"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Extension of time limits* 10. Despite any other provision of these Rules, if a proceeding is referred to mediation or an other ADR process, the time for taking any step in a proceeding under any of those Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be calculated as if time did not run during the period of any adjournment to facilitate the mediation or other ADR process. [1] Order originally inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a Civil Bill required to start civil proceedings in the Circuit Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Civil proceedings in the Court shall, unless otherwise provided by Statute or by these Rules, be instituted by the issue of a Civil Bill"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings - Court: Circuit 1. Civil proceedings in the Court shall, unless otherwise provided by Statute or by these Rules, be instituted by the issue of a Civil Bill, which shall be in the appropriate form in accordance with the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) to these Rules (being Forms 2A to 20), or such modification thereof as may be suitable and shall state such facts as may be necessary to show the jurisdiction of the Court. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) Civil Bill Ejectments on the title and Civil Bills issued for the purpose of establishing questions of title to land, other than ejectments for overholding or for non-payment of rent, shall be headed "**Title Jurisdiction**" and shall contain, as the case may be, - (a) a statement that the market value (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html)) of the land does not exceed €3,000,000 or - such statement of the rent as shall show jurisdiction. At the hearing of any such case the plaintiff may be required to produce a map of the land. 3.[[2]](#_ftn2) (1) Subject to [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-Circuit-Actions-by-and-against-firms-and-persons-carrying-on-business-in-names-other-than-their-own), the Civil Bill shall state: - (a) the given or first name, surname, occupation and residence or place of business of the plaintiff; - the surname of the defendant, his residence or place of business, and, where known, his given or first name and his occupation, and, if the defendant is sued in a representative capacity, the capacity in which he is sued. (2) A solicitor acting for a plaintiff shall additionally indorse upon the Civil Bill his or her name or that of his or her firm and: - the registered place of business where documents may be left for him or her, and - where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff suing in person consent to receiving documents via email instead of physical delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the plaintiff consents to the receipt of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of an address for service) to which documents may be sent in electronic form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) The indorsement required by sub-rules (1) and (2) shall be in the following form: “This Civil Bill was issued by......., whose registered place of business is........, \*[and who consents to the service of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail to ............... ], solicitor for the plaintiff, ........., who \*[resides/has his/her place of business] at...... and is..........” (4) A plaintiff suing in person shall additionally indorse upon the Civil Bill: - an address for service, where documents may be left for him or her, and - where the plaintiff consents to the receipt of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of an address for service) to which documents may be sent in electronic form. (5) The indorsement required by sub-rules (1) and (4) shall be in the following form: “This Civil Bill was issued by the plaintiff,......., who \*[resides/has his/her place of business] at...... and is.......... \*[and who consents to the service of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail to ...............],” 4. The Civil Bill shall call upon a defendant to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the plaintiff, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 5. Every Civil Bill shall be signed by the plaintiff, or by his Solicitor, and shall be endorsed with particulars of the plaintiff’s demand:—'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the plaintiff to state the specific amount that needs to be accounted for if they desire an account to be taken?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If, in the first instance, the plaintiff desires an account to be taken, that fact shall be stated, together with the specific amount (if any) which the plaintiff claims to be subject to that account"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(*a*) stating the nature, extent and grounds thereof, full particulars of all items of special damage being claimed and the relief sought and, where it is a money claim, the amount thereof and the rate and amount of interest (if any) claimed. If, in the first instance, the plaintiff desires an account to be taken, that fact shall be stated, together with the specific amount (if any) which the plaintiff claims to be subject to that account; where there is more than one claim, stating like particulars of each claim to those in paragraph (*a*), and the relief sought in respect of each; stating the abandonment of any part of a claim, if the plaintiff desires abandonment in order to bring the claim within the jurisdiction; where the plaintiff sues in a representative capacity, stating the capacity in which he sues; and where the plaintiff sues as assignee, stating the name, address and description of the assignor at the date of the assignment, and the date of such assignment. 5A.[[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) In the case of proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), the indorsement of claim shall contain a statement - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board](https://www.injuries.ie/eng/) - specifying the section of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html) or the rule made under section 46(3) of that Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific schedule mentioned for determining costs when there has not been any special service out of the jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The amount to be so claimed for costs in all such cases where there has not been any order for service of the Civil Bill, or notice thereof, out of the jurisdiction, or for substituted or other service, or declaring service effected sufficient, or any notice by advertisement of the issuing of the Civil Bill, shall be in accordance with a Schedule of fees to be determined by the County Registrar for the County of the City of Dublin from time to time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '6. Whenever the plaintiff’s claim is for a debt or liquidated claim only, the endorsement, besides stating the nature of the claim shall state the amount claimed for debt or in respect of such demand, and for costs, respectively, and shall further state that, upon payment of such amount and costs within six days after service, further proceedings will be stayed. The amount to be so claimed for costs in all such cases where there has not been any order for service of the Civil Bill, or notice thereof, out of the jurisdiction, or for substituted or other service, or declaring service effected sufficient, or any notice by advertisement of the issuing of the Civil Bill, shall be in accordance with a Schedule of fees to be determined by the County Registrar for the County of the City of Dublin from time to time. If there are more defendants than one, the above amounts may be increased by a reasonable sum for each additional defendant served. 7. Where, by any Statute not mentioned in these Rules, proceedings are authorised or directed to be taken in the Court, such proceedings shall be commenced by Civil Bill. 8.[[5]](#_ftn5) The Consent prescribed by Section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html) which provides for the enlargement of the jurisdiction of the Court by consent of the parties shall be in the form set forth in [Form 1](/content/consent-enlargement-jurisdiction) of the Schedule of Forms, and shall be lodged with the County Registrar either before or at any time during the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 5 - Judges'' Robes', 'Court Rules', 'Did the new rules amend the existing District Court Rules 1997?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The District Court Rules 1997 are amended by the substitution for Order 5 of the Order set out in the Schedule."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5 - Judges'' Robes - Court: District # District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017****[1]**** 1. (1) These Rules, which shall come into operation on the day of March 2017, may be cited as the District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the District Court Rules 1997 ([S.I. No. 93 of 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93/made/en/print)) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the District Court Rules 1997 to 2017. 2. The District Court Rules 1997 ([S.I. No. 93 of 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93/made/en/print)) are amended by the substitution for Order 5 of the Order set out in the Schedule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 5 - Judges'' Robes', 'Court Rules', 'Do judges have the option to wear different attire when dealing with cases involving children?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge, when hearing and determining such proceedings as are referred to in section 45(1) of the Judicial Separation and Family Law Reform Act 1989 or proceedings involving a child shall not be required to wear either such gown but shall during the sittings of the Court wear white bands or a single white neck tab and dark attire."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Schedule 1. (1) Save as otherwise provided by Statute or these Rules, the official attire to be worn by the Judges during the sittings of the Court shall be as follows: - (a) a black coat and gown of uniform nature and material and white bands or - a black gown of uniform nature and material with sleeves bearing blue double ribbon banding and a single white neck tab or white bands. (2) A Judge appointed to the Court after the coming into operation of sub-rule (1) and this sub-rule shall wear the official attire specified in paragraph of sub-rule (1). 2. A Judge, when hearing and determining such proceedings as are referred to in [section 45(1)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/6/section/45/enacted/en/html#sec45) of the [Judicial Separation and Family Law Reform Act 1989 (No. 6 of 1989)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/6/enacted/en/html) or proceedings involving a child shall not be required to wear either such gown but shall during the sittings of the Court wear white bands or a single white neck tab and dark attire. [1] Order 5 substituted by [S.I. 77 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/77/made/en/print?q 77&years 2017), effective 15 March 2017'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about legal roles such as trustees, executors, and administrators?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is it the responsibility of the officer issuing the summons to assign it to a specific judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"it shall be the duty of the officer issuing the summons to mark and assign the summons for the Judge assigned as mentioned in the said rule or (if more than one Judge has been so assigned) for the Judges so assigned in rotation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Every originating summons relating to such other matter or matters as Rules of Court may from time to time specify. 5. In the case of any originating summons within rule 4, it shall be the duty of the officer issuing the summons to mark and assign the summons for the Judge assigned as mentioned in the said rule or (if more than one Judge has been so assigned) for the Judges so assigned in rotation. Any case of doubt or difficulty shall be determined by the Master and the assignment or non-assignment of any summons at the time of issue shall be without prejudice to the power of the Master to vary or alter such assignment or non-assignment. 6. Where an originating summons has been so assigned under rules 4 and 5 to a particular Judge or has (whether assigned or not) been heard by a particular Judge, every subsequent summons, notice of motion, or petition, relating to the same matter, or so connected therewith as to be conveniently dealt with by the same Judge, shall whenever practicable be marked by the proper officer with the name of such Judge, and the party or solicitor presenting such summons, notice of motion, or petition, shall, if there be to his knowledge such relation or connection, so certify. Such certificate shall be in the [Form No 5 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon2); and such certificate shall be countersigned by the Registrar of the Judge to whom such originating summons had been assigned or by whom such originating summons had been heard as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is the originating summons required to be sealed and marked with the record number?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every originating summons shall be sealed and marked with the record number by the proper officer, and shall thereupon be deemed to be issued."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. There shall be books in the Central Office to be called Cause Books in which all proceedings commenced by originating summons, issued out of the Central Office, shall be entered. Every summons shall be entered consecutively in order of issue and shall be distinguished by the date of the year and a number in consecutive order commencing on the first day of January in each year, with or without a distinguishing letter or other sign; and the said date and number, together with the distinguishing letter or sign (if any) shall constitute the record number of the proceeding. 8. Every originating summons shall bear date of the day of issue and shall be authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice, or if the office of Chief Justice be vacant, in the name of the President of the Court of Appeal[[2]](#_ftn2) and shall be sealed with the seal of the High Court. 9. Every originating summons shall be sealed and marked with the record number by the proper officer, and shall thereupon be deemed to be issued. No originating summons shall be served until the same shall have been so sealed and marked. 10. One duplicate or more of every originating summons shall be so sealed and marked on the application of the plaintiff or his solicitor. 11. The plaintiff or other party or his solicitor shall, on presenting an originating summons for sealing, leave with the proper officer a copy, written or printed, or partly written and partly printed, on paper of the description aforesaid, of such summons and all the indorsements thereon, and such copy shall be signed by the solicitor leaving the same, or by the plaintiff himself if he sues in person. 12. The officer receiving the copy summons pursuant to rule 11 shall cause the same to be marked with the record number and to be filed and shall also cause an entry of the particulars thereof to be made in the appropriate Cause Book as herein before provided.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is a plaintiff required to obtain court leave before issuing a summons for service outside the jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. The issue of a summons in probate proceedings shall be preceded by the filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons. On issuing the summons the plaintiff shall, if he has not already so done, lodge a caveat in the Probate Office entitled in the estate of the deceased person. 14. [[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) [[5]](#_ftn5) (1) Save as is otherwise provided for in these Rules, no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court. (2) Service of an originating summons or other originating document or notice of an originating summons or other originating document out of the jurisdiction is permissible without the leave of the Court, if, but only if, it complies with the following conditions: - each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and - no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention. 15. Save as otherwise provided in these Rules, every petition to the Court shall be presented by leaving it with the proper officer at the Central Office. Subject thereto, the foregoing provisions of this Order shall apply to a petition in the same manner as they apply to an originating summons, and references in this Order to “**originating summons**” and “**plaintiff**” shall be construed as including references to “**petition**” and “**petitioner**” respectively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a minimum of two clear days between the service and the hearing of a petition unless the court grants permission otherwise?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '16. At the foot of every petition presented to the Court, and of every copy thereof, a statement shall be made of the persons, if any, intended to be served therewith, and if no person is intended to be served a statement to that effect shall be made at the foot of the petition and of every copy thereof. 17. Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 5 rule substituted by 149 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2010/en.si.2010.0149.pdf). 149 of 2010 is effective 10 May 2010, subject to paragraph 2 which reads: “Any application for registration of a lis pendens containing the particulars required by law before 1 December 2009 for such registration which is received after 1 December 2009 and prior to the date mentioned in paragraph 1 shall be deemed to comply with the requirements for registration of a lis pendens in accordance with section 121 of the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009.” [[2]](#_ftnref2) “President of the Court of Appeal” substituted for “President of the High Court” by 404 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/404/made/en/print), effective 2 October 2017. [[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 5 rule 14 substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) by 14 of 1989](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1989/en/si/0014.html), effective 1 February 1989. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 5 rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) were substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2)(1) and 14(2)(2) by 506 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0506.html), effective 10 August 2005. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 5 rule 14(2) substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about affidavits in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a videoconference defined in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**videoconference**\"[1] includes any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- reference to an affidavit includes reference to any affidavit, solemn affirmation or the acknowledgment of any deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**deponent**” means a person making an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court, but includes reference to a person making a solemn affirmation or acknowledgment of a deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**relevant document**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html), “**videoconference**”[1] includes any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can an affidavit be sworn via videoconference if it''s not practical for the deponent to attend in person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Making an affidavit* 2.[2] (1) Subject to sub-rule (2), all affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court (which may be in the [Form 50.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b849640e-dfd9-4e8d-b505-99429c139026/Affidavit - general No. 50.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made before a Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court, or a practising solicitor (in the remainder of this sub-rule, the “officer”). (2) Where the person making an affidavit resides outside the State, or is for the time being outside the State, the affidavit may be made before any person authorised by law to administer oaths in the place where the person making the affidavit resides or is. (3) An affidavit sworn in the State may be sworn by the deponent- - (a) in the physical presence of the officer before whom it is to be sworn, or - where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer, subject to and in accordance with sub-rule (4). (4) Where an affidavit is sworn in the manner referred to in sub-rule the following conditions shall be complied with - - (a) the officer shall be provided in advance or at the videoconference with a copy (which may be in electronic form) of the affidavit, copies of any exhibits referred to in it and, in a case where rule 6(b)(iii) applies, a certified copy of the relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; - the officer shall be satisfied that the videoconference facility enables the deponent to see and hear the officer and to be seen and heard by the officer; - in a case to which rule 6(b)(ii) applies, the officer shall ensure that the requirement in the paragraph concerned for identification of the deponent has been met before the affidavit is sworn; - the officer shall satisfy himself that the appropriate sacred text for taking the oath is available to the deponent;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the officer required to ensure that the documents received after the videoconference are the same as those shown during the call?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the officer shall before attesting the affidavit and signing or marking any and every exhibit referred to in it, satisfy himself that the document (and each and any exhibit) is the same as that which had been identified to him during the videoconference"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- during the videoconference and within sight and hearing of the officer, the deponent shall produce the original of any relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; shall identify each page of the affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it, shall sign or mark any and every exhibit, and shall sign and swear the affidavit; - the sworn affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it shall immediately following the videoconference be sent to the officer, for attestation by the officer; - the officer shall before attesting the affidavit and signing or marking any and every exhibit referred to in it, satisfy himself that the document (and each and any exhibit) is the same as that which had been identified to him during the videoconference and, where relevant, sign and append to the affidavit the certified copy of the relevant document used to verify the deponent’s identity, and - notwithstanding rule 6, the jurat of the affidavit shall indicate the date on which the affidavit was made by the deponent, the place at which the officer was when taking the affidavit and the fact that the affidavit was sworn using a videoconference.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Must all affidavits for civil proceedings in the Court include the title of the case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"include the title of the civil proceedings in which they are sworn."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Form of affidavit* 3. All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) be written or printed book-wise; - be expressed in the first person of the deponent; be drawn up in numbered paragraphs; and - include the title of the civil proceedings in which they are sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the deponent required to provide their place of residence or place of business in an affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the deponent’s place of business, or the deponent’s place of residence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Particulars of deponent and other requirements* 4.[3] All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) state the deponent’s occupation and - the deponent’s place of business, or - the deponent’s place of residence; - state that the deponent is over 18 years of age, but if the deponent is under 18 years of age, the affidavit must state the deponent’s exact age; - be confined to such facts as the deponent is able to prove of his or her own knowledge; - state the deponent’s means of knowledge of the facts sworn, except on interlocutory motions, on which a statement by the deponent as to his or her belief, and the grounds of his or her belief, may be admitted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit invalid if it was sworn before the solicitor representing the party using the affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Affidavit may not be sworn before solicitor for party* 5. No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used, or before the partner, agent, correspondent or clerk of that solicitor, or before the party himself.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the person taking the affidavit to state the date and place when the affidavit is taken?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: ... must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Attestation by person taking affidavit and jurat* 6. Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit; otherwise the affidavit must be taken not to be authentic and must not be filed without the permission of the Court; - must certify in the jurat either: - that he personally knows the deponent, or - that the deponent has been identified to him or her by some person personally known to him or her and named in the jurat who certifies his personal knowledge of the deponent, or - (iii) that the identity of the deponent has been established by him or her by reference to a relevant document containing a photograph of the deponent before the affidavit was taken, and in a case to which paragraph (iii) applies, must give particulars of the relevant document concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a special certification process required when an affidavit is taken from someone who is illiterate or blind?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person taking the affidavit must certify that: (a) the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent; that the deponent appeared to understand it, and that the deponent made his or her signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Additional requirements for affidavit by illiterate or blind person* 7. (1) When an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court is sworn or made by a person who appears to the person taking the affidavit to be illiterate or blind, the person taking the affidavit must certify that: - (a) the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent; - that the deponent appeared to understand it, and - that the deponent made his or her signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit. (2) No affidavit mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be used in evidence in the absence of the certificate mentioned in sub-rule (1) unless the Court is otherwise satisfied that the affidavit was read over to, and appeared to be understood by, the deponent. (3)[4] Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the interpreter to confirm their qualifications when filing a foreign language affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his or her qualifications as an interpreter"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Additional requirements for swearing and filing a foreign language affidavit* 9. (1) Where the deponent appears to the person taking an affidavit not to be capable of understanding one of the official languages of the State, the person taking the affidavit must: - (a) ensure that the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8; and - ensure that the affidavit is read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter in the presence of the person taking the affidavit, and that the deponent has fully understood it; and - certify in the jurat that the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, that the deponent fully understood it and that the deponent signed the foreign language affidavit in his or her presence. (2) Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit. (3) Where the translator and interpreter are one and the same person, a single affidavit may be sworn by that person for the purposes of rule 8(3) and this rule. (4) No foreign language affidavit may be used in evidence in the absence of the affidavit referred to in rule 8(3), unless the Court is otherwise satisfied as to the evidence contained in the foreign language affidavit. (5)[5] Notwithstanding paragraph of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can an affidavit with alterations be used in court without permission if it meets certain conditions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit; or ... in the case of an erasure, the words or figures appearing at the time of taking the affidavit and erased are re-written and signed or initialled in the margin of the affidavit by the person taking it."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Amendments* 11. An affidavit which has in either the body or the jurat any interlineation, alteration, or erasure, may not be filed, read, or made use of in any civil proceeding in the Court without the permission of the Court unless: - (a) the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit; or - in the case of an erasure, the words or figures appearing at the time of taking the affidavit and erased are re-written and signed or initialled in the margin of the affidavit by the person taking it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court accept an affidavit even if there are defects in the description of the parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may receive any affidavit sworn for the purpose of being used in civil proceedings in the Court: despite any defect by misdescription of the parties or otherwise in the title or in the jurat;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Power of Court to receive defective affidavit* 12. The Court may receive any affidavit sworn for the purpose of being used in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) despite any defect by misdescription of the parties or otherwise in the title or in the jurat; or - despite any other irregularity in its form, and where the Court does so, it may direct a memorandum to be made on the document that it has been so received.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for affidavits to be filed with the Clerk before being used in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before an affidavit is used in civil proceedings in the Court, it must be filed with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Filing of affidavits* 13. (1) Before an affidavit is used in civil proceedings in the Court, it must be filed with the Clerk. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not prevent the Judge from making an order on the undertaking of the applicant or his solicitor to file any affidavit sworn before the making of the order, or permitted by the Judge to be made after the order, provided that the Judge may stay the issue of any order until the affidavit has been filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to write the filing date on an affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Date of filing* 14. The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on using affidavits after a specified time period without court approval?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Affidavit may not be used after limited time without permission* 15. Where a special time is limited for delivering or filing an affidavit, no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Must documents referred to in an affidavit be attached directly to the affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Exhibits* 16. (1) Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits. (2) Every certificate on an exhibit referred to in an affidavit signed by the person before whom the affidavit is sworn must be marked with the short title of the civil proceedings. (3) Nothing in this rule requires or authorises any marking on an original will which has not been admitted to probate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order a party to bear the costs of an affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17 Costs of affidavit* 17. The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which: - (a) unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, or - which contains argumentative matter, or - which is of unnecessary length, regardless of the outcome of the hearing at which it is used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party require the deponent to attend a trial or hearing for cross-examination?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a party may, by written notice served on the party relying on the affidavit concerned at least seven days before the trial or hearing, require the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, for the purpose of being cross-examined."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18 Court or party may require attendance of deponent* 18. (1) The Court may direct the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, where it considers the deponent’s attendance necessary in the interests of justice. (2) Unless the Court has ordered otherwise, a party may, by written notice served on the party relying on the affidavit concerned at least seven days before the trial or hearing, require the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, for the purpose of being cross-examined. (3) In any case mentioned in sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2) in which the deponent does not attend at the trial or hearing. the affidavit may not be used, unless the Court orders otherwise. [1] Order 50, rule 1 definition of “**videoconference**” inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [2] Order 50, rule 2 substituted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [3] Order 50, rule 4 substituted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [4] Order 50, rule 7(3) inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [5] Order 50, rule 9(5) inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021 **Related link** [S.I. No. 17 of 2014 - provisions overview](https://www.courts.ie/rules/si-no-17-2014-district-court-civil-procedure-rules-2014-provisions-overview)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to the execution and enforcement of judgments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments - Court: District # **Order 51: Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Is a warrant of execution considered a type of warrant in this context?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**warrant of execution**” or, when used without qualification, “**warrant**” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— “**warrant of execution**” or, when used without qualification, “**warrant**” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment be executed more than six years after it was given without special permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Duration of judgments* 3. (1) Judgments remain in full force and effect for twelve years from the date on which they were given or made, but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court. (2) An application for permission to execute after six years must be made by notice of motion, which must be served on the person sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party apply to the court to amend a judgment if there is a change in the parties involved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If, at any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, a change takes place, by death, assignment or otherwise, in the parties, a party may apply to the Court on notice served on the other party to have the judgment amended accordingly."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Change of parties* 4. (1) If, at any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, a change takes place, by death, assignment or otherwise, in the parties, a party may apply to the Court on notice served on the other party to have the judgment amended accordingly. (2) If satisfied that the party applying under sub-rule (1) is entitled to execution, the Court may make any appropriate order and may make any amendment to a judgment required to give effect to that order and may impose such terms as to costs or otherwise as appear just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can enforcement of a joint judgment proceed against one of multiple respondents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the judgment or order may be enforced by warrant or otherwise against any of the respondents as if the order had been made against that respondent separately."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Execution against two or more persons* 5. (1) If a judgment is given or made against two or more respondents jointly, the judgment or order may be enforced by warrant or otherwise against any of the respondents as if the order had been made against that respondent separately. (2) If an order against two or more respondents jointly is satisfied by any of the respondents, no further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favour the order so satisfied was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can execution be issued against a partner who was out of the state when the claim notice was issued?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Except as against any property of the partnership, a judgment against a firm does not render liable, or otherwise affect any member of the partnership who was out of the State when the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued, and who has not entered an appearance unless he has been made a party to the civil proceedings under Order 43, or has been served within the jurisdiction after the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Execution against partners* 6. (1) Where a judgment or order is against a firm, execution may issue: - (a) against any property of the partnership within the State; - against any person who has appeared in his own name under [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), rule 22 and has failed to deliver a defence, or who has admitted on the pleadings that he is, or who has been adjudged to be, a partner. (2) If the person who has obtained judgment claims to be entitled to issue execution against any other person as being a member of the firm, he or she may apply to the Court on notice to that other person for permission to do so. (3) The Court may give permission to issue execution if the liability is not disputed. If the liability is disputed, the Court may order that the liability be tried and determined in any manner in which any issue or question in any action may be tried and determined. (4) Except as against any property of the partnership, a judgment against a firm does not render liable, or otherwise affect any member of the partnership who was out of the State when the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued, and who has not entered an appearance unless he has been made a party to the civil proceedings under [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), or has been served within the jurisdiction after the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Do the rules of the Circuit Court apply to the execution of warrants by a County Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution apply, with such modifications as are necessary, to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Application of certain rules, practice and procedure of Circuit Court* 7. Subject to this Order and except where otherwise expressly provided by these Rules, the rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution apply, with such modifications as are necessary, to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant issued to one County Registrar be executed by another County Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant addressed to a County Registrar may be executed by another County Registrar if the person against whom the warrant has been issued has goods within the county for which that other County Registrar acts."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Execution by another County Registrar* 8. A warrant addressed to a County Registrar may be executed by another County Registrar if the person against whom the warrant has been issued has goods within the county for which that other County Registrar acts.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Is the seizure of goods mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"SEIZURE OF GOODS IN SATISFACTION OF JUDGMENT FOR MONEY OR COSTS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2****-****SEIZURE OF GOODS IN SATISFACTION OF JUDGMENT FOR MONEY OR COSTS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can the period for selling seized goods by auction be extended beyond one month?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the Court may from time to time extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire and so on from time to time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Execution of warrants* 10. (1) Where a warrant is for the payment of money and goods are seized under the warrant the person to whom the warrant is addressed may sell the goods by auction within the period fixed by the warrant or, if no period is so fixed, within one month from the day on which the goods were seized, unless the sum for which the warrant was issued and the expenses of taking and keeping the goods are paid before the goods are sold. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire and so on from time to time. (3) Where goods are sold under sub-rule (1), the surplus, if any, after retaining: - (a) the amount to be levied; and - all reasonable expenses actually incurred in auctioning the goods; and - the expenses of taking and keeping the goods, must be paid to the person from whom the goods were seized. (4) The person conducting an auction under this rule need not procure a licence to act as an auctioneer. (5) Where the person against whom a warrant under rule 2 is issued pays or tenders to the person responsible for the execution of the warrant the amount to be levied by the warrant, the person responsible for the execution of the warrant must refrain from executing the warrant. (6) When any money is levied or paid to a court messenger under any warrant, the court messenger must give a receipt for the money.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section about legal roles such as trustees, executors and administrators?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for an originating summons to be sealed and marked with the record number before it can be served?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No originating summons shall be served until the same shall have been so sealed and marked."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. There shall be books in the Central Office to be called Cause Books in which all proceedings commenced by originating summons, issued out of the Central Office, shall be entered. Every summons shall be entered consecutively in order of issue and shall be distinguished by the date of the year and a number in consecutive order commencing on the first day of January in each year, with or without a distinguishing letter or other sign; and the said date and number, together with the distinguishing letter or sign (if any) shall constitute the record number of the proceeding. 8. Every originating summons shall bear date of the day of issue and shall be authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice, or if the office of Chief Justice be vacant, in the name of the President of the Court of Appeal[[2]](#_ftn2) and shall be sealed with the seal of the High Court. 9. Every originating summons shall be sealed and marked with the record number by the proper officer, and shall thereupon be deemed to be issued. No originating summons shall be served until the same shall have been so sealed and marked. 10. One duplicate or more of every originating summons shall be so sealed and marked on the application of the plaintiff or his solicitor. 11. The plaintiff or other party or his solicitor shall, on presenting an originating summons for sealing, leave with the proper officer a copy, written or printed, or partly written and partly printed, on paper of the description aforesaid, of such summons and all the indorsements thereon, and such copy shall be signed by the solicitor leaving the same, or by the plaintiff himself if he sues in person. 12. The officer receiving the copy summons pursuant to rule 11 shall cause the same to be marked with the record number and to be filed and shall also cause an entry of the particulars thereof to be made in the appropriate Cause Book as herein before provided.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is leave of the Court required for serving an originating summons out of the jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. The issue of a summons in probate proceedings shall be preceded by the filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons. On issuing the summons the plaintiff shall, if he has not already so done, lodge a caveat in the Probate Office entitled in the estate of the deceased person. 14. [[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) [[5]](#_ftn5) (1) Save as is otherwise provided for in these Rules, no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court. (2) Service of an originating summons or other originating document or notice of an originating summons or other originating document out of the jurisdiction is permissible without the leave of the Court, if, but only if, it complies with the following conditions: - each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and - no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention. 15. Save as otherwise provided in these Rules, every petition to the Court shall be presented by leaving it with the proper officer at the Central Office. Subject thereto, the foregoing provisions of this Order shall apply to a petition in the same manner as they apply to an originating summons, and references in this Order to “**originating summons**” and “**plaintiff**” shall be construed as including references to “**petition**” and “**petitioner**” respectively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for at least two clear days between the service and the hearing of a petition unless the court grants permission otherwise?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '16. At the foot of every petition presented to the Court, and of every copy thereof, a statement shall be made of the persons, if any, intended to be served therewith, and if no person is intended to be served a statement to that effect shall be made at the foot of the petition and of every copy thereof. 17. Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 5 rule substituted by 149 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2010/en.si.2010.0149.pdf). 149 of 2010 is effective 10 May 2010, subject to paragraph 2 which reads: “Any application for registration of a lis pendens containing the particulars required by law before 1 December 2009 for such registration which is received after 1 December 2009 and prior to the date mentioned in paragraph 1 shall be deemed to comply with the requirements for registration of a lis pendens in accordance with section 121 of the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009.” [[2]](#_ftnref2) “President of the Court of Appeal” substituted for “President of the High Court” by 404 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/404/made/en/print), effective 2 October 2017. [[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 5 rule 14 substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) by 14 of 1989](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1989/en/si/0014.html), effective 1 February 1989. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 5 rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) were substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2)(1) and 14(2)(2) by 506 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0506.html), effective 10 August 2005. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 5 rule 14(2) substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is this order specifically about affidavits in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can an affidavit be sworn over videoconference if it''s not practical for the deponent to attend in person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer, subject to and in accordance with sub-rule (4)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Making an affidavit* 2.[2] (1) Subject to sub-rule (2), all affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court (which may be in the [Form 50.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b849640e-dfd9-4e8d-b505-99429c139026/Affidavit - general No. 50.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made before a Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court, or a practising solicitor (in the remainder of this sub-rule, the “officer”). (2) Where the person making an affidavit resides outside the State, or is for the time being outside the State, the affidavit may be made before any person authorised by law to administer oaths in the place where the person making the affidavit resides or is. (3) An affidavit sworn in the State may be sworn by the deponent- - (a) in the physical presence of the officer before whom it is to be sworn, or - where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer, subject to and in accordance with sub-rule (4). (4) Where an affidavit is sworn in the manner referred to in sub-rule the following conditions shall be complied with - - (a) the officer shall be provided in advance or at the videoconference with a copy (which may be in electronic form) of the affidavit, copies of any exhibits referred to in it and, in a case where rule 6(b)(iii) applies, a certified copy of the relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; - the officer shall be satisfied that the videoconference facility enables the deponent to see and hear the officer and to be seen and heard by the officer; - in a case to which rule 6(b)(ii) applies, the officer shall ensure that the requirement in the paragraph concerned for identification of the deponent has been met before the affidavit is sworn; - the officer shall satisfy himself that the appropriate sacred text for taking the oath is available to the deponent;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the affidavit required to include the title of the civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"include the title of the civil proceedings in which they are sworn."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Form of affidavit* 3. All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) be written or printed book-wise; - be expressed in the first person of the deponent; be drawn up in numbered paragraphs; and - include the title of the civil proceedings in which they are sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the deponent required to provide their exact age if they are under 18?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if the deponent is under 18 years of age, the affidavit must state the deponent’s exact age"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Particulars of deponent and other requirements* 4.[3] All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) state the deponent’s occupation and - the deponent’s place of business, or - the deponent’s place of residence; - state that the deponent is over 18 years of age, but if the deponent is under 18 years of age, the affidavit must state the deponent’s exact age; - be confined to such facts as the deponent is able to prove of his or her own knowledge; - state the deponent’s means of knowledge of the facts sworn, except on interlocutory motions, on which a statement by the deponent as to his or her belief, and the grounds of his or her belief, may be admitted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit invalid if it was sworn before the solicitor representing one of the parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Affidavit may not be sworn before solicitor for party* 5. No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used, or before the partner, agent, correspondent or clerk of that solicitor, or before the party himself.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the person taking the affidavit to state the date and place where the affidavit is taken?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: [...] must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Attestation by person taking affidavit and jurat* 6. Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit; otherwise the affidavit must be taken not to be authentic and must not be filed without the permission of the Court; - must certify in the jurat either: - that he personally knows the deponent, or - that the deponent has been identified to him or her by some person personally known to him or her and named in the jurat who certifies his personal knowledge of the deponent, or - (iii) that the identity of the deponent has been established by him or her by reference to a relevant document containing a photograph of the deponent before the affidavit was taken, and in a case to which paragraph (iii) applies, must give particulars of the relevant document concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific requirement for affidavits made by illiterate or blind individuals to include a certification?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person taking the affidavit must certify that:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Additional requirements for affidavit by illiterate or blind person* 7. (1) When an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court is sworn or made by a person who appears to the person taking the affidavit to be illiterate or blind, the person taking the affidavit must certify that: - (a) the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent; - that the deponent appeared to understand it, and - that the deponent made his or her signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit. (2) No affidavit mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be used in evidence in the absence of the certificate mentioned in sub-rule (1) unless the Court is otherwise satisfied that the affidavit was read over to, and appeared to be understood by, the deponent. (3)[4] Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to have a separate affidavit from the interpreter when filing a foreign language affidavit in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Additional requirements for swearing and filing a foreign language affidavit* 9. (1) Where the deponent appears to the person taking an affidavit not to be capable of understanding one of the official languages of the State, the person taking the affidavit must: - (a) ensure that the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8; and - ensure that the affidavit is read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter in the presence of the person taking the affidavit, and that the deponent has fully understood it; and - certify in the jurat that the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, that the deponent fully understood it and that the deponent signed the foreign language affidavit in his or her presence. (2) Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit. (3) Where the translator and interpreter are one and the same person, a single affidavit may be sworn by that person for the purposes of rule 8(3) and this rule. (4) No foreign language affidavit may be used in evidence in the absence of the affidavit referred to in rule 8(3), unless the Court is otherwise satisfied as to the evidence contained in the foreign language affidavit. (5)[5] Notwithstanding paragraph of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit with alterations allowed to be used in court without permission if the alterations are properly authenticated?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Amendments* 11. An affidavit which has in either the body or the jurat any interlineation, alteration, or erasure, may not be filed, read, or made use of in any civil proceeding in the Court without the permission of the Court unless: - (a) the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit; or - in the case of an erasure, the words or figures appearing at the time of taking the affidavit and erased are re-written and signed or initialled in the margin of the affidavit by the person taking it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court accept an affidavit even if there are defects in the description of the parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may receive any affidavit sworn for the purpose of being used in civil proceedings in the Court: ... despite any defect by misdescription of the parties or otherwise in the title or in the jurat;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Power of Court to receive defective affidavit* 12. The Court may receive any affidavit sworn for the purpose of being used in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) despite any defect by misdescription of the parties or otherwise in the title or in the jurat; or - despite any other irregularity in its form, and where the Court does so, it may direct a memorandum to be made on the document that it has been so received.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for an affidavit to be filed with the Clerk before it can be used in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before an affidavit is used in civil proceedings in the Court, it must be filed with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Filing of affidavits* 13. (1) Before an affidavit is used in civil proceedings in the Court, it must be filed with the Clerk. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not prevent the Judge from making an order on the undertaking of the applicant or his solicitor to file any affidavit sworn before the making of the order, or permitted by the Judge to be made after the order, provided that the Judge may stay the issue of any order until the affidavit has been filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to write the date on which the affidavit was filed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Date of filing* 14. The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on using affidavits after a specified time period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Affidavit may not be used after limited time without permission* 15. Where a special time is limited for delivering or filing an affidavit, no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to attach documents directly to an affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Exhibits* 16. (1) Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits. (2) Every certificate on an exhibit referred to in an affidavit signed by the person before whom the affidavit is sworn must be marked with the short title of the civil proceedings. (3) Nothing in this rule requires or authorises any marking on an original will which has not been admitted to probate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order a party to bear the costs of an affidavit they have used?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17 Costs of affidavit* 17. The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which: - (a) unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, or - which contains argumentative matter, or - which is of unnecessary length, regardless of the outcome of the hearing at which it is used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Is a warrant of execution considered a type of warrant in this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“warrant of execution” or, when used without qualification, “warrant” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— “**warrant of execution**” or, when used without qualification, “**warrant**” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment be executed more than six years after it was given without permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Duration of judgments* 3. (1) Judgments remain in full force and effect for twelve years from the date on which they were given or made, but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court. (2) An application for permission to execute after six years must be made by notice of motion, which must be served on the person sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment against multiple respondents be enforced against any one of them individually?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the judgment or order may be enforced by warrant or otherwise against any of the respondents as if the order had been made against that respondent separately."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Execution against two or more persons* 5. (1) If a judgment is given or made against two or more respondents jointly, the judgment or order may be enforced by warrant or otherwise against any of the respondents as if the order had been made against that respondent separately. (2) If an order against two or more respondents jointly is satisfied by any of the respondents, no further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favour the order so satisfied was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk release a warrant to seize goods if the time for appealing against the judgment or order has expired and no appeal has been brought?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an appeal has been dismissed and the Circuit Court has not issued execution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Warrant to seize goods* 11. (1) Where the Court has given judgment for a sum of money or made an order for the payment of a sum of money for costs, a Clerk may release a warrant to seize goods of the person against who the judgment or order has been made for the purpose of satisfying the judgment debt where: - (a) any Act under which the judgment was given or order was made either specifies no method of enforcement of the order or provides for enforcement by distress, and - either— - the time for appealing against the judgment or order has expired and no appeal has been brought, or - an appeal has been dismissed and the Circuit Court has not issued execution.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Is a warrant considered issued only after it has been both signed by a judge and issued by the clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant referred to in this rule is issued when the warrant is signed by the Judge and issued by the Clerk to the person requesting its issue."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Issue of a warrant* 12. (1) A warrant referred to in this rule is issued when the warrant is signed by the Judge and issued by the Clerk to the person requesting its issue. (2) A warrant referred to in this rule must bear the date of its issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant of execution be extended beyond its initial validity period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may from time to time extend the period of the validity of the warrant for the purpose of execution for a period of not more than one year from the day on which it would otherwise expire and so on from time to time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Duration of a warrant of execution* 13. (1) A warrant is valid for the purpose of execution for one year after the day it is issued. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period of the validity of the warrant for the purpose of execution for a period of not more than one year from the day on which it would otherwise expire and so on from time to time. (3) An extension under sub-rule (2) must not be made after the day of expiry of the warrant. (4) An application for an order under sub-rule (2) may be made without notice to any person. (5) A copy of an order under sub-rule (2) must be delivered to the County Registrar by the party obtaining the order. (6) The priority of a warrant in respect of which an extension under sub-rule (2) had been made must be determined by reference to the date on which the warrant was originally delivered to the person to whom it is directed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk issue a warrant of delivery if the Court orders the delivery of goods?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If an order is made by the Court— (a) for delivery of goods; or for delivery of goods or recovery of their assessed value— a Clerk may issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Warrant of delivery [3]* 14. (1) If an order is made by the Court— - (a) for delivery of goods; or - for delivery of goods or recovery of their assessed value— a Clerk may issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-35-District-Certified-Copies-Of-Orders-And-Of-Other-Documents) a warrant of delivery. (2) If the order of the Court is for the assessed value of goods only, the order may be enforced by the same means as any other order for the payment of money.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can a warrant for possession be issued more than six months after an order becomes enforceable?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"After the expiration of six months from the date on which the order becomes enforceable, a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant, or the successor to or assignee of the estate or interest of the claimant, by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Warrant for possession [4]* 15.(1) In this rule, “land” has the same meaning as in section 3 of the [Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html). (2) In any case in which the Court is empowered to make, and makes in any proceedings, an order which has the effect of- - (a) requiring a person to vacate, or deliver up possession of, any land; or - requiring a person to be put into possession of, any land, a Clerk may, subject to the provisions of this rule and to the terms of the order of the Court, issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-35-District-Certified-Copies-Of-Orders-And-Of-Other-Documents) a warrant for possession of the land specified in the order, which may be in the [Form 51.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f24402e8-0ed6-4b19-bfcf-7eedc42a53ec/Warrant to Sheriff or County Registrar No. 51.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such modifications as are necessary, when the order is made, or at any time not exceeding six months after the date on which the order becomes enforceable. (3) After the expiration of six months from the date on which the order becomes enforceable, a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant, or the successor to or assignee of the estate or interest of the claimant, by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the respondent. (4) A warrant for possession may not issue under this rule at any time when the order mentioned in sub-rule (2) has not taken effect in accordance with its terms or is stayed, whether by order of the Court or otherwise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can an urgent application to stay execution of an order or to postpone the date of possession be made without prior notice to the other party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In a case of urgency, however, the application may be made parte on the lodgment of the notice of motion with the Clerk and where the Court grants such application the Clerk shall forthwith notify the other party or parties to those proceedings accordingly."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) An application to the Court to stay execution of an order mentioned in sub-rule (2) or to postpone the date of possession may be made by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the other party or parties to those proceedings. In a case of urgency, however, the application may be made parte on the lodgment of the notice of motion with the Clerk and where the Court grants such application the Clerk shall forthwith notify the other party or parties to those proceedings accordingly. (6) A warrant for possession must be addressed for execution to the County Registrar or Sheriff for the county in which the land is situated. [1] Order 51 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 51, rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020 [3] Order 51, rule 14 replaced by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020 [4] Order 51, rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 51A related to enforcement of judgments and orders in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders ****[1]****"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders - Court: District # Order 51A:Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''debt'' defined to include any balance of a debt remaining due after partial payments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order:- the “**1926 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html) (No. 18 of 1926); the “**1940 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 23 of 1940); the “**1986 Act**” means the [Courts (No. 2) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1986); the “**2009 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due; “**instalment order**” means an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings; “**judgment**” includes any order or decree of a competent court; “**return date**” means the date of the sitting of the Court at which the examination of the debtor is to take place or, as the case may be, at which an application to vary an instalment order is scheduled to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for issuing a summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"summons in the [Form 51A.01]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Summons for attendance of debtor and statutory declaration* 3. (1) When a debt is due on foot of a judgment of a competent court and the creditor requires the attendance of the debtor before the Court for examination as to the debtor’s means under section 15 (as substituted by section 1(1) of the 1986 Act) of the 1926 Act, the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/29460aba-435b-452a-9c88-14168036a521/Summons for attendance of debtor under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate) required by section 15(2) of the 1926 Act. (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) The summons must be served on the debtor in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days or, if service is by registered post, at least 21 days, before the return date. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7)[2] Where the debt to which the applications relates arises from - a judgment given in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015; - an authentic instrument formally drawn up or registered in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015, or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required to exhibit certain documents under the Jurisdiction Regulation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the statutory declaration by or on behalf of the creditor must also: exhibit the documents referred to in Article 42(1) or, as the case may be, Article 42(2) and, where required, Article 42(3) or Article 42(4) of the Jurisdiction Regulation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) a court settlement approved or concluded in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015 which falls within the scope of the Jurisdiction Regulation (as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 1(1)), the statutory declaration by or on behalf of the creditor must also: - (a) exhibit the documents referred to in Article 42(1) or, as the case may be, Article 42(2) and, where required, Article 42(3) or Article 42(4) of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - include proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - confirm whether or not the requirements of Article 43(2) (as to service of a translation of the judgment) apply and if so, that they have been complied with.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the debtor required to complete and file a statement of means before the court appearance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A summons under rule 3, in addition to requiring the attendance of the debtor in Court on the return date for examination as to his or her means, also requires the debtor to complete and file with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date a statement of means"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Statement of means* 4. (1) A summons under rule 3, in addition to requiring the attendance of the debtor in Court on the return date for examination as to his or her means, also requires the debtor to complete and file with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date a statement of means ([Form 51A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c2615f2e-91f4-4c33-b865-6e70289549b7/Statement of means under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule attached to the summons. (2) The creditor or creditor’s solicitor may, on payment of the prescribed fee, inspect and take or obtain copies of the statement of means at any time after it is lodged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the creditor''s solicitor to provide a certificate detailing the amount outstanding at the time of the examination?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a certificate in the [Form 51A.04] Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 5 Creditor’s proofs 5. (1) At an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2) the creditor or creditor’s solicitor must produce to the Court: - (a) the judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, - a certificate in the [Form 51A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f5e9eb2-b30e-401d-80e4-661cf1d834a9/Certificate of amount due under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(6) No. 51A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and - evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place. (2) A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is an instalment order automatically terminated once the debt and costs are fully paid?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Instalment order* 6. (1) An instalment order may be served on the debtor in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (2) An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full. (3) No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required when applying to vary an instalment order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"that person must apply to the Clerk for the issue of a summons in the [Form 51A.05]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Variation of an instalment order* 7. (1) Where a person wishes to apply to the Court under section 5 of the 1940 Act to vary the terms of an instalment order, that person must apply to the Clerk for the issue of a summons in the [Form 51A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cffc020d-ed44-4481-ad36-72f1e5c6270e/Summons to vary an instalment order No. 51A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate. (2) The summons to vary must be served on the creditor or the debtor, as the case may be, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (3) The original summons and a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (4) The applicant must serve the order of the Court granting the application to vary on the other party in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (5) An order varying an instalment order does not operate to make the instalment order enforceable after the expiration of 12 years from the date of the relevant judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Must the original of the summons and a statutory declaration of service be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Failure to comply with an instalment order* 8. (1) When a creditor wishes to apply for a summons under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act (as substituted by section 2 of the 2009 Act), the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2fc18a39-5b44-430b-82cd-f083e1a431d1/Summons on failure to comply with an instalment order No. 51A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and a statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate). (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise) at least 14 days before the return date of the summons. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7) An application for a direction under section of the 1940 Act that a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act be served on the debtor otherwise than by personal service may be made parte to the Court at any sitting of the Court. (8) Where such a direction is given, the summons may, notwithstanding sub-rule (2), be served in accordance with the direction. (9) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notice in writing under section 6(5) of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing of a summons may be handed by the Clerk to the debtor in Court or sent by ordinary post to the debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal written notice required when informing the debtor of a new hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notification under section of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing at which the debtor is required to attend must be by notice in writing served personally on the debtor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(10) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notification under section of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing at which the debtor is required to attend must be by notice in writing served personally on the debtor. (11) A copy of a notice mentioned in sub-rule (10) and a statutory declaration of service of the notice must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the new date fixed for the hearing. (12) Where the Court, in accordance with section of the 1940 Act, requests the creditor and the debtor to seek resolution by mediation within such period as the Court may specify, the Court must adjourn the proceeding generally with liberty to re-enter it. (13) Where the creditor wishes to re-enter the proceeding, he or she must apply in writing to the Clerk for re-entry, certifying in that application that mediation has failed to achieve a resolution. (14) The Clerk must re-list the proceeding for hearing and must send notice of the re-listing to the debtor, to any solicitor who appeared for the debtor on the initial hearing of the summons, and to the creditor by ordinary post. (15) The creditor may effect further service of a copy of the notice on the debtor in accordance with sub-rule (2). (16) Where the Court, being satisfied that the instalment order was duly served on the debtor and the debtor has failed to comply with the instalment order, is also satisfied, beyond reasonable doubt, on the evidence presented, that the creditor has established that - - (a) the failure to pay the sum in respect of which the debtor has made default is not due to the debtor’s mere inability to pay but is due to his or her wilful refusal or culpable neglect, and - the debtor has no goods which could be taken in execution under any process of the Court by which the judgment, order or decree for the debt was given,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for a warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment pursuant to section 6(7) of the 1940 Act must be in the Form 51A.09 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'and the Court makes an order under section or section of the 1940 Act, that order must be in the [Form 51A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6f409-24ef-4b8a-9fee-14c16fcf8c60/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.07.docx/docx/1) or [51A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5eac4885-6df8-481d-af2e-e70a07de52f4/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate. (17) Where an order is made under section of the 1940 Act, any failure by the debtor to comply with a condition of postponement may be proved by statutory declaration of the creditor lodged with the Clerk, and a warrant may issue on lodgment of such proof but the Clerk may, in any case, re-enter the matter before the Court. (18) A warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment pursuant to section 6(7) of the 1940 Act must be in the [Form 51A.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4df60f3a-e472-4398-8147-b0e46f51d515/Warrant for arrest of debtor No. 51A.09.docx/docx/1) Schedule and may be added to the form of an order under section or section of the 1940 Act. (19) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(9) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (20) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must send notice of the re-listing to the creditor and to the debtor by ordinary post. (21) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(10) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (22) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must notify the creditor, the debtor and the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned of the re-listing of the matter by ordinary post and such other means as the Clerk considers appropriate. (23) No order under sub-rule (16) may be made against a debtor who is a member of the permanent Defence Forces or a reservist for the time being called out on permanent service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a warrant allowed to be issued if an appeal is already in progress?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Where: (a) a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 No warrant to issue, or warrant to be returned, where an appeal is lodged* 9. (1) Where: - (a) a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and - a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and - the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be. (2) Where a warrant to enforce the order has been issued but not executed when a notice of appeal is lodged, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that a notice of appeal has been lodged (and that a recognisance has been entered into, if that be the case); and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Does the Clerk need to inform the Superintendent about the payment received?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Clerk to secure return of warrant where amount due is paid to him or her* 10. Where a warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been issued but not executed and the amount of the arrears of instalments and costs specified in the order is paid to the Clerk, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made; and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Governor of the prison required to notify the Clerk about the debtor''s arrival?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Notice by Governor of prison to Clerk* 11. The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk required to notify the governor after receiving payment and ensuring the debtor is in custody?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the Clerk must: - (a) give a certificate of payment to the person making the payment on behalf of the debtor; - forthwith forward a similar certificate to the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned and to the creditor or creditor’s solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Clerk to notify Governor when payment is received and debtor is in custody* 12. Where, subsequent to the arrest and imprisonment of a debtor under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act, the amount of the arrears of instalments and costs specified in the order for arrest and imprisonment is paid to the Clerk, the Clerk must: - (a) give a certificate of payment to the person making the payment on behalf of the debtor; - forthwith forward a similar certificate to the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned and to the creditor or creditor’s solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about other enforcement mentioned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**3 - OTHER ENFORCEMENT**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - OTHER ENFORCEMENT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order a specific officer of a company to produce documents if the company fails to do so?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may ... make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Attendance of company* 13. (1) This Rule applies where - - (a) the Court by witness summons or otherwise makes an order in any proceeding for the production by a company of any document or thing; and - after service of the order the company defaults in producing the document or thing in accordance with the order. (2) In the circumstances referred to in sub-rule (1), the Court may - - (a) make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing; and - order the company to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court appoint someone else to perform an act if the original person fails to do so?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If an order that has been made against a person requires the person to do an act and the person does not do the act, the Court may - direct that the act be done by a person appointed by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Substituted performance* 14. (1) If an order that has been made against a person requires the person to do an act and the person does not do the act, the Court may - - (a) direct that the act be done by a person appointed by the Court; and - (a) order the person against whom the order has been made to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a non-party enforce an order obtained in their favor using the same methods as a party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Enforcement by or against non-party* 15. (1) A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party. (2) If an order may be enforced against a person not a party, the order may be enforced against the person by the same means as if the person were a party. (3) If an order may be enforced against a company not a party, the processes of enforcement apply to an officer of the company as if the company were a party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person lose their entitlement to an order if they fail to meet a specified condition?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person entitled to an order subject to the fulfilment of a condition who fails to fulfil the condition must be taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Non-performance of condition* 16. A person entitled to an order subject to the fulfilment of a condition who fails to fulfil the condition must be taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order, and, unless the Court otherwise orders, any other person interested may take any steps which are warranted by the order or which might have been taken if the order had not been made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make orders to help enforce a warrant of execution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may make any order that it thinks just in aid of the enforcement of a warrant of execution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Order in aid of enforcement* 17. (1) The Court may make any order that it thinks just in aid of the enforcement of a warrant of execution. (2) An application for an order under sub-rule (1) may be made by a County Registrar or other person to whom a warrant of execution is directed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Do the provisions of Order 26 apply to warrants issued under this Order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions contained in [Order 26] apply to warrants issued under this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Provisions of Order 26 to apply* 18. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) (relating to warrants in criminal proceedings) apply to warrants issued under this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment of the Court that requires payment of money be registered in the Central Office of the High Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the Courts Act 1981) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Registration of judgments of the Court* 19. (1) Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the [Courts Act 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/11/enacted/en/html)) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office. (2) The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court applies to and must be followed in relation to the registration of a judgment or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board be enforced similarly to a court judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of these Rules which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, with any necessary modifications, to any order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board under section 38(1) of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Enforcement of PIAB orders to pay and judgments of courts* 20. (1) The provisions of these Rules which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, with any necessary modifications, to any order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board under section 38(1) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html). (2) Any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to pay. (3) The provisions of this Order which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, where and to the extent so provided by these Rules, to a judgment or other instrument issued by a court in a Member State of the European Union other than the State. [1] Order 51A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 51A sub-rule (7) of rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 617 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/617/made/en/print?q 617 &years 2015), effective 30 December 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Does a claimant need to provide their full name and description when making a claim for goods taken in execution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"contain the full name and description of the claimant;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Notice of claim to goods taken in execution* 1. A claim to or in respect of any goods or chattels not exceeding in value the monetary limit of the Court’s jurisdiction which have been taken in execution or intended execution by a County Registrar must: - (a) be in writing ([Form 51B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/477f7eb6-abe4-4109-9051-dec5862ff7cf/Notice of claim to goods taken in execution No. 51B.01.docx/docx/1)Schedule - contain the full name and description of the claimant; and - contain an address at which service will be accepted by or on behalf of the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is the County Registrar required to send a written notice upon receiving a claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the County Registrar must immediately send written notice of the claim to the party claiming execution or to his or her solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 County Registrar’s notice to party claiming execution* 2. On receipt of a claim mentioned in rule 1, the County Registrar must immediately send written notice of the claim to the party claiming execution or to his or her solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for the party claiming execution to respond after receiving the notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Notice of admission or denial of claim* 3. Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice (which may be in the [Form 51B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6878de80-1b71-42f1-a18b-92f033863f91/Notice of admission of title of claimant, or request to County Registrar to withdraw No. 51B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the County Registrar of whether he or she disputes or admits the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or requests the County Registrar to withdraw from possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claimant required to make a deposit if they do not respond within two days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the County Registrar must immediately send written notice to the claimant: requiring him or her within two days of the service of that notice to deposit with the County Registrar the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, if the value of the goods or chattels seized is less than the amount set out in the warrant of execution, the value of the goods or chattels"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Deposit by claimant* 4. If within the period of two days mentioned in rule 3 the party claiming execution does not: - (a) admit the title of the claimant or - request the County Registrar to withdraw from possession, the County Registrar must immediately send written notice to the claimant: - requiring him or her within two days of the service of that notice to deposit with the County Registrar the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, if the value of the goods or chattels seized is less than the amount set out in the warrant of execution, the value of the goods or chattels, and - giving the claimant notice that in default of his or her making the deposit required, an application will be made, after service of an interpleader summons (which is a summons in civil proceedings), to the Court for an order for sale.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Can the County Registrar release the seized goods after a deposit is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Procedure on deposit being made* 5. Where the claimant deposits with the County Registrar: - (a) the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, - if the value of the goods or chattels as determined by the County Registrar or by a valuer appointed by the County Registrar, being less than the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued, a sum equal to the value as so determined, the County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels and the sum deposited may be disposed of as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be used when applying to the court for the sale of seized goods?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application to the Court for an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized must be in [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Application for sale* 6. (1) Where the claimant does not make the deposit required under rule 4, the Court may, at any time after the service of an interpleader summons, on application made: - (a) by the execution creditor on notice to the claimant and to the County Registrar, or - by the County Registrar on notice to the parties, make an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized, subject to such conditions as to the giving of security by the execution creditor or otherwise as the Court thinks just. (2) The notice of application to the Court for an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized must be in [Form 51B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7dd5304-f26b-4a2f-8c33-481b35567c49/Notice of motion on application to the Court for sale of chattels No. 51B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and must be served two clear days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application under rule 6 be heard outside of the scheduled court sittings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under rule 6 may be heard otherwise than at a scheduled sitting of the Court at any time and place within the appropriate Court district which the Judge deems suitable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Application may be heard outside of scheduled Court sittings* 7. (1) An application under rule 6 may be heard otherwise than at a scheduled sitting of the Court at any time and place within the appropriate Court district which the Judge deems suitable. (2) The costs of any application under rule 6 may be provided for by the Court on the hearing of the interpleader summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is the interpleader summons served on both the claimant and the party claiming execution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An interpleader summons must be served on the claimant (or where the claim has been made by a solicitor for the claimant, on the claimant’s solicitor) and on the party claiming execution (or where the warrant of execution has been lodged with the County Registrar by a solicitor for the party claiming execution, on the party’s solicitor)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Service of interpleader summons* 9. (1) An interpleader summons ([Form 51B.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a4e02878-c4f6-4800-bde8-ac16ff23564a/Interpleader summons No. 51B.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be served on the claimant (or where the claim has been made by a solicitor for the claimant, on the claimant’s solicitor) and on the party claiming execution (or where the warrant of execution has been lodged with the County Registrar by a solicitor for the party claiming execution, on the party’s solicitor). (2) An interpleader summons must be served in a manner provided by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Court responsible for determining the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court must determine: ... the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Liability for costs* 10. (1) On the hearing of the interpleader summons the Court must determine: - (a) the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses; - the amount of the costs and expenses; and - by whom and to whom the costs and expenses are to be paid. (2) The scale of costs for tort cases in the Schedule of Costs is the appropriate scale for proceedings begun by interpleader summons. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order related to European Enforcement Orders?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order European Enforcement Orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - European Enforcement Orders - Court: District # **Order European Enforcement Orders******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is Regulation No. 805/2004 related to the creation of a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Regulation No 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 21 April 2004 creating a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order:- “**domestic judgment**” means any judgment or decree of the Court for the recovery of any sum of money, or any order (including an order made by consent) of the Court or dismiss by the Court requiring the payment of any sum of money, to which [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) applies; “**Regulation No. 805/2004**” means [Regulation No 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 21 April 2004 creating a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims, 143/15 of 30 April 2004; “**Regulation No. 1869/2005**” means [Commission Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869) replacing the Annexes to Regulation No 805/2004 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 21 April 2004 creating a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims, 300/6 of 16 November 2005; the “**2005 Regulations**” means the European Communities (European Enforcement Order) Regulations 2005 ([S.I. No. 648 of 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/648/made/en/print)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''debt'' defined to include any balance of a debt remaining due after partial payments have been made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order:- the “**1926 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html) (No. 18 of 1926); the “**1940 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 23 of 1940); the “**1986 Act**” means the [Courts (No. 2) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1986); the “**2009 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due; “**instalment order**” means an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings; “**judgment**” includes any order or decree of a competent court; “**return date**” means the date of the sitting of the Court at which the examination of the debtor is to take place or, as the case may be, at which an application to vary an instalment order is scheduled to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for issuing a summons in duplicate?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"summons in the [Form 51A.01]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Summons for attendance of debtor and statutory declaration* 3. (1) When a debt is due on foot of a judgment of a competent court and the creditor requires the attendance of the debtor before the Court for examination as to the debtor’s means under section 15 (as substituted by section 1(1) of the 1986 Act) of the 1926 Act, the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/29460aba-435b-452a-9c88-14168036a521/Summons for attendance of debtor under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate) required by section 15(2) of the 1926 Act. (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) The summons must be served on the debtor in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days or, if service is by registered post, at least 21 days, before the return date. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7)[2] Where the debt to which the applications relates arises from - a judgment given in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015; - an authentic instrument formally drawn up or registered in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015, or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration by or on behalf of the creditor required to exhibit certain documents under the Jurisdiction Regulation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"exhibit the documents referred to in Article 42(1) or, as the case may be, Article 42(2) and, where required, Article 42(3) or Article 42(4) of the Jurisdiction Regulation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) a court settlement approved or concluded in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015 which falls within the scope of the Jurisdiction Regulation (as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 1(1)), the statutory declaration by or on behalf of the creditor must also: - (a) exhibit the documents referred to in Article 42(1) or, as the case may be, Article 42(2) and, where required, Article 42(3) or Article 42(4) of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - include proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - confirm whether or not the requirements of Article 43(2) (as to service of a translation of the judgment) apply and if so, that they have been complied with.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the statement of means required to be filed with the Clerk before the debtor''s court appearance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"not less than one week before the return date a statement of means"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Statement of means* 4. (1) A summons under rule 3, in addition to requiring the attendance of the debtor in Court on the return date for examination as to his or her means, also requires the debtor to complete and file with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date a statement of means ([Form 51A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c2615f2e-91f4-4c33-b865-6e70289549b7/Statement of means under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule attached to the summons. (2) The creditor or creditor’s solicitor may, on payment of the prescribed fee, inspect and take or obtain copies of the statement of means at any time after it is lodged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Must a copy of the certificate mentioned in sub-rule be provided to the debtor or debtor''s solicitor before the return date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 5 Creditor’s proofs 5. (1) At an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2) the creditor or creditor’s solicitor must produce to the Court: - (a) the judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, - a certificate in the [Form 51A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f5e9eb2-b30e-401d-80e4-661cf1d834a9/Certificate of amount due under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(6) No. 51A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and - evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place. (2) A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Does an instalment order automatically end if the debt and costs are fully paid?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Instalment order* 6. (1) An instalment order may be served on the debtor in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (2) An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full. (3) No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required when applying to the court to vary the terms of an instalment order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"that person must apply to the Clerk for the issue of a summons in the [Form 51A.05]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Variation of an instalment order* 7. (1) Where a person wishes to apply to the Court under section 5 of the 1940 Act to vary the terms of an instalment order, that person must apply to the Clerk for the issue of a summons in the [Form 51A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cffc020d-ed44-4481-ad36-72f1e5c6270e/Summons to vary an instalment order No. 51A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate. (2) The summons to vary must be served on the creditor or the debtor, as the case may be, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (3) The original summons and a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (4) The applicant must serve the order of the Court granting the application to vary on the other party in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (5) An order varying an instalment order does not operate to make the instalment order enforceable after the expiration of 12 years from the date of the relevant judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal service required for a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise) at least 14 days before the return date of the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Failure to comply with an instalment order* 8. (1) When a creditor wishes to apply for a summons under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act (as substituted by section 2 of the 2009 Act), the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2fc18a39-5b44-430b-82cd-f083e1a431d1/Summons on failure to comply with an instalment order No. 51A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and a statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate). (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise) at least 14 days before the return date of the summons. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7) An application for a direction under section of the 1940 Act that a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act be served on the debtor otherwise than by personal service may be made parte to the Court at any sitting of the Court. (8) Where such a direction is given, the summons may, notwithstanding sub-rule (2), be served in accordance with the direction. (9) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notice in writing under section 6(5) of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing of a summons may be handed by the Clerk to the debtor in Court or sent by ordinary post to the debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Should a warrant be issued if an appeal is lodged before it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Where a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 No warrant to issue, or warrant to be returned, where an appeal is lodged* 9. (1) Where: - (a) a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and - a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and - the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be. (2) Where a warrant to enforce the order has been issued but not executed when a notice of appeal is lodged, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that a notice of appeal has been lodged (and that a recognisance has been entered into, if that be the case); and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Does the Clerk need to inform the Superintendent about the payment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Clerk to secure return of warrant where amount due is paid to him or her* 10. Where a warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been issued but not executed and the amount of the arrears of instalments and costs specified in the order is paid to the Clerk, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made; and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order a specific officer of a company to produce a document if the company fails to do so?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may ... make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Attendance of company* 13. (1) This Rule applies where - - (a) the Court by witness summons or otherwise makes an order in any proceeding for the production by a company of any document or thing; and - after service of the order the company defaults in producing the document or thing in accordance with the order. (2) In the circumstances referred to in sub-rule (1), the Court may - - (a) make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing; and - order the company to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a non-party person enforce an order obtained in their favor using the same methods as a party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Enforcement by or against non-party* 15. (1) A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party. (2) If an order may be enforced against a person not a party, the order may be enforced against the person by the same means as if the person were a party. (3) If an order may be enforced against a company not a party, the processes of enforcement apply to an officer of the company as if the company were a party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Do criminal proceedings warrants相关规定是否适用于此命令下签发的 WARRANTS?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) (relating to warrants in criminal proceedings) apply to warrants issued under this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Provisions of Order 26 to apply* 18. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) (relating to warrants in criminal proceedings) apply to warrants issued under this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment or order for costs issued by the Court be registered in the Central Office of the High Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the Courts Act 1981) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Registration of judgments of the Court* 19. (1) Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the [Courts Act 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/11/enacted/en/html)) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office. (2) The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court applies to and must be followed in relation to the registration of a judgment or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can enforcement rules for court judgments also be applied to orders to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of these Rules which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, with any necessary modifications, to any order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board under section 38(1) of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Enforcement of PIAB orders to pay and judgments of courts* 20. (1) The provisions of these Rules which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, with any necessary modifications, to any order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board under section 38(1) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html). (2) Any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to pay. (3) The provisions of this Order which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, where and to the extent so provided by these Rules, to a judgment or other instrument issued by a court in a Member State of the European Union other than the State. [1] Order 51A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 51A sub-rule (7) of rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 617 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/617/made/en/print?q 617 &years 2015), effective 30 December 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Must a claim to goods taken in execution be in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"be in writing ([Form 51B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/477f7eb6-abe4-4109-9051-dec5862ff7cf/Notice of claim to goods taken in execution No. 51B.01.docx/docx/1)Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Notice of claim to goods taken in execution* 1. A claim to or in respect of any goods or chattels not exceeding in value the monetary limit of the Court’s jurisdiction which have been taken in execution or intended execution by a County Registrar must: - (a) be in writing ([Form 51B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/477f7eb6-abe4-4109-9051-dec5862ff7cf/Notice of claim to goods taken in execution No. 51B.01.docx/docx/1)Schedule - contain the full name and description of the claimant; and - contain an address at which service will be accepted by or on behalf of the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the party claiming execution to provide a written notice within two days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Notice of admission or denial of claim* 3. Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice (which may be in the [Form 51B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6878de80-1b71-42f1-a18b-92f033863f91/Notice of admission of title of claimant, or request to County Registrar to withdraw No. 51B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the County Registrar of whether he or she disputes or admits the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or requests the County Registrar to withdraw from possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when applying to the court for the sale of seized goods?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application to the Court for an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized must be in [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Application for sale* 6. (1) Where the claimant does not make the deposit required under rule 4, the Court may, at any time after the service of an interpleader summons, on application made: - (a) by the execution creditor on notice to the claimant and to the County Registrar, or - by the County Registrar on notice to the parties, make an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized, subject to such conditions as to the giving of security by the execution creditor or otherwise as the Court thinks just. (2) The notice of application to the Court for an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized must be in [Form 51B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7dd5304-f26b-4a2f-8c33-481b35567c49/Notice of motion on application to the Court for sale of chattels No. 51B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and must be served two clear days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Is an interpleader summons served on both the claimant and the party claiming execution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An interpleader summons must be served on the claimant (or where the claim has been made by a solicitor for the claimant, on the claimant’s solicitor) and on the party claiming execution (or where the warrant of execution has been lodged with the County Registrar by a solicitor for the party claiming execution, on the party’s solicitor)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Service of interpleader summons* 9. (1) An interpleader summons ([Form 51B.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a4e02878-c4f6-4800-bde8-ac16ff23564a/Interpleader summons No. 51B.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be served on the claimant (or where the claim has been made by a solicitor for the claimant, on the claimant’s solicitor) and on the party claiming execution (or where the warrant of execution has been lodged with the County Registrar by a solicitor for the party claiming execution, on the party’s solicitor). (2) An interpleader summons must be served in a manner provided by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the term ''judgment'' in Order 51A rules 1 to 12 include references to judgments, authentic instruments, or court settlements certified as a European Enforcement Order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any reference in Order 51A, rules 1 to 12 inclusive to a “judgment”, where the context so admits, includes a reference to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order in a Member State of origin."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 Provisions on enforcement to apply to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement certified as a European Enforcement Order in the Member State of origin. 2. (1) Subject to [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) and to the 2005 Regulations, the provisions of [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 1 to 12 inclusive, so far as they may be applied to a judgment of the High Court, may be applied to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order in the Member State of origin. (2) Any reference in [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 1 to 12 inclusive to a “**judgment**”, where the context so admits, includes a reference to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order in a Member State of origin. In such a case, any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, order or decree may be adapted to refer to the European Enforcement Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application to certify a domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order be made after the initial hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if not made at that hearing, must be made parte to the Court on another occasion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Application to certify a judgment as a European Enforcement Order* 4. Where a domestic judgment has been given or made, an application to certify that domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order: - (a) may be made parte to the Court at the hearing at which that domestic judgment is given or made; or - if not made at that hearing, must be made parte to the Court on another occasion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required to support an application for certification under Regulation No. 805/2004?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to certify a domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order must, unless the Court otherwise directs or permits, be supported by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Application to certify to be supported by affidavit* 5. (1) An application to certify a domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order must, unless the Court otherwise directs or permits, be supported by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The affidavit may be in the [Form No. 51C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6cd051d8-d303-4ba4-8ad4-7753b0ffe6c3/Affidavit to certify a European Enforcement Order No. 51C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such modifications as are necessary. (2) A certificate given on foot of an application pursuant to Article 6(1) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application be made parte to the Court for issuing a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004] for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of that domestic judgment may be made parte to the Court by any party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Application to certify lack or limitation of enforceability* 6. (1) Where a domestic judgment, which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order, has ceased to be enforceable or its enforceability is or has been suspended or limited, an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of that domestic judgment may be made parte to the Court by any party. (2) A certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment given on foot of an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a replacement certificate be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004] for the issue of a replacement certificate may be made parte to the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Application for replacement certificate* 7. (1) Where the Court gives a judgment or makes an order following a challenge to a domestic judgment, which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order, an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate may be made parte to the Court by any party at the hearing at which that judgment is given or order is made. (2) A replacement certificate given on foot of an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to file a completed form of application with the Clerk before making an application for the rectification or withdrawal of a European Enforcement Order certificate?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before making an application under Article 10(1), the moving party must complete the Form of application in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005], and must file the completed form of application with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Application for rectification or withdrawal of a European Enforcement Order certificate* 9. (1) An application under Article 10(1) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the rectification or the withdrawal of a European Enforcement Order certificate must be made to the Court which certified the domestic judgment concerned as a European Enforcement Order. (2) Before making an application under Article 10(1), the moving party must complete the Form of application in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869), and must file the completed form of application with the Clerk. (3) The moving party must serve a copy of the completed form of application on the judgment creditor or (as the case may be) the judgment debtor, together with a copy of any affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party and intended to be used in the application. (4) Where rectification is sought, there must be exhibited to any affidavit in support of the application a copy of the form of European Enforcement Order certificate previously issued, marked with the rectification sought, and the contents of the marked certificate must be verified in the grounding affidavit. (5) Where, on an application under this rule, it is determined that the European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned ought to be rectified or withdrawn, the party on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order must within seven days of that determination lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned with the Clerk. (6) In the case of rectification, the party who applied for rectification must lodge a draft rectified certificate with the Clerk. (7) The Clerk must, in a case of rectification, produce the rectified certificate to the Judge to be re-signed. (8) Subject to any direction made by the Court in that regard, the Clerk must issue the rectified certificate to the party on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to provide a certificate to the applicant when the original European Enforcement Order certificate is not lodged within seven days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must, at the request of the applicant, provide the applicant with a certificate signed by the Judge certifying the fact that the European Enforcement Order certificate has been rectified or (as the case may be) withdrawn."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(9) In the case of withdrawal, the Clerk must produce the certificate to the Judge to be cancelled. (10) Where the person on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order fails in accordance with sub-rule (5) to lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned with the Clerk within seven days of a determination, the Clerk must, at the request of the applicant, provide the applicant with a certificate signed by the Judge certifying the fact that the European Enforcement Order certificate has been rectified or (as the case may be) withdrawn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a clerk issue a duplicate certificate upon request?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may at the request of a party, present for signature by the Judge and issue to the party a duplicate of any certificate referred to in this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Duplicate certificate* 10. (1) The Clerk may at the request of a party, present for signature by the Judge and issue to the party a duplicate of any certificate referred to in this Order. (2) Any duplicate certificate must be marked as a duplicate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to submit a draft certificate to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant must in every case lodge with the Clerk a draft of the completed form of the certificate for which application has been made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Lodgment of draft certificate* 11. The applicant must in every case lodge with the Clerk a draft of the completed form of the certificate for which application has been made, where a draft certificate has not already been exhibited to an affidavit supporting the application for the certificate. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Can notifications between the Clerk and creditor be made over the phone?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"All notifications by the Clerk to the creditor required under this Order or in accordance with Regulation 5 of the 2016 Regulations may be by telephone (if subsequently confirmed in writing by electronic mail, facsimile or letter sent by ordinary prepaid post)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Preliminary and general 1. In this Order:- “**2016 Regulations**” means the European Union (European Account Preservation Order) Regulations 2016 ([S.I. 645 of 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/645/made/en/print)); “**EAPO Regulation**” means [Regulation No. 655/2014](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/655/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 189/59 of 27 June 2014); “**competent authority**” means the Minister for Justice and Equality; “**creditor**” and “**debtor**” each has the same meaning as in the EAPO Regulation; “**Implementing Regulation**” means Commission Implementing [Regulation 2016/1823](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg_impl/2016/1823/oj/eng) of 10 October 2016 establishing the forms referred to in [Regulation No. 655/2014](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/655/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council establishing a European Account Preservation Order procedure to facilitate cross-border debt recovery in civil and commercial matters of 19 October 2016); “**information authority**” means the Minister for Justice and Equality; “**judgment**” has the same meaning as in the 2016 Regulations; “**Member State**” means a member state of the European Union but does not include Denmark or the United Kingdom; “**Member State of enforcement**” means the Member State in which the bank account to be preserved is maintained; “**Preservation Order**” has the same meaning as in the EAPO Regulation. 2. (1) All notifications by the Clerk to the creditor required under this Order or in accordance with Regulation 5 of the 2016 Regulations may be by telephone (if subsequently confirmed in writing by electronic mail, facsimile or letter sent by ordinary prepaid post) or by electronic mail or by such other means as the Clerk considers sufficient. (2) All notifications or requests by the Clerk to the information authority required under this Order or in accordance with the 2016 Regulations may be by electronic mail or by such other means as the Clerk shall agree with the information authority. (3) A notice required under Regulation 10(2) of the 2016 Regulations to be given by the Clerk to the Property Registration Authority shall be given by the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Titles of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Is electronic communication allowed for transmitting decisions according to Article 10.2 or Article 36.5 of the EAPO Regulation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by electronic mail, facsimile or such other means as the Clerk shall agree with the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) A notice required under Regulation 10(4) of the 2016 Regulations to be given by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies shall be given by the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post. (5) A decision referred to in Article 10.2 or, as the case may be, Article 36.5 of the EAPO Regulation shall be transmitted to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement, in the form set out in Annex III or, as the case may be, Annex VIII to the Implementing Regulation by the transmission by the Clerk to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement of a certified copy of the relevant decision by electronic mail, facsimile or such other means as the Clerk shall agree with the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required if the creditor has obtained an equivalent national order against the same debtor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The creditor shall, where: (a) he has obtained an equivalent national order against the same debtor to secure the same claim during the proceedings for the issuing of a Preservation Order, file an affidavit without delay setting out the terms of the equivalent national order against the debtor which has been obtained and, exhibiting a copy of that order and a certified translation thereof into Irish or English, and providing details of any subsequent execution of the national order granted;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Application to the Court for a Preservation Order 3. (1) An application to the Court by a creditor for a Preservation Order shall be made: - (a) in the case of an application to which Article 5(a) of the EAPO Regulation applies, by the lodgment with the Clerk of the completed application in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation which shall be treated as a motion parte* in the intended action; - in the case of an application to which Article of the EAPO Regulation applies, by the lodgment with the Clerk of the completed application in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation, which shall be treated as a motion*ex parte* in the action, which may be lodged on or after the delivery of judgment by the Court. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall be grounded upon the verification by the applicant of the completed application form in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation and any evidence submitted with that application. (3) The creditor shall lodge with the application a draft of the Preservation Order in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation with Part A completed in the terms sought. (4) The creditor shall, where: - (a) he has obtained an equivalent national order against the same debtor to secure the same claim during the proceedings for the issuing of a Preservation Order, file an affidavit without delay setting out the terms of the equivalent national order against the debtor which has been obtained and, exhibiting a copy of that order and a certified translation thereof into Irish or English, and providing details of any subsequent execution of the national order granted; - he has made any application for an equivalent national order which has been rejected as inadmissible or unfounded, file an affidavit without delay providing particulars of the same.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court decide not to require security if it deems it inappropriate?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"unless, in accordance with Article 12.1 of the EAPO Regulation, it considers that the provision of security is inappropriate in the circumstances of the case and dispenses with such requirement"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. (1) Having considered the application, the Court, in accordance with the time limits set out in Article 18 of the EAPO Regulation: - (a) in a case to which Article 12.1 of the EAPO Regulation applies, unless, in accordance with Article 12.1 of the EAPO Regulation, it considers that the provision of security is inappropriate in the circumstances of the case and dispenses with such requirement, or in a case to which Article 12.2 of the EAPO Regulation applies, where it considers it necessary and appropriate in the circumstances of the case, shall fix the amount of security required and form or forms of security acceptable; - where the Court considers in accordance with Article 9.1 of the EAPO Regulation that the evidence provided is insufficient, may direct the delivery of further documentary evidence verified by affidavit or, subject to Article 9.2 of the EAPO Regulation, oral evidence and the nature of the evidence which the Court requires for the purpose of its determining the application, and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly; - where the Court considers in accordance with Article 17.3 of the EAPO Regulation that the application is incomplete, may fix the time within which and the means by which the creditor may complete or rectify the application and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly; - in a case to which Article 14.3 of the EAPO Regulation applies, may direct the Clerk to transmit a request for information to the information authority; - in every case, may give such directions and make such orders for the conduct of the proceedings on the application as appear convenient for the determination of the proceedings consistently with the requirements of the EAPO Regulation and in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings, and - shall determine the application and order accordingly. (2) The Clerk shall notify the creditor of all directions as to the amount and form of security required in respect of a Preservation Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Is the creditor responsible for transmitting Part A of the Preservation Order to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The creditor shall be the person responsible in accordance with Article 23.3 of the EAPO Regulation for the transmission of Part A of the Preservation Order to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) The Court’s decision on the application for a Preservation Order and, where appropriate, the date by which any appeal may be made against the decision, shall be notified to the creditor by the Clerk. (4) Where security is required, the creditor shall lodge proof of entry into the security with the Clerk. (5) Where the Court makes a Preservation Order, the order shall, following the lodgment of proof of entry into any security required, issue to the creditor in the form in Annex to the Implementing Regulation. (6) The creditor shall be the person responsible in accordance with Article 23.3 of the EAPO Regulation for the transmission of Part A of the Preservation Order to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement. (7) The creditor shall be the person responsible in accordance with Article 28.3 of the EAPO Regulation for the transmission of the documents referred to in Article 28.1 of the EAPO Regulation to the competent authority of the Member State in which the debtor is domiciled.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court revoke a Preservation Order if there is no proof of initiating proceedings within the specified time?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court shall revoke the Preservation Order and shall issue an order of revocation in the form in Annex III to the Implementing Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## III. Issue of proceedings on the substance of the claim 5. (1) In the case of an application to which Article 5(a) of the EAPO Regulation applies, the creditor shall deliver to the Clerk within the time prescribed by Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation a copy of the originating claim notice in the proceedings on the substance of the matter issued by the Clerk. (2) An application for an extension of time in accordance with Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation shall be by motion on notice in the intended action, which need not be grounded upon an affidavit. 6. Where evidence of the initiation of proceedings on the substance of the matter has not been delivered to the Clerk within the time prescribed by Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation and no extension of time has been permitted, the application shall be listed before the Court and, if the Court has not received proof of the initiation of proceedings within the time period referred to in Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation, the Court shall revoke the Preservation Order and shall issue an order of revocation in the form in Annex III to the Implementing Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required for an application made in accordance with sub-rule (1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall: ... be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Subsequent proceedings 7. (1) Subject to the EAPO Regulation and the 2016 Regulations, any of the following applications to the Court by a creditor or debtor shall be made: - (a) where there are no proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of the EAPO Regulation as between the creditor and the debtor, or - where there are proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of motion in the proceedings: - any application by a debtor pursuant to Regulation 8 of the 2016 regulations and Article 33 of the EAPO Regulation; - any application by a debtor pursuant to Regulation 9 of the 2016 regulations and Article 34 of the EAPO Regulation; - (iii) any application by a debtor or a creditor pursuant to Regulation 9 of the 2016 regulations and Article 35 of the EAPO Regulation. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall: - (a) be in the form set out in Annex VII to the Implementing Regulation and - be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party, which may be endorsed upon the completed application form, or if not so endorsed, which shall exhibit and verify the completed application form and shall exhibit and verify each other document relied upon in the application. 8. (1) Subject to the EAPO Regulation and the 2016 Regulations, any of the following applications to the Court shall be made: - (a) where there are no proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of application entitled in the matter of the EAPO Regulation as between the creditor and the debtor, or - where there are proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of motion in the proceedings:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required when making an application according to rules mentioned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- any application by a creditor or debtor pursuant to Article 31 of the EAPO Regulation; - any application by a debtor pursuant to Article 38 of the EAPO Regulation; - (iii) any application by a third party pursuant to Article 39(3) of the EAPO Regulation; - any other application for relief pursuant to the 2016 Regulations, the EAPO Regulation or this Order. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 9. (1) Every person served with notice of an application made under rule 7 or rule 8 shall be at liberty to deliver a replying affidavit. (2) On the return date of a notice of application or notice of motion under rule 7 or rule 8 (or on any adjournment from such date), the Court shall give directions and make orders for the conduct of the proceedings on the application as appear convenient for the determination of the application consistently with the EAPO Regulation in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings which, where appropriate, may include: - (a) directions as to the service of notice of the application on any other person, including mode of service and the time allowed for such service (and the Court may for that purpose adjourn the hearing of the notice of motion or further hearing of such application to a date specified); - directions as to the filing and delivery of any further affidavits by any party or parties; - orders fixing time limits.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to costs in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 53 - Costs - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 53 - Costs - Court: District # **Order 53: Costs******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court consider a party''s refusal to participate in ADR when deciding on costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in considering the awarding of the costs in proceedings may, where it considers it just, have regard to the refusal or failure without good reason of any party to participate in another ADR process"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Costs in general to be in the discretion of Court* 1.[2] (1) Save as otherwise provided by statute or by these Rules, the granting or withholding of the costs of any party to civil proceedings or other proceedings in the Court in which by law the Court may award costs are in the discretion of the Court. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), the Court - in considering the awarding of the costs in proceedings in which the parties have been invited by the Court to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings in accordance with section 16 (1) of the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) , may, where it considers it just, have regard to the matters set out in section 21 of that Act, - in considering the awarding of the costs in proceedings may, where it considers it just, have regard to the refusal or failure without good reason of any party to participate in another ADR process referred to in [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution), rule 1, where an order has been made in the proceedings under [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution), rule 7'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court award more than the specified costs in certain cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, where appropriate in the special circumstances of a case, to be specified by the Court, award an amount for costs and/or counsel’s fees in excess of the amount provided in the Schedule of Costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Scales of costs* 2. (1) Save as otherwise provided, the costs specified in each scale in the Schedule of Costs are the only lawful costs. (2) The Court may, where appropriate in the special circumstances of a case, to be specified by the Court, award an amount for costs and/or counsel’s fees in excess of the amount provided in the Schedule of Costs. (3) The costs in the Schedule of Costs are in every instance exclusive of and in addition to any sum allowed as recovery of value-added tax and all actual and necessary outlay as is allowed. (4) The Schedule of Costs must be revised no less frequently than once every three years. (5) In any case where the Court is of the opinion that there is no appropriate scale of costs provided, it may measure the costs. (6) In this rule: “**actual and necessary outlay**” must include a sum for miscellaneous outlays set out under the heading “**Schedule of Outlays**” in the Schedule of Costs to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries and the Schedule of Costs must also be read accordingly.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a party required to provide information or documents to support their application for costs not covered by the Schedule of Costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a party applies for an item of cost not provided for in the Schedule of Costs to be allowed, that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes that the item of cost was necessary or reasonable to be incurred, and documents vouching the cost (if already incurred or paid) or providing an estimate of such cost."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Information and documents in support of application for costs* 3. (1) Where a party intends to apply for costs otherwise than in accordance with the Schedule of Costs, that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes the special circumstances in the case which to support such an application. (2) Where a party applies for an item of cost not provided for in the Schedule of Costs to be allowed, that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes that the item of cost was necessary or reasonable to be incurred, and documents vouching the cost (if already incurred or paid) or providing an estimate of such cost. (3) Where a party applies for the costs of a civil proceeding, that party must have available in Court information or documents sufficient to confirm the particular pre-hearing steps taken or applications made in the proceeding (including particulars, discovery, applications for judgment on affidavit or judgment in default and any case management hearing) so as to enable the proper amount of costs to be determined.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court decide whether to cover the expenses of witnesses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court has discretion to allow or to refuse to allow the expenses (or any part thereof) of any witness"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Witnesses’ expenses* 4. The Court has discretion to allow or to refuse to allow the expenses (or any part thereof) of any witness (including a claimant or respondent) and where allowed, the amount of such expenses (or part thereof) may be measured by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific cost scale applied when the respondent is not professionally represented and loses the case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the costs must be in the appropriate scale for undefended cases, unless the Court, on application made to it at the hearing, directs that the scale for defended cases is to apply."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Where respondent not professionally represented* 6. Where the claimant is successful and the respondent has not been professionally represented at the hearing, the costs must be in the appropriate scale for undefended cases, unless the Court, on application made to it at the hearing, directs that the scale for defended cases is to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order separate payment for the costs of adjournment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may if it thinks it reasonable to do so, make a separate order for their payment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Costs of adjournment* 7. The Court may allow the costs and expenses of any adjournment of the hearing or further hearing of any civil proceedings and may order that such costs be added to or deducted from the costs allowed to either party on the final determination of the proceedings, or may if it thinks it reasonable to do so, make a separate order for their payment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the proceedings to be struck out if it lacks jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where civil proceedings are brought in the Court or in a Court district or Court area which the Court has no jurisdiction to hear and determine, the Court must, as soon as such want of jurisdiction becomes apparent, order the proceedings to be struck out."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Power to strike out with costs claims where no jurisdiction* 8. (1) Where civil proceedings are brought in the Court or in a Court district or Court area which the Court has no jurisdiction to hear and determine, the Court must, as soon as such want of jurisdiction becomes apparent, order the proceedings to be struck out. (2) Where the court strikes out proceedings in accordance with sub-rule (1), it may, if it thinks proper, make an order awarding the respondent such costs as the Court could have awarded if it had jurisdiction to try and determine the proceedings and either the claimant did not appear or appeared and failed to prove his or her claim. Note: See [Courts of Justice Act 1936](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1936/act/48/enacted/en/html) (No. 48 of 1936), section 60'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court decide on specific costs related to certain parts of a civil proceeding?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may make an order for costs in relation to a particular question in or a particular part of a civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Costs of question or part of proceeding* 9. (1) The Court may make an order for costs in relation to a particular question in or a particular part of a civil proceeding. (2) If the Court makes an order under sub-rule (1), the Court must by order fix the amount of the total costs of the proceeding which is attributable to the particular question in or the particular part of the proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the party required to pay costs for applying to extend or shorten the time specified in the rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"that party must, unless the Court otherwise orders, pay the costs of and occasioned by the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Extension or abridgement of time* 10. If a party applies for an extension or abridgement of any time fixed by these Rules or by any order fixing, extending or abridging time, that party must, unless the Court otherwise orders, pay the costs of and occasioned by the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is there an exception for small claims proceedings in the rule about discontinuance or withdrawal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"(2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply to small claims proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Discontinuance or withdrawal* 11. (1) Unless the Court otherwise orders, a party who discontinues or withdraws part of a proceeding, counterclaim or claim by third party notice must pay the costs of the party to whom the discontinuance or withdrawal relates to the time of the discontinuance or withdrawal. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply to small claims proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Must liability for costs be determined according to Order 45 if a lodgment or tender offer is served and not accepted by the time of a final order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"liability for costs must be determined in accordance with [Order 45]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Lodgment or tender offer* 12. If a lodgment or tender offer is served and the lodgment or tender offer has not been accepted at the time a final order is made on the claim that relates to the lodgment, tender offer or offer of compromise, liability for costs must be determined in accordance with [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific schedule mentioned for determining counsel''s fees in cases not covered by existing scales?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the fees must be determined by the Court having regard to the scales and to the amount involved in the case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Scale fees* 13. Where counsel is allowed, the scales of counsel’s fees in the Schedule of Costs apply, provided that in any proceedings not covered by these scales the fees must be determined by the Court having regard to the scales and to the amount involved in the case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court choose a different scale of costs if it deems it inappropriate or unjust?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if in a proceeding or matter the Court considers that the application of the rules in this Order which determine that a particular scale of costs applies would be inappropriate or unjust, the Court may, either at the hearing, or within a reasonable time after the hearing, fix the costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Application of scales* 14. (1) In fixing costs for work done in a civil proceeding the appropriate scales must be determined as follows— - (a) as between party and party, the amount recovered or the value of the property in dispute regulates the scale of the claimant''s costs, and the amount sought to be recovered or the value of the property in dispute regulates the scale of the respondent''s costs; and - as between solicitor and client, unless the Court otherwise orders, the amount sued for, or the value of the property in dispute, regulates the scale without reference to the result; - where a counterclaim is made the scale on which the costs of the parties are to be fixed or taxed must be determined as follows— - if the claimant is successful on both claim and counterclaim, by the amount which the claimant recovers on the claim, unless the amount of the respondent''s counterclaim is the larger, in which case the costs incurred subsequently to the delivery of the counterclaim must be determined by the amount of that counterclaim; - if the respondent is successful on both claim and counterclaim, by the amount which the respondent recovers on the counterclaim, or the amount of the claimant''s claim, whichever is the larger; - (iii) if both parties are successful, by the amounts which they recover on their respective claims; and if both claims fail, by the amount claimed by the opposite party; - in a proceeding or matter for which no provision has been specifically made in the Schedule of Costs, the Court may direct that a scale of costs specified by the Court applies; - despite anything in these Rules, if in a proceeding or matter the Court considers that the application of the rules in this Order which determine that a particular scale of costs applies would be inappropriate or unjust, the Court may, either at the hearing, or within a reasonable time after the hearing, fix the costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the amount recovered defined to exclude interest or damages in the nature of interest that relate to the period after a payment into court was made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any amount recovered by or awarded to the claimant for interest or damages in the nature of interest relating to the period after the day the payment into Court was made or the offer of compromise was served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) For the purposes of sub-rule (1)(a) the amount recovered is— - (a) the amount of the order in the claimant''s favour including any amount for interest or damages in the nature of interest; and - any interest or damages in respect of the amount awarded by the Court under any enactment— but does not include any amount recovered by or awarded to the claimant for interest or damages in the nature of interest relating to the period after the day the payment into Court was made or the offer of compromise was served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court stay or dismiss a proceeding if the claimant fails to pay ordered costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if that party is the claimant, that the proceeding be stayed or dismissed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Time for costs order and payment* 16. (1) The Court may in any proceeding exercise its power and discretion as to costs at any stage of the proceeding or after the conclusion of the proceeding. (2) Costs which a party is required to pay under any of these Rules or an order of the Court must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be paid forthwith. (3) If the Court makes an interlocutory order for costs, the Court may then or thereafter order that if the party liable to pay the costs fails to do so— - (a) if that party is the claimant, that the proceeding be stayed or dismissed; - if that party is a respondent, that the respondent''s defence is to be struck out. (4) In sub-rule (3)— “r**espondent**” includes any person against whom a claim is made in a proceeding; “**claimant**” includes any person who makes a claim in a proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a proceeding that is dismissed by the court automatically associated with costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A proceeding that is or stands dismissed by or under an order of the Court or these Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed with costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Proceeding or counterclaim dismissed* 17. (1) A proceeding that is or stands dismissed by or under an order of the Court or these Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed with costs. (2) Sub-rule (1), with any necessary modification, applies to a counterclaim and to a claim by third party notice as if the counterclaim or third party claim were a claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the party responsible for their own costs if they amend their pleading?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the costs of and occasioned by the amendment and the costs of any application for permission to make the amendment are the parties'' costs in the proceeding"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Amendment* 18. If a pleading is amended (whether with or without permission) the costs of and occasioned by the amendment and the costs of any application for permission to make the amendment are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Must a party pay the costs of proof if they dispute a fact or the authenticity of a document and it is later proven?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"that party must pay the costs of proof, unless the Court otherwise orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Non-admission of fact or document* 19. If a party serves a notice - - (a) under [Order 45D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45D-District-Admissions), rule 3, disputing a fact, and afterwards that fact is proved in the proceeding; - under [Order 45D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45D-District-Admissions), rule 5, disputing the authenticity of a document, and afterwards the authenticity of that document is proved in the proceeding that party must pay the costs of proof, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court change the decision on reserved costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court otherwise orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Costs reserved* 20. If by order of the Court the costs of any interlocutory or other application, or of any step in a proceeding, are reserved, the reserved costs are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can a trustee or mortgagee recover their costs from the fund they hold or the mortgaged property?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A party who sues or is sued as trustee or mortgagee must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be entitled to the costs of the proceeding out of the fund held by the trustee or out of the mortgaged property in so far as the costs are not paid by any other person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Trustee or mortgagee* 21. A party who sues or is sued as trustee or mortgagee must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be entitled to the costs of the proceeding out of the fund held by the trustee or out of the mortgaged property in so far as the costs are not paid by any other person.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the measurement of costs in proceedings related to hire-purchase agreements considered as an action in contract?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings by the owner of a chattel against the hirer of the chattel under a hire-purchase agreement for the recovery or return of the chattel must, for the purpose of the measurement of the costs, be deemed to be an action in contract"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *22 Costs in hire purchase claims* 22. Proceedings by the owner of a chattel against the hirer of the chattel under a hire-purchase agreement for the recovery or return of the chattel must, for the purpose of the measurement of the costs, be deemed to be an action in contract in which the amount sued for is the amount of the instalments due and unpaid under the agreement at the date of commencement of the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the cost calculation in wrongful detention claims based on the value of the detained goods?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the costs awarded must be on the tort scale according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Costs in claims for wrongful detention* 23. In claims for wrongful detention brought by virtue of section 33(3) of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html), the costs awarded must be on the tort scale according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Schedule of Costs applicable to proceedings involving the Attorney General?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The scales of costs in the Schedule of Costs apply to proceedings to which the Attorney General or any Minister of the Government or any Minister of State or any Government Department is a party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Costs in claims to which the Attorney General or a Minister is a party* 24. The scales of costs in the Schedule of Costs apply to proceedings to which the Attorney General or any Minister of the Government or any Minister of State or any Government Department is a party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs in consent proceedings governed by specific rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in consent proceedings to which section of the Courts Act 1991 and Order 40, rule 7 relate, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 10 in the Schedule of Costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Costs in consent proceedings* 25. Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in consent proceedings to which section of the [Courts Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/20/enacted/en/html) and [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 7 relate, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 10 in the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs for proceedings transferred from the High Court or Circuit Court governed by specific rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in civil proceedings remitted or transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court and to which Order 40, rule 8 relates, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 11 in the Schedule of Costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Costs in proceedings transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court* 26. Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in civil proceedings remitted or transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court and to which [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 8 relates, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 11 in the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is value-added tax included in the costs if it is not recoverable?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"There must be added to the costs and, where relevant, counsel’s fees, awarded in any civil proceeding any sum payable by way of value-added tax on the costs by the party to whom they are awarded where, and only where, that party establishes that the sum payable by way of value-added tax is not otherwise recoverable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Value Added Tax* 27. There must be added to the costs and, where relevant, counsel’s fees, awarded in any civil proceeding any sum payable by way of value-added tax on the costs by the party to whom they are awarded where, and only where, that party establishes that the sum payable by way of value-added tax is not otherwise recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about counsel''s fees?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**3****-****COUNSEL''S FEES**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3****-****COUNSEL''S FEES**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a fee for counsel not included in awards of costs for actions in contract or tort where the amount does not exceed €2,000?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in any action in contract, breach of contract, tort or in claims for damages unconnected with contract, where the amount recovered by the claimant or, where the claim was dismissed, the amount claimed against the respondent does not exceed €2,000"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Not allowed where sum does not exceed €2,000* 28. (1) Subject to rule 2(2), in any award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court a fee for counsel may not be included - - (a) in any action in contract, breach of contract, tort or in claims for damages unconnected with contract, where the amount recovered by the claimant or, where the claim was dismissed, the amount claimed against the respondent does not exceed €2,000, and - in any landlord and tenant proceedings for overholding or non-payment of rent, where the annual rent does not exceed €2,000.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is certification by the court required for including a fee for counsel in the award of costs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a fee for counsel may not be included unless the Court certifies that, in its opinion, the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Court to certify for counsel* 29. In the award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply, a fee for counsel may not be included unless the Court certifies that, in its opinion, the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a barrister''s fee allowed to be included in a party''s costs when they are employed on a full-time basis by the party''s solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 No separate counsel’s fee for barrister employed on a full-time basis* 30. Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee. [1] Order 53 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 53 rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the small claims procedure mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 53A: Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure - Court: District # Order 53A: Small Claims Procedure **[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is a claim for debt excluded from the definition of a business small claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"for debt or liquidated damages"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- “**business**” means a natural or legal person (including a company, partnership or natural person trading as a sole trader) who supplies, sells or purchases goods or services in the ordinary course of a business; “**business small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order by a business purchaser against a business vendor in relation to a contract in respect of any goods or service purchased, but excluding any claim— - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, or - for debt or liquidated damages, provided that in every such case the amount of the claim does not exceed the sum of €2,000; “**consumer**” means a purchaser of goods or a service of a type ordinarily supplied for private use or consumption, where the purchaser does not make the contract in the course of a business and the vendor does make the contract in the course of a business; “**Consumer Credit Regulations**” means the European Communities (Consumer Credit Agreements) Regulations 2010 ([S.I. 281 of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/281)); “**consumer small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order (1) in relation to a consumer contract, by the consumer against the vendor in respect of any goods or service purchased, which is not a claim - - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, (2) in relation to a tort, by the claimant (not being a body corporate) against the respondent in respect of minor damage caused to property belonging to the claimant but excluding personal injuries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant start small claim proceedings by applying to a Small Claims Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person so intending (in this Order called “the claimant”) may, instead of issuing a claim notice, apply to the appropriate Small Claims Registrar to have the claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application to begin small claim proceedings* 2. Whenever it is intended to begin civil proceedings in the District Court and the claim to which the proceedings relate is a small claim as defined in this Order, the person so intending (in this Order called “**t****he claimant**”) may, instead of issuing a claim notice, apply to the appropriate Small Claims Registrar to have the claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure, and the proceedings may then be commenced and dealt with in accordance with the provisions of this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application be submitted electronically?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"which may be in electronic form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Filing application* 3. An application to which rule 2 relates must be in writing, which may be in electronic form, in the [Form 53A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/88869131-d146-4c43-8b9b-e75e7cc7423f/Small Claims Procedure - Application to Small Claims Registrar No. 53A.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule The application, when completed, must be filed with the Small Claims Registrar together with any supporting documents required and the appropriate fee. The claimant may call to the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Small Claims Registrar required to record the details of the application in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Recording of application* 4. The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details. The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Small Claims Registrar required to inform the claimant if their claim is not suitable for the Small Claims Procedure?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Rejection or acceptance of application* 5. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and must refund the fee. (2) If the Small Claims Registrar considers the claim to be appropriate to the Small Claims Procedure, he or she must serve by registered post (or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) on the respondent a Notice of Claim in the [Form 53A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bfcc43c-8d9a-4307-8e92-90fa1b8d239c/Small Claims Procedure - Notice of claim against Respondent No. 53A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (containing also Forms [53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) and [53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule together with a copy of the Notice of Claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent pay a claim by instalments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the respondent wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, the Small Claims Registrar must seek the consent of the claimant to the terms proposed by the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Admission of small claim by respondent* 6. (1) If the respondent admits the claim made against him and - (a) agrees to pay the amount claimed, or - consents to judgment being given against him, or - wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, he must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Acceptance of Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. On receipt of such Notice the Registrar must inform the claimant accordingly. (2) Where the respondent agrees to pay the amount claimed, he or she may forward to the Small Claims Registrar, together with [Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule payment by cheque, postal order(s) or money order(s), made payable to the claimant, for the full amount claimed. The Small Claims Registrar must transmit any such payment to the claimant. If the respondent''s agreement to pay is conditional, (e.g. on condition that goods are returned by the claimant), the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and seek his agreement to comply with the respondent''s requirement. (3) Where the respondent consents to judgment being given against him, the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in the manner provided in rule 11. (4) Where the respondent wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, the Small Claims Registrar must seek the consent of the claimant to the terms proposed by the respondent. (5) The details of every agreement reached or settlement effected under this rule must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for the respondent to dispute the claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04] Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claim disputed by respondent* 7.(1) If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim, he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. (2) Where a counterclaim is made the Notice of Dispute must be accompanied by the appropriate fee (or where the Notice of Dispute is sent electronically, the fee must be paid by cheque, postal order or money order to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following transmission of the Notice of Dispute). (3) The Small Claims Registrar must promptly furnish the claimant with a copy of any Notice of Dispute received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Small Claims Registrar proceed to judgment if there''s a default in payment of an instalment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Settlement* 8. (1) The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear. (2) Where a settlement is effected, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (3) Where the terms of an agreement or settlement (including an agreement to pay by instalments) are not complied with, the Small Claims Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party. (4) In cases other than those where payment by instalments has been agreed, he or she must proceed in accordance with the provisions of rule 11. (5) If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications. (6) Where a judgment is issued in a case to which this rule relates, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the party against whom it was issued accordingly and particulars of the request for and the issue and notification of such judgment must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Small Claims Registrar refer a case to the District Court without a request from either party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Registrar may at any time on his own initiative and must, if so requested by either party, refer any application or proceeding under the Small Claims Procedure to the District Court for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Referral to Court for hearing* 9. (1) Where the Small Claims Registrar fails to effect a settlement of the dispute between the parties, he or she must refer the matter to the District Court for hearing. (2) The Registrar may at any time on his own initiative and must, if so requested by either party, refer any application or proceeding under the Small Claims Procedure to the District Court for hearing. (3) On referral under this rule, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the parties of the place, date and time of hearing. He or she must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Are the parties responsible for their own legal costs in the Small Claims Procedure?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The claimant and the respondent are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any) incurred in respect of any claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Liability for costs and expenses* 10. The claimant and the respondent are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any) incurred in respect of any claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant obtain a judgment if the respondent does not respond within the specified time?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the respondent fails to return either the Notice of Acceptance or Liability or the Notice of Dispute to the Small Claims Registrar within the time permitted and fails to contact the Small Claims Registrar within that period, he or she must be deemed to have admitted the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Default by respondent* 11. (1) Where the respondent fails to return either the Notice of Acceptance or Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule or the Notice of Dispute ([Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within the time permitted and fails to contact the Small Claims Registrar within that period, he or she must be deemed to have admitted the claim. (2) The claimant may then apply for judgment by swearing an affidavit of debt and lodging same with the Small Claims Registrar together with a requisition for judgment and a Small Claims judgment, and the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) as if the Notice of Claim and copy claim served under these Rules were a claim notice issued and served under [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court). (3) The forms of affidavit provided in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) may, with necessary modifications, be used for that purpose. (4) The claimant may call to the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the forms. (5) When a judgment is issued under this rule, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the respondent accordingly, and particulars of such issue and notification must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is each party responsible for their own legal costs in an application related to a default judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Review of default judgment* 12. The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 (which relates to the review of default judgments) apply, with necessary modifications, in the case of a judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11 and [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 must be construed accordingly, save that in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can existing forms of judgment be modified for use in Small Claims judgments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Forms of judgment may be used* 14. A judgment granted under the Small Claims Procedure is a Small Claims judgment, and the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a fee required when a party makes an affidavit or affirmation before a Small Claims Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"No fee is payable by any party in respect of any affidavit or affirmation made by him before a Small Claims Registrar under this rule."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Power of Small Claims Registrar to take affidavits and affirmations* 15. (1) Every Small Claims Registrar has the power and is authorised by these Rules, to take affidavits and affirmations for the purposes of processing claims through the Small Claims Procedure and issuing judgments under the Small Claims Procedure. (2) No fee is payable by any party in respect of any affidavit or affirmation made by him before a Small Claims Registrar under this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Notice of Claim be served electronically according to the given rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the service of: ... a Notice of Claim by the Small Claims Registrar on a respondent; ... is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the respondent''s electronic mail address"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 16 Electronic filing 16. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Judge for the time being assigned to the relevant Court district (or in the case of the Dublin Metropolitan District, the President of the District Court) has so directed, the service of: - a Notice of Claim by the Small Claims Registrar on a respondent; - a Notice of Acceptance of Liability by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar; - (iii) a Notice of Dispute by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the respondent''s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the respondent) or to the Small Claims Registrar''s electronic mail address (as identified on a website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic message was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as provided for by rules 5, 6 and 7 within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is it acceptable for a fee to be sent separately from a document if it''s sent immediately after the document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a fee or payment be “lodged together with or forwarded together with” a document or that a document be “accompanied by” a fee, the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and accompanied by a written note quoting any reference or claim number given in respect of the small claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent under the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of the document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document. [1] Order 53A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 mentioned in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “2008 Regulations” means the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order— the “**2****008 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 ([S.I. 533 of 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/533/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,533/2008 - European Communities (European,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2008.&text 1.,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008.)) as amended by the European Communities (European Small Claims Procedure and European Order for Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017 ([S.I. 312 of 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/312/made/en/print)); “**claim form**” means the initiating document completed by a claimant in a European Small Claims Case in the Form A in the Annex to the Regulation; the Regulation**” means [Regulation No 861/2007](https://interlex-portal.eu/FindLaw/Doc/LegalAct/5578101) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 11 July 2007 199 of 31 July 2007, page 1) establishing a European Small Claims Procedure, as amended by [Regulation No. 2015/2421](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2015/2421/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 December 2015, 341 of 24 December 2015; “**European Small Claim**” means a claim referred to in Article 2(1) of the Regulation and which is not excluded from the application of the Regulation by Article 2(2) of the Regulation; “**European Small Claims Procedure**” means the method provided in the Regulation and in this Order for commencing and dealing with a European Small Claim; “**Member State**” means a Member State of the European Union other than Denmark; “**Small Claims Registrar**” or “**Registrar**” has the same meaning as in [Order 53A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53A-District-Small-Claims-Procedure) and, for the avoidance of doubt, includes a District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which a European Small Claim is lodged or to which a European Small Claim is remitted or transferred who for the time being is performing functions of the Court specified in the 2008 Regulations which may be exercised by a District Court Clerk, references in this Order to any form prescribed by or in any Annex to the Regulation include reference to such forms as amended or substituted, and to any other forms for the time being prescribed for use in connection with the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Must all proceedings to which the Order applies be brought and determined according to specific orders and rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"all proceedings to which this Order applies must be brought and determined in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40], rule 4 and, where applicable, [Order rules 2 and 3."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of this Order, all proceedings to which this Order applies must be brought and determined in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 and, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rules 2 and 3. (2) Where proceedings for a European Order for Payment are remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure by the Master of the High Court, the proceedings will be continued and determined in accordance with this Order, and: - the application for a European Order for Payment will stand as the claim form, and - the statement of opposition to a European order for payment will stand as the defendant’s answer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents be considered validly served even if they are sent electronically without a manuscript signature?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Electronic filing* 3. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Court or Registrar has so directed, the service of any document required to be sent, delivered, dispatched or served under the European Small Claims Procedure is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the claimant’s or respondent’s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the claimant or respondent, or as used by either to send any communication to the Registrar) or to the Registrar’s electronic mail address (as identified on any website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature. (3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a document be “accompanied by” any fee or payment, such fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is paid or sent to the Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and the mode of payment includes or is accompanied by any reference or claim number given in respect of the European Small Claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of such document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the recording of details required for both claim forms and proceedings for a European Order for Payment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"every claim form received, and every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Recording of application* 5. The Registrar must, in respect of: - every claim form received, and - every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure, record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Judge assigned to the court district dismiss the claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'he or she may refer the claim to the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) In such circumstances the Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the claimant of the Court’s order and that no appeal lies against the making of such order and must refund any fee, where appropriate. (6) Where the Registrar considers the properly filled in claim comes within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, he or she must, within the time limit prescribed by Article 5.2 of the Regulation: - (a) complete Part of the standard answer form, in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation, and - serve by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) on the respondent copies of the claim form, of the supporting documents (where applicable) and the answer form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific fee required for a counterclaim by the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any counterclaim by the respondent must be accompanied by the appropriate fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Respondent’s response if claim not admitted* 8. (1) Any counterclaim by the respondent must be accompanied by the appropriate fee. (2) The Registrar must dispatch copies of the respondent’s response, including the completed Part of the standard answer form or answer in other written form and the supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(4) of the Regulation. (3) The Registrar must dispatch copies of any counterclaim and any supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(6) of the Regulation. (4) Where, in his or her standard answer form or answer in other written form, the respondent claims that the value of a non-monetary claim exceeds the limit of €5,000 set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation, the Registrar must refer the proceeding to the District Court, which may make such order as it deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) Where a counterclaim exceeds the limit set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation the claim and counterclaim must not proceed in the European Small Claims Procedure and the Registrar must so inform the claimant and the respondent, where possible by electronic mail (and if not possible, by registered or recorded delivery post). (6) The Registrar must advise the claimant and the respondent that he or she may commence proceedings on the claim (or counterclaim) as ordinary civil proceedings before the court in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) or, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 2 or 3. (7) The Registrar must notify the claimant of any order made by the Court under this rule. (8) The provisions of this Order apply to any counterclaim made under the European Small Claims Procedure as they apply to any European Small Claim, with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Registrar extend time limits while trying to settle a dispute?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Registrar may extend the time limits provided for in the Regulation where he or she is seeking to reach a settlement between the parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Settlement* 9. (1) Whenever he or she considers it appropriate, the Registrar must, in accordance with Article 12(3) of the Regulation, seek to reach a settlement between the parties. In that connection he or she may interview (in person or by such other means as he or she considers appropriate) the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him or her to hear. Where a settlement is reached, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (2) Without prejudice to the generality of Article 14 of the Regulation, the Registrar may extend the time limits provided for in the Regulation where he or she is seeking to reach a settlement between the parties. (3) Where the terms of a settlement are not complied with, the Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party in accordance with the provisions of rule 14.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant obtain a default judgment by swearing an affidavit of debt?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the claimant or respondent (as the case may be) may swear an affidavit of debt and file the affidavit with the Registrar, and the Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Default* 10. (1) Where the respondent fails to return the answer form or deliver an answer in other written form to the Registrar within the 30 day period permitted by Article 5(3) of the Regulation, or where the claimant fails to respond to any counterclaim to the Registrar within the 30 day period permitted by Article 5(6) of the Regulation, judgment must be entered in default of answer in accordance with sub-rule (2). (2) Where judgment in default is sought under sub-rule (1) in a claim or counterclaim for a liquidated amount, the claimant or respondent (as the case may be) may swear an affidavit of debt and file the affidavit with the Registrar, and the Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) as if the claim form or counterclaim (as the case may be) were a claim notice issued and served. (3) The forms of affidavit and judgment provided in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) may, with necessary modifications, be used for that purpose. (4) The claimant may call to or contact the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the forms. (5) In a case to which sub-rule (2) applies, where requested by the claimant or (as the case may be) the respondent, the Registrar must issue to the claimant or (as the case may be) the respondent a certificate in the amount in which judgment was given in accordance with rule 14. (6) Where a claim to which no answer form or answer in other written form is returned within the time permitted or a counterclaim to which no response is provided within the time permitted is for an unliquidated amount, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court in accordance with rule 11.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court proceed directly to give judgment without requiring further information, evidence, or an oral hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Referral to Court* 11. (1) Within the time prescribed by Article 7(1) of the Regulation, or such extended time as the Registrar has permitted, where the Registrar is satisfied that a settlement of the proceedings cannot be reached, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court and must notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court. (2) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court in considering the proceedings. (3) When the proceedings are before the Court, the Court may: - (a) direct in accordance with Article 7(1)(a) of the Regulation that further details concerning the claim be demanded from the parties within a period of time specified by the Court, and on the giving of same or the expiry of the time permitted for the giving of same, the proceedings be re-entered before the Court; - direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that evidence be taken and give directions for the taking of evidence in accordance with Article 9 of the Regulation as are appropriate; - where it considers that the conditions set out in Article 5(1a) of the Regulation for the holding of an oral hearing are satisfied, direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that the parties be summoned to an oral hearing and give such directions for the conduct of the oral hearing in accordance with Article 8 of the Regulation or otherwise as are appropriate; - subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim. (4) Where the Court refuses a request by a party for an oral hearing, the reasons for refusal must be given in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation. (5) The Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the parties, or relevant party, in writing, of:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Registrar required to be present at the taking of evidence or oral hearing upon request by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) any further details concerning the claim demanded and the time within which they are to be provided; - the place, date and time at which (and where relevant, any communications technology by means of which) evidence is to be taken or any oral hearing is to be conducted; - any judgment given on any claim and/or counterclaim. (6) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Registrar require a translation of a document submitted in a language other than Irish or English?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If a document (other than a document referred to in Article 6(1) of the Regulation) is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English, the Registrar may, where a translation of that document appears to be necessary for giving a judgment on the claim or counterclaim, require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Translations* 12. (1) If a document (other than a document referred to in Article 6(1) of the Regulation) is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English, the Registrar may, where a translation of that document appears to be necessary for giving a judgment on the claim or counterclaim, require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (2) Where a party to a European Small Claim refuses to accept a document because it is not in: - (a) the official language of the Member State addressed, or, if there are several official languages in that Member State, the official language or one of the official languages of the place where service is to be effected or to where the document is to be dispatched, or - a language which the addressee understands, the Registrar must so inform the other party and request that other party to provide a translation of the document concerned within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (3) Where, on request, a party has failed to comply with the translation requirements set out in Article 6(2), Article 6(3)(a) or Article of the Regulation, as may be appropriate, the Registrar must proceed as if the document concerned were never received by the Court, or by the other party, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court decide on costs in European Small Claims cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may make such order for costs in proceedings on any European Small Claim as it considers appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Costs* 13. The Court may make such order for costs in proceedings on any European Small Claim as it considers appropriate, consistently with the requirements of Article 16 of the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent apply to set aside or vary a judgment by default in a European Small Claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A respondent against whom judgment by default has been given in a European Small Claim in accordance with the provisions of this Order may apply by notice of motion to the Court in the Court area in which the order was obtained for an order to set aside and/or vary the said order on either of the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Application for review of the judgment in accordance with Article 18* 15. (1) A respondent against whom judgment by default has been given in a European Small Claim in accordance with the provisions of this Order may apply by notice of motion (in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications) to the Court in the Court area in which the order was obtained for an order to set aside and/or vary the said order on either of the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation. (2) The notice of motion must be issued within the time limit specified in Article 18(2) of the Regulation and must be served on the claimant or solicitor for the claimant, if any, not less than seven days before the date on which the application is listed before the Court. (3) Service of the notice of motion does not operate as a stay of proceedings. (4) The Court may declare sufficient the service of the notice of motion actually effected. (5) The notice of motion must set out clearly and briefly the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation relied on by the party applying. (6) The Court may, on the hearing of the motion, grant or refuse the application on the basis of the provisions of Article 18(1) of the Regulation. (7) Where the Court rejects the review on the basis that none of the grounds referred to in Article 18(1) of the Regulation applies, the judgment remains in force. (8) Where the Court decides that the review is justified for one of the reasons laid down in Article 18(1) of the Regulation, then the judgment given in the European Small Claims Procedure must be set aside and is null and void.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a creditor applying for enforcement of a judgment from the European Small Claims Procedure to provide additional documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the judgment creditor must, in addition to lodging with the Clerk the summons in duplicate and statutory declaration, provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Enforcement* 16. (1) Subject to the Regulation, the provisions of Orders 51 and 51A, insofar as they may be applied to a judgment of the District Court, may be applied to a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State, and any reference in Orders 51 and 51A to a “judgment” includes, where the context so admits, a reference to such a judgment or court settlement. In such a case, any relevant Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, or order may be adapted to refer to such a judgment. (2) Where an application is made by a creditor for enforcement in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), rule 3 in respect of a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State other than the State, the judgment creditor must, in addition to lodging with the Clerk the summons in duplicate and statutory declaration, provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Is a barrister''s fee allowed to be included in a party''s costs if they are employed full-time by the party''s solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 No separate counsel’s fee for barrister employed on a full-time basis* 30. Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee. [1] Order 53 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 53 rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the small claims procedure covered under Order 53A?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 53A: Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure - Court: District # Order 53A: Small Claims Procedure **[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is a business small claim excluded if it arises from a leasing agreement breach?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- “**business**” means a natural or legal person (including a company, partnership or natural person trading as a sole trader) who supplies, sells or purchases goods or services in the ordinary course of a business; “**business small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order by a business purchaser against a business vendor in relation to a contract in respect of any goods or service purchased, but excluding any claim— - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, or - for debt or liquidated damages, provided that in every such case the amount of the claim does not exceed the sum of €2,000; “**consumer**” means a purchaser of goods or a service of a type ordinarily supplied for private use or consumption, where the purchaser does not make the contract in the course of a business and the vendor does make the contract in the course of a business; “**Consumer Credit Regulations**” means the European Communities (Consumer Credit Agreements) Regulations 2010 ([S.I. 281 of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/281)); “**consumer small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order (1) in relation to a consumer contract, by the consumer against the vendor in respect of any goods or service purchased, which is not a claim - - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, (2) in relation to a tort, by the claimant (not being a body corporate) against the respondent in respect of minor damage caused to property belonging to the claimant but excluding personal injuries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant initiate small claim proceedings by applying to a Small Claims Registrar?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person so intending (in this Order called “the claimant”) may, instead of issuing a claim notice, apply to the appropriate Small Claims Registrar to have the claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application to begin small claim proceedings* 2. Whenever it is intended to begin civil proceedings in the District Court and the claim to which the proceedings relate is a small claim as defined in this Order, the person so intending (in this Order called “**t****he claimant**”) may, instead of issuing a claim notice, apply to the appropriate Small Claims Registrar to have the claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure, and the proceedings may then be commenced and dealt with in accordance with the provisions of this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Small Claims Registrar required to interview the claimant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Recording of application* 4. The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details. The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Small Claims Registrar required to inform the claimant if the claim is not suitable for the Small Claims Procedure?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Rejection or acceptance of application* 5. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and must refund the fee. (2) If the Small Claims Registrar considers the claim to be appropriate to the Small Claims Procedure, he or she must serve by registered post (or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) on the respondent a Notice of Claim in the [Form 53A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bfcc43c-8d9a-4307-8e92-90fa1b8d239c/Small Claims Procedure - Notice of claim against Respondent No. 53A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (containing also Forms [53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) and [53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule together with a copy of the Notice of Claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a respondent make a counterclaim when disputing a small claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claim disputed by respondent* 7.(1) If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim, he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. (2) Where a counterclaim is made the Notice of Dispute must be accompanied by the appropriate fee (or where the Notice of Dispute is sent electronically, the fee must be paid by cheque, postal order or money order to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following transmission of the Notice of Dispute). (3) The Small Claims Registrar must promptly furnish the claimant with a copy of any Notice of Dispute received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Small Claims Registrar interview other people besides the parties involved in the dispute?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Settlement* 8. (1) The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear. (2) Where a settlement is effected, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (3) Where the terms of an agreement or settlement (including an agreement to pay by instalments) are not complied with, the Small Claims Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party. (4) In cases other than those where payment by instalments has been agreed, he or she must proceed in accordance with the provisions of rule 11. (5) If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications. (6) Where a judgment is issued in a case to which this rule relates, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the party against whom it was issued accordingly and particulars of the request for and the issue and notification of such judgment must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Small Claims Registrar refer a case to the District Court on their own initiative?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Registrar may at any time on his own initiative and must, if so requested by either party, refer any application or proceeding under the Small Claims Procedure to the District Court for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Referral to Court for hearing* 9. (1) Where the Small Claims Registrar fails to effect a settlement of the dispute between the parties, he or she must refer the matter to the District Court for hearing. (2) The Registrar may at any time on his own initiative and must, if so requested by either party, refer any application or proceeding under the Small Claims Procedure to the District Court for hearing. (3) On referral under this rule, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the parties of the place, date and time of hearing. He or she must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is each party responsible for their own legal costs when applying to review a default judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Review of default judgment* 12. The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 (which relates to the review of default judgments) apply, with necessary modifications, in the case of a judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11 and [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 must be construed accordingly, save that in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can existing forms of judgment be modified for use in Small Claims cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Forms of judgment may be used* 14. A judgment granted under the Small Claims Procedure is a Small Claims judgment, and the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is a fee considered validly paid if it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar shortly after the document is transmitted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a fee or payment be “lodged together with or forwarded together with” a document or that a document be “accompanied by” a fee, the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and accompanied by a written note quoting any reference or claim number given in respect of the small claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent under the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of the document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document. [1] Order 53A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is electronic communication considered valid if no confirmation of delivery is received within seven days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Electronic filing* 3. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Court or Registrar has so directed, the service of any document required to be sent, delivered, dispatched or served under the European Small Claims Procedure is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the claimant’s or respondent’s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the claimant or respondent, or as used by either to send any communication to the Registrar) or to the Registrar’s electronic mail address (as identified on any website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature. (3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a document be “accompanied by” any fee or payment, such fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is paid or sent to the Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and the mode of payment includes or is accompanied by any reference or claim number given in respect of the European Small Claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of such document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the Registrar to record the details of the claimant and respondent in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Registrar must, in respect of: every claim form received, and every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure, record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Recording of application* 5. The Registrar must, in respect of: - every claim form received, and - every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure, record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific timeframe mentioned for the claimant to respond to the Registrar''s request?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the period specified by the Registrar, which must be 21 days of the sending by the Registrar of Form or such longer period as the Registrar may specify."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Rejection or acceptance of application* 6. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, the Registrar must so inform the claimant, where possible by the same means by which the claimant’s application was sent to the Registrar (and if not possible, by registered or recorded delivery post) and must advise the claimant that he or she may: - (a) withdraw the claim, or - commence proceedings on the claim as ordinary civil proceedings before the Court in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 or, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 2 or 3. (2) Where the claimant withdraws the claim, the Registrar must refund any fee received in respect of the claim. (3) Where the Registrar considers the information provided by the claimant to be inadequate or insufficiently clear, or that the claim form is not filled in properly, he or she must send to the claimant (by the means by which the claim form was sent to him) a request in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation to be completed by the claimant and returned to the Registrar by the same means within the period specified by the Registrar, which must be 21 days of the sending by the Registrar of Form or such longer period as the Registrar may specify. (4) Where the Registrar considers that: - the completed claim is clearly unfounded, or - the application is inadmissible, or - (iii) the information provided by the claimant was inadequate or insufficiently clear or the claim form was not filled in properly, and the claimant was given the opportunity to complete or rectify the claim form or to supply supplementary information or documents or to withdraw the claim, within a period specified by the Registrar, and the claimant fails to complete or rectify the claim form within the time specified,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the claim be dismissed by the Judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'he or she may refer the claim to the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) In such circumstances the Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the claimant of the Court’s order and that no appeal lies against the making of such order and must refund any fee, where appropriate. (6) Where the Registrar considers the properly filled in claim comes within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, he or she must, within the time limit prescribed by Article 5.2 of the Regulation: - (a) complete Part of the standard answer form, in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation, and - serve by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) on the respondent copies of the claim form, of the supporting documents (where applicable) and the answer form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the claimant notified about any order made by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Registrar must notify the claimant of any order made by the Court under this rule."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Respondent’s response if claim not admitted* 8. (1) Any counterclaim by the respondent must be accompanied by the appropriate fee. (2) The Registrar must dispatch copies of the respondent’s response, including the completed Part of the standard answer form or answer in other written form and the supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(4) of the Regulation. (3) The Registrar must dispatch copies of any counterclaim and any supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(6) of the Regulation. (4) Where, in his or her standard answer form or answer in other written form, the respondent claims that the value of a non-monetary claim exceeds the limit of €5,000 set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation, the Registrar must refer the proceeding to the District Court, which may make such order as it deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) Where a counterclaim exceeds the limit set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation the claim and counterclaim must not proceed in the European Small Claims Procedure and the Registrar must so inform the claimant and the respondent, where possible by electronic mail (and if not possible, by registered or recorded delivery post). (6) The Registrar must advise the claimant and the respondent that he or she may commence proceedings on the claim (or counterclaim) as ordinary civil proceedings before the court in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) or, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 2 or 3. (7) The Registrar must notify the claimant of any order made by the Court under this rule. (8) The provisions of this Order apply to any counterclaim made under the European Small Claims Procedure as they apply to any European Small Claim, with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court proceed directly to judgment without requiring additional information, evidence, or an oral hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Referral to Court* 11. (1) Within the time prescribed by Article 7(1) of the Regulation, or such extended time as the Registrar has permitted, where the Registrar is satisfied that a settlement of the proceedings cannot be reached, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court and must notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court. (2) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court in considering the proceedings. (3) When the proceedings are before the Court, the Court may: - (a) direct in accordance with Article 7(1)(a) of the Regulation that further details concerning the claim be demanded from the parties within a period of time specified by the Court, and on the giving of same or the expiry of the time permitted for the giving of same, the proceedings be re-entered before the Court; - direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that evidence be taken and give directions for the taking of evidence in accordance with Article 9 of the Regulation as are appropriate; - where it considers that the conditions set out in Article 5(1a) of the Regulation for the holding of an oral hearing are satisfied, direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that the parties be summoned to an oral hearing and give such directions for the conduct of the oral hearing in accordance with Article 8 of the Regulation or otherwise as are appropriate; - subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim. (4) Where the Court refuses a request by a party for an oral hearing, the reasons for refusal must be given in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation. (5) The Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the parties, or relevant party, in writing, of:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Registrar required to be present at all evidence takings and oral hearings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) any further details concerning the claim demanded and the time within which they are to be provided; - the place, date and time at which (and where relevant, any communications technology by means of which) evidence is to be taken or any oral hearing is to be conducted; - any judgment given on any claim and/or counterclaim. (6) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a creditor applying for enforcement of a judgment from the European Small Claims Procedure in another member state to provide additional documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the judgment creditor must, in addition to lodging with the Clerk the summons in duplicate and statutory declaration, provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Enforcement* 16. (1) Subject to the Regulation, the provisions of Orders 51 and 51A, insofar as they may be applied to a judgment of the District Court, may be applied to a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State, and any reference in Orders 51 and 51A to a “judgment” includes, where the context so admits, a reference to such a judgment or court settlement. In such a case, any relevant Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, or order may be adapted to refer to such a judgment. (2) Where an application is made by a creditor for enforcement in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), rule 3 in respect of a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State other than the State, the judgment creditor must, in addition to lodging with the Clerk the summons in duplicate and statutory declaration, provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Must notifications given by the Registrar to a party to a European Small Claim include particulars and any record number for the claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must include particulars and any record number for the European Small Claim concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18 Notifications by Registrar* 18. Any notification or notice given by the Registrar to a party to a European Small Claim for any purpose set out in the Regulation must be given by the means by which that party has communicated to him (or to the address or contact detail provided for that party) and must include particulars and any record number for the European Small Claim concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person disconnect from a hearing conducted via video link or telephone without the judge''s permission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A person may not cease to take part in a hearing conducted in accordance with this rule by disconnecting his telephone or other means of communication unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of the Judge or Registrar"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *19 Hearings by videolink or telephone* 19. (1) For the purposes of this Order, the contemporaneous linking together by telephone or other means of electronic communication of persons entitled or permitted to be present in the Court at a hearing must be deemed to constitute a hearing before the Court, and all the provisions in these Rules as to hearings apply to such hearing, provided that: - each of the persons taking part in such a hearing is able to hear, and speak to, each of the other persons taking part; and - at the commencement of such a hearing each such person acknowledges his presence and that he or she accepts that the proceedings will be deemed to be a hearing before the Court. (2) A person may not cease to take part in a hearing conducted in accordance with this rule by disconnecting his telephone or other means of communication unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of the Judge or Registrar and a person must be conclusively presumed to have been present at all times during the hearing unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of Judge or Registrar to leave the hearing. [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftnref1) Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), substituted by [S.I. 315 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/315/made/en/print?q 315&years 2018), effective 2 September 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to maintenance for spouses, civil partners, and children?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children - Court: District # **Order 54: Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Family Law Act 1995 referred to as the Act of 1995?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “**Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions. 1. In this Order— “**the Act of 1976**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No. 11 of 1976); the “**Act of 1987**” means the [Status of Children Act 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/26) (No. 26 of 1987); the “**Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995); the “**Act of 1996**” means the [Family Law (Divorce) Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) (No. 33 of 1996); the “**Act of 2010**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (No. 24 of 2010); the “**Act of 2015**” means the [Children and Family Relationships Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) (No. 9 of 2015); “**competent authority**” has the meaning assigned to it in [Order 98]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-98-District-Social-welfare).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the Act of 1976 or the Act of 2010 be heard at any sitting of the Court in the district where either party resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"proceedings under the [Act of 1976] or under the [Act of 2010] may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2.(1) Subject to the provisions of [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), proceedings under the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a provision for hearings to be held not in public?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under the [Act of 1976] or the [Act of 2010] shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* 3. Proceedings under the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when an order is made for a lump sum payment in the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order of the Court may be in the Form 54.24, 54.25, 54.26 or 54.27 Schedule as the case may be, with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where, under the powers conferred by section 42 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) or, as the case ma\y be, under the powers conferred by section 51 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), an order is made in the District Court providing for the making of a lump sum payment or lump sum payments, the order of the Court may be in the Form [54.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b4eb2ec-ced5-4096-a26e-24453a5d88af/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) (A) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.24.docx/docx/1), [54.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e410ed40-f291-4a4c-94c5-bd9fdce034a0/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.25.docx/docx/1), [54.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cf6f0e07-c4ec-4d7d-a727-c0edcd16c7a4/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.26.docx/docx/1) or [54.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/101a15ef-86bb-4452-be5b-f71ea3f71e6d/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(2) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application under Article 6(2) or 6(3) of Regulation No. 805/2004 required to be made by notice of motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004] for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment or an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004] for the issue of a replacement certificate must be made by notice of motion in the [Form No. 44.01]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 8 Application by motion following hearing where decision made 8. (1) Unless made in accordance with rule 6(1) or, as the case may be, rule 7(1), an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment or an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate must be made by notice of motion in the [Form No. 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) A copy of the notice of motion must be served on the judgment creditor or judgment debtor (as the case may be). (3) The application must be supported, where necessary, by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (4) There must be exhibited to any affidavit in support of any such application a completed draft of the form of European Enforcement Order certificate sought, and the contents of the draft certificate must be verified in the affidavit. (5) A copy of the notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit intended to be used in the application must be served on the judgment creditor or judgment debtor (as the case may be) in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) not later than seven days before the return date of the application. (6) The original of any affidavit intended to be used in the application must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Can a maintenance debtor apply to discharge part of a maintenance order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by a maintenance debtor for the discharge of part of a maintenance order under section 6(3) of the Act of 1976"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to discharge or vary maintenance order.* 5.(1) An application: - (a) by a maintenance debtor for the discharge of a maintenance order under section 6(1)(a) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by either party to the proceedings under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) to discharge or vary a maintenance order made by the District Court, or - by a maintenance debtor for the discharge of part of a maintenance order under section 6(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by the maintenance creditor, the maintenance debtor or the Clerk on whose application the order was made, for an order discharging or varying an attachment of earnings order under section 17(1) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by either party to the proceedings under section 46 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) to discharge, vary or terminate a maintenance order made by the District Court, or - by either party to the proceedings under section 173(6) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) to vary or discharge an order or to suspend or revive a provision of an order made under section 175 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), or - by the maintenance creditor, the maintenance debtor or the Clerk on whose application the order was made, for an order discharging or varying an attachment of earnings order under section 183(1) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24),'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application form required before issuing a maintenance summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"must be preceded by the completion by the applicant of an application form in the [Form 54.9]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'must be preceded by the completion by the applicant of an application form in the [Form 54.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/674d4ee7-8dd2-4342-b325-2a3c7a9a6454/Summons to discharge maintenance order or part thereof - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application form, the Clerk shall issue a maintenance summons in the [Form 54.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cfbc556f-537f-4880-bf03-7333a56ff05e/Maintenance Summons - Family Law (Maintenance Of Spouses And Children) Act, 1976 section as amended No. 54.2.docx/docx/1). The maintenance summons and a copy of the application form must be served on the maintenance debtor and on any other person who would be affected by the making of the order sought by the maintenance creditor. (2) The order of the Court on the application may be in the [Form 54.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9a42b3fc-e8ee-4e34-8f78-1c508e8a1ee2/Order discharging maintenance order or part thereof No. 54.10.docx/docx/1) or [54.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/401889bb-1270-4f1b-b982-525f03e1ea02/Order discharging maintenance order varying No. 54.12.docx/docx/1) , Schedule with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is an interim order under section 7 of the Act of 1976 allowed to use Form 54.13?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An interim order made by the Court under: - (a) section 7 of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Interim order.* 6. An interim order made by the Court under: - (a) section 7 of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - section 47 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), may be in the [Form 54.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 54.13.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice required when making an parte application for a direction that payments be made to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of such application in the Form 54.16 Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for direction that payments be made to Clerk.* 8. An application under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), for a direction that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order be made to the Clerk may be made parte. Notice of such application in the [Form 54.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a799024a-e277-4b7c-8d88-f0511d68a317/Notice of application to have payments made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 54.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 54.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b8241e4b-354d-4b09-afaa-780b16bbca6c/Order directing that payments under a maintenance - variation - interim order shall be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.17.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to provide a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk shall give a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment made by him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payments to the Clerk.* 9.(1) Where the Court directs that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order shall be made to the Clerk, such Clerk must send a notice in the [Form 54.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/53087a22-e64e-4dd0-ae24-dc1108d8b618/Notice of direction that payments be made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.18.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations, by prepaid ordinary post to the maintenance debtor indicating the place at which and the days and hours during which payments under the order should be made. (2) The Clerk shall give a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment made by him or her and shall transmit such payment to the maintenance creditor or, if authorised in writing by the maintenance creditor so to do, the Clerk may transmit the payment to the competent authority.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before a maintenance debtor can apply to have a direction discharged?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 9(3) of the [Act of 1976] or, as the case may be, section 50(3) of the [Act of 2010], by a maintenance debtor to have a direction under section 9(1) of the [Act of 1976] or, as the case may be, section 50(1) of the [Act of 2010], discharged must be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance creditor of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to discharge direction.* 10. An application under section 9(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section 50(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), by a maintenance debtor to have a direction under section 9(1) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section 50(1) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), discharged must be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance creditor of a summons in the [Form 54.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0644dad-4442-43cb-a658-6bc384ed3425/Summons to discharge direction that payments under - maintenance - variation - interim order be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 54.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9146ff2b-d4fc-4674-ac6f-e6935acd99ce/Order discharging direction that payments under maintenance - variation - interim order be made to the district court clerk No. 54.20.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration regarding service of the summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, a statutory declaration as to service of the summons (and any other document concerned) must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of summonses.* 12.(1) A summons (and any document required to accompany it) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the summons is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, a statutory declaration as to service of the summons (and any other document concerned) must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to register particulars of an order for maintenance pending suit received from the Registrar of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such Clerk shall register particulars of the order and shall proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Rules to apply to orders for maintenance pending suit etc.* 13. Where the Clerk receives a copy— - (a) of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 18 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 22 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html), or - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), from the Registrar of the Court which made that order, and payments under the order are directed to be made to the District Court Clerk (as provided for in section 20 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) and in section 28 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) (or, as the case may be, section 50, or section 50 as applied by section 134 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24))), such Clerk shall register particulars of the order and shall proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued before making an application to secure payments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 54.22 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Orders to secure payments.* 14.(1) Where the Court has made an order providing for periodical payments by way of support or maintenance by a maintenance debtor to a maintenance creditor, an application may be made to the Court on a date subsequent to the date on which such order is made pursuant to the provisions of section 41 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) or, as the case may be, section 52 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), by any person having an interest in the proceedings to secure the said payments to the maintenance creditor. (2) Such application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 54.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd67ed61-5ef9-4380-9150-6bce33999806/Application to secure maintenance payments - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 & Family Law Act, 1995 No. 54.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order of the Court granting such application may be in the [Form 54.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/00f50b6b-fa81-4e47-8694-8b7a20287e61/Order to secure maintenance payments - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.23.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when the court orders a report under section 47?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order%20directing%20report%20-%20Family%20Law%20Act%201995,%20section%2047%20No.%2058.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report under section 47 of the Act of 1976.* 16.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order giving directions for the purpose of procuring a report in writing on any question affecting the welfare of a party to the proceedings or any other person to whom they relate may be included in writing in the application form or summons, or made at the hearing. (2) Where the Court grants an application for an order mentioned in sub-rule (1), or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report may be in the [Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order directing report - Family Law Act 1995, section 47 No. 58.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54 substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 referred to in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2010)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - “**the Act**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2010).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the Act be held in any district within the same state if they are deemed urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2.(1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Are proceedings under the Act held in private?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public. # Shared Home Protection'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.1 required before making an application under section 34(1) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(1) of the Act* 4. An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f86fb3ab-d9fc-4b3e-9d67-b7af5da927dd/Order prohibiting - disposition - removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.5 used when a civil partner makes a complaint under section 34(3) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 34(3) of the Act* 5. Where complaint is made by a civil partner to a Judge under section 34(3) of the Act that the other civil partner has contravened the provisions of section 34(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.6 required before an application can be made under section 34(4) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(4) of the Act* 6. An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.8 used when a complaint is made under section 39 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 39 of the Act* 7. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 39 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Third Party Procedure Order applicable to the proceedings mentioned in section 34(5) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure) (Third Party Procedure) shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 34(5) of the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Joinder of parties* 8. The provisions of [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure) (Third Party Procedure) shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 34(5) of the Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application to declare a conveyance void required to be in a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the Form 60.9"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a person who wants to declare a conveyance void to enter relevant particulars of their proceedings as a lis pendens?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of section 28(1) of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Lis Pendens* (3) A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of section 28(1) of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the [Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate from a consultant psychiatrist required if it is alleged that the civil partner is incapable of consenting?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where it is alleged that the civil partner whose consent is required under section 28 of the Act is incapable of consenting, the original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist, within the meaning of the Mental Health Act 2001, shall be annexed to the notice of application lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order dispensing with consent or giving consent* 10. (1) An application for an order under section 29(1), section 29(3) or section 29(4) of the Act to dispense with, or as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, of a civil partner to the conveyance of the shared home shall be in the [Form 54A.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1584a21-776d-486c-88ad-e98591ac402b/Notice of Application to -dispense with consent †give consent of civil partner to conveyance of shared home No. 54A.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where it is alleged that the civil partner whose consent is required under section 28 of the Act is incapable of consenting, the original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist, within the meaning of the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), shall be annexed to the notice of application lodged with the Clerk. The Court may accept affidavit evidence of the certification, subject to the right of any party contesting the certification to cross-examine. (3) The order of the Court on such an application shall be in the [Form 54A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f66baa3-063e-4444-b063-9edd66eb2db2/Order -Dispensing with Consent †Giving Consent of Civil Partner to Conveyance of Shared Home - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 29 No. 54A.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4) On granting an application under section 29 of the Act to dispense with or, as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, the Court may order pursuant to section 33 of the [Trustee Act 1893](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1893/act/53/enacted/en/print.html) that a person be appointed to execute the conveyance of the interest in question and the order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6232d23b-0016-4559-a960-0b355c5c68c0/Order appointing a person to execute consent to conveyance of family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 4(1) No. 60.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for an application related to loss of interest in the shared home?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under section 30(2) of the Act to compensate the applicant civil partner or a dependant child of the civil partners for loss of interest in the shared home occasioned by the conduct of the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.18]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Conduct leading to loss of Shared Home* 12.(1) An application to the Court for an order under section 30(2) of the Act to compensate the applicant civil partner or a dependant child of the civil partners for loss of interest in the shared home occasioned by the conduct of the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3ae2cb1e-21c5-4e31-92a0-2a6a60b55277/Application for an order for compensation for loss relating to the family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(2) No. 60.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before a qualified cohabitant can apply for an order under section 194?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a qualified cohabitant for an order under section 194 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the legal personal representative of the cohabitant of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 194* 13. An application by a qualified cohabitant for an order under section 194 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the legal personal representative of the cohabitant of a summons in the [Form 54A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e0402f-8d78-4ea1-ac0b-d7dad17d58e3/Summons - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 194 No. 54A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54A substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a specific type of court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings - Court: District #'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Family Law Act of 1995 mentioned in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions. 1.[1] In this Order — “**the Act**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11/enacted/en/html) (No. 11 of 1976); “**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995); “**competent authority**” has the meaning assigned to it in [Order 98]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-98-District-Social-welfare) of these Rules;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Can legal proceedings be held in any sitting of the Court within the court area where either party resides or conducts business?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Venue. 2. (1) Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the hearing conducted in public according to the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"such proceedings shall be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* (2) such proceedings shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application for an attachment of earnings order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application.* 3.[2] An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons in the Form [56.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bf99d413-4010-4654-a8b2-838840cd81af/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) Section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.1.docx/docx/1) or [56.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/689f01ce-dd1a-44c1-8127-b34a84073475/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be. Where the Court grants the application or, where the Court, having made an antecedent order, makes, in accordance with subsection (1A) (a) of the Act, as inserted by the Act of 1995, an attachment of earnings order in the same proceedings in order to secure payments under the antecedent order, the order of the Court shall be in accordance with Form [56.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a225df3-572c-4c7e-8dbf-c9b2a7ac2c0c/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.3.docx/docx/1) or [56.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/737fe077-d48e-44fb-afc3-dc7f3b20872e/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Can service be performed by sending an order via registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such service may be effected by leaving a copy of the order at, or sending a copy of the order by registered prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of the person to be served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mode of service.* 5. Such service may be effected by leaving a copy of the order at, or sending a copy of the order by registered prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of the person to be served. A copy of the order shall also be sent by registered prepaid post to the maintenance debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk send payments received under an attachment of earnings order via post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payment by Clerk.* 7. The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application can be made for a determination as to whether payments are earnings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments of a particular class or description are earnings for the purposes of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for determination as to earnings.* 9. An application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments of a particular class or description are earnings for the purposes of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule upon each of the other parties to the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the employer included as a party in the proceedings mentioned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The parties to proceedings in respect of an application under rule 9 shall be the employer, the maintenance debtor and the person to whom payments under the order are being made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Parties to such proceedings Order of Court.* 10. The parties to proceedings in respect of an application under rule 9 shall be the employer, the maintenance debtor and the person to whom payments under the order are being made. The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with Form 56.7 Schedule A copy of such order shall be sent by the Clerk by prepaid post to each of the parties to the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice of the application required to be given to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of such application in the Form 54.16 Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for direction that payments be made to Clerk.* 8. An application under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), for a direction that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order be made to the Clerk may be made parte. Notice of such application in the [Form 54.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a799024a-e277-4b7c-8d88-f0511d68a317/Notice of application to have payments made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 54.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 54.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b8241e4b-354d-4b09-afaa-780b16bbca6c/Order directing that payments under a maintenance - variation - interim order shall be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.17.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to provide a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment received?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk shall give a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment made by him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payments to the Clerk.* 9.(1) Where the Court directs that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order shall be made to the Clerk, such Clerk must send a notice in the [Form 54.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/53087a22-e64e-4dd0-ae24-dc1108d8b618/Notice of direction that payments be made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.18.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations, by prepaid ordinary post to the maintenance debtor indicating the place at which and the days and hours during which payments under the order should be made. (2) The Clerk shall give a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment made by him or her and shall transmit such payment to the maintenance creditor or, if authorised in writing by the maintenance creditor so to do, the Clerk may transmit the payment to the competent authority.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when the court orders a welfare-related report?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order requisitioning the report may be in the [Form 58.50]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report under section 47 of the Act of 1976.* 16.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order giving directions for the purpose of procuring a report in writing on any question affecting the welfare of a party to the proceedings or any other person to whom they relate may be included in writing in the application form or summons, or made at the hearing. (2) Where the Court grants an application for an order mentioned in sub-rule (1), or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report may be in the [Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order directing report - Family Law Act 1995, section 47 No. 58.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54 substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 - Court: District # Order 54A: Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in the same district if they are certified as urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2.(1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Are proceedings under the Act conducted in private?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public. # Shared Home Protection'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.1 required before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(1) of the Act* 4. An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f86fb3ab-d9fc-4b3e-9d67-b7af5da927dd/Order prohibiting - disposition - removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.5 used when a civil partner files a complaint under section 34(3) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 34(3) of the Act* 5. Where complaint is made by a civil partner to a Judge under section 34(3) of the Act that the other civil partner has contravened the provisions of section 34(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.6 required before making an application under section 34(4) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(4) of the Act* 6. An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application to declare a conveyance void required to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application under section 194 can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a qualified cohabitant for an order under section 194 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the legal personal representative of the cohabitant of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 194* 13. An application by a qualified cohabitant for an order under section 194 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the legal personal representative of the cohabitant of a summons in the [Form 54A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e0402f-8d78-4ea1-ac0b-d7dad17d58e3/Summons - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 194 No. 54A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54A substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the attachment of earnings order issued by a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings - Court: District #'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Family Law Act, 1995 referred to in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions. 1.[1] In this Order — “**the Act**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11/enacted/en/html) (No. 11 of 1976); “**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995); “**competent authority**” has the meaning assigned to it in [Order 98]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-98-District-Social-welfare) of these Rules;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Can legal proceedings be held in any sitting of the Court within the same court area as where one of the parties resides or conducts business?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Venue. 2. (1) Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before applying for an attachment of earnings order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application.* 3.[2] An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons in the Form [56.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bf99d413-4010-4654-a8b2-838840cd81af/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) Section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.1.docx/docx/1) or [56.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/689f01ce-dd1a-44c1-8127-b34a84073475/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be. Where the Court grants the application or, where the Court, having made an antecedent order, makes, in accordance with subsection (1A) (a) of the Act, as inserted by the Act of 1995, an attachment of earnings order in the same proceedings in order to secure payments under the antecedent order, the order of the Court shall be in accordance with Form [56.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a225df3-572c-4c7e-8dbf-c9b2a7ac2c0c/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.3.docx/docx/1) or [56.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/737fe077-d48e-44fb-afc3-dc7f3b20872e/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk send payments received under an attachment of earnings order by post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payment by Clerk.* 7. The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order for a statement of particulars required to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order under section 13 (1) of the Act requiring a statement of particulars of a maintenance debtor’s earnings shall be in accordance with [Form 56.5]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order requiring statement of particulars.* 8. An order under section 13 (1) of the Act requiring a statement of particulars of a maintenance debtor’s earnings shall be in accordance with [Form 56.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55da6c2-3c16-41c9-b312-825be96ac80a/Order of the court requiring statement of particulars of maintenance debtor''s earnings - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.5.docx/docx/1)Schedule The Clerk shall cause the order to be served upon the person to whom it is directed by sending a copy thereof by prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of such person.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application can be made for a determination on earnings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments of a particular class or description are earnings for the purposes of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for determination as to earnings.* 9. An application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments of a particular class or description are earnings for the purposes of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule upon each of the other parties to the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application can be made to vary or discharge an attachment of earnings order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 17 of the Act for the variation or discharge of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to vary or discharge attachment of earnings order.* 11. An application under section 17 of the Act for the variation or discharge of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons ([Form 56.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/48a13e52-8edd-4ff7-a05d-8cbc5e1842cb/Summons to vary or discharge attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.8.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the maintenance creditor and/or the maintenance debtor, as the case may be. The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in accordance with [Form 56.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0526426a-fae3-4939-aeb1-f22b846c7f1b/Order varying - discharging attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.9.docx/docx/1) Schedule The Clerk or the maintenance creditor, as the case may be, shall cause the order to be served upon the employer in the manner prescribed in rule 5 of this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Do enforcement proceedings and related warrants cease when an attachment of earnings order is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any proceedings commenced under section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1940] shall lapse and any warrant or order issued or made under that section in any such proceedings shall cease to have effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Cesser of warrant and lapse of enforcement proceedings.* 13. Where an attachment of earnings order has been made, any proceedings commenced under section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), shall lapse and any warrant or order issued or made under that section in any such proceedings shall cease to have effect.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to provide evidence of the maintenance order when applying for an attachment of earnings order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the maintenance order, variation order, interim order (as the case may be) and in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to produce documents.* 14. On the hearing of an application for an attachment of earnings order the Clerk to whom payments under the maintenance order, variation order, interim order, or enforceable maintenance order are payable shall tender as evidence - - (a) the maintenance order, variation order, interim order (as the case may be) and in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order, - the request in writing received by the Clerk from the maintenance creditor, - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court, and - any other relevant document. The Clerk shall also prove the amount of arrears due. [1] Order 56 rule 1 amended by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [2] Order 56 rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the 1964 Act be heard at any sitting of the Court in the district if the Clerk certifies they are urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on an originating document that the proceedings are urgent, the said originating document may, subject to the provisions of rule 10, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2.(1) Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where any party to the proceedings resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where, however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on an originating document that the proceedings are urgent, the said originating document may, subject to the provisions of rule 10, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which an applicant ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or where no applicant under that section ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Dublin Metropolitan District.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific rule regarding the hearing of proceedings concerning children under 18 years old?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under the [1964 Act] and proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act] concerning a child under the age of 18 years shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) and proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) concerning a child under the age of 18 years shall be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application form required to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"which must be submitted to the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of applications* 4. An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) may be begun by the completion by the applicant of an application form in the [Form 58.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application form, the Clerk will issue a notice in the [Form 58.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/850a2605-a072-411b-84e6-dfd3fd171597/Notice of application by surviving guardian - testamentary guardian for order - Guardianship of Infants Acts 1964, section 7(4) No. 58.3.docx/docx/1): - (a) under section 6A (as inserted by the 1987 Act and as substituted by section 48 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person who, being a parent of a child, is not a guardian of the child, for an order appointing the person as guardian of the child; the notice and copy application form must be served on the other parent and on any other guardian of the child; - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person who, not being a parent of a child, is eligible under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) to make such application for an order appointing the person as a guardian of the child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each person who is a parent or guardian of the child concerned and in the case of an application by a person to whom section 6C(2)(b) of the 1964 Act applies, the notice and copy application form must also be served upon the Child and Family Agency;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice and copy application form required to be served on specific individuals when applying for certain orders related to guardianship?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the notice and copy application form and a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6 must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) appointing a nominated person as a guardian of the child, on the application of a qualifying guardian or nominated person under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form and a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6 must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a temporary guardian or the qualifying guardian concerned for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a declaration that a person named in the application is or is not a guardian, by virtue of the circumstances set out in section 2(4A) or of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), of a child named in the application (the “child concerned”): the notice and copy application form must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) and upon any other person directed by the Court to be given notice of the application; - for an order under section 7(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 50 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on the surviving guardian or testamentary guardian of the child, as the case may be;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is service of notice required when applying to remove a guardian mentioned in section 8(4) of the 1964 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(2) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), unless the application is made by the surviving parent (in which case it can be made parte* in accordance with rule 5): where the application is not heard parte*, the notice and copy application form must be served on any person directed by the Court to be given notice of the application; - for an order to remove from office a guardian mentioned in section 8(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (substituted by section 51 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) and to appoint another guardian in his or her place under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order to appoint a guardian in place of a deceased guardian, under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), unless the child has no guardian, or the applicant is the only guardian (in which case it can be made parte* in accordance with rule 5): where the application is not heard parte*, the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order to remove from office a guardian mentioned in section 8(6) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 51 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order giving the Court’s direction under section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each other person who is a parent or guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) giving a relative of a child or a person with whom the child resides or has formerly resided access to the child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each other guardian of the child concerned;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is an parte application required before a guardian can be appointed under the 1964 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act] shall be made parte in the first instance subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the [Form 58.1 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications parte* 5.(1) An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall be made parte* in the first instance subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the [Form 58.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1): - (a) an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(1) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(2) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the application is made by the surviving parent, - for an order to appoint a guardian in place of a deceased guardian, under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the child has no guardian, or the applicant is the only guardian;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is a witness required for the signing of a nomination under section', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The nomination shall be signed and dated by the qualifying guardian concerned in the presence of a witness who is not the nominated person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Nomination* 6.(1) A nomination under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) by a qualifying guardian shall be in the [Form 58.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77911c9d-7de9-4045-a206-b5f9fd657ab8/Nomination - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section (inserted by section 49 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) No. 58.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be signed and dated by the qualifying guardian concerned in the presence of a witness who is not the nominated person. (2) The original or a true copy of the nomination shall be annexed to the application form lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the summons for alleged offences under sections 5, 11, and of the 1964 Act served on the person against whom the offence is alleged?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the Form 58.28 or 58.29 Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where complaint is made to a Judge alleging an offence of failure or refusal under section 5 of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986, to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order under section 7 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or section (inserted by the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the [Form 58.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3e57c96e-f893-4c05-8a0b-39b5d0b778d7/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.28.docx/docx/1) or [58.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b802823-d92d-4d19-9693-8aabef61b2ec/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the consent of the applicant mentioned in section of the 2015 Act required for the declaration of parentage?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in the case of the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act], confirm that he or she consents to the making of a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for declaration of parentage: DAHR* 9.****[2]****(1) An application to the Court under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) for a declaration of parentage shall be preceded by the issue by the applicants of a notice in the [Form 58.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6a26fa7f-6bac-49a5-9c05-67fbbea7f3ba/Notice of Application for a declaration of parentage, Children and Family Relationships Act 2015, Section 21 No. 58.54.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The child to whom an application for a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) relates shall be named as a respondent to the application. (3) The application shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn by each applicant, and where necessary other affidavit evidence in support of the application, which shall: - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the child to whom the application relates is a child to whom section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, and in particular in a case to which section 20(1)(b)(ii) of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, verify that the person who performed the DAHR procedure outside the State was authorised to do so under the law of the place where the procedure was performed and the law providing for such authorisation; - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) was, at the time referred to in section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the intending parent of the child, and - (iii) in the case of the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), confirm that he or she consents to the making of a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html). (4) True copies of the notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be served on each respondent not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing. (5) The original notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be lodged, together with a statutory declaration as to service, with the Clerk not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Must a solicitor provide a statutory declaration when acting for the applicant in certain sections of the 1964 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in which a solicitor is acting for the applicant, the notice and copy application form must be accompanied by a copy of a statutory declaration of the solicitor indicating, if it be the case, that the solicitor has complied with subsection (2) of section 20 of the [1964 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents* 10.(1) A notice and copy application form (and any relevant court order) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice is returnable. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2), the notice and copy application form (and any relevant court order) must be served at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice is returnable. (3) Additionally, in proceedings under: - section 6A (as inserted by section 12 of the 1987 Act and as substituted by section 48 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or - (iii) section (inserted by section 9 of the 1987 Act) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), in which a solicitor is acting for the applicant, the notice and copy application form must be accompanied by a copy of a statutory declaration of the solicitor indicating, if it be the case, that the solicitor has complied with subsection (2) of section 20 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 11 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html) and as amended by section 24 of the Mediation Act 2017) in relation to the matter. The original statutory declaration must be filed with the Clerk. (4) A statutory declaration as to service of any notice, application form or court order served in accordance with rule 4 or rule 8 must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to provide a copy of an order or declaration to individuals involved in the case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11. Where the Court makes an order under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) or a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Can a child''s age be proven with a certified extract from the Register of Births?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The age of a child may be proved by producing a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the child’s birth"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proof of age* 12. The age of a child may be proved by producing a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the child’s birth or by such other evidence as the Court considers sufficient.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court order the delivery of a notice to someone who hasn''t received it yet?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may direct the service of notice upon any person not already served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court may direct service* 13. In any proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) the Court may direct the service of notice upon any person not already served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Does an appeal automatically stay the operation of an order made under the 1964 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"an appeal from an order made under the 1964 Act shall stay the operation of the order only if, and to such extent and upon such terms (if any), as the Court shall determine."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Effect of appeal from orders* 14. Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 4 and Order 101 and that an appellant has entered into a recognizance for appeal, an appeal from an order made under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall stay the operation of the order only if, and to such extent and upon such terms (if any), as the Court shall determine.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Child and Family Agency notified when the court adjourns proceedings and directs them to investigate a child''s circumstances?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Child and Family Agency"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where, under either 12A(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) or section 20 of the Child Care Act 1991, the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Child and Family Agency to undertake an investigation of a child''s circumstances, if the Child and Family Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Child and Family Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s decision. (7) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the Child Care Act 1991 as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation by the Child and Family Agency — - (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. [1] Order 58 originally amended as per Schedule 1 to [S.I. 125 of 1999](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1999/si/125/made/en/print?q 125&years 1999), substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016, and resubstituted by [S.I. 434 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/434/made/en/print), effective 22 October 2020 and resubstituted by [S.I. 220 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/220/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [2] Order 58 rule 9 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text for Order 59 related to domestic violence a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 59 - Domestic Violence - Court: District # **Order 59: Domestic Violence**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Domestic Violence Act 2018 referred to in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “2018 Act” means the [Domestic Violence Act 2018]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order- the “**2****018 Act**” means the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6) (No. 6 of 2018); “**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency, and unless the context otherwise requires, words and phrases used in this Order which are defined in section 2 of the 2018 Act have the same meaning as in the 2018 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under this Order be heard in a special sitting of the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a special sitting of the District Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings under this Order may be brought, heard and determined before: - a sitting of the District Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 22(2) of the 2018 Act as residing or, if the application is for a barring order or an emergency barring order, where there is situate the place in relation to which that application is made, or - a special sitting of the District Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific section mentioned that allows proceedings to be held not in public?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under the 2018 Act must, subject to section 23 of the 2018 Act, be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the 2018 Act must, subject to section 23 of the 2018 Act, be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to provide the Clerk with information to complete the Domestic Violence Summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Safety Order* 4.(1) An application to the Court under section 6 of the 2018 Act for a safety order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a safety order may be in the [Form 59.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8782b974-2642-44b0-aa3d-f4396f780f8b/Safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 No. 59.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to provide information to the Clerk to complete the Domestic Violence Summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Barring Order* 5.(1) An application to the Court under section 7 of the 2018 Act for a barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a barring order may be in the [Form 59.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55a5bf8-b6ee-4b19-a89c-4a9fefa0218c/Barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 7 No. 59.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an interim barring order be made without serving the required summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An interim barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Interim Barring Order* 6.(1) An application to the Court under section 8(1) of the 2018 Act for an interim barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons ( [Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)); - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An interim barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served. (3) An order of the Court granting an interim barring order may be in the [Form 59.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63a952ab-89e5-4b08-8341-7fdf769a49df/Interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.7.docx/docx/1). (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an interim barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an emergency barring order be applied for without serving a summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An emergency barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by sub-rule (1) has not been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Emergency Barring Order* 7.(1) An application to the Court under section 9(3) of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order must, subject to sub-rule (3), be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 59.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f9afe07-f783-46db-ac43-344a44039615/Summons for an emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.17.docx/docx/1). (2) An application to the Court under section 9 of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order: - may be made on the date on which the summons has been listed for hearing (provided the summons has been served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1); or - may, where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1). (3) An emergency barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by sub-rule (1) has not been served. (4) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86fc13e3-6868-4b1a-801f-bce8b0bf749d/Emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act section 9 No. 59.19.docx/docx/1). (5) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an emergency barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a protection order be made without notifying the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the application is not being made parte, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Protection Order* 8.(1) An application to the Court under section 10(1) of the 2018 Act for a protection order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a safety order and/or a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons; - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An order of the Court granting a protection order may be in the [Form 59.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b60d519-6deb-4554-b964-a8866bdd5138/Protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.9.docx/docx/1). (3) A protection order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 4 or rule 5 has not yet been served. (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where a protection order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before varying any of the mentioned orders?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 6(8) to vary a safety order, section 7(12) to vary a barring order, section 8(7) to vary an interim barring order, section 9(8) to vary an emergency barring order or section 10(4) to vary a protection order, must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Vary Safety/ Barring/ Interim Barring/ Emergency Barring Order/ Protection Order* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 6(8) to vary a safety order, section 7(12) to vary a barring order, section 8(7) to vary an interim barring order, section 9(8) to vary an emergency barring order or section 10(4) to vary a protection order, must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b921df5c-f0e6-42ab-bebf-e788db94793a/Summons to vary a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring order - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.10.docx/docx/1). (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df43420-af97-4146-811a-4b79576c72c2/Order varying a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.11.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an application can be made to the court to discharge certain orders?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 21 of the 2018 Act for the discharge of a safety order, a barring order, an interim barring order, an emergency barring order or a protection order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Discharge Safety/Barring/ Interim Barring / Emergency Barring/ Protection Order* 10.(1) An application to the Court under section 21 of the 2018 Act for the discharge of a safety order, a barring order, an interim barring order, an emergency barring order or a protection order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/10350a75-187a-4b09-9aad-e936cff77e2f/Summons to discharge a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 21 No. 59.12.docx/docx/1). (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c8f54875-17e0-4ea9-b50d-c84366e802bf/Order discharging a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 21 No. 59.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to send a certified copy of the order to the Garda Síochána station by prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person for whose benefit the safety order or protection order was made resides, and ... by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11.(1) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a safety order or a protection order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(1) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, the applicant for the safety order or barring order concerned, - to the respondent to the application for the safety order or in respect of a protection order, the respondent to the application for the safety order or barring order concerned, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, for the safety order or barring order, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person for whose benefit the safety order or protection order was made resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a safety order or a protection order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such safety order or protection order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (2) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a barring order or an interim barring order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(2) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the barring order,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the method of sending copies of orders to the Garda Síochána members specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- to the respondent to the application for the barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the barring order was made, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a barring order or an interim barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such barring order or interim barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (3) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an emergency barring order, the Clerk must in accordance with section 19(3) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the emergency barring order, - to the respondent to the application for the emergency barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the emergency barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the emergency barring order was made, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the emergency barring order sent to the Garda Síochána member via prepaid registered post or email?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the order in question is a variation or discharge of an emergency barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such emergency barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to notify the Gardaí when a protection order no longer applies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Protection Order/Interim Barring Order/Emergency Barring Order ceases to have effect* 12.(1) Where a protection order has been made and: - the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined, or - the protection order is discharged before the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be. (2) Where an interim barring order has been made and the interim barring order has ceased to have effect otherwise than by expiry of the time for which the order is stated on its face to be in force, the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons be served less than seven days before the hearing if it''s considered urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service* 13.(1) A summons issued under this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) A request for a direction under section 18(4) of the 2018 Act that a relevant order be served personally by a member of the Garda Síochána on a respondent who was not present at the sitting of the Court at which the order was made may be made *viva voce* at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte* at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. The Court may in any case give such a direction of its own motion when the order is made, (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under the 2018 Act in accordance with section 31 of the 2018 Act, direct or deem sufficient service of a document under the 2018 Act by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal stay the operation of a safety order or barring order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an appeal from a safety order or a barring order shall, if the Court or the Circuit Court so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Effect of appeal from orders* 14.(1) In accordance with section 20 of the 2018 Act, notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 9(4) and Order 101 and that an appellant has entered into a recognisance for appeal: - (a) an appeal from a safety order or a barring order shall, if the Court or the Circuit Court so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination; - an appeal from a protection order, an interim barring order or an emergency barring order shall not stay the operation of the order. (2) An application to the Court to stay the operation of a safety order or a barring order under the terms of section 20 of the 2018 Act, may be made following the service and lodgment of a notice of appeal and lodgment of the recognisance for appeal and when made otherwise than upon the occasion of the making of those orders must be preceded by the issue of a notice in the [Form 59.15, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9b0bb38d-2de1-44bb-83bf-6f34c56e7bb3/Application for a stay on the operation of a safety order - barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.15.docx/docx/1) which must be served upon the respondent to the application two days before the hearing of the application. (3) Where the Court grants a stay on the operation of a safety order or a barring order, and the Clerk has previously supplied the copies of the orders as directed by rule 11, the Clerk must send a copy of the order granting the stay (which may be in the [Form 59.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/829bd6d2-f7e6-44d7-8690-fc0aa82cd503/Order staying operation of a safety order - barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.16.docx/docx/1)) or notice of the making of that order to the same persons and in the manner directed by rule 11.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report/ascertaining the views of the child* 15.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order: - under section 12 of the 2018 Act for a care order or a supervision order to be made with respect to a dependent person concerned in the proceedings, or - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, may be made at the hearing. (2) The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order: - to adjourn the proceedings and give a direction under section 12(1) of the 2018 Act and to give such directions under the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as it sees fit as to the care and custody of, and/or make a supervision order in respect of, the dependent person concerned pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, at any time and from time to time during the proceedings, having heard the parties. (3) Where, in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation (or further investigation) of a dependent person’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s direction. (4) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation (or further investigation) by the Agency —'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required when the court appoints an expert to convey a child''s views?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the Form 58.52"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1), - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. (5) Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3822a621-37c7-41bb-9ce4-858ff7413791/Order directing report - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section No. 58.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. [1] Order 59 substituted in full by [S.I. 219 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/219/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Must the notice and copy application form be served on each parent and guardian of the child when applying for an enforcement order under section 18A(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"for an enforcement order under section 18A(1) of the [1964 Act] (inserted by section 60 of the [2015 Act]): the notice and copy application form must be served on each parent and guardian of the child concerned;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 57 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) giving a person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) custody of a child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under Part III of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) for the production of a child: the notice and copy application form must be served on the person having custody of the child; - for an enforcement order under section 18A(1) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 60 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on each parent and guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 60 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)), on the application of a parent or guardian of the child, requiring another guardian or parent to reimburse expenses incurred: the notice and copy application form must be served on each parent and guardian of the child concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application form required before making an parte application to the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the Form 58.1 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications parte* 5.(1) An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall be made parte* in the first instance subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the [Form 58.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1): - (a) an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(1) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(2) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the application is made by the surviving parent, - for an order to appoint a guardian in place of a deceased guardian, under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the child has no guardian, or the applicant is the only guardian;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is a witness required when a qualifying guardian signs a nomination?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The nomination shall be signed and dated by the qualifying guardian concerned in the presence of a witness who is not the nominated person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Nomination* 6.(1) A nomination under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) by a qualifying guardian shall be in the [Form 58.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77911c9d-7de9-4045-a206-b5f9fd657ab8/Nomination - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section (inserted by section 49 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) No. 58.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be signed and dated by the qualifying guardian concerned in the presence of a witness who is not the nominated person. (2) The original or a true copy of the nomination shall be annexed to the application form lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 58.28 or 58.29 used when issuing a summons for an offense related to the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the Form 58.28 or 58.29 Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where complaint is made to a Judge alleging an offence of failure or refusal under section 5 of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986, to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order under section 7 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or section (inserted by the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the [Form 58.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3e57c96e-f893-4c05-8a0b-39b5d0b778d7/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.28.docx/docx/1) or [58.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b802823-d92d-4d19-9693-8aabef61b2ec/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 58.54 required before an application for a declaration of parentage can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 21 of the [2015 Act] for a declaration of parentage shall be preceded by the issue by the applicants of a notice in the [Form 58.54]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for declaration of parentage: DAHR* 9.****[2]****(1) An application to the Court under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) for a declaration of parentage shall be preceded by the issue by the applicants of a notice in the [Form 58.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6a26fa7f-6bac-49a5-9c05-67fbbea7f3ba/Notice of Application for a declaration of parentage, Children and Family Relationships Act 2015, Section 21 No. 58.54.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The child to whom an application for a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) relates shall be named as a respondent to the application. (3) The application shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn by each applicant, and where necessary other affidavit evidence in support of the application, which shall: - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the child to whom the application relates is a child to whom section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, and in particular in a case to which section 20(1)(b)(ii) of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, verify that the person who performed the DAHR procedure outside the State was authorised to do so under the law of the place where the procedure was performed and the law providing for such authorisation; - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) was, at the time referred to in section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the intending parent of the child, and - (iii) in the case of the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), confirm that he or she consents to the making of a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html). (4) True copies of the notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be served on each respondent not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing. (5) The original notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be lodged, together with a statutory declaration as to service, with the Clerk not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to provide a copy of an order or declaration to all parties involved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11. Where the Court makes an order under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) or a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the order related to domestic violence a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 59 - Domestic Violence - Court: District # **Order 59: Domestic Violence**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to provide information to the Clerk to complete the Domestic Violence Summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Safety Order* 4.(1) An application to the Court under section 6 of the 2018 Act for a safety order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a safety order may be in the [Form 59.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8782b974-2642-44b0-aa3d-f4396f780f8b/Safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 No. 59.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an interim barring order be granted without prior service of a summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An interim barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Interim Barring Order* 6.(1) An application to the Court under section 8(1) of the 2018 Act for an interim barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons ( [Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)); - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An interim barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served. (3) An order of the Court granting an interim barring order may be in the [Form 59.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63a952ab-89e5-4b08-8341-7fdf769a49df/Interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.7.docx/docx/1). (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an interim barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an emergency barring order be applied for without serving the summons first?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An emergency barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by sub-rule (1) has not been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Emergency Barring Order* 7.(1) An application to the Court under section 9(3) of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order must, subject to sub-rule (3), be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 59.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f9afe07-f783-46db-ac43-344a44039615/Summons for an emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.17.docx/docx/1). (2) An application to the Court under section 9 of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order: - may be made on the date on which the summons has been listed for hearing (provided the summons has been served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1); or - may, where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1). (3) An emergency barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by sub-rule (1) has not been served. (4) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86fc13e3-6868-4b1a-801f-bce8b0bf749d/Emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act section 9 No. 59.19.docx/docx/1). (5) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an emergency barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a protection order be made without prior notice to the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Protection Order* 8.(1) An application to the Court under section 10(1) of the 2018 Act for a protection order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a safety order and/or a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons; - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An order of the Court granting a protection order may be in the [Form 59.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b60d519-6deb-4554-b964-a8866bdd5138/Protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.9.docx/docx/1). (3) A protection order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 4 or rule 5 has not yet been served. (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where a protection order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to send a certified copy of the order to the applicant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to the applicant for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, the applicant for the safety order or barring order concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11.(1) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a safety order or a protection order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(1) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, the applicant for the safety order or barring order concerned, - to the respondent to the application for the safety order or in respect of a protection order, the respondent to the application for the safety order or barring order concerned, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, for the safety order or barring order, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person for whose benefit the safety order or protection order was made resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a safety order or a protection order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such safety order or protection order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (2) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a barring order or an interim barring order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(2) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the barring order,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the method of sending copies of orders to the Garda Síochána member specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- to the respondent to the application for the barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the barring order was made, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a barring order or an interim barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such barring order or interim barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (3) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an emergency barring order, the Clerk must in accordance with section 19(3) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the emergency barring order, - to the respondent to the application for the emergency barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the emergency barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the emergency barring order was made, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an emergency barring order be sent via email?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the order in question is a variation or discharge of an emergency barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such emergency barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to notify the Gardaí when a protection order ceases to have effect?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Protection Order/Interim Barring Order/Emergency Barring Order ceases to have effect* 12.(1) Where a protection order has been made and: - the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined, or - the protection order is discharged before the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be. (2) Where an interim barring order has been made and the interim barring order has ceased to have effect otherwise than by expiry of the time for which the order is stated on its face to be in force, the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons be served less than seven days before the hearing if the proceedings are urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service* 13.(1) A summons issued under this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) A request for a direction under section 18(4) of the 2018 Act that a relevant order be served personally by a member of the Garda Síochána on a respondent who was not present at the sitting of the Court at which the order was made may be made *viva voce* at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte* at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. The Court may in any case give such a direction of its own motion when the order is made, (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under the 2018 Act in accordance with section 31 of the 2018 Act, direct or deem sufficient service of a document under the 2018 Act by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child on its own initiative?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order ... under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report/ascertaining the views of the child* 15.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order: - under section 12 of the 2018 Act for a care order or a supervision order to be made with respect to a dependent person concerned in the proceedings, or - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, may be made at the hearing. (2) The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order: - to adjourn the proceedings and give a direction under section 12(1) of the 2018 Act and to give such directions under the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as it sees fit as to the care and custody of, and/or make a supervision order in respect of, the dependent person concerned pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, at any time and from time to time during the proceedings, having heard the parties. (3) Where, in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation (or further investigation) of a dependent person’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s direction. (4) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation (or further investigation) by the Agency —'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for appointing an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1), - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. (5) Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3822a621-37c7-41bb-9ce4-858ff7413791/Order directing report - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section No. 58.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. [1] Order 59 substituted in full by [S.I. 219 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/219/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing a court procedure for personal injuries cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons - Court: Circuit # Order 5A: Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons **[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Does this order take precedence over other rules when there is a conflict in personal injury cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in respect of personal injuries actions, prevail"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application of this Order* 2.(1) The provisions of this Order shall apply to personal injuries actions and to all proceedings in personal injuries actions. (2) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, in the event that any conflict shall arise between the provision of any rule of this Order and any other provision of these Rules, the provision of the rule of this Order shall, in respect of personal injuries actions, prevail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form for initiating personal injury actions involving Garda compensation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act shall be instituted by an originating document, which shall be accordance with Form of the Schedule of Forms, and shall be referred to as a Garda compensation personal injuries summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Personal injuries summons and Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 3.(1) A personal injuries action shall be instituted by an originating document which shall be in accordance with [Form 2P](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-summons) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms), and shall be referred to as a personal injuries summons. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) shall be instituted by an originating document, which shall be accordance with [Form 2U](https://www.courts.ie/content/garda-compensation-personal-injuries-summons) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms), and shall be referred to as a Garda compensation personal injuries summons. (3) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, the provisions of these Rules which apply to a Civil Bill shall, with appropriate modifications, apply to a personal injuries summons and to a Garda compensation personal injuries summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Must a plaintiff provide additional information if they were unable to include it in the initial summons?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The plaintiff shall, at the time the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide such of the information required as was not included in the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Failure to serve letter of claim* 4.(1) Where a plaintiff who has not served the notice required by section 8(1) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) within the time prescribed for service of such a notice alleges that there was a reasonable cause for such failure, the personal injuries summons shall include particulars of the cause of the said failure. (2) Where a plaintiff alleges that he was unable, at the time at which a personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons was issued, to include in the summons any of the information required by the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or these Rules to be specified there, he shall include in the personal injuries summons or, as the case may be, the Garda compensation personal injuries summons, a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the summons. The plaintiff shall, at the time the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide such of the information required as was not included in the summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific act mentioned that pleadings must conform to in personal injury actions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In every personal injuries action pleadings shall conform to the requirements of section 13 of the [2004 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Pleadings* 5. In every personal injuries action pleadings shall conform to the requirements of section 13 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time frame for delivering a defence after a defendant enters an appearance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The defence shall be delivered to the plaintiff or his Solicitor within 6 weeks of the entry by the defendant of an Appearance."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appearance, defence and counterclaim* 6.(1) A defence shall be delivered by each defendant who has entered an Appearance. The defence shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(i)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-defence) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) (with the necessary adaptations in the case of a defence to a Garda compensation personal injuries summons). Where any defendant makes a counterclaim, such counterclaim shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(ii)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-counterclaim) of the Schedule of Forms and shall be appended to the defence. (2) The defence shall be delivered to the plaintiff or his Solicitor within 6 weeks of the entry by the defendant of an Appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit of verification required to be delivered to the opposing party when it is appended to a pleading or document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the affidavit is appended to the pleading or other document, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading or other document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Affidavit of verification* 7.(1) An affidavit of verification of a pleading or of further information requiring under section 14(1), 14(2) or 14(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be verified on oath shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) annexed hereto. Where the affidavit is not made separately to the pleading or other document concerned, it shall be appended to such pleading or other document. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading or other document is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is appended to the pleading or other document, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading or other document. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 14 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for lodgement of the affidavit in court. (3) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading or other document, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading or other document in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy. (4) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 14(4) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) by being filed in the Office.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a party to write to the opposing party before making certain applications?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the moving party shall have first written to the relevant opposing party requesting that such party agree to the moving party’s request"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications by motion on notice* 8.(1) The following applications in a personal injuries action shall, subject to the following rules of this Order, be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded, where necessary, upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - An application by a defendant under section 10(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for a stay or dismissal of the action by reason of a plaintiff’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 10 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - An application under section 11(3) or section 12(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for relief by reason of the opposing party’s failure to provide further information requested under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), or for an order for the delivery by the opposing party of further and better particulars of any pleading delivered by such party; - (iii) An application by a party wishing to have evidence in the action given by affidavit, under section 19 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); An application referred to in paragraphs or of this sub-rule shall not be issued unless: - (a) the moving party shall have first written to the relevant opposing party requesting that such party agree to the moving party’s request; - a period of 28 days for compliance with the moving party’s request has been allowed; and - the party requested has failed, refused or neglected to comply with, such request. (2) No application for judgment or for other relief in default of pleading shall be granted in a personal injuries action unless the moving party has satisfied the Court that he has verified his previous pleadings in that action on oath in accordance with this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is a mediation conference report required to verify whether the conference took place?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"whether the mediation conference was or was not held"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mediation* 9.(1) A request by a party for a direction of the Court under section 15 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) that a mediation conference be held shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where the Court directs that a mediation conference be held, it may adjourn the proceedings for such time as it considers appropriate to enable the mediation conference to be held. (3) Where the Court directs that a mediation conference be held, it may extend the time for compliance by the parties or any of them with any provision of these Rules or any order of the court in the proceedings. (4) The report under section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) of the person appointed under section 15(4) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be the chairperson of a mediation conference shall be by way of affidavit which, in addition to any matters required by section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be contained in such report, shall verify: - (a) his or her appointment as mediator; - whether the mediation conference was or was not held; - if not held, the reasons why the mediation conference did not take place; - if held, - the time and place at which the mediation conference was held; - the parties in attendance; - (iii) whether or not a settlement has been reached in the action and - the terms of any settlement signed by the parties. (5) The Court may give a direction under section 15 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) of its own motion on any occasion on which the personal injuries action is before the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a non-Judge presiding over a pre-trial hearing give directions that can be appealed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any direction given or order made at a pre-trial hearing by a person, other than a Judge, presiding over such hearing, may be appealed to the Court by a party affected."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Pre-trial hearings under section 18 of the 2004 Act* 11.(1) A person presiding over a pre-trial hearing directed by the Court under section 18 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as may be necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the action are in dispute. (2) Any direction given or order made at a pre-trial hearing by a person, other than a Judge, presiding over such hearing, may be appealed to the Court by a party affected. [1] Order 5A inserted by 526 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/526/made/en/print), effective 20 September 2005, and substituted in its entirely by 230 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/230/made/en/print#:~:text 1.,Court Rules 2001 to 2022.), effective 31 May 2024. Superseded amendments: Order 5A rule 4 substituted by 215 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/215/made/en/print), effective 19 June 2019. Order 5A rule 9(5) inserted by 11 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/11/made/en/), effective 22 January 2018.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is a ''personal injuries action'' defined to include proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a personal injuries action has the same meaning as section 2 of the 2004 Act, but includes proceedings referred to in section 23 of the 2022 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires - the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); the “**2022 Act**” means the [Garda Síochána (Compensation) Act 2022](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**dependant**” includes: - a dependant within the meaning of section 47 of the [Civil Liability Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/41/enacted/en/html), and - in the case of a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), a claimant who had been an applicant to whom section or 8(4) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) refers, who brings proceedings in accordance with section 23(1) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**Garda compensation personal injuries summons**” means a summons by which a personal injuries action involving proceedings in the Court under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**personal injuries action**” has the same meaning as section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), but includes proceedings referred to in section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) in accordance with section 24 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), and “**action**” shall be interpreted accordingly; “**personal injury**” includes any disease and any impairment of a person’s physical or mental condition; “**personal injuries summons**” means an initiating document by which a personal injuries action is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**plaintiff**” includes a deceased person, where a personal injuries action is instituted for the benefit of dependants of a deceased person; “**pleading**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); “**Personal Public Service Number**” means the Personal Public Service Number allocated and issued to a person under section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26/enacted/en/index.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific deadline for defendants to serve their replying affidavit to the plaintiff''s claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in Form 5 in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) A Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall be served, together with a copy of the affidavit mentioned in rule 5, on each defendant not later than 21 days before the return date mentioned in rule 4. 4. Every Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall, upon being issued, be assigned a return date before the County Registrar, which date shall be entered in the Civil Bill. (1) There shall be served with the Civil Bill a copy of an affidavit which shall conform to the requirements of [Form 54](/content/affidavit-support-civil-bill-possession-order-authorising-sale-under-section-1003-land-and) in the Schedule of Forms (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) sworn by or on behalf of the plaintiff, verifying and supporting the claim indorsed on the Civil Bill. (2) Where the agreement for a mortgage on foot of which proceedings to which this Order relates have been commenced is or was at the material time or times one to which a code drawn up by the Central Bank of Ireland in accordance with section 117 of the [Central Bank Act 1989](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/16/enacted/en/html) applies, the affidavit shall identify the code concerned. (3) A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in [Form 5](/content/entry-appearance) in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date. 6. (1) No party shall have the right in proceedings to which this Order applies to adduce any evidence otherwise than by affidavit, except - - (a) by leave of the Judge, - where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or - where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'Can a County Registrar extend the time for filing affidavits?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"For the purposes of this rule, or for the purpose of any hearing before himself, the County Registrar may extend the time for filing affidavits"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) Any party desiring to cross-examine a deponent who has sworn an affidavit filed on behalf of the opposite party may serve upon the party by whom such affidavit has been filed a notice in writing requiring the production of the deponent for cross-examination, and unless such deponent is produced accordingly his affidavit shall not be used as evidence unless by the special leave of the Court. (1) On the return date of the Civil Bill (or on any adjournment from such date), the County Registrar may, in addition to any other order which the County Registrar has power to make: - (a) order service of the Civil Bill on any other person; - make an order enlarging the time for entry of an appearance; - give directions and fix time limits for the filing and delivery of any further affidavits by any party or parties; - give any other directions for the preparation of the proceedings for trial; - where an appearance has not been entered or an affidavit in accordance with rule 5(2) setting out a defence has not been filed and delivered, make an order for possession in accordance with paragraph (xxxiii) or (xxxiv) of the Second Schedule to the [Courts and Courts Officers Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/31/enacted/en/html); - where the parties are sui juris, make an order to receive a consent and make the same a rule of court. (2) Where a replying affidavit has been filed in accordance with rule 5(2) which discloses a prima facie defence, the County Registrar shall transfer the Civil Bill, when in order for hearing, to the Judge’s list on the first opportunity. (3) For the purposes of this rule, or for the purpose of any hearing before himself, the County Registrar may extend the time for filing affidavits and give such directions and adjourn the case before himself as he thinks fit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'Can the judge provide specific instructions regarding the enforcement of a judgment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Judge may give any special directions touching the carriage or execution of any judgment or order, or the service thereof upon persons not parties, as he thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the defendant is seeking time to remedy any other breach of obligation arising under the mortgage, set out detailed particulars of the defendant’s proposal to effect such remedy. 9. On the hearing of any Civil Bill to which this Order applies, the Judge may give judgment for the relief to which the plaintiff appears to be entitled. 10. (1) The Judge may give any special directions touching the carriage or execution of any judgment or order, or the service thereof upon persons not parties, as he thinks just. (2) The Judge or the County Registrar may make such order as to costs as he considers just, including an order measuring any costs awarded [1] Order inserted by 264 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/264/made/en/print), effective 8 July 2009. [2] Title amended by 171 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/171/made/en/print), effective 19 May 2016. [3] Order rule 1 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [4] Order rule 3 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [5] Order rule 5 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [6] Order rule 5(2) substituted by 358 of 2012](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2012/si/358/made/en/print), effective 15 October 2012. [7] Order 5 rule 7(2) and 7(4) substituted by 358 of 2012](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2012/si/358/made/en/print), effective 15 October 2012. [8] Order rule 8(3) inserted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text for Order of the Defamation Act 2009 a Circuit Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Circuit # **Order Defamation Act 2009******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Defamation Act 2009 referenced in the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Act” means the [Defamation Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1. In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Defamation Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) and any reference in this Order to a section shall, unless the context otherwise requires, be deemed to be a reference to a section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html); “**defamation action**” has the same meaning as in section 2.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit of verification required to be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is addressed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8 3. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the Schedule of Forms, with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate to the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon that pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of that pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court, as required by section 8(5), by filing the same in the Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a ruling under section 14 required to be made on notice to the opposing party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application for a ruling under section 14;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 4. (1) An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (3) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an order directing the party who made the offer to take certain measures made by motion on notice to the opposing party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: ... shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted 5. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include directions as to the terms upon which any pleadings may be amended) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1). 6. Where an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) to bring or to proceed with a defamation action against another person in respect of the statement to which the offer to make amends applies shall: - where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court direct that an application be determined by way of a plenary hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, at such hearing: ... direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of paragraph of section 23(1) and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the other person referred to in paragraph of section 23(1) shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 5 and 6 shall: - identify with sufficient precision, or exhibit a copy or transcript of, the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. In addition to any other order which may be made on the hearing of an originating notice of motion under sub-rule (3) of rule 4 or paragraph of rule 6, the Court may, at such hearing: - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application; - direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defendant notify their intention to provide certain evidence through their defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act] by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the applicant to provide evidence of their request for an apology, correction, or retraction from the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"contain an averment that the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish an apology, correction or retraction (as the case may be) in relation to the alleged defamatory statement and specify when and the manner in which the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish such apology, correction or retraction in relation to the alleged defamatory statement (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such request and proof of delivery of same)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications for declaratory orders under section 28 10. (1) A motion referred to in section 28(5) shall be an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 28 and in which the person who claims to be the subject of a statement that he or she alleges is defamatory shall be named as applicant and the person against whom relief is sought shall be named as respondent. (2) A grounding affidavit referred to in section 28(5) shall: - (a) set out the circumstances in which it is claimed that the alleged defamatory statement was made, including the time and method of publication; - set out the grounds on which it is claimed that the statement is defamatory of the applicant; - contain an averment that the respondent has no defence to the application; - contain an averment that the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish an apology, correction or retraction (as the case may be) in relation to the alleged defamatory statement and specify when and the manner in which the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish such apology, correction or retraction in relation to the alleged defamatory statement (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such request and proof of delivery of same), and - produce evidence of the response (if any) by the respondent to the request (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such response).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the defendant required to provide advance notice to the plaintiff about the evidence they intend to present for mitigation of damages?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation to be given 11. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by 486 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/486/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff join multiple defendants even if they are not all interested in every cause of action?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **PARTIES** 1. All persons may be joined in one action as plaintiffs in whom any right to relief in respect of or arising out of the same transactions is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if such persons brought separate actions, any common question of law or fact would arise; provided that if, upon a motion on notice by any defendant, it shall appear that such joinder may embarrass or delay the trial, the Judge may order separate trials, or make such other order as may be right, and provided also that no person shall be made a plaintiff without his consent. 2. All persons may be joined as defendants against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. When the plaintiff is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more defendants, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the defendants is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him; but the Judge may make such order as may appear just, to prevent any defendant from being embarrassed, or put to expense, by being required to attend any proceedings in which he has no interest. 3. The plaintiff may, at his option, join as defendants to the same action all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can an infant sue by their next friend?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An infant may sue by his next friend, and in such case there shall be lodged with the Civil Bill a written authority authorising the commencement and prosecution of the suit on behalf of the infant and the use of the name of such person as next friend, signed by such person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. [[1]](#_ftn1) No action, cause or matter shall be defeated by reason of the misjoinder or non-joinder of parties, and the Judge may in every action, cause or matter deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before him. The Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, either upon or without the application of any party, and on such terms as may appear to him to be just, order that the name of any party, whether plaintiff or defendant, who has been improperly joined, be struck out, and that the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Judge to adjudicate upon and settle all the questions involved in the cause or matter, be added as a plaintiff or a defendant. No person shall be added as a plaintiff suing without a next friend, or as the next friend of a plaintiff under any disability, without his consent in writing thereto. Every person whose name is so added as defendant shall be served with a Civil Bill in such manner as may be prescribed by any Order of the Court, and the action, cause or matter, as against such party, shall be deemed to have begun only on the making of the Order adding such party. 5. An infant may sue by his next friend, and in such case there shall be lodged with the Civil Bill a written authority authorising the commencement and prosecution of the suit on behalf of the infant and the use of the name of such person as next friend, signed by such person. 6. An infant may defend by his guardian litem* appointed for that purpose in accordance with [Order 19]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-19-Circuit-Side-bar-applications) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge secure or invest money for an infant''s benefit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may direct that any money or other personal property to which such infant may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of such infant in such manner as the Judge shall consider advisable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. When proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against an infant, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem* to act for or on behalf of such infant, and may change any next friend or guardian litem*, and appoint another in his place, and may also direct that any money or other personal property to which such infant may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of such infant in such manner as the Judge shall consider advisable. 8. [[2]](#2) (1) In this rule, the “**2015 Act**” means the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person a decision-making representation order which authorises a decision-making representative appointed in respect of the person to institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her decision-making representative, and service on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power of attorney in respect of which a notification of lack of capacity has been accepted, which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney, and service on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/12/enacted/en/html), which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney under the Act of 1996, and service on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a ward of court initiate legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where there is in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer a registered co-decision-making agreement which provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered in the proceedings shall be signed by, or shall include a certificate that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by, the appointer and co-decision-maker. (6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee 9. Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and shall be considered as representing such persons; but the Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of such persons to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties. This rule shall apply to trustees, executors, and administrators sued in proceedings to enforce a security by sale or otherwise. 10. Save in actions founded on tort, when there are numerous persons having the same interest in one action or matter, one or more of such persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Judge to defend, in such action or matter, on behalf of or for the benefit of all persons so interested.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person who was not originally served with the Civil Bill appear and defend the case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any person not named in or served with the Civil Bill may by leave of the Judge appear and defend at the hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '11. Where proceedings are taken for the recovery of land, any tenant, under-tenant, or other person in actual possession of the property sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, may be named as defendant and the Civil Bill shall be directed to such tenant, under-tenant, or other person, with the addition of the words ‘‘and all persons concerned’’. 12. Where proceedings are taken as mentioned in the last preceding rule, any person not named in or served with the Civil Bill may by leave of the Judge appear and defend at the hearing, and the Judge may thereafter deal with such person, both as to costs and otherwise, as if he had originally been served with the Civil Bill as defendant. 13. When any person residing outside the Circuit, but inside the State, is a necessary and proper party to a proceeding properly instituted in the Court against some person within the Circuit, such first mentioned person may be served with the Civil Bill or other document without special leave. 14. Subject to the requirements of Rule 9 of Section 66 of the [Chancery (Ireland) Act, 1867](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1867/act/44/enacted/en/print.html), wherever, in any action for the administration of the estate of a deceased person, or for the execution of the trusts of any deed or instrument, or for the partition or sale of any hereditaments, a judgment or order has been pronounced affecting the rights or interests of persons not parties to the action, the Court may direct that any persons interested in the estate, or under the trusts, or in the hereditaments, shall be served with notice of the judgment or order; and after such notice such persons shall be bound by the proceedings, in the same manner as if they had originally been made parties, and shall be at liberty to attend the proceedings under the judgment or order. Any person so served may within one month after such service apply to the Court to discharge, vary or add to the said judgment or order. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 6 rule 4 substituted by 312 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/312/made/en/print), effective 20 July 2007. [2] Order 6 rule 8 substituted by 201 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/201/made/en/pdf) effective 27 April 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 6 - Right of Audience', 'Court Rules', 'Is the right of audience being discussed in a district court context?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Right of Audience - Court: District # Order 6: Right of Audience [1] ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 6 - Right of Audience', 'Court Rules', 'Can a brother of a party appear on their behalf in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Save where otherwise provided by statute or by rules of court, the father, mother, son, daughter, husband, wife, brother or sister of any party may appear on behalf of that party"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Persons entitled to appear and address the court* 1. The following persons shall be entitled to appear and address the Court and conduct proceedings— - (a) any party to the proceedings; or - a solicitor for such party; or - a counsel instructed by the solicitor for such party; or - where the proceedings are in relation to the taxes and duties under the care and management of the Revenue Commissioners, or in relation to any fine, penalty or forfeiture incurred in connection therewith or otherwise incurred under the Customs Acts, a duly authorised officer of the Revenue Commissioners or the Revenue solicitor; or - in proceedings at the suit of the Director of Public Prosecutions in respect of an offence, the said Director or any member of the Garda Síochána or other person appearing on behalf of or prosecuting in the name of the Director. 2. Save where otherwise provided by statute or by rules of court, the father, mother, son, daughter, husband, wife, brother or sister of any party may appear on behalf of that party provided that any such person has the leave of the Court to appear and be heard and that the Court is satisfied that the party is, from infirmity or other unavoidable cause, unable to appear. [1] Order 6 inserted by[S.I. No. 93/1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) - District Court Rules, 1997'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff issue multiple concurrent summonses at different times within a year?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summonses"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses - Court: Superior 1. The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summons or summonses, each concurrent summons to bear the same date of issue as the original summons, and to be marked with a seal bearing the word “**concurrent**” and the date of issue of the concurrent summons; and such seal shall be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer; provided always, that such concurrent summons or summonses shall only be in force for the period during which the original summons in such proceedings shall be in force. 2. A summons for service within the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction; and a summons for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service within the jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings be heard at any sitting of the Court within the same district if the Clerk certifies them as urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2. (1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home, as defined in section 2 of the Act, is situate. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the court district within which such court area is situate, certifies on a notice of application or a summons that the proceedings are urgent, the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the hearing conducted in private according to the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under or referred to in the Act in which each spouse is a party (whether by joinder or otherwise) shall be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* 3. Proceedings under or referred to in the Act in which each spouse is a party (whether by joinder or otherwise) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.1 Schedule required before a spouse can apply under section 9(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a spouse under section 9(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.1 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(1).* 4. An application by a spouse under section 9(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.4 Schedule required before a spouse can apply to remove household items under section 9(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(2).* 5. An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.5 Schedule used for summonses issued under section 9(4) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.5 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 9(4).* 6. Where complaint is made by a spouse to a Judge under section 9(4) of the Act that the other spouse has contravened the provisions of section 9(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.6 Schedule required before a spouse can apply under section 9(5)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a spouse under section 9(5) of the Act for an order that the respondent spouse provide household chattels for the applicant spouse or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.6 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(5).* 7. An application by a spouse under section 9(5) of the Act for an order that the respondent spouse provide household chattels for the applicant spouse or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.8 Schedule used when a summons is issued under section 15 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 15.* 8. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 15 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Must the original notice or summons be lodged with the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents.* 9. (1) A notice or summons required by this Order to be served may be served in accordance with the provisions of [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) of these Rules and every such notice shall be served at least fourteen days or, in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2) hereof, at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Third Party Procedure Order applicable to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) (Third Party Procedure) of these Rules shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Joinder of parties.* 10. The provisions of [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) (Third Party Procedure) of these Rules shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a person who initiated proceedings under section 3(1) to enter relevant particulars as a lis pendens?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lis Pendens.* (3) A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court give consent on behalf of a spouse who is incapable of giving their own consent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the spouse whose consent is required under subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act is incapable of consenting by reason of unsoundness of mind or other mental disability or has not after reasonable inquiries been found, application may be made to the Court in the [Form 60.14, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Consent by the Court.* 13.[3] (1) Where the spouse whose consent is required under subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act is incapable of consenting by reason of unsoundness of mind or other mental disability or has not after reasonable inquiries been found, application may be made to the Court in the [Form 60.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1310b421-b173-42aa-8a7a-6ee0eed68d8a/Application for an order giving consent on behalf of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.14.docx/docx/1), under subsection (4) of section 4 of that Act for the Court to give the consent on behalf of that spouse. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.15, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a7da286-3928-4f2d-a647-bba86336145b/Order consenting to conveyance of family home No. 60.15.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when applying to the court for protection of the family home?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home in the interest of the applicant spouse of a dependent child shall be in the [Form 60.16, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Protection of Family Home.* 14.[4] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home in the interest of the applicant spouse of a dependent child shall be in the [Form 60.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6342e31-1520-448a-9ee7-509e76cd2abf/Order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(1) No. 60.17.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when applying to the court for compensation related to loss of the family home?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act to compensate the applicant spouse and any dependent child of the family for loss occasioned by the conduct of the other spouse Home. shall be in the [Form 60.18, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Conduct leading to loss of Family Home.* 15.[5] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act to compensate the applicant spouse and any dependent to loss of Family child of the family for loss occasioned by the conduct of the other spouse Home. shall be in the [Form 60.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3ae2cb1e-21c5-4e31-92a0-2a6a60b55277/Application for an order for compensation for loss relating to the family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(2) No. 60.18.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 60 rule 11 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [2] Order 60 rule 12 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [3] Order 60 rule 13 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [4] Order 60 rule 14 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [5] Order 60 rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to determining parentage through blood tests?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required to be served on all parties before an application for a direction for the use of blood tests can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where in any civil proceedings before the Court the parentage of any person is in question, an application under section 38 (1) of the Act by a party to the proceedings for a direction for the use of blood tests shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for a direction for the use of blood tests* 2. (1) Where in any civil proceedings before the Court the parentage of any person is in question, an application under section 38 (1) of the Act by a party to the proceedings for a direction for the use of blood tests shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 61.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83d7a649-d1b7-4e05-bda2-03e28cff563c/Notice of application for direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 section 38(1) No. 61.1.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other party or parties to the proceedings and upon each person in respect of whom the direction is sought or, where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her and shall be served at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (3) Where the Court of its own motion proposes to give a direction for the use of blood tests or where application for such a direction is made in the course of hearing the proceedings, and if each of the parties to the proceedings and each person in respect of whom the direction is proposed or sought (or his or her legal or other representative, as the case may be) is then present in court, the Court may dispense with the requirement to serve notice of application. (4) The direction of the Court shall be in the [Form 61.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b10be890-211b-4f39-a987-0f83ec683d17/Direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act, 1987 section 38 (1) No. 61.2.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person in respect of whom it was given or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order for revoking or varying a direction required to be served on each person directly affected by that order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order revoking or varying a direction* 3. Where under section 38 (3) of the Act the Court revokes or varies a direction previously given under section 38 (1) of the Act, the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d12db6d0-b7b7-40cc-8859-ef8fba9b0317/Order revoking - varying a direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.3.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the original notice and proof of service to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of intention to call witness* 4. (1) A notice under section 40 (5) of the Act by a party to civil proceedings of that party''s intention to call a person as a witness shall be in the [Form 61.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ed129f6-37c8-46f4-926a-7adee2623b90/Notice of intention to call witness - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.4.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other parties to the proceedings or upon such of them as the Court may direct, at least fourteen days before the sitting of the Court at which it is intended to call as a witness the person named in the notice. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk responsible for sending the direction form to the sampler?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to send direction form to sampler* 5. Where the Court gives a direction under section 38 (1) of the Act, the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004 - Court: District # Order 61A: Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004**[1][2]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is a recorder someone who prepares and publishes reports of proceedings according to the 2004 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a “**recorder**” means a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) intending to attend or attending any proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of such proceedings in accordance with section 40(3) of the 2004 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this rule: the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); a “**recorder**” means a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) intending to attend or attending any proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of such proceedings in accordance with section 40(3) of the 2004 Act; “**relevant enactment**” has the same meaning as in section 39 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is a recorder required to identify themselves before starting the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Recorders* 2.[3] (1) A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court and apply for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (2) On any such application, the Court - (a) if satisfied that the applicant is a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and that the recorder intends to attend the proceedings for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, and - having heard any submission made by or on behalf of any party to the proceedings, may allow the recorder to attend the proceedings (or any part of the proceedings) subject to such directions as the Court may give in that regard. (3) The Court may, of its own motion or on the application of any party or person, vary or modify any such directions given under section 40(3) of the Act during the course of the proceedings. (4) Where the Court refuses to allow a recorder who has made an application under sub-rule (1) to attend the relevant proceedings, the Court must give its reasons for such refusal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court verify if someone is a bona fide representative of the press?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Bona fide representatives of the press* 3. (1) Prior to, at the commencement of, or during the course of the hearing of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, the Court may - (a) make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press within the meaning of section 40(3A) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - hear any application by or on behalf of a party or person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub- section refers) for an order under 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or may for the purposes of considering the making of any such order of its own motion, hear submissions from any such party or person. (2) The Court may, at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings, of its own motion or on the application of a person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub-section refers), having heard the parties and any other person it considers necessary, vary or modify any order made in accordance with sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is the approval of an accompanying person in parte applications solely at the discretion of the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of Form No. 61A.1 duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Accompanying persons* 4.[4] (1) Where a party (in this rule referred to as the “applicant”) wishes to be accompanied in court in any proceedings referred to in section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), save for proceedings to which section 26 of the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6/enacted/en/html) applies, by another person (in this rule referred to as “the accompanying person”), the applicant must, unless the Court otherwise directs, complete a notice of application in the [Form 61A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) Where the other party or parties agree to the accompanying person, the applicant must lodge [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed, with the Clerk prior to the commencement of the hearing in the proceedings, and must apply to the Court at that hearing to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (3) Except in parte applications, where the other party or parties have not agreed to the accompanying person, the applicant must, by application to the Court in the [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1), on notice to the other party or parties, returnable not later than seven days prior to the date fixed for the hearing in such proceedings, apply to the Court to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (4) In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a certificate of qualification be made in multiple court areas if the applicant plans to conduct business there?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for certificate of qualification* 2. (1) An application for a certificate of qualification pursuant to Part III of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court in the court area in which the applicant proposes to carry on business or, in case the applicant proposes to carry on business in more than one court area, in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served on the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a newspaper before their hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published, at least twenty-eight days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published, at least twenty-eight days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for lodging documents with the Clerk in advance of the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of the application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and newspaper* (4) A copy of the notice of the application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the applicant required to provide certificates during the hearing of the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"On the hearing of the application the applicant shall furnish to the Court the certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to furnish required certificates* (5) On the hearing of the application the applicant shall furnish to the Court the certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act (as inserted by section 12 of the [Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1967](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1967/act/9/enacted/en/print.html)) as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate issued when the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 63.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ed8d17e-7da9-4d5a-9042-f4577cde3d5b/Certificate of qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1947 No. 63.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of objection required to be served on the applicant under the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. A notice of objection pursuant to section 11 (5) of the Act to the grant of a certificate of qualification shall be in accordance with [Form 63.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7d63184-090a-4651-990b-62fde646d8a5/Notice Of Objection To The Grant Of A Certificate Of Qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act 1947 No. 63.2.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served upon the applicant and a copy, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Betting Act of 1931 referred to in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In this Order \"the Act\" means the [Betting Act, 1931 (No. 27 of 1931)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931 - Court: District 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Betting Act, 1931 (No. 27 of 1931)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931', 'Court Rules', 'Is the appeal process for a refused certificate outlined in the Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The procedure to be followed in an appeal from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act is the procedure set out in the [Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931 (Statutory Rules and Orders, 1931 No. 81)]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Procedure for appeal against refusal of Superintendent to grant certificate* 2. The procedure to be followed in an appeal from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act is the procedure set out in the [Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931 (Statutory Rules and Orders, 1931 No. 81)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text related to fisheries?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 65 - Fisheries - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to serve a notice on Inland Fisheries Ireland before making an application for a certificate of fitness?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for cert. of fitness* 2. (1) An application pursuant to section 158 (as amended by section 14 of [the Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html) and the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 65.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08e99c10-7260-410a-bac2-8f1c8548b8e5/Notice of application for a certificate of fitness - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 section 158 No. 65.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3)[1] The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 324 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) A certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence granted under the said section 158 shall be in the [Form 65.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2776117-18da-4d59-809b-aa6d1b39086c/Certificate of fitness to hold a salmon dealer''s licence - eel dealer''s licence - molluscan shellfish dealer''s licence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be completed before making an application for the detention of a boat and its passengers?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before making such application the applicant shall complete and lodge with the Clerk a notice in the Form 65.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for detention of boat and persons (for 48 hours)* 3. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court pursuant to section 233A (as amended by section 12 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) and as substituted by section 11 of [the Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/23/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for an Order authorising the continued detention of a boat and the persons on board the boat (for a period of 48 hours) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which is situated the port in which the boat and persons concerned are detained. (2) Before making such application the applicant shall complete and lodge with the Clerk a notice in the [Form 65.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ded52b27-89d4-4f64-a4f5-613bd5189680/Notice of application for an order authorising the continued detention of a boat and persons under section 233A as amended (for 48 hours) No. 65.3.docx/docx/1), and shall deliver a copy thereof to each of the persons in respect of whom the order is sought. (3) Where the Court grants the application the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 65.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08ba4aac-0bda-4e2e-a035-1d99f461aecf/Order for detention under section 233a of the act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the detention of a boat required until the conclusion of all related legal proceedings including appeals?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"pending, ... the determination of the appeal or any other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (incl. appeals and trials)* 8. An order of the Court pursuant to section 235 (1) - as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the further detention of a boat pending, - in the case of an appeal from, or any other proceedings in relation to, an order convicting a person of an offence under Chapter or III of Part XIII of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) or an order dismissing proceedings in relation to such an offence, the determination of the appeal or any other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), in a case where a person is sent forward for trial or for sentence charged with an offence under the said Chapter or III, the determination of the case in the court to which that person was sent forward and, in the event of an appeal or other proceedings arising therefrom, the determination of the appeal or the other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), shall be in the [Form 65.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/21862828-3330-408b-aaa2-fc23b2a85e4b/Order for further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (including appeals) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.9.docx/docx/1) or [65.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f25ec15-eef3-449b-a0ab-681f0f750b9b/Order for further detention of boat on sending forward - for trial - for sentence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for an order of detention under section 301(2A)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"requiring the detention of a boat and person or persons or of the boat only until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the Form 65,12, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat/boat and persons pending adjudication of proceedings* 10. An order of the Court pursuant to section 301 (2A) — as inserted by section 53 of [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the detention of a boat and person or persons or of the boat only until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65,12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/47d29fc7-0609-4de2-aeb3-7bacdc26474d/Order for detention under section 301 (2A) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.12.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting approval for something?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a warrant under section 297 be made at any sitting of the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 297 — as amended by section 71 of [the Act of 1980] — of [the Principal Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *— venue* 11. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 297 — as amended by section 71 of [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the garden, dwellinghouse or curtilage thereof in respect of which the issue of the warrant is sought is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is an authorized person required to make the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 65.13, Schedule of an authorised person within the meaning of section 292"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *— by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 65.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0549f5af-f10b-4cdd-b171-c0974f25291b/Information for warrant (under section 297) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.13.docx/docx/1), of an authorised person within the meaning of section 292 — as substituted in the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the given text about a specific court case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries - Court: District # Order 66: Gaming and lotteries**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of Notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/481b1d1f-ea20-4506-ba4b-69e615e0da41/Application for a certificate - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 14 days before such date of hearing in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 14 days before such date of hearing in a newspaper circulating in the locality. (5) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act 1981](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/section/24/enacted/en/html) shall apply to such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the original notice of application to be submitted along with other documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (6) The original of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a lottery licence be submitted at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the grant of a licence for the promotion of a lottery pursuant to section 28 of the [1956 Act] (as substituted by section 12 of the [2019 Act]) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries to which the application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for Lottery Licence* 3.(1) An application for the grant of a licence for the promotion of a lottery pursuant to section 28 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 12 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries to which the application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence to be issued in a specific format if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 66.4]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 66.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4d2ac493-93d6-417b-85ef-839e588bbb3d/Licence for promotion of a lottery - 28 Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 No. 66.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be brought against the refusal to grant a gaming permit at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 9A(18) of the [1956 Act] (as inserted by section 4 of the [2019 Act]) against the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a gaming permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue- Appeal against refusal to grant gaming permit* 4.(1) An appeal pursuant to section 9A(18) of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 4 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a gaming permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the lottery is to be held?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section of the [1956 Act] (as inserted by section 11 of the [2019 Act]) from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a lottery permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the lottery is to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue- Appeal against refusal to grant lottery permit* (2) An appeal pursuant to section of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 11 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a lottery permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the lottery is to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before filing an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice of appeal* (3) An appeal under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.5,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b9005911-1bca-4513-b74a-5513e8726cc0/Notice of appeal against refusal of superintendent to grant a permit - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 27 No. 66.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Superintendent to lodge documents with the Clerk before the court sitting?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (4) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána concerned at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court at which the appeal is to be heard. When service has been effected the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of the said sitting. (5) The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting permission to conduct a search?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Application for search warrant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for search warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a search warrant be made at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the issue of a search warrant under section 39 of the [1956 Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue* 5.(1) An application for the issue of a search warrant under section 39 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a search warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fed46a08-bd3a-4bda-8545-696d98d68c27/Information for search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the search warrant required to be in a specific form if granted by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 66.8]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) Where the Court grants the application, a search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 66.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f036d233-d395-4335-9815-6bfdcc023c49/Search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for revoking or suspending a licence or permit be made orally after criminal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application for an order under section 46 of the [1956 Act] (as substituted by section 19 of the [2019 Act]) that a lottery licence, lottery permit, gaming licence or gaming permit be revoked or suspended may be made orally to the Court when the Court has determined the criminal proceedings concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for an order that a licence or permit be revoked or suspended* 6.(1) Where possible, an application for an order under section 46 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 19 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) that a lottery licence, lottery permit, gaming licence or gaming permit be revoked or suspended may be made orally to the Court when the Court has determined the criminal proceedings concerned, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that the person to whom the application relates would not thereby be prejudiced. (2) In any other case, such an application shall be in the [Form 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, to which shall be attached a copy of the order of conviction, and shall be served by personal service or by prepaid registered post on the respondent. (3) If served personally, the notice shall be served at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable; if served by prepaid registered post, the notice must be served at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. [1] Order 66 substituted by [S.I. 63 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/63/made/en/print) effective 25 February 2021'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific deadline for defendants to file a replying affidavit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in Form 5 in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) A Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall be served, together with a copy of the affidavit mentioned in rule 5, on each defendant not later than 21 days before the return date mentioned in rule 4. 4. Every Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall, upon being issued, be assigned a return date before the County Registrar, which date shall be entered in the Civil Bill. (1) There shall be served with the Civil Bill a copy of an affidavit which shall conform to the requirements of [Form 54](/content/affidavit-support-civil-bill-possession-order-authorising-sale-under-section-1003-land-and) in the Schedule of Forms (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) sworn by or on behalf of the plaintiff, verifying and supporting the claim indorsed on the Civil Bill. (2) Where the agreement for a mortgage on foot of which proceedings to which this Order relates have been commenced is or was at the material time or times one to which a code drawn up by the Central Bank of Ireland in accordance with section 117 of the [Central Bank Act 1989](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/16/enacted/en/html) applies, the affidavit shall identify the code concerned. (3) A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in [Form 5](/content/entry-appearance) in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date. 6. (1) No party shall have the right in proceedings to which this Order applies to adduce any evidence otherwise than by affidavit, except - - (a) by leave of the Judge, - where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or - where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified as Circuit in Order of the Defamation Act 2009?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Circuit # **Order Defamation Act 2009******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit of verification required to be delivered to the opposing party when it is attached to a pleading?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of that pleading."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8 3. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the Schedule of Forms, with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate to the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon that pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of that pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court, as required by section 8(5), by filing the same in the Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for leave under section 11(2) be brought without prior notice to the opposing party?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 4. (1) An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (3) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court make additional orders beyond those specified in rules 5 and 6?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, at such hearing: ... In addition to any other order which may be made on the hearing of an originating notice of motion under sub-rule (3) of rule 4 or paragraph of rule 6, the Court may, at such hearing:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of paragraph of section 23(1) and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the other person referred to in paragraph of section 23(1) shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 5 and 6 shall: - identify with sufficient precision, or exhibit a copy or transcript of, the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. In addition to any other order which may be made on the hearing of an originating notice of motion under sub-rule (3) of rule 4 or paragraph of rule 6, the Court may, at such hearing: - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application; - direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defendant notify the plaintiff of their intention to give evidence under section 24(1) by including a statement in their defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act] by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the applicant to provide evidence of their request for an apology, correction, or retraction from the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"contain an averment that the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish an apology, correction or retraction (as the case may be) in relation to the alleged defamatory statement and specify when and the manner in which the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish such apology, correction or retraction in relation to the alleged defamatory statement (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such request and proof of delivery of same)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications for declaratory orders under section 28 10. (1) A motion referred to in section 28(5) shall be an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 28 and in which the person who claims to be the subject of a statement that he or she alleges is defamatory shall be named as applicant and the person against whom relief is sought shall be named as respondent. (2) A grounding affidavit referred to in section 28(5) shall: - (a) set out the circumstances in which it is claimed that the alleged defamatory statement was made, including the time and method of publication; - set out the grounds on which it is claimed that the statement is defamatory of the applicant; - contain an averment that the respondent has no defence to the application; - contain an averment that the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish an apology, correction or retraction (as the case may be) in relation to the alleged defamatory statement and specify when and the manner in which the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish such apology, correction or retraction in relation to the alleged defamatory statement (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such request and proof of delivery of same), and - produce evidence of the response (if any) by the respondent to the request (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such response).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the defendant required to provide details about their intended evidence for mitigation at least seven days before the trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation to be given 11. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by 486 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/486/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff join multiple defendants who might be liable for different parts of the relief sought?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"All persons may be joined as defendants against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **PARTIES** 1. All persons may be joined in one action as plaintiffs in whom any right to relief in respect of or arising out of the same transactions is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if such persons brought separate actions, any common question of law or fact would arise; provided that if, upon a motion on notice by any defendant, it shall appear that such joinder may embarrass or delay the trial, the Judge may order separate trials, or make such other order as may be right, and provided also that no person shall be made a plaintiff without his consent. 2. All persons may be joined as defendants against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. When the plaintiff is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more defendants, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the defendants is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him; but the Judge may make such order as may appear just, to prevent any defendant from being embarrassed, or put to expense, by being required to attend any proceedings in which he has no interest. 3. The plaintiff may, at his option, join as defendants to the same action all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can an infant defend a suit by having a guardian litem appointed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An infant may defend by his guardian litem appointed for that purpose in accordance with Order 19 of these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. [[1]](#_ftn1) No action, cause or matter shall be defeated by reason of the misjoinder or non-joinder of parties, and the Judge may in every action, cause or matter deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before him. The Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, either upon or without the application of any party, and on such terms as may appear to him to be just, order that the name of any party, whether plaintiff or defendant, who has been improperly joined, be struck out, and that the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Judge to adjudicate upon and settle all the questions involved in the cause or matter, be added as a plaintiff or a defendant. No person shall be added as a plaintiff suing without a next friend, or as the next friend of a plaintiff under any disability, without his consent in writing thereto. Every person whose name is so added as defendant shall be served with a Civil Bill in such manner as may be prescribed by any Order of the Court, and the action, cause or matter, as against such party, shall be deemed to have begun only on the making of the Order adding such party. 5. An infant may sue by his next friend, and in such case there shall be lodged with the Civil Bill a written authority authorising the commencement and prosecution of the suit on behalf of the infant and the use of the name of such person as next friend, signed by such person. 6. An infant may defend by his guardian litem* appointed for that purpose in accordance with [Order 19]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-19-Circuit-Side-bar-applications) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a ward of court initiate legal proceedings independently?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where there is in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer a registered co-decision-making agreement which provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered in the proceedings shall be signed by, or shall include a certificate that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by, the appointer and co-decision-maker. (6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee 9. Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and shall be considered as representing such persons; but the Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of such persons to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties. This rule shall apply to trustees, executors, and administrators sued in proceedings to enforce a security by sale or otherwise. 10. Save in actions founded on tort, when there are numerous persons having the same interest in one action or matter, one or more of such persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Judge to defend, in such action or matter, on behalf of or for the benefit of all persons so interested.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 6 - Right of Audience', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a High Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Right of Audience - Court: District # Order 6: Right of Audience [1] ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff issue multiple concurrent summonses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summonses"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses - Court: Superior 1. The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summons or summonses, each concurrent summons to bear the same date of issue as the original summons, and to be marked with a seal bearing the word “**concurrent**” and the date of issue of the concurrent summons; and such seal shall be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer; provided always, that such concurrent summons or summonses shall only be in force for the period during which the original summons in such proceedings shall be in force. 2. A summons for service within the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction; and a summons for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service within the jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher level court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Family Home Protection Act, 1976 referred to in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the [Family Home Protection Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1976)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition.* 1. In this Order — “**the Ac**t” means the [Family Home Protection Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1976).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings be heard at any sitting of the Court within the same district if they are certified as urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2. (1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home, as defined in section 2 of the Act, is situate. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the court district within which such court area is situate, certifies on a notice of application or a summons that the proceedings are urgent, the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is the hearing conducted in private when both spouses are involved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under or referred to in the Act in which each spouse is a party (whether by joinder or otherwise) shall be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* 3. Proceedings under or referred to in the Act in which each spouse is a party (whether by joinder or otherwise) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 60.4 Schedule required before a spouse can apply under section 9(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(2).* 5. An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 60.8 Schedule used when a person is summoned for providing false or misleading information?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 15 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 15.* 8. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 15 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for lodging the original notice or summons with the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents.* 9. (1) A notice or summons required by this Order to be served may be served in accordance with the provisions of [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) of these Rules and every such notice shall be served at least fourteen days or, in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2) hereof, at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a person who initiated proceedings to declare a conveyance void to enter particulars of those proceedings as a lis pendens?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lis Pendens.* (3) A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form for an application to dispense with a spouse''s consent to conveyance of the family home?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under subsection (1) of section 4 of the Act to dispense with the consent required under section 3 of that Act, of a spouse to the conveyance of the family home shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Dispensing with consent.* 12.[2] (1) An application under subsection (1) of section 4 of the Act to dispense with the consent required under section 3 of that Act, of a spouse to the conveyance of the family home shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df0ce4a-6d5d-4c09-939d-6893aeb7ca2b/Order dispensing with consent of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.12.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df0ce4a-6d5d-4c09-939d-6893aeb7ca2b/Order dispensing with consent of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.12.docx/docx/1). (3) On granting an application under section 4 of the Act to dispense with the consent required under section 3 of that Act, the Court may order pursuant to section 33 of the [Trustee Act, 1893](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1893/act/53/enacted/en/print.html) that a person be appointed to execute the conveyance of the interest in question and the order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6232d23b-0016-4559-a960-0b355c5c68c0/Order appointing a person to execute consent to conveyance of family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 4(1) No. 60.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for an application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act to compensate the applicant spouse and any dependent child of the family for loss occasioned by the conduct of the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.18, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Conduct leading to loss of Family Home.* 15.[5] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act to compensate the applicant spouse and any dependent to loss of Family child of the family for loss occasioned by the conduct of the other spouse Home. shall be in the [Form 60.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3ae2cb1e-21c5-4e31-92a0-2a6a60b55277/Application for an order for compensation for loss relating to the family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(2) No. 60.18.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 60 rule 11 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [2] Order 60 rule 12 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [3] Order 60 rule 13 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [4] Order 60 rule 14 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [5] Order 60 rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about the use of blood tests in determining parentage?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be used when serving a notice for an application for a direction for the use of blood tests?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other party or parties to the proceedings and upon each person in respect of whom the direction is sought or, where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her and shall be served at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for a direction for the use of blood tests* 2. (1) Where in any civil proceedings before the Court the parentage of any person is in question, an application under section 38 (1) of the Act by a party to the proceedings for a direction for the use of blood tests shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 61.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83d7a649-d1b7-4e05-bda2-03e28cff563c/Notice of application for direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 section 38(1) No. 61.1.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other party or parties to the proceedings and upon each person in respect of whom the direction is sought or, where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her and shall be served at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (3) Where the Court of its own motion proposes to give a direction for the use of blood tests or where application for such a direction is made in the course of hearing the proceedings, and if each of the parties to the proceedings and each person in respect of whom the direction is proposed or sought (or his or her legal or other representative, as the case may be) is then present in court, the Court may dispense with the requirement to serve notice of application. (4) The direction of the Court shall be in the [Form 61.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b10be890-211b-4f39-a987-0f83ec683d17/Direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act, 1987 section 38 (1) No. 61.2.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person in respect of whom it was given or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order for revoking or varying a direction required to be served on individuals directly affected by it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order revoking or varying a direction* 3. Where under section 38 (3) of the Act the Court revokes or varies a direction previously given under section 38 (1) of the Act, the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d12db6d0-b7b7-40cc-8859-ef8fba9b0317/Order revoking - varying a direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.3.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the original notice and a statutory declaration regarding its service to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of intention to call witness* 4. (1) A notice under section 40 (5) of the Act by a party to civil proceedings of that party''s intention to call a person as a witness shall be in the [Form 61.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ed129f6-37c8-46f4-926a-7adee2623b90/Notice of intention to call witness - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.4.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other parties to the proceedings or upon such of them as the Court may direct, at least fourteen days before the sitting of the Court at which it is intended to call as a witness the person named in the notice. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk responsible for sending a direction form to the sampler?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to send direction form to sampler* 5. Where the Court gives a direction under section 38 (1) of the Act, the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is a recorder someone who prepares and publishes reports of certain proceedings according to the 2004 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a “**recorder**” means a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) intending to attend or attending any proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of such proceedings in accordance with section 40(3) of the 2004 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this rule: the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); a “**recorder**” means a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) intending to attend or attending any proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of such proceedings in accordance with section 40(3) of the 2004 Act; “**relevant enactment**” has the same meaning as in section 39 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is a recorder required to identify themselves before or at the start of the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Recorders* 2.[3] (1) A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court and apply for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (2) On any such application, the Court - (a) if satisfied that the applicant is a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and that the recorder intends to attend the proceedings for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, and - having heard any submission made by or on behalf of any party to the proceedings, may allow the recorder to attend the proceedings (or any part of the proceedings) subject to such directions as the Court may give in that regard. (3) The Court may, of its own motion or on the application of any party or person, vary or modify any such directions given under section 40(3) of the Act during the course of the proceedings. (4) Where the Court refuses to allow a recorder who has made an application under sub-rule (1) to attend the relevant proceedings, the Court must give its reasons for such refusal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court verify if a person is a bona fide representative of the press?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Bona fide representatives of the press* 3. (1) Prior to, at the commencement of, or during the course of the hearing of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, the Court may - (a) make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press within the meaning of section 40(3A) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - hear any application by or on behalf of a party or person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub- section refers) for an order under 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or may for the purposes of considering the making of any such order of its own motion, hear submissions from any such party or person. (2) The Court may, at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings, of its own motion or on the application of a person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub-section refers), having heard the parties and any other person it considers necessary, vary or modify any order made in accordance with sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Is the approval of an accompanying person in parte applications left to the discretion of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of Form No. 61A.1 duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Accompanying persons* 4.[4] (1) Where a party (in this rule referred to as the “applicant”) wishes to be accompanied in court in any proceedings referred to in section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), save for proceedings to which section 26 of the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6/enacted/en/html) applies, by another person (in this rule referred to as “the accompanying person”), the applicant must, unless the Court otherwise directs, complete a notice of application in the [Form 61A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) Where the other party or parties agree to the accompanying person, the applicant must lodge [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed, with the Clerk prior to the commencement of the hearing in the proceedings, and must apply to the Court at that hearing to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (3) Except in parte applications, where the other party or parties have not agreed to the accompanying person, the applicant must, by application to the Court in the [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1), on notice to the other party or parties, returnable not later than seven days prior to the date fixed for the hearing in such proceedings, apply to the Court to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (4) In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published, at least twenty-eight days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published, at least twenty-eight days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk prior to the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of the application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and newspaper* (4) A copy of the notice of the application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate issued when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 63.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ed8d17e-7da9-4d5a-9042-f4577cde3d5b/Certificate of qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1947 No. 63.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice of objection to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a copy, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. A notice of objection pursuant to section 11 (5) of the Act to the grant of a certificate of qualification shall be in accordance with [Form 63.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7d63184-090a-4651-990b-62fde646d8a5/Notice Of Objection To The Grant Of A Certificate Of Qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act 1947 No. 63.2.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served upon the applicant and a copy, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931', 'Court Rules', 'Is the appeal process for refusing a certificate governed by specific regulations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The procedure to be followed in an appeal from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act is the procedure set out in the Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Procedure for appeal against refusal of Superintendent to grant certificate* 2. The procedure to be followed in an appeal from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act is the procedure set out in the [Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931 (Statutory Rules and Orders, 1931 No. 81)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be served to Inland Fisheries Ireland before an application for a certificate of fitness can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for cert. of fitness* 2. (1) An application pursuant to section 158 (as amended by section 14 of [the Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html) and the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 65.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08e99c10-7260-410a-bac2-8f1c8548b8e5/Notice of application for a certificate of fitness - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 section 158 No. 65.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3)[1] The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 324 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) A certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence granted under the said section 158 shall be in the [Form 65.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2776117-18da-4d59-809b-aa6d1b39086c/Certificate of fitness to hold a salmon dealer''s licence - eel dealer''s licence - molluscan shellfish dealer''s licence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when ordering the detention of a boat and persons under section 234(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order of the Court pursuant to section 234 (1) - as substituted by section 13 of [the Act of 1978] of [the Principal Act] requiring the detention of a boat and persons (including the master) on board such boat until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat and persons pending adjudication of proceedings* 4. An order of the Court pursuant to section 234 (1) - as substituted by section 13 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the detention of a boat and persons (including the master) on board such boat until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/17b05ad3-0423-4b2f-a78f-c12720b11b83/Order for detention under section 234 (1) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when ordering the distress and sale of a boat?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for distress and the sale of a boat on the non-payment of a fine and costs (if any) shall be in the [Form 65.8, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order for distress and sale of boat* 6. An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for distress and the sale of a boat on the non-payment of a fine and costs (if any) shall be in the [Form 65.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05092604-13a3-449e-ad6d-6fff1fddf4fc/Order for detention of boat pending the taking of possession of article ordered to be - which stands - forfeited - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *— by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 65.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0549f5af-f10b-4cdd-b171-c0974f25291b/Information for warrant (under section 297) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.13.docx/docx/1), of an authorised person within the meaning of section 292 — as substituted in the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the given text about a court case?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries - Court: District # Order 66: Gaming and lotteries**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to precede the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/481b1d1f-ea20-4506-ba4b-69e615e0da41/Application for a certificate - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of Notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/481b1d1f-ea20-4506-ba4b-69e615e0da41/Application for a certificate - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Superintendent to provide documents to the Clerk before the court sitting?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (4) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána concerned at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court at which the appeal is to be heard. When service has been effected the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of the said sitting. (5) The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Is an inspector required to make an application for a search warrant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7], Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fed46a08-bd3a-4bda-8545-696d98d68c27/Information for search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Do parties need to combine their requests for further information and further particulars into one notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"all such requests shall, except by consent or order of the Court, be made in the same notice or letter"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notices under the 2004 Act* 10.(1) Where a party intends both to request further information under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and to request further particulars in accordance with [Order 17]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-17-Circuit-Particulars-and-further-particulars-in-claim-or-defence), all such requests shall, except by consent or order of the Court, be made in the same notice or letter, and be replied to in the same notice or letter. (2) Copies of the plaintiff’s notice of an offer of terms of settlement required by section 17(1) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and of the defendant’s notice required by section 17(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be lodged in court by being filed (together with an affidavit as to the service of the same on the opposing party) in the Office as soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period referred to in section 17(3) of the 2004 Act. Such notice shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iv)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-notice-offer-terms-settlement) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is the General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 referenced in this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 67 - General dealers - Court: District 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1903/act/44/enacted/en/print.html) (3 Edw. VII 44).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a General Dealer''s Licence be made at any sitting of the Court within the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 2. (1) An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be used when issuing a notice for an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34bc3ede-f823-4446-b466-3366f4277bc6/Notice of application for a general dealer''s licence - General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 section 1 No. 67.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for lodging the original notice and a statutory declaration with the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) When service has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued according to a specific form when the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4dde7091-171c-4c95-b51f-5402ef56bb8a/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Order related to licensing certificates and declarations of fitness?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**- Certificates for spirit retailers’ licences, beer retailers’ licences, wine retailers’ licences, wholesale beer licences, producer’s retail licences;** **- Declarations of fitness under section 15 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 - Court: District # Order 68: Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1) **- Certificates for spirit retailers’ licences, beer retailers’ licences, wine retailers’ licences, wholesale beer licences, producer’s retail licences;** **- Declarations of fitness under section 15 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a certificate or declaration be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive an excise licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor for consumption off the premises or for a declaration as to the fitness and convenience of proposed licensed premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 1. (1) An application for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive an excise licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor for consumption off the premises or for a declaration as to the fitness and convenience of proposed licensed premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Forms of notice* (2) Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 68.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ba678d47-364c-423d-a6d3-635a539b9ebc/Notice Of Application For A Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence. No. 68.1.docx/docx/1) to [68.5A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b655656f-3ba7-458f-adb7-2c4b25b2f01e/Notice of application for a certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (Breweries and Distilleries) Act 2018, section 1 No. 68.5A.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a local newspaper when applying for certain types of licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice for spirit, beer or wine retailer’s or producer’s application* (4) Where the application is for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive a spirit retailer’s licence, a beer retailer’s licence, a wine retailer’s licence or a producer’s retail licence, the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a local newspaper when applying for a declaration about their premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is for a declaration that the premises would be fit and convenient to be licensed the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice of application for declaration* (5) Where the application is for a declaration that the premises would be fit and convenient to be licensed the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk prior to the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises shall be lodged with the Clerk at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, newspaper, etc.* (6) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises shall be lodged with the Clerk at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate or declaration required to be in accordance with specific forms if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 68.6] to [68.11], [Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (7) Where the application is granted, the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 68.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eff3a56c-ed83-45fb-9512-6f52327059d3/Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence No. 68.6.docx/docx/1) to [68.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/edd299f3-eebd-4444-a908-7e4b9817732e/Certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (breweries and Distilleries) Act 2019, section 1 No. 68.11.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be. [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftnref1) Order 68 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher level court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a restaurant certificate be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for applications* 2. (1) An application for the grant of - - (a) a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), - a restaurant certificate, made by the holder of a wine retailer''s on-licence pursuant to section 12 (1A) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 8 of the [Act of 1943](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1943/act/7/enacted/en/html)), - a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 12 of the said Act (as inserted by section 48 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)), - a limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12A of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 9 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html)), or - a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 16 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Forms of notice* (2) Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 69.1 to 69.5 Schedule C,](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) as the case may be, signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to deposit a copy of the plan of the premises with the officer when applying for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana for the licensing area at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application and, where the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk prior to the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and map* (4) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate or declaration required to follow a specific format when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a Circuit Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Third Party Procedure - Court: Circuit'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court allow a defendant to issue a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may give leave to the defendant to issue and serve a third party notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Actions by and against Firms and Persons Carrying on Business in names other than their own** 1. Where in any action a defendant claims as against any person not already a party to the action (in this Order called ‘‘**the third party**’’) (*a*) that he is entitled to contribution or indemnity; that he is entitled to any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the action and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the plaintiff; that any question or issue relating to or connected with the said subject matter is substantially the same as some question or issue arising between the plaintiff and the defendant and should properly be determined not only as between the plaintiff and the defendant but as between the plaintiff and the defendant and the third party or between any or either of them, the Court may give leave to the defendant to issue and serve a third party notice and may, at the same time, if it shall appear desirable to do so, give the third party liberty to appear at the trial and take such part therein as may be just, and generally give such directions as to the Court shall appear proper for having any question or the rights or liabilities of the parties most conveniently determined and enforced and as to the mode and extent in or to which the third party shall be bound or made liable by the decision or judgment in the action. 2. The application for such leave shall be made by motion on notice to the plaintiff in accordance with [Form 6C](http://icsmweb09/content/application-leave-issue-and-serve-third-party-notice) as set out in the Schedule of Forms attached hereto. Unless the plaintiff wishes to add the third party as a defendant, his attendance at the hearing of the motion shall not be necessary. If the plaintiff does attend he shall not be entitled to costs in respect of the motion except by special direction of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a digital user file and serve a third party notice through digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 11A]) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 11A]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Application for leave to issue the third party notice shall, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, be made after the service of an Appearance and at any time prior to the trial of the action. 4. The third party notice shall state the nature and grounds of the claim or the nature of the question or issue sought to be determined and all information required to be set out in the indorsement of a Civil Bill as provided for in these rules and any directions of the Court given under Rule 1 hereof. The third party notice shall be issued and served in the same manner as in the case of a Civil Bill and shall be served within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. A copy of the Civil Bill and defence together with a copy of the Order joining the third party shall be served with the third party notice which said third party notice shall also be served upon the Plaintiff(s). Where the third party is joined as a defendant, an amended Civil Bill together with a copy of the Order joining the third party as a defendant shall be served upon all defendants by the plaintiff within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. Any amended defence of an original defendant to the proceedings shall be served upon the plaintiff within ten days from the date of service of the amended Civil Bill. 4A.[1] A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt)) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt) and, in the case of service, where the third party or third party’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a third party be added to an action through a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant and shall be entitled to be served with all pleadings in the proceedings by the party filing and/or delivering same. 6. The third party notice shall call upon a third party to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the defendant, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 7. Where a third party enters an appearance, he shall deliver his defence within ten days from the date thereof or within such further period as may be allowed by the Court or consented to by the defendant(s) in the proceedings. 8. After the third party enters an appearance, and before the expiration of the time limited for the delivery of defence, he may, after serving notice of the intended application upon the plaintiff and all defendants, apply to the Court to vary any directions given by the Court under Rule 1 of this Order. 9. The Court may decide all questions of costs as between a third party and the other parties to the action, and may order any one or more to pay the costs of any other or others or give such directions as to costs as the justice of the case may require. [1] Order 7 rule 4A inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is this order specifically about minors and other persons under disability?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Minors And Other Persons Under Disability"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''minor'' defined by a specific act in this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In this Order- “**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Construction* 1. In this Order- “**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1985/act/2/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 2 of 1985).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a minor defend a proceeding without a guardian litem?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A minor may sue by his or her next friend, and may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Minors - next friend/guardian litem* 2. A minor may sue by his or her next friend, and may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem. In any such case, before the name of any person shall be used in proceedings as next friend or guardian litem of the minor, such person shall sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule for that purpose, which shall be lodged with the Clerk together with the civil summons or other originating document or, as the case may be, with a notice of intention to defend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court appoint a next friend or guardian litem for a minor involved in legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, if it thinks it expedient so to do, at any stage of the proceedings by an order in writing in the Form 7.2, Schedule appoint a next friend or a guardian litem to act for and on behalf of such minor"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appointment by the Court* 3. Where any proceedings are brought before the Court on behalf of or against a minor the Court may, if it thinks it expedient so to do, at any stage of the proceedings by an order in writing in the Form 7.2, Schedule appoint a next friend or a guardian litem to act for and on behalf of such minor, and may at any time replace a person so appointed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is court approval necessary before accepting a lodgment made by a defendant in an action involving a minor plaintiff?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court approval required for acceptance of lodgments, etc.* 4.(1) Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing. (2) The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 2 (4) of these Rules shall apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor, where a settlement, compromise, payment or acceptance of money paid into court therein is proposed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court direct the securing or investing of money or property for a minor''s benefit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A], direct that any sum of money or other personal property to which the minor may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of the minor in such manner as the Court may consider advisable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Orders for investment, etc.* 5.(1)[1] The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any sum of money or other personal property to which the minor may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of the minor in such manner as the Court may consider advisable. A copy of any order made under rule 4, 5 or 6 of this Order shall, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is an order from the Court required for an interim payment to be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim payments* (2) Unless the Court shall otherwise decide, no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court made upon the application of the minor''s next friend or guardian litem. Such application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the proceedings were heard and determined, upon lodging with the Clerk a notice in the Form 7.4, Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is proof of age required for an application to receive payment under rule 5(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Payment out of sums invested* (2) A person who, on attaining full age, seeks the payment of any sum of money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit under rule 5 (1) hereof or any balance of such sum remaining due, may apply at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the proceedings were heard and determined for an order authorising such payment. Notice of the application in the Form 7.5, Schedule shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days prior to the date of hearing. The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to serve the notice of application on the respondent at least seven days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served- ... not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order for payment* (3) On hearing the application the Court may by order direct the payment out to the applicant of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to the applicant, together with accrued interest or dividend thereon (if any), or may make any other order on such application as to the Court shall seem just. 6A[2]. (1) An application by the next friend, committee or other person referred to in subsection (1) of section 35 of the Act shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district within which the claimant ordinarily resides. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form 7.6, Schedule and shall be addressed to the respondent by name and shall be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. Such notice shall be served- - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished by the respondent, at that address, or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4)[3] Where the Court approves an assessment in accordance with this rule it may give directions as to how the amount recoverable by the minor, ward or relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 is to be dealt with, including a direction for lodgement in Court and investment of the amount concerned. (5) The Clerk shall send by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail to the Personal Injuries Assessment Board a certified copy of any order made pursuant to this rule. (6) In the event of an order to pay issuing in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy thereof shall be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certified extract from the Register of Births required to prove a minor''s age?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth shall, if required, be produced and proved on behalf of the minor"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proof of age* 7. A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth shall, if required, be produced and proved on behalf of the minor at the hearing of proceedings involving such minor, on an application to have a proposed settlement approved by the Court or on any other application relating to a minor or a person who has lately been a minor. The said date of birth shall be noted in any order of the Court made in any such proceeding or application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a decision-making representative initiate legal proceedings on behalf of a relevant person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Relevant person to whom the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 applies* 8[4].(1) In this rule, the “2015 Act” means the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015, and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where notification of lack of capacity has been accepted in respect of a registered enduring power of attorney made by a relevant person as the donor, which power includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where a registered enduring power under the Act of 1996, made by a relevant person as the donor, includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney under the Act of 1996 may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service. (5) Where a registered co-decision-making agreement in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered on behalf of that party in such proceedings shall state that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by the appointer and co-decision-maker.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court make orders regarding the capacity of an adult party involved in proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is service of documents on minors governed by specific rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"service of documents upon a minor shall be effected in accordance with the provisions (including rule 8) of [Order 41]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of documents* 9.[5] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents upon a minor shall be effected in accordance with the provisions (including rule 8) of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules, and upon a relevant person to whom rule 8 applies in accordance with the provisions (including rule 9) of that Order. [1] Order 7 rule 5(1) substituted by [S.I. 258 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/258/made/en/print?q 258&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005 [2] Order 7 rule 6A inserted by [S.I. 526 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/526/made/en/print?q 526&years 2004), effective 8 September 2004 [3] Order 7 rule 6A(4) substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.[4] [4] Order 7 rule 8 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [5] Order 7 rule 9 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party change their solicitor without needing an order from the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A party suing or defending by a solicitor shall, save in any matrimonial cause or matter, be at liberty to change his solicitor or to discharge his solicitor and sue or defend in person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Solicitors - Court: Superior 1. Every solicitor whose name shall be indorsed on any summons or other originating document shall, on demand in writing made by or on behalf of any defendant who has been served with the same or with notice thereof, or has appeared thereto, declare forthwith in writing whether such summons or other originating document has been issued by him or with his authority or privity; and if such solicitor shall declare that the summons or other originating document was not issued by him or with his authority or privity all proceedings upon the same shall be stayed, and no further proceedings shall be taken thereon without leave of the Court. 2. (1) A party suing or defending by a solicitor shall, save in any matrimonial cause or matter, be at liberty to change his solicitor or to discharge his solicitor and sue or defend in person, and any party suing or defending in person shall be at liberty to appoint a solicitor, in any cause or matter, without an order for that purpose, upon notice of such change, discharge, or appointment being filed in the Central Office, but until such notice is so filed and a copy thereof served as hereinafter provided, no such change, discharge, or appointment shall be deemed to have taken effect. (2) The party giving such notice shall serve a copy thereof upon every other party to the proceedings (not being a party in default as to entry of appearance). (2A)[[1]](#_ftn1) Where such notice is given at any time in which an appeal is pending in the Court of Appeal or the Supreme Court, the party concerned shall additionally lodge a copy of the notice in the Office of the Registrar of the Court of Appeal or, as the case may be, the Office of the Registrar of the Supreme Court. (3) Every such notice shall state a registered place of business or address for service as prescribed by [Order 4](full-court-rule?id abaea3e0-921b-4d8d-b19c-1be17598937b).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor perform duties through a new solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The party giving any such notice may perform the duties prescribed by this rule either in person or (except where he intends to act in person) through his new solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The party giving any such notice may perform the duties prescribed by this rule either in person or (except where he intends to act in person) through his new solicitor. 3. (1) Where a solicitor who has acted for a party in any proceedings has died or become bankrupt or cannot be found or has failed to take out a practising certificate or has been struck off the roll of solicitors or has ceased to act for the party, and the party has not given notice of change of solicitor or notice of intention to act in person in accordance with the provisions of rule 2, any other party to the proceedings or (where the solicitor has ceased to act) the solicitor may, on notice to be served on the first-mentioned party, personally, or by letter addressed to his last-known place of residence, unless the Court otherwise directs, apply to the Court for an order declaring that the solicitor has ceased to be the solicitor acting for the first-mentioned party in the proceedings, and the Court may make an order accordingly. (2) Where such order shall have been made the party or the solicitor who applied therefor shall forthwith give a notice to the same effect as the order, and the provisions of rule 2 as to filing and service shall apply thereto with the necessary modifications and subject to any direction in such order as to service on the first-mentioned party. (3) Where the party or solicitor who applied for such order shall have complied with the said provisions then, if the first-mentioned party does not appoint another solicitor or give such an address for service as is required of a party acting in person, and comply with the provisions of rule 2, any documents in respect of which personal service is not requisite may be served on the said party by being filed with the proper officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can an order under rule 3 be made without both parties being present?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order under the provisions of rule 3 may be made on an parte application unless the Court shall otherwise direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where the said order is made on the application of a solicitor, such solicitor shall, subject to the provisions of rules 2 and 3 be considered the solicitor of the party to the final conclusion of the proceedings unless and until he has complied with the provisions of paragraph (2) of this rule. 4. An order under the provisions of rule 3 may be made on an parte application unless the Court shall otherwise direct. 5. Any order made under the provisions of rule 3 shall not affect the rights of the solicitor and the party as between themselves. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 7 rule 2A inserted by 485 of 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/485/made/en/print), effective 28 October 2014, subject to the provisions of paragraph 2 of 485 of 2014.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can an objection to the first grant of a Wine Retailer''s On-Licence be made by a member of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An objection by a member of the Garda Síochána (not below the rank of Inspector) to the first grant by the Revenue Commissioners of a Wine Retailer''s On-Licence, pursuant to section 14 of the [Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. An objection by a member of the Garda Síochána (not below the rank of Inspector) to the first grant by the Revenue Commissioners of a Wine Retailer''s On-Licence, pursuant to section 14 of the [Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1860/act/107/enacted/en/print.html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises sought to be licensed are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before an objection can be made against a licence application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection—* 2. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 70.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d001a1a1-4aca-48ea-a1f5-647dd3990559/Summons (objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence) - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act 1860 No. 70.1.docx/docx/1) upon the applicant for such licence at least seven days prior to the sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise when a summons is issued?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Upon issuing the summons for service the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a notice by way of caveat in the [Form 70.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *caveat to Collector of Customs & Excise* (2) Upon issuing the summons for service the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a notice by way of caveat in the [Form 70.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e09bd10-6ae5-46d1-af8d-f70596b18719/Notice by way of caveat to collector of custom and excise - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.2.docx/docx/1). (3) When the summons has been served the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of the said sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certified copy of the court''s order sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A certified copy of such order shall be sent by the Clerk to the Collector of Customs and Excise."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* 3. (1) The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 70.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/84cca641-8697-47f4-91c7-2e122ef3ce6e/Order affirming objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.3.docx/docx/1) or [70.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d08e01e8-276e-43e1-bd05-7d94b151adb0/Order disallowing objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate. A certified copy of such order shall be sent by the Clerk to the Collector of Customs and Excise. (2) Where a notice of appeal against such an order is lodged with the Clerk he or she shall forthwith send notice to that effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 71 related to special exemption orders in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 71: Special exemption orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 71 - Special exemption orders - Court: District # Order 71: Special exemption orders**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a special exemption order allowed to be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application for a special exemption order pursuant to section 5 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927 (as substituted by section 11 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 and as amended by section 10 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) Save as is hereinafter provided, an application for a special exemption order pursuant to section 5 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 11 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) and as amended by section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/17/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order to be issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 71.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 71.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3aa71ae-b309-4ac4-83a0-cace9fe92db7/Special exemption order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927, section 5 as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008, section 10 No. 71.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge grant an exemption order at any sitting if special circumstances apply?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such exemption order at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *In certain circumstances may be granted at any sitting.* (4) A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such exemption order at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district. [1] Order 71 originally substituted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), re-substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), effective 25 May 2009'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a general exemption order required to be made at the Annual Licensing Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application for a general exemption order pursuant to section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), as amended by section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html), section 15 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) and section 5 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/17/enacted/en/html), may be made at a sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. The application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to precede the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 72.1 or 72.2)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Form of notice (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 72.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b4575765-00ec-484f-9686-b7167b6977d8/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a public market or fair - Intoxicating Liquor Acts No. 72.1.docx/docx/1) or [72.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/58a0fce5-0cdb-4dd2-ad8f-40026f0e8d7d/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a place at which a considerable number of persons are following a lawful trade or calling No. 72.2.docx/docx/1) [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Does an order remain in effect beyond the date it was issued?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *In force to Annual Licensing Court* \*(6) Every such order shall, unless withdrawn in pursuance of subsection (6) of section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), or expressed to expire sooner, remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on granting a general exemption order on Sundays?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"for any time on any Sunday"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited premises and days* †2.[2] A general exemption order shall not be granted in respect of premises unless a general exemption order was in force in respect of the premises on 30 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) [Sec. 10]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (Sec. 4(7) as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008 [Sec. 5] and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) [Sec. [1] Order 72 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), effective 25 May 2009 [2] Order 72 rule 2 re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 73 related to exemptions for special events in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 73 - Exemptions for special events - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 73 - Exemptions for special events - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an exemption order be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in the county borough of Dublin for an exemption order in respect of a special event pursuant to section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given at least seven days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Order of Court to be issued in a specific format if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f853200-09a8-468c-b759-f0ce1443579d/Exemption order for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 10 No. 73.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge notice of the application with the Clerk prior to the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of Notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that the order of the court must follow when hearing an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cce42bdc-661a-4032-b000-1eb6b0c895f6/Order revoking exemption for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962 No. 73.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required to be given to the Garda Síochána when an order is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the making of such order shall be given by the Clerk to the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the revoked application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice to Garda Síochána* (4) Notice of the making of such order shall be given by the Clerk to the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the revoked application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to exemptions for licensed businesses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an exemption order be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order in respect of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day between the hours of twelve o''clock and half-past twelve in the afternoon, pursuant to section 16 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order in respect of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day between the hours of twelve o''clock and half-past twelve in the afternoon, pursuant to section 16 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration when lodging a notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (5) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Order of Court specified to follow a particular form if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4eeab324-ae33-4e1d-b0f8-9c5018e0f6c9/Exemption order for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s Day - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 No. 74.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Can a subsequent application be made to revoke an already granted application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation* 2. (1) Where an application referred to in rule 1 (1) or 1 (2) of this Order has been granted, a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a local newspaper before their hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper Notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice of application to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order to be issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aff577ec-10d6-4395-915b-54bca6e604d2/Order revoking exemption for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 74.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 75 related to business exemptions on specific days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an exemption order to open or keep open premises for business purposes other than the sale or supply of intoxicating liquor be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the holder of a licence ... may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence (not being a licence granted by virtue of paragraph (2) of section 2 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1902](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1902/act/18/enacted/en/print.html)) in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order to open or keep open the premises for the purpose of carrying on any business other than the sale or supply of intoxicating liquor during any one period and not exceeding forty-five minutes in duration on the mornings of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day, pursuant to section 17 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice of application to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (5) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order to be issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2eb82a05-a935-4d0f-8971-227985d82fbd/Order permitting the opening and keeping open of premises for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Can a subsequent application be made to revoke or amend an already granted application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked or amended."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation or amendment* 2. (1) Where an application referred to in rule 1 (1) or 1 (2) of this Order has been granted, a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked or amended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice of application to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the form referenced in the court order available for viewing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 75.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb242f64-64bc-4749-9446-79f888d75e0d/Order revoking an order permitting premises to open or keep open for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb242f64-64bc-4749-9446-79f888d75e0d/Order revoking an order permitting premises to open or keep open for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a Supreme Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 76 - Occasional licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an occasional licence be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application for an occasional licence, pursuant to section 11 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 (as amended) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) Save as is hereinafter provided, an application for an occasional licence, pursuant to section 11 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) (as amended) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a General Dealer''s Licence be submitted at any sitting of the Court within the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 2. (1) An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34bc3ede-f823-4446-b466-3366f4277bc6/Notice of application for a general dealer''s licence - General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 section 1 No. 67.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the original notice and a statutory declaration to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) When service has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued according to a specific form when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4dde7091-171c-4c95-b51f-5402ef56bb8a/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Order 68 related to licensing acts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 - Court: District # Order 68: Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1) **- Certificates for spirit retailers’ licences, beer retailers’ licences, wine retailers’ licences, wholesale beer licences, producer’s retail licences;** **- Declarations of fitness under section 15 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a certificate or declaration be made at any sitting of the Court within the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive an excise licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor for consumption off the premises or for a declaration as to the fitness and convenience of proposed licensed premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 1. (1) An application for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive an excise licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor for consumption off the premises or for a declaration as to the fitness and convenience of proposed licensed premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants seeking certain types of licences to publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice for spirit, beer or wine retailer’s or producer’s application* (4) Where the application is for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive a spirit retailer’s licence, a beer retailer’s licence, a wine retailer’s licence or a producer’s retail licence, the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper when applying for a declaration about the premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice of application for declaration* (5) Where the application is for a declaration that the premises would be fit and convenient to be licensed the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a statutory declaration as to service thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, newspaper, etc.* (6) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises shall be lodged with the Clerk at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a restaurant certificate be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for applications* 2. (1) An application for the grant of - - (a) a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), - a restaurant certificate, made by the holder of a wine retailer''s on-licence pursuant to section 12 (1A) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 8 of the [Act of 1943](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1943/act/7/enacted/en/html)), - a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 12 of the said Act (as inserted by section 48 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)), - a limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12A of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 9 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html)), or - a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 16 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to deposit a copy of the plan of the premises with the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana for the licensing area at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application and, where the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk prior to the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and map* (4) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate or declaration required to be in accordance with specific forms if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can a third party be added to an action after being served with a third party notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant and shall be entitled to be served with all pleadings in the proceedings by the party filing and/or delivering same. 6. The third party notice shall call upon a third party to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the defendant, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 7. Where a third party enters an appearance, he shall deliver his defence within ten days from the date thereof or within such further period as may be allowed by the Court or consented to by the defendant(s) in the proceedings. 8. After the third party enters an appearance, and before the expiration of the time limited for the delivery of defence, he may, after serving notice of the intended application upon the plaintiff and all defendants, apply to the Court to vary any directions given by the Court under Rule 1 of this Order. 9. The Court may decide all questions of costs as between a third party and the other parties to the action, and may order any one or more to pay the costs of any other or others or give such directions as to costs as the justice of the case may require. [1] Order 7 rule 4A inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order specifically about minors and other persons under disability?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is the term ''minor'' defined by a specific act in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In this Order- “**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Construction* 1. In this Order- “**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1985/act/2/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 2 of 1985).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a minor defend a proceeding through a guardian litem?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Minors - next friend/guardian litem* 2. A minor may sue by his or her next friend, and may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem. In any such case, before the name of any person shall be used in proceedings as next friend or guardian litem of the minor, such person shall sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule for that purpose, which shall be lodged with the Clerk together with the civil summons or other originating document or, as the case may be, with a notice of intention to defend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court appoint a guardian litem for a minor involved in legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, if it thinks it expedient so to do, at any stage of the proceedings by an order in writing in the Form 7.2, Schedule appoint a next friend or a guardian litem to act for and on behalf of such minor"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appointment by the Court* 3. Where any proceedings are brought before the Court on behalf of or against a minor the Court may, if it thinks it expedient so to do, at any stage of the proceedings by an order in writing in the Form 7.2, Schedule appoint a next friend or a guardian litem to act for and on behalf of such minor, and may at any time replace a person so appointed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is court approval necessary before accepting lodgments in cases involving minors?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court approval required for acceptance of lodgments, etc.* 4.(1) Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing. (2) The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 2 (4) of these Rules shall apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor, where a settlement, compromise, payment or acceptance of money paid into court therein is proposed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application required to make an interim payment?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court made upon the application of the minor''s next friend or guardian litem."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim payments* (2) Unless the Court shall otherwise decide, no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court made upon the application of the minor''s next friend or guardian litem. Such application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the proceedings were heard and determined, upon lodging with the Clerk a notice in the Form 7.4, Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is proof of age required for someone seeking payment of a sum invested for their benefit?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Payment out of sums invested* (2) A person who, on attaining full age, seeks the payment of any sum of money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit under rule 5 (1) hereof or any balance of such sum remaining due, may apply at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the proceedings were heard and determined for an order authorising such payment. Notice of the application in the Form 7.5, Schedule shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days prior to the date of hearing. The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of application required to be served on the respondent at least seven days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served- ... not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order for payment* (3) On hearing the application the Court may by order direct the payment out to the applicant of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to the applicant, together with accrued interest or dividend thereon (if any), or may make any other order on such application as to the Court shall seem just. 6A[2]. (1) An application by the next friend, committee or other person referred to in subsection (1) of section 35 of the Act shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district within which the claimant ordinarily resides. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form 7.6, Schedule and shall be addressed to the respondent by name and shall be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. Such notice shall be served- - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished by the respondent, at that address, or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4)[3] Where the Court approves an assessment in accordance with this rule it may give directions as to how the amount recoverable by the minor, ward or relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 is to be dealt with, including a direction for lodgement in Court and investment of the amount concerned. (5) The Clerk shall send by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail to the Personal Injuries Assessment Board a certified copy of any order made pursuant to this rule. (6) In the event of an order to pay issuing in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy thereof shall be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a decision-making representative authorized by a decision-making representation order institute legal proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Relevant person to whom the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 applies* 8[4].(1) In this rule, the “2015 Act” means the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015, and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where notification of lack of capacity has been accepted in respect of a registered enduring power of attorney made by a relevant person as the donor, which power includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where a registered enduring power under the Act of 1996, made by a relevant person as the donor, includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney under the Act of 1996 may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service. (5) Where a registered co-decision-making agreement in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered on behalf of that party in such proceedings shall state that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by the appointer and co-decision-maker.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court make orders regarding the capacity of an adult party to proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor''s client perform their duties through a new solicitor?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The party giving any such notice may perform the duties prescribed by this rule either in person or (except where he intends to act in person) through his new solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The party giving any such notice may perform the duties prescribed by this rule either in person or (except where he intends to act in person) through his new solicitor. 3. (1) Where a solicitor who has acted for a party in any proceedings has died or become bankrupt or cannot be found or has failed to take out a practising certificate or has been struck off the roll of solicitors or has ceased to act for the party, and the party has not given notice of change of solicitor or notice of intention to act in person in accordance with the provisions of rule 2, any other party to the proceedings or (where the solicitor has ceased to act) the solicitor may, on notice to be served on the first-mentioned party, personally, or by letter addressed to his last-known place of residence, unless the Court otherwise directs, apply to the Court for an order declaring that the solicitor has ceased to be the solicitor acting for the first-mentioned party in the proceedings, and the Court may make an order accordingly. (2) Where such order shall have been made the party or the solicitor who applied therefor shall forthwith give a notice to the same effect as the order, and the provisions of rule 2 as to filing and service shall apply thereto with the necessary modifications and subject to any direction in such order as to service on the first-mentioned party. (3) Where the party or solicitor who applied for such order shall have complied with the said provisions then, if the first-mentioned party does not appoint another solicitor or give such an address for service as is required of a party acting in person, and comply with the provisions of rule 2, any documents in respect of which personal service is not requisite may be served on the said party by being filed with the proper officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons required before filing an objection to a licence application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection—* 2. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 70.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d001a1a1-4aca-48ea-a1f5-647dd3990559/Summons (objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence) - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act 1860 No. 70.1.docx/docx/1) upon the applicant for such licence at least seven days prior to the sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the special exemption order referenced in the court''s order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 71.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 71.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3aa71ae-b309-4ac4-83a0-cace9fe92db7/Special exemption order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927, section 5 as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008, section 10 No. 71.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing a court order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 72 - General Exemption Orders - Court: District # Order 72: General Exemption Orders**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Does an order under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927 remain in effect until the next Annual Licensing Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *In force to Annual Licensing Court* \*(6) Every such order shall, unless withdrawn in pursuance of subsection (6) of section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), or expressed to expire sooner, remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 73 related to a specific court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 73 - Exemptions for special events - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration regarding the service of the notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order to be issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f853200-09a8-468c-b759-f0ce1443579d/Exemption order for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 10 No. 73.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge the notice of the application with the Clerk prior to the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of Notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order to be issued based on a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cce42bdc-661a-4032-b000-1eb6b0c895f6/Order revoking exemption for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962 No. 73.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration regarding service of the notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (5) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Order of Court to be issued in a specific format if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4eeab324-ae33-4e1d-b0f8-9c5018e0f6c9/Exemption order for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s Day - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 No. 74.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice of the application required to be given at least ten days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper Notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order specifically about exemptions for unlicensed businesses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"# Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an exemption order be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence (not being a licence granted by virtue of paragraph (2) of section 2 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1902](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1902/act/18/enacted/en/print.html)) in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order to open or keep open the premises for the purpose of carrying on any business other than the sale or supply of intoxicating liquor during any one period and not exceeding forty-five minutes in duration on the mornings of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day, pursuant to section 17 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order to be issued based on a specific form if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2eb82a05-a935-4d0f-8971-227985d82fbd/Order permitting the opening and keeping open of premises for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to publish a notice in a local newspaper before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice of application to be submitted along with other documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order to revoke permission related to business operations on specific days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb242f64-64bc-4749-9446-79f888d75e0d/Order revoking an order permitting premises to open or keep open for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb242f64-64bc-4749-9446-79f888d75e0d/Order revoking an order permitting premises to open or keep open for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 76 - Occasional licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence to be issued in a specific format if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 76.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 76.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afadc1ab-9522-4564-8435-e48214152f9a/Occasional licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962 No. 76.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on granting occasional licences after 10', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time after the hour of ten o''clock in the evening"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hours* \*2. An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time after the hour of ten o''clock in the evening or before the hour of eight o''clock in the morning unless the event to which the licence relates is a dinner or dance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is Christmas Day listed as a prohibited day for granting occasional licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited days* †3.[1] An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge hear an application and grant an occasional license at any sitting of the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *In certain cases may be granted at any sitting* 4. A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11 (10)]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11(5) as amended by [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2000 10)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/17/enacted/en/print) and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) 4(a)) [1] Order 76 rule 3 and note substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to interim transfers of licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (3) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26eb9350-0ca7-4721-9ac0-2038eb75af01/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence No. 77.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the person to whom the license is transferred continue the business authorized by the license for a period after the transfer?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to trade until Annual Licensing Court* (5) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court transfer a license to someone other than the executor or administrator?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Extension of power to temporarily transfer licences* 2. (1) The power conferred on the Court under the Licensing Acts to transfer temporarily an on-licence or an off-licence upon the death of the holder of the licence shall, pursuant to section 34 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), include power to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for trading after the transfer of a license?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the licence is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *To trade until Annual Licensing Court* (2) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the licence is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a licence be transferred to another person by an application to the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such licence may, on the application by the nominator of the transferee to the Court at any sitting thereof for the court area within which the premises are situate, be transferred by endorsement made by the Court on the licence or, if the licence is not available, on a copy thereof, to such other person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) as the nominator may nominate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to transfer to another person* (3) Where the licence has been transferred, such licence may, on the application by the nominator of the transferee to the Court at any sitting thereof for the court area within which the premises are situate, be transferred by endorsement made by the Court on the licence or, if the licence is not available, on a copy thereof, to such other person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) as the nominator may nominate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 77.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce8c1245-89c9-42c4-802a-9e7c5db968d2/Notice of application for ad-interim transfer of a licence to person other than the owner - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960 No. 77.2.docx/docx/1) or [77.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b843971a-fcf7-4234-a38c-fdc2fee8c320/Notice of application for a certificate for the renewal of a licence in cases where the owner has ceased to carry on business - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 No. 77.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the notice to be given to the Garda Síochána officer and the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 77.5 used when renewing a licence that has expired within one year?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the licence has expired and the application is made within one year after such expiry, the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of renewal certificate* (5) Where the licence has expired and the application is made within one year after such expiry, the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court hear applications and grant temporary transfers under special circumstances?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Special circumstances* 4.[1] The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District. [1] Order 77 rule 4 inserted by [S.I. 123 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/123/made/en/print?q 123&years 1998), effective 28 April 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to transfers of licences held by nominees?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the endorsement of transfer by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 78.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (3) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 78.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/892731dd-d4b4-42fd-a72e-da4fe0bba592/Form of endorsement of transfer of licence held by nominee No. 78.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 79 related to certificates of transfer in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 79 - Certificates of transfer - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 79 - Certificates of transfer - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk prior to the Annual Licensing Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk for retention by him or her, at least seven days before the date of such Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice etc* (4) A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk for retention by him or her, at least seven days before the date of such Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is the applicant required to attend the Annual Licensing Court in person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall attend in person (unless the Court is satisfied that there is good reason for his or her non-attendance) at the Annual Licensing Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applicant to attend in person* 2. The applicant shall attend in person (unless the Court is satisfied that there is good reason for his or her non-attendance) at the Annual Licensing Court and present himself or herself for examination as to his or her general character, possession of the premises, and any other questions which the Court may think fit to put to the said applicant. 3. The applicant shall produce in Court any document upon which he or she grounds the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate issuance conditional on the production of certain documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may grant such application subject to the subsequent production of such document. The appropriate certificate shall not be given to such applicant until such document is produced."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Grant of certificate subject to production of documents* 4. Where the applicant has not at the time obtained or is for any other reason unable to produce any document upon which he or she relies, the Court may grant such application subject to the subsequent production of such document. The appropriate certificate shall not be given to such applicant until such document is produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party to an action request a statement of the names and details of co-partners from the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own - Court: Circuit 1. Any two or more persons claiming or being liable as co-partners and carrying on business within the jurisdiction may sue or be sued in the name of the respective firms, if any, of which such persons were co-partners at the time of the accruing of the cause of action and in the names of such persons; and any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct. 2. When a Civil Bill is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall, on demand in writing by or on behalf of any defendant, forthwith declare in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. If the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall fail to comply with such demand, all proceedings in the action may, upon an application for that purpose, be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct. When the names of the partners are so declared, the action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Civil Bill be served on a partner''s representative if the partner is out of the jurisdiction?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such service shall be deemed good service on the firm so sued, whether any of the members thereof are out of the jurisdiction or not"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm under Rule 1 of this Order, the Civil Bill shall be served either upon any one or more of the partners personally or at the principal place, within the jurisdiction, of the business of the partnership, upon any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there; and, subject to these rules, such service shall be deemed good service on the firm so sued, whether any of the members thereof are out of the jurisdiction or not, and no leave to issue a Civil Bill against them shall be necessary; provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the plaintiff before the commencement of the action, the Civil Bill shall be served on every person within the jurisdiction sought to be made liable. 4. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, they shall appear individually in their own names; but all subsequent proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm. 5. Debts owing by a firm carrying on business within the jurisdiction may be attached under [Order 38]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-38-Circuit-Attachment-of-debts-by-garnishee), although one or more members of such firm may be resident abroad, provided that any person having the control or management of the partnership business, or any member of the firm within the jurisdiction, is served with the garnishee order. An appearance by any member pursuant to an order shall be a sufficient appearance by the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff sue someone in a business name that is not registered?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963] may be sued in such name or style;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '6. The above Rules shall apply to actions between a firm and one or more of its members, and to actions between firms having one or more members in common, provided such firm or firms carry on business within the jurisdiction, but no execution shall be issued in such actions without leave of the Judge after motion on notice to the party so to be affected, and on an application for leave to issue such execution, all such accounts and inquiries may be directed to be taken and made and directions given as may be just. 7. Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in such name or style; and the plaintiff in such cases may apply by Notice of Motion to the Court for an Order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing such business to furnish the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time of the accruing of the cause of action was carrying on the business as aforesaid, in such manner and verified upon oath or otherwise as the Court may direct. 8. In all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies service of a Civil Bill or any other document may be effected by service in the manner provided by these Rules on the person carrying on business or on such person who at the time of the service appears to have control or to be managing the said business, at the place where the said business is carried on. Such service shall be deemed to be good service upon the person sued whether or not that person is out of the jurisdiction and no leave to issue the Civil Bill or other document shall be necessary. 9. In so far as the nature of the case will permit, all rules relating to the proceedings against firms shall apply to all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to tendering of evidence in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence - Court: District # **Order 8: Tendering of Evidence******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Master renew a summons beyond the initial twelve-month period?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"but if any defendant therein named shall not have been served therewith, the plaintiff may apply before the expiration of twelve months to the Master for leave to renew the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Renewal of Summons - Court: Superior 1. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) No original summons shall be in force for more than twelve months from the day of the date thereof, including the day of such date; but if any defendant therein named shall not have been served therewith, the plaintiff may apply before the expiration of twelve months to the Master for leave to renew the summons. (2) The Master on an application made under sub-rule (1), if satisfied that reasonable efforts have been made to serve such defendant, or for other good reason, may order that the original or concurrent summons be renewed for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive. (3) After the expiration of twelve months, and notwithstanding that an order may have been made under sub-rule (2), application to extend time for leave to renew the summons shall be made to the Court. (4) The Court on an application under sub-rule (3) may order a renewal of the original or concurrent summons for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive where satisfied that there are special circumstances which justify an extension, such circumstances to be stated in the order. (5) The summons shall, where an order of renewal has been made, be renewed by being stamped with the date of the day, month and year of such renewal; such stamp to be provided and kept for that purpose in the Central Office and to be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer, upon delivery to him by the plaintiff or his solicitor of a memorandum in the [Form No. 4 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon1); and a summons so renewed shall remain in force and be available to prevent the operation of any statute whereby a time for the commencement of the action may be limited and for all other purposes from the date of the issuing of the original summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is a defendant allowed to request a motion to set aside an order after a summons renewal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any defendant shall be at liberty before entering an appearance to serve notice of motion to set aside such order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '2. In any case where a summons has been renewed on an parte application, any defendant shall be at liberty before entering an appearance to serve notice of motion to set aside such order. 3. The production of a summons purporting to be marked with a stamp showing the same to have been renewed in the matter aforesaid, shall be sufficient evidence of its having been so renewed and of the commencement of the action as of the first date of such renewed summons for all purposes. 4. Where a summons, of which the production is necessary, has been destroyed or lost, the Court upon being satisfied of the destruction or loss, and of the correctness of a copy thereof, may order that such copy shall be sealed and served in lieu of the original summons. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 8 rule 1 substituted by 482 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/482/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2019.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the order related to a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 referred to as the Act of 1986 in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"\"the Act of 1986\" means the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 (No. 26 of 1986)]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 (No. 26 of 1986)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1988**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1988 (No. 16 of 1988)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can objections to the renewal of certain licenses be made at the last sitting of the court in June?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the objection is made to the renewal of a wholesale beer dealer''s licence or any other off-licence which, by virtue of section 49 of the Finance (1909-10) Act, 1910, expires on the thirtieth day of June each year, such objection may be made at the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (2) of this rule, where an objection is made under section 4 (6) of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html) to the renewal of - - (a) an on-licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor, - a special restaurant licence granted under Part of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - a licence or licences for the sale of spirits or beer in retail quantities for consumption off the premises where sold, it shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate. (2) Where the objection is made to the renewal of a wholesale beer dealer''s licence or any other off-licence which, by virtue of section 49 of the [Finance (1909-10) Act, 1910](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1910/act/8/enacted/en/html), expires on the thirtieth day of June each year, such objection may be made at the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the notice of objection to be served on the licence holder at least twenty-one days before the court sitting?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice shall be served upon the holder of the licence or licences attached to the premises to which the objection relates at least twenty-one days before the date of sitting of the said Annual Licensing Court or other sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 80.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dc936958-b2db-44be-99ed-105b826761d1/Notice of objection to renewal of intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986 No. 80.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the objector or solicitor for the objector. (2) The notice shall be served upon the holder of the licence or licences attached to the premises to which the objection relates at least twenty-one days before the date of sitting of the said Annual Licensing Court or other sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing. When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk as soon as possible but not later than seven days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Does the Clerk need to notify the Collector of Customs and Excise when receiving a notice of objection?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the Form 80.2, Schedule the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Collector of & etc.* 4. Upon receipt of the notice of objection the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the [Form 80.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7648106-7b2f-45a2-a586-c857c9c5b515/Notification of the lodgment of a notice of objection to the renewal of an intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986. No. 80.2.docx/docx/1)) the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly and, where the objector is not a member of the Garda Síochána, the Clerk shall also notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order related to the objection hearing specified in Form 80.3?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 80.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of the Court* 5. (1) The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 80.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85bd770e-8620-490f-8f68-407e7d125349/Order on hearing objection to the renewal of intoxicating liquor licence No. 80.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the Clerk to send a copy of the order to the Collector of Customs and Excise if the Court''s objection is allowed and no appeal is filed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"(2) Where the Court allows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certified copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to send copy to Collector & (2) Where the Court allows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certified copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to send a renewal certificate or its copy to the Collector after the Court disallows the objection?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to send a renewal cert. (or copy) to Collector* (3) Where the Court disallows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence in the [Form 80. 4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1).(or copy thereof).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to inform the Collector of Customs and Excise about an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such Clerk shall forthwith send notice to this effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to notify Collector in cases of appeal* 6. Where notice of an appeal against any order of the Court to which this Order relates is at any time lodged with the Clerk, such Clerk shall forthwith send notice to this effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents required by the Order be sent via registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Documents which are required by this Order to be sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise may be sent by registered post"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mode of service* 7. Documents which are required by this Order to be sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise may be sent by registered post or, may be delivered to the office of the said Collector where appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for renewing a six-day license?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the Form 80.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Forms of renewal certificate* 8. The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the [Form 80.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1). Where a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) such certificate shall be in the [Form 77.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when making an application under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form 80.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for redress under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003* 10.[1] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be made to the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court for the court district in which the relevant licensed premises are situated. Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 80.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83c69ddd-f2d6-4abd-813d-2c9ed6078f15/Notice of application - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 section 19 [section 23] No. 80.5.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the said [Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 80.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6c622bf-fec0-4217-9967-474cb6667497/Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 No. 80.6.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 80 rule 10 inserted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 81 - Annual licensing court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Annual Licensing Court held on the last sitting day of the court in September?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in the month of September each year."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 81 - Annual licensing court - Court: District 1. A Judge of the District Court shall hold a court, to be known as the Annual Licensing Court, in each court area in the Judge''s district on the day of the last sitting of the Court for that court area for the transaction of the business of the Court exercising its summary jurisdiction held in the month of September each year. 2. Every such Annual Licensing Court shall hear and determine - all such applications made to it for certificates, licenses, orders, or renewals thereof, and objections to the grant or renewal of such certificates, licences or orders, as are provided for in [Orders 63]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-63-District-Auctioneers-and-house-agents) to [89]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-89-District-Wildlife) of these [Rules]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]C07733B1-CAA0-4F89-8468-D48198AE2F9F?page 3#targetSearch) and are required to be made at the Annual Licensing Court; - any other application, objection or other matter which is required by statute or by Rules of Court to be made or brought at that court; and the Judge may adjourn any such court from time to time as circumstances may deem it necessary. 3. For the purposes of this Order the day of the last sitting of the Court in the month of September in the Dublin Metropolitan District shall be that sitting held on the last Thursday in that month each year.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk responsible for entering details about licences in the Register of Licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk shall keep a book which shall be known as the Register of Licences and shall enter or cause to be entered in such Register particulars of all licences for the sale of intoxicating liquors existing in respect of premises situate within the court area"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 82 - Register of licences - Court: District 1. The Clerk shall keep a book which shall be known as the Register of Licences ([Form 82.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e6f0b62-d97f-4918-9de6-47dbac268070/Register of licences No. 82.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall enter or cause to be entered in such Register particulars of all licences for the sale of intoxicating liquors existing in respect of premises situate within the court area and of all renewals, transfers and other proceedings affecting the said licences or any of them and shall retain all maps, plans or other documents lodged which relate to such licences or premises.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for license holders to provide a written note to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of particulars of licensed premises* 2. Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing ([Form 82.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f3b3e1c3-089d-43ee-8bf6-5acff952358e/Notice describing licensed premises No. 82.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the holder, setting forth the holders full name and address and description and location of the house or premises in which intoxicating liquors are licensed to be sold and the full name and address of the owner of the said house or premises in accordance with the provisions of section 10 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1833/act/68/enacted/en/print.html), as amended. 3.[1] Where a temporary closure order is made pursuant to section 36A(2) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) , the order shall be in the [Form 82.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec1c77e6-8976-4a4f-a108-36851c4e44d5/Temporary Closure Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988 No. 82.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 82 rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2006), effective 9 May 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to a specific court level?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Equal Status Act 2000 mentioned in the definitions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**the Act of 2000**” means the [Equal Status Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) (No. 8 of 2000);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1.[1] In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (4 Edw. 7. 9); "**the Act of 1924**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) (No. 62 of 1924); "**the Act of 1927**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (No. 15 of 1927); "**the Act of 1962**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1962); "**the Act of 1988**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 1988); "**licensing year"** means a period of twelve months ending on the thirtieth day of September in any year; "**registered club**" means a club holding a certificate of registration in force at the time. “**the Act of 2000**” means the [Equal Status Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) (No. 8 of 2000); “**Determination Order**” means an Order made under sub-section (6) or sub-section (15) of section 8 of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)[.](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Registrar of Clubs also referred to as the clerk in the context of the court area where the club is located?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"For the purposes of the Act the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Registrar of Clubs* 2. (1) For the purposes of the Act the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Registrar of Clubs to maintain a register?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every such Registrar of Clubs shall keep a register in which shall be entered the name of each club situate within his or her court area to which a certificate of registration is granted under the provisions of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to keep a register* (2) Every such Registrar of Clubs shall keep a register in which shall be entered the name of each club situate within his or her court area to which a certificate of registration is granted under the provisions of the Act and, where appropriate, the further particulars required by the Act. # **Application for certificate of registration**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the superintendent of the Garda Síochána notified about the application for an original certificate of registration?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to notify Garda Supt.* 3. (1) Where the secretary of a club desiring an original certificate of registration lodges with the registrar, pursuant to subsection (1) of section 2 of the Act, the documents mentioned in that subsection, the registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána in like manner as prescribed in rule 4 (6) hereof in the case of an application for the renewal of such a certificate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the registrar to send documents to the County Registrar after ten days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to transmit file to Registrar* (2) After the expiration of ten days from the date of the said lodgment the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the registrar required to issue a certificate of registration upon entering the particulars in the register?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"and shall thereupon issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted - to record particulars and issue certificate* (3) Upon the return of the file together with notification from the County Registrar of the granting of the application the registrar shall enter in the register of clubs the particulars required by section 1 (1) of the Act, and shall thereupon issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1). # **Renewal of certificates, Objections thereto**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to publish the notice in a daily newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also publish the notice of such application once in a daily newspaper circulating in the locality"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (2) The applicant shall also publish the notice of such application once in a daily newspaper circulating in the locality and shall, when the notice has been published, lodge a copy of the newspaper with the registrar.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate signed by Peace Commissioners required with the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a certificate in the [Form 83.2, Schedule signed by two Peace Commissioners for the district in which the club premises are situated"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Documents to accompany application* (3) Such application for renewal shall be accompanied by— - (a) two copies of the rules of the club, - a list containing the names and addresses of the officials and committee of management or governing body and the names of the members, and - a certificate in the [Form 83.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f990d829-5435-4e71-8e05-2a7d0cb17fdd/Certificate to accompany application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.2.docx/docx/1), signed by two Peace Commissioners for the district in which the club premises are situated, and where such premises are not owned by the club, the certificate shall be signed by the owner of such premises or, where the owner is under any legal disability, by the legal representative of the owner. The application form shall be stamped to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee (if any) required by law to be paid in respect of such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is compliance with specific sections of the Registration of Clubs Acts necessary for club registration?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904] to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Club rules qualifying for registration* (4) In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of - section 4 of the Act, as amended by section 42 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), and - section 56 (which relates to prohibited hours for the supplying for consumption on club premises of excisable liquor) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 26 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to be aware of the Fire Services Act, 1981?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) (No. 30 of 1981) shall apply to every such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the registrar required to send a notice to the Garda superintendent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Registrar to notify Garda Supt.* (6) The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12f2f2e8-bfb6-48b7-a784-8509ed14ce18/Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.3.docx/docx/1), together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can objections to the renewal of a certificate be considered if they do not fall under the specified grounds?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988], or section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924], or section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Objections to grant or renewal of certificate* 7.(1) It shall be competent for the superintendent of the Garda Síochána on receiving notice of an application given as aforesaid, and for any person resident in the parish in which the club premises are situated, to lodge objections to the grant of the certificate on any of the grounds of objection specified in the Act, and it shall be competent for any person to lodge objections to the renewal of the certificate on any such grounds. (2)[2] The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in - section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html), or - section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when lodging an objection to the grant or renewal of a certificate of registration?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An objection to the grant or renewal of a certificate of registration of a club shall be by notice in the [Form 83.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (3) An objection to the grant or renewal of a certificate of registration of a club shall be by notice in the [Form 83.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f82d20e0-58df-41fc-8ddf-c1ac5865cb3f/Notice of objection to the grant-renewal of certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.5.docx/docx/1), signed by the objector or solicitor for the objector, and shall be lodged with the registrar within ten days of the receipt or publication of notice of the application, and at the same time a copy of such notice of objection shall be sent to the secretary of the club applying for the grant of renewal of the certificate. When the superintendent of the Garda Síochána is not an objector, the registrar shall give notice of the lodgment of the objection or objections to the said superintendent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the registrar responsible for issuing a certificate of registration when the court grants the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted registrar to record particulars and issue certificate* (5) If, upon hearing the application and the objection, the Court grants the application, the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Does a certificate of registration issued under the Registration of Clubs Acts last indefinitely?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"A certificate of registration duly issued by a Registrar of Clubs under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904] to 1988 shall, as provided in section 3 (3) of the Act (as amended by the first schedule to the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 — No. 26 of 1986), and subject to the other provisions of the Act, remain in force until the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the club premises are situated held next after the grant of the application for such certificate, and shall then expire."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Duration of certificate* 8. (1) A certificate of registration duly issued by a Registrar of Clubs under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 shall, as provided in section 3 (3) of the Act (as amended by the first schedule to the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 — No. 26 of 1986), and subject to the other provisions of the Act, remain in force until the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the club premises are situated held next after the grant of the application for such certificate, and shall then expire.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can a current certificate remain valid beyond three months if the court decides to extend it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- extension pending Court''s decision* (2) Notwithstanding the provisions of the Act as to the duration of certifcates, where a renewal has been applied for the current certificate shall remain in force pending the final decision of the Court, but not exceeding three months unless the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about club authorizations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**Club Authorisations**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners* 9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an authorisation under section 21(1) of the Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 21 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924] as amended by section 8 of the [Act of 1962], may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 10. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 21 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) as amended by section 8 of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice of the application required to be served on the superintendent of the Garda Síochána before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the authorisation granted through a specific form when the application is successful?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted, the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb19bab5-78a1-4b4c-add6-c84979d9c518/Club authorisation - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 - Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 section 21 (as amended) No. 83.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a limit to the number of authorizations a club can receive in a licensing year?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Not more than fifteen such authorisations shall be granted to any club in any licensing year."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Not more than 15 per year* (4) Not more than fifteen such authorisations shall be granted to any club in any licensing year. # **Authorisations for special events**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an authorisation under section 14(1) of the Act of 1962 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 11. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice of the application required to be served on the superintendent of the Garda Síochana?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochana within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochana within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of an application for a Determination Order required to be served on the club at least seven days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of an application for a Determination Order shall be in the Form 83.9, Schedule a copy of such notice shall be served upon the club (or in the case of an application under section 8(15), upon the original applicant) in the manner prescribed by section 8(5) of the Act of 2000 not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of* (3) Where the application is granted, the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cae20262-a429-4ae4-ad7a-ba43edccca5c/Club authorisation for special event - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 No. 83.8.docx/docx/1). 12.[4] An application pursuant to section 8(3) or section 8(15) of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) for a Determination Order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the club is situated. Notice of an application for a Determination Order shall be in the [Form 83.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49d0a221-efe7-4f8c-a0cf-433cef03e507/Notice Of Application For Determination Order - Registration Of Clubs Acts 1904 To 2000 - Equal Status Act 2000 section 8(3) - 8(15) No. 83.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule a copy of such notice shall be served upon the club (or in the case of an application under section 8(15), upon the original applicant) in the manner prescribed by section 8(5) of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct. A Determination Order shall be in the [Form 83.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/16eccbad-631b-4b73-9784-14924de97dd6/Determination Order - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 2000 - Equal Status Act 2000 section 8(3) - 8(15) No. 83.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk shall transmit a copy of any Determination Order to the Minister for Justice, Equality and Law Reform. [1] Order 83 rule 1 amended by [S.I. 161 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/161/made/en/print?q 161&years 2006), effective 8 May 2006 [2] Order 83 sub-rule (2) of rule 7 substituted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005 [3] Order 83 rule 9 deleted by [S.I. 198 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/198/made/en/print?q 198&years 2005), effective 6 April 2005 [4] Order 83 rule 12 inserted by [S.I. 161 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/161/made/en/print?q 161&years 2006), amended by [S.I. 397 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/397/made/en/print?q 397&years 2006), effective 25 August 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to child care?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Child care"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84 - Child care - Court: District # **Order 84: Child Care******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Are court proceedings under certain parts of the Act held in private?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the Act of 2001), Part IVB (inserted by the Act of 2001) or Part of the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (No. 17 of 1991); “**the Act of 2001**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2001); “**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency established under section 7 of the [Child and Family Agency Act 2013](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/act/40/enacted/en/html) (No. 40 of 2013); “**child**” means a person under the age of eighteen year other than a person who is or has been married; “**parents**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 2(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). 2.[3] (1) Proceedings under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion may allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing. (2) The Judge may, if he or she thinks it proper to do so, order any witness who is not a party to the proceedings to leave the court either until his or her evidence is required or after his or her evidence has been given. (3) Proceedings in the Court under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be as informal as is practicable and consistent with the administration of justice. Neither Judges hearing and determining such proceedings nor barristers nor solicitors appearing in such proceedings shall wear wigs or gowns. (4)[4] Unless otherwise provided in this Order or permitted by the Court, all applications under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application specifying the order or other relief sought in the application, the provisions of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) relied on and the grounds of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be served by leaving it with a relative of the person?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode with any relative of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age and who is believed to reside there with him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of documents* 3. (1) A document required by these Rules to be served shall, subject to paragraphs (2) and (3) hereof, be served upon the person to whom it is directed— - (a) by delivering to him or her a copy thereof or, - if he or she cannot be conveniently met with, by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode with any relative of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age and who is believed to reside there with him or her, or by leaving it with the person in charge of the house or premises of such residence or abode, or, - by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her place of business with any agent, clerk, employee or servant of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age, or - by sending a copy thereof by ordinary prepaid post in an envelope addressed to him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode or at his or her place of business. (2)[7] A document may be served on the Agency or any other statutory board or body or on an unincorporated society by leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the Agency, or of the board, body or society concerned at its principal office or by sending such copy by ordinary prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the Agency or to the board, body or society concerned at such principal office. (3) The Court may, if for special reason in any particular case it considers it proper to do so, deem the service actually effected to be good and sufficient service, even though it was not effected in accordance with the provisions of this Order. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge the original notice or summons along with a statutory declaration after it has been served?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgment for hearing* 4. When a notice of application, summons or notice of appeal issued under this Order has been served, the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing specific proceedings under Part III of an Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under Part III of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part III of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an emergency care order application be heard and made without prior notice to both parties?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the Judge may deem sufficient the notice of the application actually given to the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an application for an emergency care order may be heard and made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the notice of application ([Form 84.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/578b4525-2f2f-4f59-a65a-9967f0b17c40/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 12 (4) No. 84.1.docx/docx/1) or [84.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d188ed27-41b1-4b7a-8f08-b83aa6a4625c/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is not in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13(1) No. 84.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be) duly completed; - an application for an emergency care order may be heard and an order may be made thereon elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court; - the Judge may deem sufficient the notice of the application actually given to the respondent. (3) An application to which sub-rule (2) applies shall be made on affidavit unless the Judge permits the application to be heard on oral evidence because of the exceptional urgency of the case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an emergency care order application be made to any judge if the assigned judge is not immediately available?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, such Judge is not immediately available, the application may be made to any judge of the District Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 6.[9] (1) An application for an emergency care order under section 13(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) must be made to the Judge assigned to the district in which the child resides or is for the time being. Where, however, such Judge is not immediately available, the application may be made to any judge of the District Court. (2) An emergency care order shall be in the [Form 84.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85df8e22-6926-41e5-af5c-2d4b7d31c55a/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.3.docx/docx/1) or [84.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the order to be served on a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, upon a person acting in loco parentis, together with, as the case may be, a copy of the affidavit which grounded the application and copies of any exhibits (unless previously served on that person) or a copy of the note of oral evidence mentioned in rule 2(5). (3) A warrant issued under section 13(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the purpose of executing such an Order may be in the [Form 84.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/14aa135a-515f-470d-836c-d5822ddad575/Warrant to execute an emergency care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 13(3) No. 84.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule (4) An appeal from an emergency care order shall not stay the operation of the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for directions under section 13(7) can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, otherwise than at the hearing of an application for an emergency care order, application is made under section 13 (7) of [the Act] for the Judge''s directions, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.6] upon the Agency, the parents of the child or either of them, a person acting in loco parentis, or any other person, as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions under section 13 (7)* 7. (1)[10] Where, otherwise than at the hearing of an application for an emergency care order, application is made under section 13 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Judge''s directions, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency, the parents of the child or either of them, a person acting in loco parentis, or any other person, as appropriate. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application An order giving directions on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be served upon each person directly affected by the Order. (2) An application to vary or discharge a direction given under the said section 13 (7) (a) shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1). Schedule The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1) Schedule which shall be served as prescribed in the said paragraph (1). 8. It shall not be necessary in any notice or application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) or in any order made under that section to name the child if such name is unknown. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required before issuing a notice for an interim care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act] for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act], be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10] Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim care order* 9. [11](1) An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d768e869-970c-4538-8b75-6367c62c667b/Notice of application for an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.10.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and any other person directly affected by the Order. (2) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in rule 27) for the purpose of executing an interim care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 84.12 required before applying for an extension of an interim care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 17(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the Form 84.12"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) An application under section 17(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9bce7aa4-5c98-4d2e-8420-814bd2b699f4/Notice of application for an extension of an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (2) No. 84.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/48eea238-5f1b-4de7-959b-46b81c6a7683/Order extending the period of an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (2) No. 84.13.docx/docx/1)Schedule and may, where appropriate, be added to or endorsed on the interim care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for a care order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 18 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a care order in respect of a child who resides or is found in its area shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Care Order* 10.(1)[12] An application by the Agency under section 18 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a care order in respect of a child who resides or is found in its area shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b9979d0-2a7f-44ec-9965-d27d8023b8b3/Notice of application for a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.14.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the care order required to be served upon the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall cause the said Order to be served upon the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* (2) A care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said Order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a restriction on when an occasional license can be granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time after the hour of ten o''clock in the evening or before the hour of eight o''clock in the morning"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hours* \*2. An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time after the hour of ten o''clock in the evening or before the hour of eight o''clock in the morning unless the event to which the licence relates is a dinner or dance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is Christmas Day mentioned as a prohibited day for granting occasional licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited days* †3.[1] An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge hear an application and grant an occasional licence at any sitting of the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *In certain cases may be granted at any sitting* 4. A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11 (10)]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11(5) as amended by [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2000 10)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/17/enacted/en/print) and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) 4(a)) [1] Order 76 rule 3 and note substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to interim transfers of licences in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the endorsement of transfer by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (3) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26eb9350-0ca7-4721-9ac0-2038eb75af01/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence No. 77.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Does the transfer of a license allow the new holder to continue trading for a period after the transfer?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to trade until Annual Licensing Court* (5) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court transfer a license to someone other than the executor or administrator after the holder''s death?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Extension of power to temporarily transfer licences* 2. (1) The power conferred on the Court under the Licensing Acts to transfer temporarily an on-licence or an off-licence upon the death of the holder of the licence shall, pursuant to section 34 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), include power to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person continue trading under a transferred license beyond one month after the transfer?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *To trade until Annual Licensing Court* (2) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the licence is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be given to the Garda Síochána officer and the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the renewal certificate granted by the Court supposed to follow a specific form if the application is made within one year after the licence''s expiry?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of renewal certificate* (5) Where the licence has expired and the application is made within one year after such expiry, the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court hear applications for temporary transfer under special circumstances?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Special circumstances* 4.[1] The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District. [1] Order 77 rule 4 inserted by [S.I. 123 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/123/made/en/print?q 123&years 1998), effective 28 April 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a federal court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 79 - Certificates of transfer - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'Is the certificate issued when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* 5. Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 79.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f0851cc5-0388-4c62-9757-36334b739c1e/Certificate of transfer of a licence - Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833 section 6 - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 29 No. 79.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff in a case involving co-partnership request a statement of the names and details of the co-partners from the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own - Court: Circuit 1. Any two or more persons claiming or being liable as co-partners and carrying on business within the jurisdiction may sue or be sued in the name of the respective firms, if any, of which such persons were co-partners at the time of the accruing of the cause of action and in the names of such persons; and any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct. 2. When a Civil Bill is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall, on demand in writing by or on behalf of any defendant, forthwith declare in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. If the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall fail to comply with such demand, all proceedings in the action may, upon an application for that purpose, be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct. When the names of the partners are so declared, the action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Civil Bill be served on a partner if the partnership has been dissolved before the action?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the plaintiff before the commencement of the action, the Civil Bill shall be served on every person within the jurisdiction sought to be made liable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm under Rule 1 of this Order, the Civil Bill shall be served either upon any one or more of the partners personally or at the principal place, within the jurisdiction, of the business of the partnership, upon any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there; and, subject to these rules, such service shall be deemed good service on the firm so sued, whether any of the members thereof are out of the jurisdiction or not, and no leave to issue a Civil Bill against them shall be necessary; provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the plaintiff before the commencement of the action, the Civil Bill shall be served on every person within the jurisdiction sought to be made liable. 4. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, they shall appear individually in their own names; but all subsequent proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm. 5. Debts owing by a firm carrying on business within the jurisdiction may be attached under [Order 38]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-38-Circuit-Attachment-of-debts-by-garnishee), although one or more members of such firm may be resident abroad, provided that any person having the control or management of the partnership business, or any member of the firm within the jurisdiction, is served with the garnishee order. An appearance by any member pursuant to an order shall be a sufficient appearance by the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a plaintiff sue someone using a business name that is not their own if it''s not registered?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in such name or style;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '6. The above Rules shall apply to actions between a firm and one or more of its members, and to actions between firms having one or more members in common, provided such firm or firms carry on business within the jurisdiction, but no execution shall be issued in such actions without leave of the Judge after motion on notice to the party so to be affected, and on an application for leave to issue such execution, all such accounts and inquiries may be directed to be taken and made and directions given as may be just. 7. Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in such name or style; and the plaintiff in such cases may apply by Notice of Motion to the Court for an Order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing such business to furnish the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time of the accruing of the cause of action was carrying on the business as aforesaid, in such manner and verified upon oath or otherwise as the Court may direct. 8. In all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies service of a Civil Bill or any other document may be effected by service in the manner provided by these Rules on the person carrying on business or on such person who at the time of the service appears to have control or to be managing the said business, at the place where the said business is carried on. Such service shall be deemed to be good service upon the person sued whether or not that person is out of the jurisdiction and no leave to issue the Civil Bill or other document shall be necessary. 9. In so far as the nature of the case will permit, all rules relating to the proceedings against firms shall apply to all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defendant request to set aside an order after a summons has been renewed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any defendant shall be at liberty before entering an appearance to serve notice of motion to set aside such order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '2. In any case where a summons has been renewed on an parte application, any defendant shall be at liberty before entering an appearance to serve notice of motion to set aside such order. 3. The production of a summons purporting to be marked with a stamp showing the same to have been renewed in the matter aforesaid, shall be sufficient evidence of its having been so renewed and of the commencement of the action as of the first date of such renewed summons for all purposes. 4. Where a summons, of which the production is necessary, has been destroyed or lost, the Court upon being satisfied of the destruction or loss, and of the correctness of a copy thereof, may order that such copy shall be sealed and served in lieu of the original summons. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 8 rule 1 substituted by 482 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/482/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2019.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about objections to the renewal of liquor licences?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to notify the Collector of Customs and Excise when receiving a notice of objection?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Upon receipt of the notice of objection the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the Form 80.2, Schedule the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Collector of & etc.* 4. Upon receipt of the notice of objection the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the [Form 80.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7648106-7b2f-45a2-a586-c857c9c5b515/Notification of the lodgment of a notice of objection to the renewal of an intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986. No. 80.2.docx/docx/1)) the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly and, where the objector is not a member of the Garda Síochána, the Clerk shall also notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to send a renewal certificate or its copy to the Collector when the Court disallows the objection?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to send a renewal cert. (or copy) to Collector* (3) Where the Court disallows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence in the [Form 80. 4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1).(or copy thereof).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for renewing a six-day licence?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the Form 80.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Forms of renewal certificate* 8. The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the [Form 80.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1). Where a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) such certificate shall be in the [Form 77.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for an order under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 required to be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form 80.5, Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for redress under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003* 10.[1] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be made to the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court for the court district in which the relevant licensed premises are situated. Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 80.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83c69ddd-f2d6-4abd-813d-2c9ed6078f15/Notice of application - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 section 19 [section 23] No. 80.5.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the said [Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 80.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6c622bf-fec0-4217-9967-474cb6667497/Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 No. 80.6.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 80 rule 10 inserted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for license holders to provide information about their premises within ten days of obtaining a license?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of particulars of licensed premises* 2. Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing ([Form 82.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f3b3e1c3-089d-43ee-8bf6-5acff952358e/Notice describing licensed premises No. 82.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the holder, setting forth the holders full name and address and description and location of the house or premises in which intoxicating liquors are licensed to be sold and the full name and address of the owner of the said house or premises in accordance with the provisions of section 10 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1833/act/68/enacted/en/print.html), as amended. 3.[1] Where a temporary closure order is made pursuant to section 36A(2) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) , the order shall be in the [Form 82.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec1c77e6-8976-4a4f-a108-36851c4e44d5/Temporary Closure Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988 No. 82.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 82 rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2006), effective 9 May 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Registrar of Clubs also referred to as the clerk in the context of the club''s location?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Registrar of Clubs* 2. (1) For the purposes of the Act the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is it the responsibility of the registrar to transmit documents to the County Registrar after ten days?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to transmit file to Registrar* (2) After the expiration of ten days from the date of the said lodgment the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary for the registrar to issue a certificate after entering the particulars in the register?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"and shall thereupon issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted - to record particulars and issue certificate* (3) Upon the return of the file together with notification from the County Registrar of the granting of the application the registrar shall enter in the register of clubs the particulars required by section 1 (1) of the Act, and shall thereupon issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1). # **Renewal of certificates, Objections thereto**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is compliance with specific sections of the Registration of Clubs Acts necessary for a club to be eligible for registration?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904] to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Club rules qualifying for registration* (4) In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of - section 4 of the Act, as amended by section 42 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), and - section 56 (which relates to prohibited hours for the supplying for consumption on club premises of excisable liquor) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 26 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the registrar required to send a notice to the Garda Supt.?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the Form 83.3, Schedule together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Registrar to notify Garda Supt.* (6) The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12f2f2e8-bfb6-48b7-a784-8509ed14ce18/Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.3.docx/docx/1), together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can objections be lodged against the renewal of a certificate based on grounds other than those specified in certain sections of acts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the Act of 1988, or section 24(2) of the Act of 1924, or section 19(10) of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Objections to grant or renewal of certificate* 7.(1) It shall be competent for the superintendent of the Garda Síochána on receiving notice of an application given as aforesaid, and for any person resident in the parish in which the club premises are situated, to lodge objections to the grant of the certificate on any of the grounds of objection specified in the Act, and it shall be competent for any person to lodge objections to the renewal of the certificate on any such grounds. (2)[2] The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in - section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html), or - section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the registrar responsible for issuing a certificate of registration when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted registrar to record particulars and issue certificate* (5) If, upon hearing the application and the objection, the Court grants the application, the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can a current certificate remain valid beyond three months if the Court decides to extend it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- extension pending Court''s decision* (2) Notwithstanding the provisions of the Act as to the duration of certifcates, where a renewal has been applied for the current certificate shall remain in force pending the final decision of the Court, but not exceeding three months unless the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document focused on club authorizations?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**Club Authorisations**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners* 9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an authorisation under section 21(1) of the Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 21 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924] as amended by section 8 of the [Act of 1962], may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 10. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 21 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) as amended by section 8 of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is notice of the application required to be given to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Is the authorisation issued in a specific format when the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted, the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb19bab5-78a1-4b4c-add6-c84979d9c518/Club authorisation - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 - Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 section 21 (as amended) No. 83.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an authorization under section 14(1) of the Act of 1962 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 11. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in Order 84 for a child care case a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84 - Child care - Court: District # **Order 84: Child Care******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Child and Family Agency mentioned in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"“**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency established under section 7 of the [Child and Family Agency Act 2013](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/act/40/enacted/en/html) (No. 40 of 2013);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (No. 17 of 1991); “**the Act of 2001**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2001); “**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency established under section 7 of the [Child and Family Agency Act 2013](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/act/40/enacted/en/html) (No. 40 of 2013); “**child**” means a person under the age of eighteen year other than a person who is or has been married; “**parents**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 2(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). 2.[3] (1) Proceedings under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion may allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing. (2) The Judge may, if he or she thinks it proper to do so, order any witness who is not a party to the proceedings to leave the court either until his or her evidence is required or after his or her evidence has been given. (3) Proceedings in the Court under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be as informal as is practicable and consistent with the administration of justice. Neither Judges hearing and determining such proceedings nor barristers nor solicitors appearing in such proceedings shall wear wigs or gowns. (4)[4] Unless otherwise provided in this Order or permitted by the Court, all applications under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application specifying the order or other relief sought in the application, the provisions of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) relied on and the grounds of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge the original notice or summons along with a statutory declaration regarding its service immediately after it has been served?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgment for hearing* 4. When a notice of application, summons or notice of appeal issued under this Order has been served, the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an emergency care order be heard parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application for an emergency care order may be heard and made parte"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an application for an emergency care order may be heard and made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the notice of application ([Form 84.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/578b4525-2f2f-4f59-a65a-9967f0b17c40/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 12 (4) No. 84.1.docx/docx/1) or [84.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d188ed27-41b1-4b7a-8f08-b83aa6a4625c/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is not in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13(1) No. 84.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be) duly completed; - an application for an emergency care order may be heard and an order may be made thereon elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court; - the Judge may deem sufficient the notice of the application actually given to the respondent. (3) An application to which sub-rule (2) applies shall be made on affidavit unless the Judge permits the application to be heard on oral evidence because of the exceptional urgency of the case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an emergency care order application required to be made to a specific judge based on where the child lives?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an emergency care order under section 13(1) of [the Act] must be made to the Judge assigned to the district in which the child resides or is for the time being."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 6.[9] (1) An application for an emergency care order under section 13(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) must be made to the Judge assigned to the district in which the child resides or is for the time being. Where, however, such Judge is not immediately available, the application may be made to any judge of the District Court. (2) An emergency care order shall be in the [Form 84.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85df8e22-6926-41e5-af5c-2d4b7d31c55a/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.3.docx/docx/1) or [84.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the order to be served on a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, upon a person acting in loco parentis, together with, as the case may be, a copy of the affidavit which grounded the application and copies of any exhibits (unless previously served on that person) or a copy of the note of oral evidence mentioned in rule 2(5). (3) A warrant issued under section 13(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the purpose of executing such an Order may be in the [Form 84.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/14aa135a-515f-470d-836c-d5822ddad575/Warrant to execute an emergency care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 13(3) No. 84.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule (4) An appeal from an emergency care order shall not stay the operation of the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before making an application for the judge''s directions under section 13(7)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, otherwise than at the hearing of an application for an emergency care order, application is made under section 13 (7) of [the Act] for the Judge''s directions, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.6"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions under section 13 (7)* 7. (1)[10] Where, otherwise than at the hearing of an application for an emergency care order, application is made under section 13 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Judge''s directions, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency, the parents of the child or either of them, a person acting in loco parentis, or any other person, as appropriate. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application An order giving directions on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be served upon each person directly affected by the Order. (2) An application to vary or discharge a direction given under the said section 13 (7) (a) shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1). Schedule The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1) Schedule which shall be served as prescribed in the said paragraph (1). 8. It shall not be necessary in any notice or application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) or in any order made under that section to name the child if such name is unknown. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required before issuing a notice for an interim care order application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act] for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act], be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10] Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim care order* 9. [11](1) An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d768e869-970c-4538-8b75-6367c62c667b/Notice of application for an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.10.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and any other person directly affected by the Order. (2) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in rule 27) for the purpose of executing an interim care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be served before an application for a care order can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 18 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a care order in respect of a child who resides or is found in its area shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Care Order* 10.(1)[12] An application by the Agency under section 18 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a care order in respect of a child who resides or is found in its area shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b9979d0-2a7f-44ec-9965-d27d8023b8b3/Notice of application for a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.14.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required for issuing a warrant under section 35 of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act] (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the Form 84.43 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- warrant* (3) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application to extend a care order can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 18 (2) of [the Act] to extend the operation of a care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.16] Schedule upon the respondent at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Extension of Care Order* 11. An application under section 18 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to extend the operation of a care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5872f203-b05b-4125-8109-144cd2afcb45/Notice of application to extend the operation of a care order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec02e236-ea2e-468f-950e-c2d7ca448531/Order extending the operation of a care order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.17.docx/docx/1) Schedule and may, where appropriate, be added to or endorsed on the care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before making an application for the court''s directions regarding a child''s care and custody?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act] for the Court''s directions as to the care and custody of a child pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.19 Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. the Agency, the parent having custody of the child, the person acting in loco parentis, as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions pending Care Order* 13.[14] An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the care and custody of a child pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2976462c-51fd-494a-98ba-43cb56c20e3f/Notice of application for court''s directions (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. the Agency, the parent having custody of the child, the person acting in loco parentis, as appropriate. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8cce50fe-fc88-440a-8815-a6a8e9e245ed/Directions under section 18 (6) of the Act (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.20.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served on each party and any other person affected directly by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for a supervision order is heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 18(6) of [the Act] for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 18* 14.[15] (1) An application under section 18(6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1) Schedule at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) The order of the Court granting an application for a supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for a supervision order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 19(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order with respect to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 19* 16.[17] (1) An application by the Agency under section 19(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order with respect to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58f9df8-d7bb-46c6-aaf3-14b284fb02ac/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 19 (1) No. 84.26.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent or respondents, i.e. the parents of the child or, as the case may be, the parent having custody of the child or a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) A supervision order made on an application under this rule shall be in the [Form 84.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/816ce2e4-77ad-43db-817a-e63cacd726bd/Supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before an application for court directions regarding child visits?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions as to visits* 17.[18] An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4cc90cc9-12ce-4a2d-b140-a425fa78ecb1/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.28.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent Agency at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42c17ab7-a5fb-4119-ada3-23357b7afbd1/Directions under section 19 (3) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Agency to serve a notice on the respondent before applying for court directions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 19 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), made during the currency of a supervision order, for the Court''s directions as to the care of the child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.30 Schedule upon the respondent or respondents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Further directions* 18.[19] An application by the Agency under section 19 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), made during the currency of a supervision order, for the Court''s directions as to the care of the child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.30](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cd859c3-206b-422e-ad88-60cab7dc7e53/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (4) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.30.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.31](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dec75767-2057-4357-9d15-8d2a87ae79ec/Directions under section 19 (4) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.31.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Agency notified by the Clerk when directed to investigate a child''s circumstances?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, under section 20(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation of a child’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Investigations under section 20 (1)* 19. (1)[20] Where, under section 20(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation of a child’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule of the Courts decision (2)[21] Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency — - (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before varying or discharging a care or supervision order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 22 of [the Act] - ... shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice..."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary or discharge care order* 20. An application under section 22 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) - - (a) to vary or discharge a care order or any condition or direction attaching to such order or to discharge the care order and make a supervision order, or - to vary or discharge a supervision order or any condition or direction attaching to such order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [84.35](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/311c2145-a1b2-4b1d-aff5-e7931afb05f6/Notice of application to vary - discharge - a care order - a condition - direction attaching to a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.35.docx/docx/1), [84.36](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cbf019b4-13dc-446b-a2ce-f0c5fdb142fc/Notice of application to discharge a care order and make a supervision order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.36.docx/docx/1) or [84.37](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c89980b-801b-4ed2-8be2-b4b0fdbe37fb/Notice of application to - vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.37.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting such application shall be in the Form [84.38](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b289db7-aeac-4228-97cb-6e927d670bd2/Order to - vary - discharge a care order a - condition - direction attaching to a care order No. 84.38.docx/docx/1), [84.39](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dcdacbc9-6402-4e42-afaa-b33abaf7d6e9/Supervision order (made on discharging a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.39.docx/docx/1) or [84.40](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f06f7cc7-ec92-4f5a-a611-f261f99e5a03/Order to vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order No. 84.40.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal lead to the suspension of an order made by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeals* 21.[22] An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA (inserted by section 16 of the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the Court making the determination. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Agency to serve a notice before making an application for a special care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act] for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A], Schedule upon the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part A of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21A.[23] (1)[24] An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6dd96b5-8fd8-419b-b09a-213846cc5672/Notice Of Application For A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. A special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77f9218a-5954-49ef-832d-9234ef175763/Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section 23 (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act, 2001) No. 84.40B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order. (2)[25] An application by the Agency under section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.40C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64d2f8b3-2884-4b70-bd86-bb11d4fa0902/Notice Of Application For Extension Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (4) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40C.docx/docx/1), Schedule An order granting such an extension shall be in the [Form 84.40D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afa0b2f2-0c17-407b-a0cb-6a817bbf0599/Order Extending The Period Of Validity Of A Special Care Order No. 84.40D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the special care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before the Agency can apply for an interim special care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3)[26] An application by the Agency under section (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.40E](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9f0d1129-cb46-4917-ac57-89bdb646649e/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (5) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40E.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4)[27] Except in a case where the Judge otherwise directs under Section (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), an application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40F](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d86d6a49-65e6-4061-8689-6c71bd0589a7/Notice Of Application For An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40F.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40G](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c04874eb-e4c8-4b44-9e10-7ceb689c6f83/Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40G.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form required before an application for an extension of an interim special care order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a person specified in section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim special care order shall, except where the Judge has otherwise directed under section (3), be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent referred to in sub-rule (4) hereof (or, as the case may be, on the Agency) of a notice in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5)[28] An application by a person specified in section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim special care order shall, except where the Judge has otherwise directed under section (3), be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent referred to in sub-rule (4) hereof (or, as the case may be, on the Agency) of a notice in the [Form 84.40H](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6f6558fd-fb78-44c1-89ba-19d4a56586a9/Notice Of Application For An Extension Of An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40H.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.40I](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa975463-42d1-4b6c-8dbe-94342380d8cc/Order Extending The Period Of An Interim Special Care Order No. 84.40I.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the interim special care order. (6) An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for the Court’s directions pending the determination of an application for a special care order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 13 of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2976462c-51fd-494a-98ba-43cb56c20e3f/Notice of application for court''s directions (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.20](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8cce50fe-fc88-440a-8815-a6a8e9e245ed/Directions under section 18 (6) of the Act (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for applications to vary or discharge a contribution order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be in the Form 84.24, Schedule modified as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(7) An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a special care order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 14 of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.21](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. (8)[29] Where, in addition to making a special care order, the Court makes an order under section 18 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requiring the parent or parents of the child to contribute towards his or her maintenance, such contribution order shall be in the [Form 84.23](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e66422b-7a44-4728-b339-805474934216/Contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (7) No. 84.23.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served by the Agency upon the said parent or parents. (9) An application under section 18 (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) to vary or discharge a contribution order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 15(2) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.24](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e63e3346-dd89-4893-9552-ba87fec2e54f/Notice of application to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.25](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2e744c31-76ee-4c72-9c16-8bf9d1ce9f1e/Order to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon the parent required to contribute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for applications under section 13(7)(a) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be in the Form 84.6, Schedule modified as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(11) An application under section 13 (7)(a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for directions shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(1) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. (12) An application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) to vary or discharge a direction shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(2) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant under section of the Act of 1991 required to be made to a specific judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21B.[31](1)[32]An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing. Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.40P](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/053971f0-cf2b-4287-a636-717f58040a91/Information For Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, Section (2) (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40P.docx/docx/1) of an authorised officer appointed by the Agency under section (1) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 84.40Q](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9cae8d1b-6479-4637-8e1a-398a22b85b12/Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40Q.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when the court makes an order to terminate a private foster care arrangement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section such order shall be in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) An application for an order under section of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the person mentioned in paragraphs (a) and of section of the said Act of a notice in the [Form 84.40R](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5beab9f5-7b74-48f5-84d0-e4a9414e478e/Notice Of Application For Order In Respect Of Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40R.docx/docx/1) , Schedule Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section such order shall be in the [Form 84.40S](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/755f0f12-1289-498c-a6ff-dd860ea0f9af/Order To Terminate Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, Section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40S.docx/docx/1), Schedule Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph or paragraph of section such order shall be (as the case may be) in the [Form 84.4](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1), [84.11](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1), [84.15](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) or [84.18](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), modified as appropriate ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section discussing applications in Part of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Applications etc. under Part of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications etc. under Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when making an application for a report under section 27(1) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.41 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Requests for reports* 22. (1) Where, other than during the hearing of the proceedings, application is made by any of the parties for an order under section 27 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requesting the preparation of a report, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.41](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c60c7466-369d-411f-9720-7837c6c18cda/Notice of application for an order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991, section 27 No. 84.41.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the other party or parties. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.42](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7085b8a3-c9e9-47f5-8b7a-c45b3bab366a/Order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.42.docx/docx/1)Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the person nominated therein to prepare the report. (2) When the report has been prepared it shall be lodged with the Clerk. A copy of the report shall be made available by the applicant to the counsel or solicitor representing each party or, if any party is not so represented, to that party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the warrant for executing a care order required to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act] to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act] directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the Form 84.43 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Warrant to execute care order* 24.[33] A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing specific proceedings under Part of an act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings Under Part of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings Under Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for an order regarding access to a child can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Access to child* 25. (1)[34] An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.44](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c2f2b3-2008-4e35-9ffc-b8c6367f1007/Notice of application for an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37(2) No. 84.44.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.45](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4857a91e-c87b-4d48-a6a4-1c80bd2fe56b/Order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.45.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application can be made to vary or discharge an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under the said section 37 (2) to vary or discharge an order to which paragraph (1) hereof relates shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Vary access* (2)[35] An application under the said section 37 (2) to vary or discharge an order to which paragraph (1) hereof relates shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.46](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b9084419-d4dd-4ed4-b802-b29e1cbcbcc1/Notice of application to vary - discharge an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.46.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents, i.e. the Agency, the parents, the persons mentioned in section 37 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), as appropriate. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.47](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1d7af80-6b81-4452-9f08-9db3d682fb6d/Order to vary - discharge an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.47.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be served before an application is made under section 43(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.52 Schedule on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order to deliver up child to the Child and Family Agency — 27.[37] An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b7e851aa-60c6-4ef7-9d6b-f2dc9325bddc/Notice of application for an order that child be delivered up to custody of the health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.52.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent. Such notice must be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 84.53](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8fb48c60-ed36-4cc6-83bf-9a8934605663/Order that child be delivered up to custody of health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.53.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Agency must cause the said order to be served on the respondent 27A.[38] (1) An application for an order under section 43A of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by a foster parent or relative with whom the child has been placed shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant of a notice in the [Form 84.53A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/765bd7e6-e9a9-44c9-ab01-4fea44d17853/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 Of The Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the Agency. A copy of the notice shall, where section 43A(2)(d)(ii) applies, be served by the Agency on the parent having custody of the child at the relevant time or a person (other than the applicant) acting in loco parentis to the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is written consent from the Agency required to be attached to the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The consent of the Agency under section 43A(2)(c) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order shall be in writing and the original consent shall be appended to the original notice of application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) The consent of the Agency under section 43A(2)(c) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order shall be in writing and the original consent shall be appended to the original notice of application. Where a consent has been obtained under section 43A(2)(d)(i) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order the original of such consent, if in writing, shall be appended to the original notice of application or produced at the hearing of the application, and where such consent in writing is not so appended or produced, such consent shall, where required, be proved by such other means as the court considers appropriate. (3) A copy of the notice of application shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50548b4b-29c2-4194-bb65-c3deb5f4f4ad/Order under section 43A of the Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before making an application under section', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall, to the extent possible, be served upon each of the persons referred to in section 43B(1)(a) to of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6cf2c6b-7f10-49ae-b5bf-a33b0be2f3d4/Order Varying - Discharging - A Condition Restriction - Attaching To - An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each of the respondents and upon any other person directly affected by the Order'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 46 (3) be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Information - (3)* 28. Where an order is sought under section 46 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency, the applicant shall lay information before the Judge on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a12d36a7-7320-4233-90a5-ac23add07eaa/Information (under section 46 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.54.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Judge may, on foot of such information, sign and issue a summons in the [Form 84.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1)[.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1) Schedule Such summons shall be served upon the respondent at least two days prior to the return date thereof. Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.56](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/445956b7-324f-4cb1-8f81-f4aa02343f39/Order That Child Be Delivered Up To Custody Of Health Board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 46(3) No. 84.56.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a search warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 46 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a search warrant shall be by information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Search warrant* 29. An application under section 46 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a search warrant shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.57.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/31012ae6-9eb4-42a4-9550-ffdb0ee99812/Information (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.57.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.58](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0f3c5a3-a0a6-44b1-b2b6-716bba960629/Search Warrant (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.58 .docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application under section 47 can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 47 of [the Act] for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Direction under 47* 30.(1) An application under section 47 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.59](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6eab7fc4-745a-4f38-83e6-91030a8e39b1/Notice Of Application For Directions On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 47 No. 84.59.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.60](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e878cfde-21b5-490d-b06c-977472a63db7/Order On Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child (under section 47 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.60.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 84.61 required before varying or discharging an order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- variation or discharge* (2) An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64e61fc5-3791-4d17-9ba7-91bbbf674fec/Notice Of Application To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.61.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.62](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75f7dce1-80fb-4075-b4f8-9ff125d0dd85/Order To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction No. 84.62.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant to enter and inspect premises where a pre-school service is provided required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 55 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter and inspect premises in which a pre-school service is being carried on shall be by information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Pre-School service — warrant* (2) An application under section 55 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter and inspect premises in which a pre-school service is being carried on shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.63.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b5d4b0da-c0bb-426c-9589-c2b23b73ce1e/Information (under section 55 (2) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.63.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.64.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1aef1076-3f97-4672-b249-22975bdaac45/Warrant To Enter And Inspect Premises - Child Care Act, 1991 section 55 (2) No. 84.64.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the appellant to provide a copy of the decision against which they are appealing before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Children''s residential centre* 32. An appeal to the Court under section 62 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by the registered proprietor or, as the case may be, the person intending to be the registered proprietor of a children''s residential centre, against a decision, specified in subsection (1) of that section, of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.65](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19803d89-7193-4e0e-95fc-0cd8d9dcb550/Notice Of Appeal (under section 62 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.65.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the Agency. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the appeal. The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 84.66](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/94a0ecd6-7d38-4813-8338-0dc9eae3eaad/Order Of Appeal - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.66.docx/docx/1). Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is Part of the Act mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Part of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Orders provided for in Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application under section 25 of the Act be made parte if the judge finds it urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - be made parte"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '8. Notwithstanding any of the preceding rules, where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - - (a) be made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the appropriate notice of application duly completed; - in the case of a child to whom section 23 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, be heard, and an order made thereon, elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court. [1] Order 84A inserted by [S.I. 97 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/97/made/en/print?q 97&years 2007), effective 2 April 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to water disconnection?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Water disconnection rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 85 - Water disconnection rules - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given before an application can be heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of such application shall be in the Form 85.1 Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of application* 2. An application by the sanitary authority for an order under section 3 (2) of the [Local Government (Delimitation of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/18/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the supply of water for domestic purposes is provided to the consumer. Notice of such application shall be in the [Form 85.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24a4ac07-80a9-4a22-8ad7-ae2e0dd9ce0e/Notice Of An Application For An Order Under Section 3 (2) - Local Government (Delimitation Of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995 No. 85.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Public Dance Halls Act of 1935 referenced in the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**the Act** means the [Public Dance Halls Act, 1935]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Public Dance Halls Act, 1935](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) (No. 2 of 1935); "**place**" means a building (including part of a building), yard, garden, or other enclosed place, whether roofed or not roofed and whether the enclosure and the roofing (if any) are permanent or temporary; "**public dancing**" means dancing which is open to the public and in which persons present are entitled to participate actively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a public dancing license be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a public dancing licence pursuant to section 2 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under section 2* 2. (1) An application for a public dancing licence pursuant to section 2 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of a place for which a licence is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the said court area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána and the local authority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district, and upon the local authority within whose functional area, is situate the place to which such application relates, at least one month before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district, and upon the local authority within whose functional area, is situate the place to which such application relates, at least one month before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to inform the Fire Authority about something?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shall apply to the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shall apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice and other documents to be submitted to the Clerk in advance of the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (6) A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which such application relates and a copy thereof, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least fortyeight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued upon granting the application supposed to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2db55c76-fdec-4189-9ea5-e0743d94a77b/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for transferring a public dancing license be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under section 8 (2)* 4. (1) An application in respect of any place for which a public dancing licence is in force, for a public dancing licence in respect of that place to another person pursuant to section 8 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html), made with the consent of the licensee, may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is a signed notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice of application* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 86.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d367a86d-e922-4411-accf-f3e7b901bc5f/Notice Of Application For A Public Dancing Licence No. 86.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration when lodging the notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which such application relates, and a copy thereof, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the applicant to inform the Fire Authority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shat apply to the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (4) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shat apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for an application to be made according to Form 86.1 or Form 86.4, Schedule', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 86.1] or [Form 86.4, Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 86.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8f3419cf-8aca-47cf-a18a-803d99ce19b3/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935. No. 86.1.docx/docx/1) or [Form 86.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb94c83a-a2b9-4723-84f3-8a497e32569c/Order Of Refusal To Grant Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.4.docx/docx/1), as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Can a licensee surrender their public dancing license at any time?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The licensee under a public dancing licence may at any time surrender such licence by notice in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Surrender of licence* 5. The licensee under a public dancing licence may at any time surrender such licence by notice in writing ( [Form 86.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/acfde066-4054-4a15-acff-916944ccc2e7/Notice Of Surrender Of Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.5.docx/docx/1)) sent or delivered, together with such licence, to the Clerk for the court area in which the place to which such licence relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to public music and singing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 87 - Public music and singing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 87 - Public music and singing - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a public music and singing license be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under sec. 51 (2)* 2. (1) An application for a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of a place for which a licence under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the said court area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (5) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued upon granting the application supposed to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/439d5063-1cbd-4578-978b-8afdedcf64d8/Licence for public music and singing - Public Health Acts Amendment Act, 1890 section 51 - Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act, 1961 section 33 No. 87.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a public music and singing license be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a public music and singing licence for a defined period not exceeding fourteen days pursuant to section 51 (11) of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under sec. 51 (11)* 3. (1) An application for a public music and singing licence for a defined period not exceeding fourteen days pursuant to section 51 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which the application relates, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which the application relates, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued upon granting the application based on a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2474c2f-3de6-493c-b602-6deb24be7f73/Licence for public music and singing (for a defined period not exceeding fourteen days) - Public Health Acts Amendment Act, 1890 section 51 - Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act, 1961 section 33 No. 87.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for the transfer of a public music and singing license be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the transfer of a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (3) of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under sec. 51 (3)* 4. (1) An application for the transfer of a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which the application relates, at least fourteen days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which the application relates, at least fourteen days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (3) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for the endorsement of transfer?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 87.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the endorsement of transfer shall be in accordance with [Form 87.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1770d54-4e97-47db-85e5-22949ba42fcb/Endorsement of transfer of public music and singing licence No. 87.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 88 related to street and house-to-house collections?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Street and house to house collections"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 88 - Street and house to house collections - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 referred to in the definition?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the [Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) (No. 13 of 1962)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order "**t****he Act**" means the [Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) (No. 13 of 1962).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the collection is proposed to be held?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal against the refusal by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a collection permit, pursuant to section 13 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit tile subject of the appeal relates, is proposed to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for Appeal under Sec. 13 (1)* 2. (1) An appeal against the refusal by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a collection permit, pursuant to section 13 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit tile subject of the appeal relates, is proposed to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given at least seven days in advance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court related to the locality where the collection is proposed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal against the attaching of a condition by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to a collection permit granted, pursuant to section 13 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 13 (2)* 3. (1) An appeal against the attaching of a condition by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to a collection permit granted, pursuant to section 13 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required for issuing a notice before an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 88.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4edd42ef-38d0-4819-952c-fb998a86e45b/Notice of appeal to the district court - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13 (2) No. 88.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 88.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4edd42ef-38d0-4819-952c-fb998a86e45b/Notice of appeal to the district court - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13 (2) No. 88.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for an appeal supposed to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d7a0071b-6b64-4cce-8dd7-92a60b952a20/Order on appeal - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13(2) No. 88.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the collection is proposed to be held?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal against the revocation by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána of a collection permit pursuant to section 13 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for Appeal under Sec. 13 (3)* 4. (1) An appeal against the revocation by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána of a collection permit pursuant to section 13 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required when issuing a notice for an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 88.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd5a422c-0500-4e52-84b7-88a8cd76e4a4/Notice of appeal to the district court - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13 (3) No. 88.5.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is Form 84.43 used for executing a care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act] (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the Form 84.43"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- warrant* (3) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the supervision order required to be served upon the respondent after being made by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order* 12.[13] Where, on an application for a care order, the Court makes a supervision order (as provided for in section 18 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 84.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1) and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application under section 18(6) is heard if it''s not made viva voce?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 18(6) of [the Act] for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 18* 14.[15] (1) An application under section 18(6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1) Schedule at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) The order of the Court granting an application for a supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before varying or discharging a contribution order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 18 (8) of [the Act] to vary or discharge a contribution order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Contribution by parent* 15. (1)[16] Where, in addition to making a care order, the Court makes an order under section 18 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requiring the parent or parents of a child to contribute towards his or her maintenance, such contribution order shall be in the [Form 84.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e66422b-7a44-4728-b339-805474934216/Contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (7) No. 84.23.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant Agency shall cause the said order to be served upon the said parent or parents. (2) An application under section 18 (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to vary or discharge a contribution order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e63e3346-dd89-4893-9552-ba87fec2e54f/Notice of application to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.24.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2e744c31-76ee-4c72-9c16-8bf9d1ce9f1e/Order to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.25.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon the parent required to contribute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before an application for the court''s directions on visiting a child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.28 Schedule upon the respondent Agency at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions as to visits* 17.[18] An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4cc90cc9-12ce-4a2d-b140-a425fa78ecb1/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.28.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent Agency at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42c17ab7-a5fb-4119-ada3-23357b7afbd1/Directions under section 19 (3) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before an application is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 19 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), made during the currency of a supervision order, for the Court''s directions as to the care of the child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.30 Schedule upon the respondent or respondents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Further directions* 18.[19] An application by the Agency under section 19 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), made during the currency of a supervision order, for the Court''s directions as to the care of the child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.30](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cd859c3-206b-422e-ad88-60cab7dc7e53/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (4) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.30.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.31](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dec75767-2057-4357-9d15-8d2a87ae79ec/Directions under section 19 (4) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.31.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to notify the Agency when directed by the Court under section 20(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, under section 20(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation of a child’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Investigations under section 20 (1)* 19. (1)[20] Where, under section 20(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation of a child’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule of the Courts decision (2)[21] Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency — - (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal lead to the suspension of an order made by the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeals* 21.[22] An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA (inserted by section 16 of the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the Court making the determination. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before the Agency can apply for a special care order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act] for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part A of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21A.[23] (1)[24] An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6dd96b5-8fd8-419b-b09a-213846cc5672/Notice Of Application For A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. A special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77f9218a-5954-49ef-832d-9234ef175763/Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section 23 (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act, 2001) No. 84.40B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order. (2)[25] An application by the Agency under section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.40C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64d2f8b3-2884-4b70-bd86-bb11d4fa0902/Notice Of Application For Extension Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (4) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40C.docx/docx/1), Schedule An order granting such an extension shall be in the [Form 84.40D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afa0b2f2-0c17-407b-a0cb-6a817bbf0599/Order Extending The Period Of Validity Of A Special Care Order No. 84.40D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the special care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for an interim special care order is heard?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Except in a case where the Judge otherwise directs under Section (3) of the Act, an application by the Agency under section (1) of the Act for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form Schedule upon the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3)[26] An application by the Agency under section (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.40E](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9f0d1129-cb46-4917-ac57-89bdb646649e/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (5) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40E.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4)[27] Except in a case where the Judge otherwise directs under Section (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), an application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40F](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d86d6a49-65e6-4061-8689-6c71bd0589a7/Notice Of Application For An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40F.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40G](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c04874eb-e4c8-4b44-9e10-7ceb689c6f83/Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40G.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the form used for applications under section 13(7)(a) of the Act specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be in the Form 84.6, Schedule modified as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(11) An application under section 13 (7)(a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for directions shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(1) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. (12) An application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) to vary or discharge a direction shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(2) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made to a specific judge?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the Act of 1991 shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21B.[31](1)[32]An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing. Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.40P](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/053971f0-cf2b-4287-a636-717f58040a91/Information For Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, Section (2) (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40P.docx/docx/1) of an authorised officer appointed by the Agency under section (1) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 84.40Q](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9cae8d1b-6479-4637-8e1a-398a22b85b12/Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40Q.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about applications in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications etc. under Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before making an application for a report under section 27(1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.41 Schedule upon the other party or parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Requests for reports* 22. (1) Where, other than during the hearing of the proceedings, application is made by any of the parties for an order under section 27 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requesting the preparation of a report, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.41](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c60c7466-369d-411f-9720-7837c6c18cda/Notice of application for an order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991, section 27 No. 84.41.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the other party or parties. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.42](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7085b8a3-c9e9-47f5-8b7a-c45b3bab366a/Order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.42.docx/docx/1)Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the person nominated therein to prepare the report. (2) When the report has been prepared it shall be lodged with the Clerk. A copy of the report shall be made available by the applicant to the counsel or solicitor representing each party or, if any party is not so represented, to that party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the warrant for executing a care order specified in Form 84.43?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act] to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act] directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the Form 84.43"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Warrant to execute care order* 24.[33] A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application for an order regarding access to a child can be heard in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.44 Schedule upon the Agency at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Access to child* 25. (1)[34] An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.44](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c2f2b3-2008-4e35-9ffc-b8c6367f1007/Notice of application for an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37(2) No. 84.44.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.45](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4857a91e-c87b-4d48-a6a4-1c80bd2fe56b/Order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.45.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Agency to serve a notice before applying for an order to refuse access to a child?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 37 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising it to refuse access to a child in its care shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.48 Schedule upon the respondent (the person against whom the order is sought)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Authority to refuse access* 26.[36] (1) An application by the Agency under section 37 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising it to refuse access to a child in its care shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.48](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6cf4d-32f5-49a2-afa9-beddc132f546/Notice of application for an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.48.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent (the person against whom the order is sought). Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.49](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4dff991-6a51-4fde-bd02-5928eb75e8c1/Order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37 (3) (A) No. 84.49.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent. (2) An application under the said section 37 (3) to vary or discharge an order to which paragraph (1) hereof relates shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ef82cf9b-2bb9-4868-9f89-7e32bceb0b75/Notice of application to vary - discharge an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 37 (3) No. 84.50.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.51](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/130a7ae7-0ff0-44d7-845f-e5f421e933fd/Order to vary - discharge an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child No. 84.51.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application is made under section 43(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act] for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 84.52 Schedule on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order to deliver up child to the Child and Family Agency — 27.[37] An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b7e851aa-60c6-4ef7-9d6b-f2dc9325bddc/Notice of application for an order that child be delivered up to custody of the health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.52.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent. Such notice must be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 84.53](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8fb48c60-ed36-4cc6-83bf-9a8934605663/Order that child be delivered up to custody of health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.53.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Agency must cause the said order to be served on the respondent 27A.[38] (1) An application for an order under section 43A of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by a foster parent or relative with whom the child has been placed shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant of a notice in the [Form 84.53A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/765bd7e6-e9a9-44c9-ab01-4fea44d17853/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 Of The Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the Agency. A copy of the notice shall, where section 43A(2)(d)(ii) applies, be served by the Agency on the parent having custody of the child at the relevant time or a person (other than the applicant) acting in loco parentis to the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is written consent required to be appended to the original notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The consent of the Agency under section 43A(2)(c) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order shall be in writing and the original consent shall be appended to the original notice of application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) The consent of the Agency under section 43A(2)(c) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order shall be in writing and the original consent shall be appended to the original notice of application. Where a consent has been obtained under section 43A(2)(d)(i) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order the original of such consent, if in writing, shall be appended to the original notice of application or produced at the hearing of the application, and where such consent in writing is not so appended or produced, such consent shall, where required, be proved by such other means as the court considers appropriate. (3) A copy of the notice of application shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50548b4b-29c2-4194-bb65-c3deb5f4f4ad/Order under section 43A of the Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application be made parte if the urgency of the matter requires it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Information - (3)* 28. Where an order is sought under section 46 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency, the applicant shall lay information before the Judge on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a12d36a7-7320-4233-90a5-ac23add07eaa/Information (under section 46 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.54.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Judge may, on foot of such information, sign and issue a summons in the [Form 84.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1)[.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1) Schedule Such summons shall be served upon the respondent at least two days prior to the return date thereof. Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.56](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/445956b7-324f-4cb1-8f81-f4aa02343f39/Order That Child Be Delivered Up To Custody Of Health Board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 46(3) No. 84.56.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a search warrant application under section 46(6) required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 46 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a search warrant shall be by information on oath"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Search warrant* 29. An application under section 46 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a search warrant shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.57.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/31012ae6-9eb4-42a4-9550-ffdb0ee99812/Information (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.57.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.58](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0f3c5a3-a0a6-44b1-b2b6-716bba960629/Search Warrant (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.58 .docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application under section 47 can be heard by the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 47 of [the Act] for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Direction under 47* 30.(1) An application under section 47 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.59](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6eab7fc4-745a-4f38-83e6-91030a8e39b1/Notice Of Application For Directions On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 47 No. 84.59.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.60](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e878cfde-21b5-490d-b06c-977472a63db7/Order On Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child (under section 47 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.60.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 84.61 required before an application to vary or discharge an order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- variation or discharge* (2) An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64e61fc5-3791-4d17-9ba7-91bbbf674fec/Notice Of Application To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.61.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.62](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75f7dce1-80fb-4075-b4f8-9ff125d0dd85/Order To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction No. 84.62.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing proceedings under Part VIII of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under Part VIII of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part VIII of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the appellant to provide a copy of the decision or notification before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Children''s residential centre* 32. An appeal to the Court under section 62 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by the registered proprietor or, as the case may be, the person intending to be the registered proprietor of a children''s residential centre, against a decision, specified in subsection (1) of that section, of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.65](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19803d89-7193-4e0e-95fc-0cd8d9dcb550/Notice Of Appeal (under section 62 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.65.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the Agency. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the appeal. The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 84.66](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/94a0ecd6-7d38-4813-8338-0dc9eae3eaad/Order Of Appeal - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.66.docx/docx/1). Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application under section 25 of the Act be made parte if the Judge finds it urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - be made parte"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '8. Notwithstanding any of the preceding rules, where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - - (a) be made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the appropriate notice of application duly completed; - in the case of a child to whom section 23 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, be heard, and an order made thereon, elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court. [1] Order 84A inserted by [S.I. 97 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/97/made/en/print?q 97&years 2007), effective 2 April 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given at least twenty-one days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Notice of such application shall be in the Form 85.1 Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of application* 2. An application by the sanitary authority for an order under section 3 (2) of the [Local Government (Delimitation of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/18/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the supply of water for domestic purposes is provided to the consumer. Notice of such application shall be in the [Form 85.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24a4ac07-80a9-4a22-8ad7-ae2e0dd9ce0e/Notice Of An Application For An Order Under Section 3 (2) - Local Government (Delimitation Of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995 No. 85.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a federal court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 86 - Public dancing - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Public Dance Halls Act, 1935 referred to in the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"**the Act** means the [Public Dance Halls Act, 1935]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Public Dance Halls Act, 1935](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) (No. 2 of 1935); "**place**" means a building (including part of a building), yard, garden, or other enclosed place, whether roofed or not roofed and whether the enclosure and the roofing (if any) are permanent or temporary; "**public dancing**" means dancing which is open to the public and in which persons present are entitled to participate actively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to publish a notice in a newspaper?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a reference to a specific act in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shall apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence to be issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2db55c76-fdec-4189-9ea5-e0743d94a77b/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice of application* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 86.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d367a86d-e922-4411-accf-f3e7b901bc5f/Notice Of Application For A Public Dancing Licence No. 86.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order format specified for applications?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with Form 86.1 or Form 86.4, Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 86.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8f3419cf-8aca-47cf-a18a-803d99ce19b3/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935. No. 86.1.docx/docx/1) or [Form 86.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb94c83a-a2b9-4723-84f3-8a497e32569c/Order Of Refusal To Grant Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.4.docx/docx/1), as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Can a licensee surrender their public dancing license?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The licensee under a public dancing licence may at any time surrender such licence by notice in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Surrender of licence* 5. The licensee under a public dancing licence may at any time surrender such licence by notice in writing ( [Form 86.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/acfde066-4054-4a15-acff-916944ccc2e7/Notice Of Surrender Of Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.5.docx/docx/1)) sent or delivered, together with such licence, to the Clerk for the court area in which the place to which such licence relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued upon granting the application based on a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/439d5063-1cbd-4578-978b-8afdedcf64d8/Licence for public music and singing - Public Health Acts Amendment Act, 1890 section 51 - Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act, 1961 section 33 No. 87.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Fire Services Act of 1981 relevant to the application process?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (3) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) shall apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is the licence issued in a specific format if the application is approved?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 87.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2474c2f-3de6-493c-b602-6deb24be7f73/Licence for public music and singing (for a defined period not exceeding fourteen days) - Public Health Acts Amendment Act, 1890 section 51 - Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act, 1961 section 33 No. 87.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (3) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form mentioned for the endorsement of transfer in case the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 87.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the endorsement of transfer shall be in accordance with [Form 87.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1770d54-4e97-47db-85e5-22949ba42fcb/Endorsement of transfer of public music and singing licence No. 87.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 88 related to collections on streets and in houses?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Street and house to house collections"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 88 - Street and house to house collections - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 referred to as ''the Act'' in this context?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In this Order \"the Act\" means the [Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order "**t****he Act**" means the [Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) (No. 13 of 1962).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court related to the locality where the collection is proposed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal against the refusal by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a collection permit, pursuant to section 13 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit tile subject of the appeal relates, is proposed to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for Appeal under Sec. 13 (1)* 2. (1) An appeal against the refusal by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a collection permit, pursuant to section 13 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit tile subject of the appeal relates, is proposed to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made against the attaching of a condition to a collection permit at any sitting of the relevant local court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal against the attaching of a condition by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to a collection permit granted, pursuant to section 13 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 13 (2)* 3. (1) An appeal against the attaching of a condition by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to a collection permit granted, pursuant to section 13 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection to which the collection permit the subject of the appeal relates is proposed to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for the appeal supposed to follow a specific format?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d7a0071b-6b64-4cce-8dd7-92a60b952a20/Order on appeal - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13(2) No. 88.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required for issuing a notice before an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 88.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd5a422c-0500-4e52-84b7-88a8cd76e4a4/Notice of appeal to the district court - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13 (3) No. 88.5.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before an application under section can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall, to the extent possible, be served upon each of the persons referred to in section 43B(1)(a) to of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6cf2c6b-7f10-49ae-b5bf-a33b0be2f3d4/Order Varying - Discharging - A Condition Restriction - Attaching To - An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each of the respondents and upon any other person directly affected by the Order'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given at least seven days in advance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a copy of the notice to be submitted to the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for the appeal supposed to follow a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7df7bf9-2542-4e31-85e7-615f4b1e2d36/Order on appeal - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13(3) No. 88.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 23(1) be made at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under Sec. 23 (1)* 5. (1) An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when issuing a notice prior to an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 88.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of, and service of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 88.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/92048d44-e8a1-4ac3-ac7d-9e2f700d53dc/Notice of application for an order under section 23 (1) of the Act - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 No. 88.7.docx/docx/1) upon the person (the respondent) to whom was granted the collection permit pursuant to which the collection was held. The notice shall be served at least forty-eight hours before the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the original notice required to be submitted along with a statutory declaration after service is effected?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certified copy of the order required to be provided to the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A certified copy of such order shall be given or sent to the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in the [Form 88.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c721def-fff2-4ab0-adcb-f6d6ac13b419/Order for information about proceeds of collection - Street and House to House Collections Act 1962 No. 88.8.docx/docx/1). A certified copy of such order shall be given or sent to the respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to wildlife?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 89 - Wildlife"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 89 - Wildlife - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal under section 29 (7) be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the appellant resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 29 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against the refusal by the Minister to grant or renew a licence to hunt with firearms may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 29 (7)* 2. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 29 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against the refusal by the Minister to grant or renew a licence to hunt with firearms may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides or, where the appellant is ordinarily resident outside the State, temporarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an appeal can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ff20174-1e3f-46a0-8f04-7b01bf4f26b9/Notice of appeal against refusal of the minister to a licence to hunt with firearms - renew - Wildlife Act, 1976 No. 89.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to send a copy of the court''s order to the Minister if the appeal is allowed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e981c916-43d9-4f8b-9225-3fcf1aaf901c/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 29(7) No. 89.2.docx/docx/1). (5) Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a wildlife dealer''s certificate be submitted at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the grant of a certificate authorising the issue of a licence or renewal of a licence to carry on business as a wildlife dealer pursuant to section 48 of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application for certificate* 3. (1) An application for the grant of a certificate authorising the issue of a licence or renewal of a licence to carry on business as a wildlife dealer pursuant to section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued and served before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8eac24c9-6d07-4437-a196-902c196cc28d/Notice of application for a certificate authorising the issue - renewal of a wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application to amend a wildlife dealer''s licence be submitted at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence pursuant to section 48 (7) of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application to amend licence* 4. (1) An application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence pursuant to section 48 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be completed before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the completion of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the completion of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9c2c498-7806-4f94-b46d-36cb81488b97/Notice of application to amend wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.5.docx/docx/1)) which shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to send a copy of the Court''s order to the Minister when a wildlife dealer''s licence is revoked?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where pursuant to section 49 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation of licence* 5. Where pursuant to section 49 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court. 6. Where, pursuant to section 75 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), the Court revokes a firearm certificate or a licence to hunt with firearms and imposes a disqualification, the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal under section 77 be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the seizure and detention occurred?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 77 of [the Act] against seizure and detention under [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such seizure and detention was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 77* 7. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 77 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against seizure and detention under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such seizure and detention was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an appeal can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fcd8b62-a25c-4f3f-a183-ce7a18dde282/Notice of appeal against seizure and detention - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 77 No. 89.6.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for notice to be given to those affected by the appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal, in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), at least seven days or, where service is effected by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge a copy of the notice with the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required to be issued before an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.9 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f738a32e-a4cc-4e86-adfa-6a504d490ed3/Notice of appeal against a direction under section 78 (3) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 78 (5) No. 89.9.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about preventing someone from entering a specific area of land?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application to prohibit entry on land*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to prohibit entry on land*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application under section 68(5) of the Act for an order prohibiting entry by an authorized officer limited to specific court sittings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 68 (5) of [the Act] for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land may be made at any sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 9. (1) An application pursuant to section 68 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the land is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the notice to be served at least seven days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service shall be effected at least seven days or, where the notice is being served by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 89.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/46467192-4950-4c80-ad47-75a19d7f2669/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Wildlife Act 1976 No. 89.12.docx/docx/1) upon the respondent (the authorised officer) in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html). Service shall be effected at least seven days or, where the notice is being served by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall then be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the form referenced in the court''s order specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 89.13, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- order of the Court* (3) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 89.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c7f6c7-c1c8-457c-99c2-f21b8ca691b4/Order (prohibiting entry on land) - (specifying conditions for entry on land) - Wildlife Act 1976 No. 89.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting permission to conduct a search?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Application for search warrant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for search warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a search warrant be made at any sitting of the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a search warrant pursuant to section 73 of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 10. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a search warrant pursuant to section 73 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or other land in respect of which the warrant is sought is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the search warrant required to be in a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 89.15] or [89.16], Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of warrant* (3) A search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 89.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8227dc00-5bf1-426e-a369-f900a16dd47b/Search warrant (to a member of the Garda Síochána) - Wildlife Act 1976 section 73 No. 89.15.docx/docx/1) or [89.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a9b62b44-6f58-453e-9c2c-e05134312b5f/Search warrant (to an authorised person) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 73 No. 89.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 9 - Joinder of Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can claims for the recovery of land be joined with other claims?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof, and damages for breach of any contract under which the land, or any part thereof, is held, or for any wrong or injury to the said land, or any part thereof."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Joinder of Claims - Court: Circuit 1. Save as in the next succeeding Rule provided, two or more claims may be made in one originating document, either alternatively or otherwise, so long as the claims are not mutually inconsistent or based on inconsistent allegations of fact, but, if it appears to the Judge that claims joined in any action or matter cannot be conveniently tried together, he may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the record to be amended accordingly, and may make such order as to costs as may seem just. 2. No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof, and damages for breach of any contract under which the land, or any part thereof, is held, or for any wrong or injury to the said land, or any part thereof. An action for redemption, and a motion for delivery by a defendant of possession of mortgaged property therein, shall not be deemed a claim for the recovery of land within the meaning of this Rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can service of a summons be effected by sending it via registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Service of summons - Court: Superior # Mode of service** 1. No service of a summons shall be required when the defendant, by his solicitor, accepts service, and undertakes in writing to enter an appearance. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) Service of any summons on the defendant shall, except in the cases in the following rules of this Order specified, be effected: - by personal service upon the person to be served, or - by personal service upon another person referred to in sub-rule (2) on behalf of the person to be served, or - (iii) by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served, provided that such service shall not be deemed effective without proof of delivery of the said envelope to the address of the person to be served, or - where the defendant is a company, in accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014. (2) Where it shall appear by affidavit that the defendant is personally within the jurisdiction and that due and reasonable diligence has been exercised in endeavouring to effect personal service on him or her, service of the summons may be effected by delivering a copy thereof at - (a) the defendant''s usual or last known place of residence within the jurisdiction, or - the defendant''s principal or last known place of business or office, to the wife, husband, civil partner (within the meaning of section 3 of the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010) father, mother, brother, or sister of the defendant, or to any employee of the defendant (the person to whom such copy shall be delivered being of the age of sixteen years or upwards) and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal service required when serving a summons on an infant defendant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"When an infant is defendant in any proceedings service on his father or mother or guardian, or, if none, then upon the person with whom the infant resides or under whose care he is, shall, unless the Court otherwise orders, be deemed good service on the infant;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Personal service shall be effected by delivering a copy of the summons to the defendant in person, and showing him the original or duplicate original. # On particular defendants** 4. When husband and wife are both defendants in any proceedings, they shall both be served unless the Court shall otherwise order. 5. When an infant is defendant in any proceedings service on his father or mother or guardian, or, if none, then upon the person with whom the infant resides or under whose care he is, shall, unless the Court otherwise orders, be deemed good service on the infant; provided that the Court may order that service made or to be made on the infant shall be deemed good service. 6.[[4]](#2612023) Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015) who is a defendant to an action, shall be in accordance with [Order 15](full-court-rule?id 0469ffe2-3989-4afd-96eb-61d6db2e2a22), rule 17.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to serve a summons on every person in actual possession or in receipt of rents and profits in actions for the recovery of land other than those for non-payment of rent or overholding?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. In the absence of any statutory provision regulating service, every summons issued against a corporation aggregate may be served on the mayor or other head officer, or on the town clerk, clerk, treasurer, or secretary of such corporation; and every summons issued against the inhabitants of a county district or other like district may be served on any officer of the Gárda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent stationed in the county in which such district is situate and every summons issued against the inhabitants of any county or any city or town, or the inhabitants of any franchise, liberty, city, town, or place not being part of the county district or other like district on some peace officer thereof: provided always that in all such cases a sufficient notice of the issuing of the summons shall be given in Iris Oifigiúil and in one of the local newspapers of the county, city, or district in which the defendant or defendants or the officer or other person to be served shall reside, the times for appearing to run in such cases from the day of the publication of such notice in Iris Oifigiúil or such newspaper, whichever shall be the latest; and where, by any statute, provision is made for service of any proceedings upon any corporation, or upon any society or fellowship, or any body or number of persons, whether corporate or incorporate, every summons may be served in the manner so provided. # **III. In particular actions** 8. In an action brought for recovery of land for non-payment of rent or for overholding, it shall not be necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 9. In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons for the recovery of land be served by posting it on the door of the property if it is vacant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '10. In actions for the recovery of land service of a summons may be effected either by personal service on the person to be served at any place within the jurisdiction or by delivering a copy of such summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister, of such person, at her house, or office, or place of business (the person with whom such copy shall be left being of the age of sixteen years or upwards), and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons, and such service as last aforesaid may be effected whether the person to be served is within the jurisdiction or not. 11. Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property; provided, however, that in such case before any judgment by default shall be given, the Court shall be satisfied that there was no person in actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits on whom other service might have been effected. # General** 12. [[2]](#_ftn2) (1) The person serving a summons shall, within three days at most after service, indorse on the summons the day and date of the service thereof; and every affidavit of service of such summons shall mention the date on which such indorsement was made. (1A) An Indorsement of service by prepaid registered post shall be in the following terms: “INDORSEMENT OF SERVICE served the within summons on [person to be served] by posting the same by prepaid registered post to [him] [her] at [address] on the ... day of ........ 20...” Signed ................ This ... day of ........ 20..”. (2) Every affidavit of service of a summons by prepaid registered post shall exhibit proof of delivery of the envelope in which a copy of the summons is contained to the address of the person to be served.”;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is the affidavit of service required to state information about people in possession of the land in actions for recovery of land other than for non-payment of rent or overholding?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every affidavit of service of a summons in other actions for recovery of land, shall state that the deponent does not know of and does not believe that there is any person, other than those who have been served, in the actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits of the land sought to be recovered, or any part thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. Every affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent, or for overholding, shall state that the deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 14. Every affidavit of service of a summons in other actions for recovery of land, shall state that the deponent does not know of and does not believe that there is any person, other than those who have been served, in the actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits of the land sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, and the said statement shall be verified by the affidavit of the plaintiff or of one of the plaintiffs, or of the solicitor for the plaintiff. 15. In any case the Court may, upon just grounds, declare the service actually effected sufficient. 16. [[3]](#_ftn3) This Order shall, so far as practicable, apply to an originating document and to notice in lieu of service, save where any other Order of these Rules requires personal service of such document or notice. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 9 rule 2 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017. [[2]](#_ftnref2) Order 9 rule 12 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 9 rule 16 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[4]](#26120231) Order 9 rule 6 substituted by 261 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/261/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,(Capacity) Act 2015) 2023&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of May, 2023.)effective 15 May 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol) - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under section 7 of the Act of 1983 be held in a location where the defendant has assets if their residence or registered office is not in the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located in the State, wherein the defendant has a place of business, or if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business in the State, wherein the defendant has assets"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings brought before the Court pursuant to section 7 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) for the recovery of a sum due to the Organisation in respect of air navigation facilities and services provided by that body, or by any other person, shall be brought, heard and determined before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area - wherein the defendant''s residence or, as the case may be, the defendant''s registered office, is located, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located in the State, wherein the defendant has a place of business, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business in the State, wherein the defendant has assets, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business or assets in the State, wherein the Organisation, for the time being, has its headquarters.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Is a civil summons used to initiate proceedings for a debt or liquidated money demand?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such proceedings shall be instituted by the issue of a civil summons for a debt or liquidated money demand in the Form 39.2"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings by civil summons* 3. Such proceedings shall be instituted by the issue of a civil summons for a debt or liquidated money demand in the Form 39.2, [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), and the provisions of these Rules relating thereto shall mutatis mutandis apply to such proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Is a court fee required when applying for a certified copy of a determination?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"shall pay any prescribed court fee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Copies of decrees and civil summonses* 4. (1) A person seeking a certified copy of a determination for the purposes of section 9 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall complete and lodge with the Clerk the relevant decree in duplicate, together with an affidavit of debt (where appropriate) in duplicate, and shall pay any prescribed court fee. When the decree has been signed by the Judge, the Clerk shall retain the original decree and affidavit, and shall certify and issue the copies to the applicant therefor. (2) Upon application being made under the said section 9 and upon payment of the prescribed court fee, the Clerk shall prepare, certify and issue to the applicant therefor a copy of the original civil summons (including the statutory declaration as to service).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application to be made to a Judge of the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of the Act has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure - Court: District # Order 90A: Railway Infrastructure [1] 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) (No. 55 of 2001); the expression “**railway undertaking**” shall have the meaning given to it by [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html). 2. (1) An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 90A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1d1db340-330e-4387-938c-e9a5ecc61795/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 No. 90A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served by the applicant on the railway undertaking by or on whose behalf the notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) was served by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) An order made pursuant to paragraph of sub-section (1) of section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 90A.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26b82729-add3-4081-bb86-32bbaa7cb989/Order (Prohibiting entry on land) - (Specifying conditions for entry on land) - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act, 2001 No. 90A.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 90A inserted by [S.I. 534 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/534/made/en/print?q 534&years 2004), effective 9 October 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a specific type of court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 91 - Control of dogs - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Control of Dogs Act, 1986 referred to in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order— "**the Act**" means the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings for an offense under the Act be heard urgently if certified by the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a summons that such proceedings are urgent, the summons may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prosecution of offences* 2. (1) Proceedings in respect of an offence alleged under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the offence is alleged to have been committed. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a summons that such proceedings are urgent, the summons may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) An offence under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be prosecuted by the local authority in whose area the offence is alleged to have been committed. (4) Proceedings in respect of such an offence may be commenced by the issuing by the appropriate office of the District Court, on the application of the relevant local authority, of a summons in the Form 7, [Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings). Such summons shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the summons. (5) When service has been effected the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Can a complaint about a dangerous dog be heard urgently?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings under section 22 (1) (a)* 3. (1) A complaint under section 22 (1) (a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a dog is dangerous and not kept under proper control may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises of the owner of the dog or, as the case may be, of the person in charge of the dog are situated. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/544ad476-7a56-498b-8aa5-8f590c7e857a/Notice of intention to make a complaint that a dog is dangerous - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.1.docx/docx/1) upon the defendant (the person in charge of the dog) and, where the defendant is not the owner of the dog, also upon such owner. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the complaint. (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7fde4400-ce69-4e93-aae2-e5cf8a343f62/Order in relation to a dangerous dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.2.docx/docx/1). A copy of such order shall be given to the defendant and, where the defendant is not the owner of the dog, a copy of the order shall also be given to such owner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Can a complaint about excessive barking be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A complaint under section 25 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a nuisance has been created as a result of excessive barking by a dog may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog, is kept are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings under sec. 25* 4. (1) A complaint under section 25 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a nuisance has been created as a result of excessive barking by a dog may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog, is kept are situated. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the occupier of the premises in which the dog is kept of the notice referred to in section 25 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) and which is prescribed in the [Control of Dogs (No. 2) Regulations, 1987 (S.I. No. 59 of 1987)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/si/59/made/en/print#). Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall forthwith be lodged with the Clerk. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eb9b13cb-37ea-4fa3-82e3-9ca378b2c360/Order in relation to excessive barking by a dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.3.docx/docx/1). A copy of such order shall be given to the defendant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a search warrant under section 26 of the Act required to be made in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The application shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 91.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant (sec. 26)* 5. (1) An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a search warrant under section 26 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated. (2) The application shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 91.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aea308cb-d223-424f-81f3-9650004e1bc1/Information for search warrant - Control of Dogs Act, 1986 section 26 No. 91.4.docx/docx/1). (3) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 91.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/215e6650-979f-4004-8e77-ca3f7cf4a220/Search Warrant - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued when making an application to remove a disqualification?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 91.6, Schedule upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to remove disqualification (sec. 29)* 6. (1) An application under section 27 (1) of the Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act, 1965 (as substituted by section 29 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html)) to remove a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/882474dd-72bc-48b5-bee9-bd2a11777c05/Notice of application to remove a disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.6.docx/docx/1) upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 91.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ff2c7d9-466f-4e80-90c8-e7b4e83c097a/Order Removing Disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text related to a higher judicial body?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 92 - Fire services - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be served on the occupier or owner of the building or land related to the fire safety notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"which notice shall be served upon the occupier or the owner, as the case may be, of the building or land to which the fire safety notice relates"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Fire safety notice —* 3. (1) An application under section 20 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) for an order concerning expenses or their apportionment shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 92.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/779274ae-4cf3-451e-83a4-2fad89593bf6/Notice Of Application Under Section 20 (4) - Fire Services Act 1981 No. 92.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant; which notice shall be served upon the occupier or the owner, as the case may be, of the building or land to which the fire safety notice relates, and upon the fire authority which served the fire safety notice. The notice shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) The original of every such notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court hearing the application shall be in the [Form 92.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54de9278-0351-4425-b9ad-85aaa9ec4414/Order Pursuant To Section 20 (4) - Fire Services Act 1981 No. 92.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of appeal required before filing an appeal against a fire safety notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal under section 21 of [the Act] against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeal against fire safety notice* 4. (1) An appeal under section 21 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal in the [Form 92.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68b51881-c383-4d75-b941-078c4ad85a8e/Notice Of Appeal - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.3.docx/docx/1), signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant; which notice shall be given to the respondent fire authority, in accordance with the provisions of sections 21 (2) and 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html), at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice of appeal is returnable. (2) A copy of the notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 92.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36288ceb-a7e4-42c5-9a63-dec4bdf9011e/Order On Appeal (Fire Services Act, 1981) No. 92.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant under section 22 (7) required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Warrant under section 22 (7)* 5. (1) An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority. The information shall be in the [Form 15.3, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d4746c0f-a588-4e2d-85f0-2c1c313b6d04/Information No. 15.3.docx/docx/1), with suitable modifications. (2) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 92.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86b21325-bbf4-4ecf-99b7-50543cb92d4e/Warrant Under Section 22 (7) Of The Act - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a High Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings) - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the Act be held at any sitting of the Court within the relevant court area?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under [the Act] may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which is situated the dwelling in relation to which the proceedings are brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which is situated the dwelling in relation to which the proceedings are brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for proof of service of notices?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proof of service shall be by statutory declaration."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of notices* 4. (1) Notices required by this Order to be served shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 4 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), and where service is effected by registered prepaid post the provisions of section 7 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended, shall apply. (2) Every such notice shall be served one month at least before the date of sitting of the Court to which the notice has been made returnable. Proof of service shall be by statutory declaration. The original of every such notice, with the statutory declaration endorsed thereon, shall be lodged with the Clerk four days at least before the date of sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Are the costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of the Act determined by specific scales?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), where allowed, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scales set out in the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any similar scales in any other such schedule for the time being in force."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), where allowed, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scales set out in the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any similar scales in any other such schedule for the time being in force. Costs of any other proceedings under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) shall be at the discretion of the Court and may be measured under [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), 14 hereof. [1]Order 93, sub-rules (4) to (7) of rule 3 replaced by sub-rules (4) to (6) by 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93A - Applications under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for an order made on an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order made on such application shall be in the Form 93A.4, 93A.5 or 93A.6, Schedule as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The copy of the notice of application referred to in this Order shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 93A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b27e136e-ac12-4e35-8a72-a566d53d6a28/Order that damage be made good - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 44(4)(a)(i) No. 93A.4.docx/docx/1), [93A.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4ef4206f-ba02-4849-9cec-f4a822a47a29/Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 45 No. 93A.5.docx/docx/1) or [93A.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3afbc994-29ad-44d1-adea-f811721a336f/Order Discharging - Modifying A Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 47 No. 93A.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served upon the building owner and every adjoining owner concerned, and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. (5) Every application mentioned in this rule may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court area wherein the party structure to which the application relates is situated. 3. Proceedings in the Court under section 44(4)(a)(ii) or under section may be commenced by civil summons in accordance with [Order 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93A - Applications under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court deem posting a notice at the entrance of the property as sufficient service if the mortgagor is untraceable?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if the mortgagor is untraceable, if a copy of the notice is affixed to, or posted at, the entrance of the property concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. An application to the Court for an order under section 98(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html) authorising a mortgagee to take possession of property may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court area wherein the mortgaged property to which the application relates is situated. Such an application shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant on the mortgagor concerned of a copy of a notice of application in the [Form 93A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bd9a4c8-9dd2-4777-9b4f-10a704cb5bb6/Notice Of Application For Order Authorising Mortgagee To Take Possession Of Abandoned Property - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 98(1) No. 93A.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which notice shall state whether any court is already seised of an application or proceedings relating to the mortgaged property. Without prejudice to the power of the Court to make an order for substituted service or to substitute notice for service, the Court may deem it sufficient service, if the mortgagor is untraceable, if a copy of the notice is affixed to, or posted at, the entrance of the property concerned. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 93A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e395eb35-4084-438f-a84d-77c8b289ed05/Order Authorising Mortgagee To Take Possession Of Abandoned Property - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 98(2) No. 93A.8.docx/docx/1), and the applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served as directed by the Court. [1] Order 93A inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2010), effective 17 May 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the applicant required to serve the Registrar with copies of the notice of application and affidavits before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall serve on the Registrar a copy of the notice of application and copies of any affidavit and exhibits relied on not later than 21 days before the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An affidavit relied on in an application under this Order shall be sworn by a director or secretary of the applicant and shall- - (a) verify the facts set out in the notice of application; - where the annual return proposed to be delivered has been prepared, exhibit a copy of same (including both the annual return in the form for the time being prescribed by the Registrar of Companies and any financial statements of the company required to be delivered to the Registrar of Companies), or explain why it has not been possible to prepare same; - set out, and verify any facts supporting, the reasons why the annual return was not delivered to the Registrar within the time permitted by section 343(2) or section 343(3) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) and set out, and verify any facts supporting, any additional reasons why it is alleged that it would be just to make an order extending time; - exhibit any correspondence between the applicant and the Registrar concerning the application, including in particular any correspondence from the applicant notifying the Registrar of its intention to make the application and any response by the Registrar. 3. (1) The applicant shall serve on the Registrar a copy of the notice of application and copies of any affidavit and exhibits relied on not later than 21 days before the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) In every case, the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The applicant shall, when lodging the original notice of application with the Clerk, also lodge a statutory declaration as to service on the Registrar. 4. Notwithstanding rule 2- - (a) the applicant shall be obliged to produce at the hearing of the application any correspondence received from the Registrar which has not been exhibited to any affidavit;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for an order extending time?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An order extending time in accordance with section 343(5) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 93B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1bad2aea-2220-45d6-9d57-ba97c8495aa/Order extending the time in which annual return may be delivered to the registrar of companies No. 93B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the Court may allow, or may direct, that evidence on the application be given viva voce and on oath by an officer of the applicant or another person in addition to, or in lieu of, evidence on affidavit. 5. An order extending time in accordance with section 343(5) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 93B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1bad2aea-2220-45d6-9d57-ba97c84951aa/Order extending the time in which annual return may be delivered to the registrar of companies No. 93B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause a certified copy of the order to be served upon the Registrar in accordance with section 343(6) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html), and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. 6. An application under this Order may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court district wherein the registered office of the applicant company is situated. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 256 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/256/made/en/print?q 256&years 2015), effective 1 July 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 - Court: District # Order Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 referred to in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “**Act of 2004**” means the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Definitions** In this Order— the “**Act of 2004**” means the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended; “**authorised officer** ” means a person appointed under section 164A of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) to be an authorised officer; the “**Board**” means the Residential Tenancies Board as established by section 150 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html); a “**determination order**” shall be interpreted having regard to the provisions of section 121 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when making an application for enforcement of a determination order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application must be in Form No. Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Determination orders** 2. (1) All applications by the Board or by a party mentioned in a determination order under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for enforcement of a determination order must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the tenancy or dwelling concerned is or was situated. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of section 124 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended and must contain the name and address of the applicant as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The notice of application must set out the grounds on which the applicant relies for the reliefs sought and must have annexed thereto the original determination order or a certified copy of same, certified by the applicant as being a true copy of the determination order. The return date of the notice of application must be not less than 21 days after the date on which the notice of application is issued. (6) The notice of application must be supported by a grounding affidavit setting out and verifying the facts relied on in the application. Copies of the affidavit and any exhibits must be served with the notice of application on the respondent. (7) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally or in accordance with sub-rule (9). (8) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal service required for serving the notice of application in all cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the notice of application must be served personally or by prepaid registered post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(9) Where the relief sought in an application includes the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, the proceedings may be served by delivering copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits, addressed to the respondent at the dwelling to which the determination relates or, where such service cannot be effected, by leaving copies of those documents at the dwelling or by attaching those documents to the door or some other conspicuous part of the dwelling. In all other cases, the notice of application must be served personally or by prepaid registered post. (10) If the respondent intends to oppose the application and the applicant is not the Board, the respondent must give notice of such intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition to the Board and to the applicant no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application. Such notice must be served on the Board by leaving a true copy of same at the registered offices of the Board or by pre-paid registered post to the registered offices of the Board. (11) Save by special leave of the Court, all applications under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be heard on affidavit evidence or as may be determined by the Court. (12) On the return date of the notice of application the Court may, if it does not hear and determine the application, proceed in accordance with [Order 40C]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40C-District-Procedure-In-Statutory-Applications-By-Notice-Of-Application), rule 7. (13)[2] Where an order is made for the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, a warrant for possession may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), and [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments) shall apply to such warrant for possession. Where an order is made for the recovery of money, or for costs, a warrant authorising execution may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments). ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for applications under section', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application must be in Form No. Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers under section 3. (1) An application by an authorised officer under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person in respect of whom the application is made resides or carries on any profession, trade or business. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must: - show on its face how or by whom the consent of the Board to the making of the application was given; - where the requirement to which the application relates was made in writing, have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the written requirement, and include particulars of service of the requirement on the respondent or delivery of the requirement to the respondent; - (iii) where the requirement to which the application relates was not made in writing, include particulars of the requirement and of how it was communicated to the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of section of the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the applicant as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The return date of the notice of application must be not less than 21 days after the date on which the notice of application is issued. (6) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (7) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application must be in Form No. Schedule modified as appropriate to the case"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers or the Board under Schedule 3** 4. (1) An application: - by an authorised officer for an order under paragraph 5 of Part of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, or - by the Board for an order under paragraph 5 of Part 2 of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person required to attend the oral hearing ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the notice in writing issued to the respondent under paragraph 2 of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and include particulars of service of the notice on the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the authorised officer or, as the case may be, the Board as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (6) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 69 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/69/made/en/print?q 69&years 2018), effective 23 March 2018 and substituted by [S.I. 431 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/431/made/en/print), effective 22 October 2020 [2] Order rule 2(13) inserted by 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 94 related to Irish nationality and citizenship?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Must a declaration of fidelity to the nation and loyalty to the State be made in open court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"when made before a Judge of the District Court, shall be made in open court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. A declaration of fidelity to the nation and loyalty to the State pursuant to section 15 (1) — (as inserted by section 4 of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/23/enacted/en/html)) - of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/26/enacted/en/print.html), when made before a Judge of the District Court, shall be made in open court and may be made at any sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Is the form of declaration for nationality and citizenship specified in the Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations of 1956?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The prescribed form of such declaration is contained in [Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations, 1956 (S.I. No. 216 of 1956)]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of declaration* 3. The prescribed form of such declaration is contained in [Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations, 1956 (S.I. No. 216 of 1956)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/si/216/made/en/print#).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 95 related to malicious injuries in a district court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Order 95 - Malicious injuries - Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 95 - Malicious injuries - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Malicious Injuries Act, 1981 referred to as the Principal Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Principal Act means the Malicious Injuries Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - "**the Acts**" means the [Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) and [1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Malicious Injuries Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 9 of 1981). "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Malicious Injuries (Amendment) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1986); "**ratepayer**" means any ratepayer of a local authority which is a party to any proceedings for compensation under the Acts; "**third party**" means a local authority notified under section 10 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the Clerk to maintain a specific book related to malicious injuries?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Malicious Injuries Book* 5. The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book in which shall be entered particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Are the costs awarded to the applicant apportioned when liability for compensation is shared between multiple local authorities?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs, where awarded, other than costs of an application for compensation which are payable by a local authority, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules. Where liability for compensation is apportioned between two or more local authorities, the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge the form of consent or settlement with the Clerk when a local authority settles a claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the form of consent or settlement (and withdrawal of application) signed by the parties (or a copy thereof) shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Settlements* 7. Where under section 16 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) a local authority settles a claim brought against it, the form of consent or settlement (and withdrawal of application) signed by the parties (or a copy thereof) shall be lodged with the Clerk, who shall note the settlement in the Malicious Injuries Book and retain the documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for making a lodgment under section 16(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgments in court* 8. A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application and the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules relating to lodgments shall mutatis mutandis apply to such lodgment, but a notice of intention to defend shall not be required.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court exempt an appellant from entering into a recognisance for appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeals to the Circuit Court* 9. (1) The provisions of [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed shall mutatis mutandis apply to every appeal, including an appeal by a ratepayer, taken under section 17 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation under [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) as amended by [the Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific order mentioned that details the procedure for cases stated to the Supreme Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 102 of these Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Cases stated to the Supreme Court* 10. The procedure to be followed in relation to cases stated for the opinion of the Supreme Court under section 18 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) are contained in [Order 102]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-102-District-Cases-stated) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before making an application under section', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall, to the extent possible, be served upon each of the persons referred to in section 43B(1)(a) to of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6cf2c6b-7f10-49ae-b5bf-a33b0be2f3d4/Order Varying - Discharging - A Condition Restriction - Attaching To - An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each of the respondents and upon any other person directly affected by the Order'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice with the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for the appeal required to follow a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7df7bf9-2542-4e31-85e7-615f4b1e2d36/Order on appeal - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13(3) No. 88.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 23(1) be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under Sec. 23 (1)* 5. (1) An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to lodge the original notice along with a statutory declaration after service is effected?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order to be given in Form 88.8 if the application is granted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in the [Form 88.8, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in the [Form 88.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c721def-fff2-4ab0-adcb-f6d6ac13b419/Order for information about proceeds of collection - Street and House to House Collections Act 1962 No. 88.8.docx/docx/1). A certified copy of such order shall be given or sent to the respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal under section 29(7) be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the appellant resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 29 (7) of [the Act] against the refusal by the Minister to grant or renew a licence to hunt with firearms may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 29 (7)* 2. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 29 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against the refusal by the Minister to grant or renew a licence to hunt with firearms may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides or, where the appellant is ordinarily resident outside the State, temporarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required before an appeal can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ff20174-1e3f-46a0-8f04-7b01bf4f26b9/Notice of appeal against refusal of the minister to a licence to hunt with firearms - renew - Wildlife Act, 1976 No. 89.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required for the Clerk to send a copy of the Court''s order to the Minister if the appeal is allowed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e981c916-43d9-4f8b-9225-3fcf1aaf901c/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 29(7) No. 89.2.docx/docx/1). (5) Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application to amend a wildlife dealer''s licence be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence pursuant to section 48 (7) of [the Act] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application to amend licence* 4. (1) An application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence pursuant to section 48 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be completed before submitting an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the completion of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the completion of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9c2c498-7806-4f94-b46d-36cb81488b97/Notice of application to amend wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.5.docx/docx/1)) which shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a minimum notice period required for serving notice on individuals affected by an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal, in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), at least seven days or, where service is effected by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal, in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), at least seven days or, where service is effected by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required when lodging a notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order for an appeal specified to follow a particular form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.7] or [89.8] Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/55bd89bf-fa2f-4689-b7b7-eb25942efe37/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.7.docx/docx/1) or [89.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7082ac7d-a829-4d9a-b80d-876e7ab00e40/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 68 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the land is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 9. (1) An application pursuant to section 68 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the land is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order specified to be in a particular form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 89.13, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- order of the Court* (3) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 89.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c7f6c7-c1c8-457c-99c2-f21b8ca691b4/Order (prohibiting entry on land) - (specifying conditions for entry on land) - Wildlife Act 1976 No. 89.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 9 - Joinder of Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claim for mesne profits be joined with a claim for the recovery of land?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Joinder of Claims - Court: Circuit 1. Save as in the next succeeding Rule provided, two or more claims may be made in one originating document, either alternatively or otherwise, so long as the claims are not mutually inconsistent or based on inconsistent allegations of fact, but, if it appears to the Judge that claims joined in any action or matter cannot be conveniently tried together, he may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the record to be amended accordingly, and may make such order as to costs as may seem just. 2. No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof, and damages for breach of any contract under which the land, or any part thereof, is held, or for any wrong or injury to the said land, or any part thereof. An action for redemption, and a motion for delivery by a defendant of possession of mortgaged property therein, shall not be deemed a claim for the recovery of land within the meaning of this Rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons be served on a defendant by sending it via registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Service of summons - Court: Superior # Mode of service** 1. No service of a summons shall be required when the defendant, by his solicitor, accepts service, and undertakes in writing to enter an appearance. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) Service of any summons on the defendant shall, except in the cases in the following rules of this Order specified, be effected: - by personal service upon the person to be served, or - by personal service upon another person referred to in sub-rule (2) on behalf of the person to be served, or - (iii) by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served, provided that such service shall not be deemed effective without proof of delivery of the said envelope to the address of the person to be served, or - where the defendant is a company, in accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014. (2) Where it shall appear by affidavit that the defendant is personally within the jurisdiction and that due and reasonable diligence has been exercised in endeavouring to effect personal service on him or her, service of the summons may be effected by delivering a copy thereof at - (a) the defendant''s usual or last known place of residence within the jurisdiction, or - the defendant''s principal or last known place of business or office, to the wife, husband, civil partner (within the meaning of section 3 of the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010) father, mother, brother, or sister of the defendant, or to any employee of the defendant (the person to whom such copy shall be delivered being of the age of sixteen years or upwards) and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is it necessary to serve the summons on every person in actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits of the lands in other actions for the recovery of land?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. In the absence of any statutory provision regulating service, every summons issued against a corporation aggregate may be served on the mayor or other head officer, or on the town clerk, clerk, treasurer, or secretary of such corporation; and every summons issued against the inhabitants of a county district or other like district may be served on any officer of the Gárda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent stationed in the county in which such district is situate and every summons issued against the inhabitants of any county or any city or town, or the inhabitants of any franchise, liberty, city, town, or place not being part of the county district or other like district on some peace officer thereof: provided always that in all such cases a sufficient notice of the issuing of the summons shall be given in Iris Oifigiúil and in one of the local newspapers of the county, city, or district in which the defendant or defendants or the officer or other person to be served shall reside, the times for appearing to run in such cases from the day of the publication of such notice in Iris Oifigiúil or such newspaper, whichever shall be the latest; and where, by any statute, provision is made for service of any proceedings upon any corporation, or upon any society or fellowship, or any body or number of persons, whether corporate or incorporate, every summons may be served in the manner so provided. # **III. In particular actions** 8. In an action brought for recovery of land for non-payment of rent or for overholding, it shall not be necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 9. In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons for recovering land be served by posting it on the door of the property if it''s vacant?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '10. In actions for the recovery of land service of a summons may be effected either by personal service on the person to be served at any place within the jurisdiction or by delivering a copy of such summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister, of such person, at her house, or office, or place of business (the person with whom such copy shall be left being of the age of sixteen years or upwards), and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons, and such service as last aforesaid may be effected whether the person to be served is within the jurisdiction or not. 11. Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property; provided, however, that in such case before any judgment by default shall be given, the Court shall be satisfied that there was no person in actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits on whom other service might have been effected. # General** 12. [[2]](#_ftn2) (1) The person serving a summons shall, within three days at most after service, indorse on the summons the day and date of the service thereof; and every affidavit of service of such summons shall mention the date on which such indorsement was made. (1A) An Indorsement of service by prepaid registered post shall be in the following terms: “INDORSEMENT OF SERVICE served the within summons on [person to be served] by posting the same by prepaid registered post to [him] [her] at [address] on the ... day of ........ 20...” Signed ................ This ... day of ........ 20..”. (2) Every affidavit of service of a summons by prepaid registered post shall exhibit proof of delivery of the envelope in which a copy of the summons is contained to the address of the person to be served.”;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'Is the affidavit of service required to state information about other people in possession of the land?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Every affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent, or for overholding, shall state that the deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. Every affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent, or for overholding, shall state that the deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 14. Every affidavit of service of a summons in other actions for recovery of land, shall state that the deponent does not know of and does not believe that there is any person, other than those who have been served, in the actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits of the land sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, and the said statement shall be verified by the affidavit of the plaintiff or of one of the plaintiffs, or of the solicitor for the plaintiff. 15. In any case the Court may, upon just grounds, declare the service actually effected sufficient. 16. [[3]](#_ftn3) This Order shall, so far as practicable, apply to an originating document and to notice in lieu of service, save where any other Order of these Rules requires personal service of such document or notice. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 9 rule 2 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017. [[2]](#_ftnref2) Order 9 rule 12 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 9 rule 16 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[4]](#26120231) Order 9 rule 6 substituted by 261 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/261/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,(Capacity) Act 2015) 2023&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of May, 2023.)effective 15 May 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 90 related to air navigation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol) - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the venue for proceedings specified based on the location of the defendant''s residence or registered office?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings brought before the Court pursuant to section 7 of the [Act of 1983] for the recovery of a sum due to the Organisation in respect of air navigation facilities and services provided by that body, or by any other person, shall be brought, heard and determined before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the defendant''s residence or, as the case may be, the defendant''s registered office, is located"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings brought before the Court pursuant to section 7 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) for the recovery of a sum due to the Organisation in respect of air navigation facilities and services provided by that body, or by any other person, shall be brought, heard and determined before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area - wherein the defendant''s residence or, as the case may be, the defendant''s registered office, is located, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located in the State, wherein the defendant has a place of business, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business in the State, wherein the defendant has assets, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business or assets in the State, wherein the Organisation, for the time being, has its headquarters.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application related to a notice given under section 48(1) of the Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of the Act has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure - Court: District # Order 90A: Railway Infrastructure [1] 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) (No. 55 of 2001); the expression “**railway undertaking**” shall have the meaning given to it by [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html). 2. (1) An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 90A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1d1db340-330e-4387-938c-e9a5ecc61795/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 No. 90A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served by the applicant on the railway undertaking by or on whose behalf the notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) was served by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) An order made pursuant to paragraph of sub-section (1) of section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 90A.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26b82729-add3-4081-bb86-32bbaa7cb989/Order (Prohibiting entry on land) - (Specifying conditions for entry on land) - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act, 2001 No. 90A.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 90A inserted by [S.I. 534 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/534/made/en/print?q 534&years 2004), effective 9 October 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order related to controlling dogs?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Control of dogs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 91 - Control of dogs - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Control of Dogs Act, 1986 referred to in this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order— "**the Act**" means the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings for an offense under the Act be heard urgently?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a summons that such proceedings are urgent, the summons may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prosecution of offences* 2. (1) Proceedings in respect of an offence alleged under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the offence is alleged to have been committed. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a summons that such proceedings are urgent, the summons may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) An offence under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be prosecuted by the local authority in whose area the offence is alleged to have been committed. (4) Proceedings in respect of such an offence may be commenced by the issuing by the appropriate office of the District Court, on the application of the relevant local authority, of a summons in the Form 7, [Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings). Such summons shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the summons. (5) When service has been effected the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be issued when making an application to remove a disqualification?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form 91.6, Schedule upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to remove disqualification (sec. 29)* 6. (1) An application under section 27 (1) of the Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act, 1965 (as substituted by section 29 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html)) to remove a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/882474dd-72bc-48b5-bee9-bd2a11777c05/Notice of application to remove a disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.6.docx/docx/1) upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 91.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ff2c7d9-466f-4e80-90c8-e7b4e83c097a/Order Removing Disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the appellant to provide a notice of appeal before making an appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal under section 21 of [the Act] against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeal against fire safety notice* 4. (1) An appeal under section 21 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal in the [Form 92.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68b51881-c383-4d75-b941-078c4ad85a8e/Notice Of Appeal - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.3.docx/docx/1), signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant; which notice shall be given to the respondent fire authority, in accordance with the provisions of sections 21 (2) and 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html), at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice of appeal is returnable. (2) A copy of the notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 92.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36288ceb-a7e4-42c5-9a63-dec4bdf9011e/Order On Appeal (Fire Services Act, 1981) No. 92.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant under section 22 (7) made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Warrant under section 22 (7)* 5. (1) An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority. The information shall be in the [Form 15.3, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d4746c0f-a588-4e2d-85f0-2c1c313b6d04/Information No. 15.3.docx/docx/1), with suitable modifications. (2) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 92.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86b21325-bbf4-4ecf-99b7-50543cb92d4e/Warrant Under Section 22 (7) Of The Act - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982 referred to in this definition?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order - "**the Act**" means the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) (Amendment) Act, 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 1983).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93A - Applications under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the original notice of application required to be lodged with the Clerk before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The copy of the notice of application referred to in this Order shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 93A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b27e136e-ac12-4e35-8a72-a566d53d6a28/Order that damage be made good - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 44(4)(a)(i) No. 93A.4.docx/docx/1), [93A.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4ef4206f-ba02-4849-9cec-f4a822a47a29/Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 45 No. 93A.5.docx/docx/1) or [93A.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3afbc994-29ad-44d1-adea-f811721a336f/Order Discharging - Modifying A Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 47 No. 93A.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served upon the building owner and every adjoining owner concerned, and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. (5) Every application mentioned in this rule may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court area wherein the party structure to which the application relates is situated. 3. Proceedings in the Court under section 44(4)(a)(ii) or under section may be commenced by civil summons in accordance with [Order 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the affidavit required to be sworn by a specific person within the company?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An affidavit relied on in an application under this Order shall be sworn by a director or secretary of the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An affidavit relied on in an application under this Order shall be sworn by a director or secretary of the applicant and shall- - (a) verify the facts set out in the notice of application; - where the annual return proposed to be delivered has been prepared, exhibit a copy of same (including both the annual return in the form for the time being prescribed by the Registrar of Companies and any financial statements of the company required to be delivered to the Registrar of Companies), or explain why it has not been possible to prepare same; - set out, and verify any facts supporting, the reasons why the annual return was not delivered to the Registrar within the time permitted by section 343(2) or section 343(3) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) and set out, and verify any facts supporting, any additional reasons why it is alleged that it would be just to make an order extending time; - exhibit any correspondence between the applicant and the Registrar concerning the application, including in particular any correspondence from the applicant notifying the Registrar of its intention to make the application and any response by the Registrar. 3. (1) The applicant shall serve on the Registrar a copy of the notice of application and copies of any affidavit and exhibits relied on not later than 21 days before the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) In every case, the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The applicant shall, when lodging the original notice of application with the Clerk, also lodge a statutory declaration as to service on the Registrar. 4. Notwithstanding rule 2- - (a) the applicant shall be obliged to produce at the hearing of the application any correspondence received from the Registrar which has not been exhibited to any affidavit;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court require additional evidence to be provided on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Court may allow, or may direct, that evidence on the application be given viva voce and on oath by an officer of the applicant or another person in addition to, or in lieu of, evidence on affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the Court may allow, or may direct, that evidence on the application be given viva voce and on oath by an officer of the applicant or another person in addition to, or in lieu of, evidence on affidavit. 5. An order extending time in accordance with section 343(5) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 93B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1bad2aea-2220-45d6-9d57-ba97c84951aa/Order extending the time in which annual return may be delivered to the registrar of companies No. 93B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause a certified copy of the order to be served upon the Registrar in accordance with section 343(6) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html), and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. 6. An application under this Order may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court district wherein the registered office of the applicant company is situated. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 256 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/256/made/en/print?q 256&years 2015), effective 1 July 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the order a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 - Court: District # Order Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time limit mentioned for the respondent to notify their intention to oppose an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the respondent must give notice of such intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition to the Board and to the applicant no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(9) Where the relief sought in an application includes the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, the proceedings may be served by delivering copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits, addressed to the respondent at the dwelling to which the determination relates or, where such service cannot be effected, by leaving copies of those documents at the dwelling or by attaching those documents to the door or some other conspicuous part of the dwelling. In all other cases, the notice of application must be served personally or by prepaid registered post. (10) If the respondent intends to oppose the application and the applicant is not the Board, the respondent must give notice of such intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition to the Board and to the applicant no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application. Such notice must be served on the Board by leaving a true copy of same at the registered offices of the Board or by pre-paid registered post to the registered offices of the Board. (11) Save by special leave of the Court, all applications under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be heard on affidavit evidence or as may be determined by the Court. (12) On the return date of the notice of application the Court may, if it does not hear and determine the application, proceed in accordance with [Order 40C]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40C-District-Procedure-In-Statutory-Applications-By-Notice-Of-Application), rule 7. (13)[2] Where an order is made for the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, a warrant for possession may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), and [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments) shall apply to such warrant for possession. Where an order is made for the recovery of money, or for costs, a warrant authorising execution may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments). ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for applications under section', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The notice of application must be in Form No. Schedule modified as appropriate to the case"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers under section 3. (1) An application by an authorised officer under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person in respect of whom the application is made resides or carries on any profession, trade or business. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must: - show on its face how or by whom the consent of the Board to the making of the application was given; - where the requirement to which the application relates was made in writing, have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the written requirement, and include particulars of service of the requirement on the respondent or delivery of the requirement to the respondent; - (iii) where the requirement to which the application relates was not made in writing, include particulars of the requirement and of how it was communicated to the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of section of the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the applicant as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The return date of the notice of application must be not less than 21 days after the date on which the notice of application is issued. (6) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (7) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of application required to be served at least seven days before the return date when served personally?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers or the Board under Schedule 3** 4. (1) An application: - by an authorised officer for an order under paragraph 5 of Part of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, or - by the Board for an order under paragraph 5 of Part 2 of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person required to attend the oral hearing ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the notice in writing issued to the respondent under paragraph 2 of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and include particulars of service of the notice on the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the authorised officer or, as the case may be, the Board as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (6) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 69 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/69/made/en/print?q 69&years 2018), effective 23 March 2018 and substituted by [S.I. 431 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/431/made/en/print), effective 22 October 2020 [2] Order rule 2(13) inserted by 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Is the declaration of fidelity and loyalty required to be made in open court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"shall be made in open court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. A declaration of fidelity to the nation and loyalty to the State pursuant to section 15 (1) — (as inserted by section 4 of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/23/enacted/en/html)) - of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/26/enacted/en/print.html), when made before a Judge of the District Court, shall be made in open court and may be made at any sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 95 related to malicious injuries?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Malicious injuries"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 95 - Malicious injuries - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Malicious Injuries Act of 1981 referred to as the Principal Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Principal Act means the Malicious Injuries Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - "**the Acts**" means the [Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) and [1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Malicious Injuries Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 9 of 1981). "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Malicious Injuries (Amendment) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1986); "**ratepayer**" means any ratepayer of a local authority which is a party to any proceedings for compensation under the Acts; "**third party**" means a local authority notified under section 10 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific book designated for recording malicious injuries cases?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Malicious Injuries Book* 5. The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book in which shall be entered particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Are the costs awarded to an applicant when they receive compensation typically shared among multiple local authorities if liability is split?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where liability for compensation is apportioned between two or more local authorities, the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs, where awarded, other than costs of an application for compensation which are payable by a local authority, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules. Where liability for compensation is apportioned between two or more local authorities, the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is it required to lodge the form of consent or settlement with the Clerk when a local authority settles a claim?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the form of consent or settlement (and withdrawal of application) signed by the parties (or a copy thereof) shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Settlements* 7. Where under section 16 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) a local authority settles a claim brought against it, the form of consent or settlement (and withdrawal of application) signed by the parties (or a copy thereof) shall be lodged with the Clerk, who shall note the settlement in the Malicious Injuries Book and retain the documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a time limit for making a lodgment under section 16(2) of the Principal Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgments in court* 8. A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application and the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules relating to lodgments shall mutatis mutandis apply to such lodgment, but a notice of intention to defend shall not be required.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Circuit Court exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeals to the Circuit Court* 9. (1) The provisions of [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed shall mutatis mutandis apply to every appeal, including an appeal by a ratepayer, taken under section 17 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation under [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) as amended by [the Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific order mentioned for cases stated to the Supreme Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Order 102"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Cases stated to the Supreme Court* 10. The procedure to be followed in relation to cases stated for the opinion of the Supreme Court under section 18 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) are contained in [Order 102]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-102-District-Cases-stated) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Mental Health Act 2001 referenced in this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Act” means the [Mental Health Act 2001]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001 - Court: District # Order 84A: Mental Health Act **[1]** 1. (1) In this Order – “**the Act**” means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html). (2) The provisions of rules 2, 3 and 4 of [Order 84]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-84-District-Child-care) of these Rules shall apply, mutatis mutandis, to proceedings to which this Order applies. 2. (1). Save where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) or in a case to which section 25(7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, an application under section 25(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising the detention of a child in an approved centre shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district court district in which the child resides or is for the time being to be found at a sitting of the Court for the said District. Save in a case to which section 25(7) of the Act applies, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84A.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/70390850-5689-4ac6-9fef-390b0d0ec1af/Notice of application for order authorising detention in an approved centre. No. 84A.1.docx/docx/1) upon the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child. Such notice shall be served at least ten days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), such notice shall be served as promptly as reasonably possible and prior to the hearing of the application at a sitting of the Court held within the time specified in section 23(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), and may be served by delivering a copy of the notice to the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order format specified for appeals?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.10]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court on hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22775a7e-21b0-4f08-bfdb-3132be53dc35/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 78(5) No. 89.10.docx/docx/1), or [89.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ee51a3b-b56e-44d2-aa6c-269789892ec4/Order on appeal (Wildlife Act, 1976) No. 89.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings be declared void due to non-compliance with the rules without a specific court directive?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Non-compliance with rules* 11. Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court modify the time limits for acts or proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court may extend time, set aside, amend, etc.* 12. The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Was the case related to air pollution?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"under the Air Pollution Act, 1987 (No. 6 of 1987)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution - Court: District # **Proceedings: - under the Air Pollution Act, 1987 (No. 6 of 1987)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting permission to perform a specific action?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a warrant to enter premises under section 14(5) of the Air Pollution Act, 1987 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 14 (5) of the [Air Pollution Act, 1987]...may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 1. (1) An application under section 14 (5) of the [Air Pollution Act, 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) (hereinafter referred to as "**t****he Act of 1987**") by an authorised person or the person by whom he or she was appointed for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/833ac759-d6d5-446d-9645-02e736dd0bb0/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act, 1987 section 14 (6) No. 96.1.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form for a warrant to enter premises under the Air Pollution Act 1987?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of warrant* (3) A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/621b859c-730e-4948-9a51-9531bb7a22f4/Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act 1987 section 14(6) No. 96.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 28A be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant court district?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under subsection (1) of section 28A ... may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises concerned are situated or wherein the emission concerned takes place."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 2. (1) An application to the Court under subsection (1) of section 28A (inserted by the third schedule to the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) — No. 7 of 1992) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) for an order pursuant to that subsection in relation to an emission from a premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises concerned are situated or wherein the emission concerned takes place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for the notice to be served at least seven days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice ... at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of, service and lodgment of notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bc6e99d6-bc5d-4161-b3de-f92395301595/Notice Of Application For AnOrder Under Section 28a(1) - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.3.docx/docx/1), upon the respondent in a manner prescribed in section 15 of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), and shall be served at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the transfer of an application to the Circuit Court or High Court governed by a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order so transferring shall be in the Form 96.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *transfer to Circuit Court or High Court* (4) Where, pursuant to the provisions of section 28A (1) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), the Court transfers an application made under the said subsection (1) to the Circuit Court or the High Court, the order so transferring shall be in the [Form 96.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d0549e9f-fc83-46fc-902c-fb879996b208/Order Transferring An Application To The Circuit Court High Court - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.5.docx/docx/1), and the Clerk shall forthwith transmit a certified copy of the said order and any other order made in the proceedings, the notice of application and any other document or exhibit handed into court in relation to that application, to the appropriate County Registrar or, as the case may be, Registrar of the High Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 96.6 required before applying for an order under section 55 (2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order under section 55 (2) of [the Act of 1987] deeming consent to have been given and directing that required works be carried out shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.6, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 55 (2)* (2) An application for an order under section 55 (2) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) deeming consent to have been given and directing that required works be carried out shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e2bf300-61a3-4537-8279-f1c07b2ba9c7/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (2) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 96.7 required before applying for an order under section 55 (3)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order under section 55 (3) of [the Act of 1987] shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 55 (3)* (3) An application for an order under section 55 (3) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) in relation to the cost of works required to be carried out pursuant to that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8d7561b3-10ad-402f-98b6-915b81fc34f5/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (3) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for serving a notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service shall be effected at least seven days or, if being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- service of notices of* (4) A notice of application required by this rule to be served shall be served in a manner prescribed in section 15 of that Act. Service shall be effected at least seven days or, if being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the order of the court related to applications granted in a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The order of the Court on granting an application to which this rule relates shall be in the [Form 96.8] or [96.9], Schedule as the case may be, with any necessary modifications required in particular cases."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- orders of the Court* (5) The order of the Court on granting an application to which this rule relates shall be in the [Form 96.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e938bf-1419-4041-97b2-31ee706f29b5/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (2) - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.8.docx/docx/1) or [96.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/402be530-61dd-4d7a-b27f-d020636ebd9e/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (3) - Air Pollution Act 1967 No. 96.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, with any necessary modifications required in particular cases. # **Proceedings: -****under the Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 (No. 1 of 1977)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 referred to as ''the Act of 1977'' in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 4. In this Order - "**t****he Act of 1977**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977); "**the** **Act of 1990**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1990).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is section 10 mentioned in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Application under sec. 10"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 10*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order under section 10(1) of the Act of 1977 be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order under section 10 (1) of [the Act of 1977] may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 5. (1) An application for an order under section 10 (1) of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of [the Act of 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the waters concerned or the land or other premises from which the entry or discharge concerned takes place is or are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/213ab9a4-3a14-41b0-9789-ef367e4837a6/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 10 (1) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977 No. 96.10.docx/docx/1), upon the person against whom the order is sought (the respondent) and, where the applicant is not a local authority or regional board, upon the local authority or regional board in whose functional area the waters concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for serving the notice if it''s done via registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where service is being effected by registered prepaid post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by registered prepaid post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- lodgment* When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting approval for something?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a warrant to enter a premises or vessel be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for a warrant under section 28 (7) of [the Act of 1977] to enter a premises or vessel may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or vessel is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 6. (1) An application for a warrant under section 28 (7) of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) to enter a premises or vessel may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or vessel is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made under oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 96.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d8ff4043-3dea-48f7-8fd0-3a0479af492e/Information (application for warrant to enter) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 section 28 (7) No. 96.12.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a warrant to enter premises under section 13(6) of the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 allowed to be made at any sitting of the relevant court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992] for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 7. (1) An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96. 14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/360bf441-bfcd-4c5c-a1d8-2d9f77156e4c/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 section 13 (6) No. 96.14.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the issue of the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about a complaint related to noise?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Complaint in relation to noise"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Complaint in relation to noise*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a complaint about noise that causes annoyance allowed to be made to the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A complaint to the Court under section 108 (1) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992] in relation to noise which is alleged to be so loud, so continuous, so repeated, of such duration or pitch or occurring at such times as to give reasonable cause for annoyance may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 8. (1) A complaint to the Court under section 108 (1) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) in relation to noise which is alleged to be so loud, so continuous, so repeated, of such duration or pitch or occurring at such times as to give reasonable cause for annoyance may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice to be issued before a complaint can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of service lodgment* (2) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the form prescribed in the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (Noise) Regulations, 1994 (S.I. No. 179 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/si/179/made/en/print), of the intention to make such a complaint, within such time as may be specified in the notice, upon the defendant, that is to say, the person alleged to have made or have caused or have been responsible for the noise. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 14 of that Act, and the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for the court order mentioned?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order shall be in the [Form 96.16, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of court order* (3) Where, upon hearing such complaint, the Court makes an order under the said section 108 (1), the order shall be in the [Form 96.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ac512aa7-a167-48df-972c-5753c0deaf43/Order Pursuant To Section 108 (1) In Relation To Noise - Environmental Protection Agency Act 1992 No. 96.16.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'Can a notice be delivered by fax if there''s a facility for receiving it electronically?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where there is a facility for receiving a facsimile of the notice by electronic means at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, by transmitting a facsimile of the notice by such means to that address"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises, or - where there is a facility for receiving a facsimile of the notice by electronic means at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, by transmitting a facsimile of the notice by such means to that address, provided that the notice is also served or given in any of the other ways referred to in this sub-rule. (3). The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4). An order made pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act on such application shall be in the [Form 96A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3279a05f-9ef0-431b-a7a4-f227273726ba/Order (Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998, Section 52) No. 96A.2.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 96A inserted by [S.I. 700 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/700/made/en/print?q 700&years 2004), effective 14 November 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application for a closure order required to be served on the licensee or manager of the catering premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the licensee or manager of the catering premises concerned not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 2. An application pursuant to section 4 of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html) for a closure order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which: in the case of a food stall or food vehicle, the stall or vehicle is used for the sale of food or is kept when not being so used, or* in the case of any other catering premises, the catering premises are situated*. 3. Notice of an application for a closure order shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/71b5ddfd-cfee-4600-8583-543082c2183c/Notice of application for closure order - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 section 4 No. 96B.1.docx/docx/1) and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the notice in writing which was served in accordance with section 4(2) of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the licensee or manager of the catering premises concerned not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct. A closure order shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b886988c-eae2-4635-a63c-c5b4191e0a68/Closure order - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 section 5 No. 96B.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a prohibition order be made at any sitting of the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010] for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010] applies) of the Court for the court district in which:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 5. An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) applies) of the Court for the court district in which: the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or* any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or* *(iii) any such structure, stall or vehicle is kept when not in use.* 6. Notice of an application for a prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bee0d4e5-64ff-4945-b634-82d19c4b730d/Notice of application for prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the prohibition notice which was served in accordance with section 7 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct in accordance with section 8(2) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2bf9faa1-8cf8-414b-8224-7135236e0c97/Prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule The applicant shall serve a copy of the order on the respondent. Where a prohibition order specifies any premises to which the order relates, and the owner of the premises is not the respondent, the applicant shall, where practicable, cause a copy of the prohibition order to be served by registered post on the owner of the premises concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued before an application to vary a prohibition order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Save where the Court otherwise directs or permits, such an application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. An application pursuant to section 9(1) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for an order varying a prohibition order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the prohibition order was made. Save where the Court otherwise directs or permits, such an application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96B.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6c73a20e-fed8-487c-a7a4-7bf4e49b1b1d/Notice of application to vary a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application (with a copy of the prohibition order appended, where the person applying is in possession of a copy of that order) shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána who applied for the prohibition order concerned not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The member shall produce the prohibition order or a true copy at the hearing. Where the Court makes an order varying the prohibition order, the order shall be in the [Form 96B.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de3b0ecb-1487-4f28-984b-c4a6e024e2dd/Order varying a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.7.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 545 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/545/made/en/print?q 545&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 536 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/536/made/en/print?q 536&years 2011), effective 4 April 2011'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific content discussed in the preliminary section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Preliminary**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a civil order be made at any sitting of the Court for the area where the respondent lives?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act] for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _2. Application for civil order_ 2. An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a copy of the notice of application required to be served on the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application must be served upon the respondent in accordance with Order 10 not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _3. Notice of application_ 3.(1) Notice of an application for a civil order may be in the [Form 96C.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1ee9a62-c7ab-4d87-a94c-ee0d07e96a81/Notice Of Application For Civil Order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115 No. 96C.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section 114 of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon the respondent in accordance with Order 10 not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that a civil order should follow?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A civil order may be in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _4. Form and service of civil order_ 4. (1) A civil order may be in the [Form 96C.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1644c92a-97fa-4443-b38b-aae26e085127/Civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 115 No. 96C.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The applicant must cause a copy of any civil order to be served on the respondent in accordance with Order 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before making an application to vary or discharge a civil order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _5. Application to vary or discharge a civil order_ 5.(1) An application pursuant to section 115(7) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for an order discharging or varying a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person subject to the civil order resides at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c78b0a4-b7e9-44f7-89e5-4ee90cab0a9d/Notice of application for variation - discharge of civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115(7) No. 96C.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with true copies of the notice of application for a civil order and attachments thereto and of the civil order) must be served upon the person referred to in section 115(8) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) in accordance with Order 10 not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application to vary or discharge and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge re-sign the original civil order after making a variation?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the civil order and re-signed by the Judge"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _6. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 6.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a civil order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the civil order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a civil order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the civil order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the civil order was made notice that the civil order has been discharged, or a copy of the civil order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a behavior order be made at any sitting of the Children Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act] for a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _7. Application for behaviour order_ 7. An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to serve a copy of the notice of application on certain individuals?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of the 2001 Act not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _8. Notice of application_ 8.(1) Notice of an application for a behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cadca7a-81ac-4669-9325-afdd44c98f72/Notice Of Application For Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001, section 257D.No. 96C.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or a copy of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued before making an application to vary or discharge a behavior order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _10. Application to vary or discharge a behaviour order_ 10.(1) An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging or varying a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99023c06-0ef4-4c8e-bc40-58193f9b66d8/Notice Of Application For Variation - Discharge Of Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001 section No. 96C.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with copies of the notice of application for a behaviour order and attachments thereto and of the behaviour order) must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application for discharge or variation and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk send notice about the discharge or variation of a behavior order to another Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _11. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 11.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific year mentioned in connection with the Act referred to in Section 28?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the 2023 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Section 28 Orders under the 2023 Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under Part 5 of the 2023 Act be held at a special sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a special sitting of the Court arranged in accordance with section 38 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _12. Venue_ 12. Proceedings under Part 5 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before: - a sitting of the Court for the Court District in which the applicant or the respondent resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 36(2) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) as residing, or - a special sitting of the Court arranged in accordance with section 38 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons in Form required before making an application for a section 28 order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 28(1) of [the 2023 Act] for a section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _13. Section 28 Order_ 13.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an interim section 28 order be made by motion on notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(12) of [the 2023 Act] for an interim section 28 order (save where made on or in the course of the hearing of an application for a section 28 order) may be made by motion on notice in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _14. Interim order inter partes_ 14.(1) When a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(12) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an interim section 28 order (save where made on or in the course of the hearing of an application for a section 28 order) may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 96C.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/447149a6-8627-48f0-bacc-7a2e97745c47/Form Notice of Application for Interim Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an parte section 28 order be made without a summons having been issued?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Whether or not a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(7) of [the 2023 Act] for an parte section 28 order may be made at any sitting of the Court mentioned in rule 12 and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _15. parte order_ 15.(1) Whether or not a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(7) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an parte section 28 order may be made at any sitting of the Court mentioned in rule 12 and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a summons in Form required before making an application for a further section 28 order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 30 of [the 2023 Act] for a further section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _17. Further section 28 order_ 17.(1) An application to the Court under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a further section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to send a certified copy of the order to the Garda Síochána member in charge of the station where the person for whom the order was made previously resided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided, but only if that member had previously been sent a copy of the section 28 order, or any order relating thereto under section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) and this rule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _18. Clerk to supply copies of orders_ 18. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a section 28 order or makes a further order under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), the Clerk must, in accordance with section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant, and - to the respondent, by ordinary prepaid post, and - where an application has been made by a member of the Garda Síochána acting in accordance with section 31 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), to that member, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person, for whose benefit the order is made, resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a section 28 order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided, but only if that member had previously been sent a copy of the section 28 order, or any order relating thereto under section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) and this rule, and - where the order in question prohibits or restricts the respondent from approaching a specified place and the Court so directs, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the specified place is situated, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons be served less than seven days before the hearing if it is deemed urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _19. Service_ 19.(1) A summons issued under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) in accordance with this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) Without prejudice to the power of the Court to give such a direction of its own motion, a request for a direction under section 34(4) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be made viva voce at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), direct or deem sufficient service of a document under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court issue a direction under section 32 or section 39 of the 2023 Act on its own initiative?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"on its own motion and having heard the parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _20. Direction in relation to cross-examination or for evidence through television link_ 20. The Court may give a direction under section 32 or section 39 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) at any time in the course of proceedings under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)– - (a) upon a request for such a direction made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, and having heard the parties, or - on its own motion and having heard the parties, and may adjourn the proceedings for the purposes of section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for such period as it considers appropriate in the circumstances, and may make such orders and give further directions in accordance with section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) accordingly. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2007), effective 20 July 2007, substituted in entirety including title by 364 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/364/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,and Behaviour Orders) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 2 September 2024. Superseded amendments: Order title substituted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007 Order rule 7 inserted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a High Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 97 - Road Traffic - Court: District # Order 97: Road Traffic**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Road Traffic Act 2016 referred to in the definitions section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the “**2016 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) (No. 21 of 2016);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order— the “**1961 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 1961) (as amended); the “**1968 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 1968](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html) (No. 25 of 1968); the “**2016 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) (No. 21 of 2016); the “**Agreement**” has the same meaning as in section 40(12)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area where the vehicle is usually stored?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 18(8)(c)(ii) of the [1961 Act] against the refusal of the issuing authority to issue a test certificate may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the vehicle is ordinarily kept."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeals - under section 18(8)(c)(ii)* 2. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 18(8)(c)(ii) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the refusal of the issuing authority to issue a test certificate may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the vehicle is ordinarily kept. (2) An appeal'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 34(5)(a)* - pursuant to section 34(5)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the decision of the issuing authority under section 34(4) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) or the deferring of such a decision. may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Must the notice be served at least 10 days before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the person to whom the application relates at least 10 days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications under sec. 28* 4. (1) An application pursuant to section 28(1) or 28(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by an officer of the Garda Síochána for a special disqualification order in respect of any person may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such person ordinarily resides. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae22a254-870f-44a4-bd3e-b280d78858e6/Notice Of Application For Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(1) No. 97.12.docx/docx/1) or [97.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/067c742b-8c5b-4b41-b82f-6cf2d2128506/Notice Of Application For Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(2) No. 97.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, signed by such officer. (3) Such notice shall be served upon the person to whom the application relates at least 10 days before the date of hearing of the application. (4) The original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the application may be in the Form [97.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/69c2a360-7094-4294-b022-cf625a0f95e5/Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(1) No. 97.14.docx/docx/1) or [97.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77ea9fd7-680c-4a41-b505-f6f826d7416f/Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(2) No. 97.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that needs to be issued and served before making an application for the removal of a disqualification?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.16], Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for removal of disqualification* 5.[2] (1) An application pursuant to section 29(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) for the removal of a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the court for the court area in which the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/df3fa82d-8c2f-4a31-8d00-d6b7d688da91/Notice Of Application For The Removal Of Disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(2)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the district in which the applicant ordinarily resides at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the application. (4) The original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the Form [97.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de60ac49-ced2-4787-bc17-76e5b08f93fd/Order for the removal of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.17.docx/docx/1) or [97.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64ffa69e-d7ad-4458-96f0-da64dc1e1c1d/Order confirming period specified in order of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is a written form required when a member of the Garda Síochána applies for a search warrant under section 106(6)(a)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act] by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant under sec. 106 (6)* 6. An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule and, where the Judge of the District Court or the Peace Commissioner grants the application, the warrant may be in the [Form 97.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/76d54504-08eb-4f65-9395-646de3aa29bf/Information For Search Warrant - Road Traffic Act, 1961 section 106 (6) (a) No. 97.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule Application for disqualification under the Agreement on the Mutual Recognition of Driving Disqualifications between Ireland and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Can a licensing authority make an application for an order declaring someone disqualified for holding a licence at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act] for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act] Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue* 7.[2] (1) An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area: - where the person the subject of the mutual recognition application concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - in which the address which appears on the Irish driving licence or learner permit held by the respondent is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application required before submitting a mutual recognition application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A mutual recognition application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Form of mutual recognition application* (2) A mutual recognition application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application [in the [Form 97.19](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/acc/alfresco/4d97d0a7-2e9d-4df9-a60c-a25f209fb489/Notice of Application for an order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence ... 40 Road Traffic Act 2016 No. 97.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed on behalf of the moving party or by the solicitor for the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate required to be appended if one has been issued for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the 2016 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent signed by an officer of the licensing authority concerned authorised in that behalf by the chief executive of the licensing authority concerned given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Documents to be appended to mutual recognition application* (3) There shall be appended to the original notice of application: - The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent signed by an officer of the licensing authority concerned authorised in that behalf by the chief executive of the licensing authority concerned given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) and any document identified in and attached to such certificate; - Where no certificate is given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/), copies of: - (a) the notification in writing concerning the case of the respondent received by the licensing authority in accordance with Article 3 of the Agreement and section 40(1) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/); - the information and documents specified in paragraph 1 of Article 6 of the Agreement concerning the case of the respondent, and - where appropriate, pursuant to the Agreement, the evidence referred to in paragraph 2 of that Article and the supplementary information referred to in paragraph 3 thereof concerning the case of the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a statutory declaration regarding the service of the notice of application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Lodgment* (5) The original notice of application, together with all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a higher court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 98 - Social welfare - Court: District # Proceedings for - contribution towards benefit or allowance'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order for contribution be brought in the court area where the liable relative resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for order for contribution* 2. (1) An application to the Court by a competent authority pursuant to subsection (2) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order directing the person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of that section (hereinafter referred to as the liable relative) to make a contribution towards a benefit or allowance being paid by that authority to a recipient may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for lodging documents with the Clerk before the hearing date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- lodgment of notice, etc.* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court order required to be served on the respondent via registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent by registered prepaid post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court order - form and service of* 3.(1) Where, upon hearing such application, the Court makes an order under section 286 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) the order shall be in the [Form 98.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12910b1e-19e5-498d-bbff-6790903272d7/Order Directing Payment Of Contribution Towards Benefit - Allowance - Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 1993 No. 98.2.docx/docx/1) (or such modification thereof as may be appropriate). The applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent by registered prepaid post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Is an order made under subsection (4) of section 286 treated as an order for payment by instalments?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order shall, as provided in subsection (5) of that section be deemed to be an order for payment by instalments made under section 17 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1926"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- variation or enforcement of* (2) For the purposes of varying or enforcing an order made under subsection (4) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) the order shall, as provided in subsection (5) of that section be deemed to be an order for payment by instalments made under section 17 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html). The relevant provisions of [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), (Enforcement of Judgments) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed, with any necessary adaptation, shall for such purposes apply in relation to every such order made under the said section 286 (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Do rules 6(2) and 7(4) not apply to orders made under section 286(4)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said [Order 53], which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- 6 (2), 7 (4) of 0.53 not to apply to* (3) The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an attachment of earnings order be made after the initial hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- attachment of earnings* (4) Where, in order to secure payments under an order made pursuant to the said section 286(4), application is made by a competent authority under section 287 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an attachment of earnings order such application, if not made at the time of the hearing of the application under section 286(2), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. The relevant provisions of Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) shall apply in every such case. The procedures to be followed and the forms to be used in relation to such applications are those provided in Order 56 (other than rule 2) of these Rules which are relevant, and that Order and those forms, with any necessary modifications, shall apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified as District in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 - Court: District # Order 99A: Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section primarily introductory or does it contain detailed information?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"## GENERAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## GENERAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to indicate if a respondent is believed to be under 18 years old?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Definitions and requirement to identify where respondent is a child* 1. (1) In this Order— the “**1****997 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html); the “**2014 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**dwelling**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 6 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**house**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/18/enacted/en/html); “**site**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Traveller Accommodation) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/33/enacted/en/html). (2) Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Are there specific proceedings mentioned under the 1997 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## PROCEEDINGS UNDER 1997 ACT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can non-compliance with the rules make proceedings invalid?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Non-compliance with rules* 11. Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court modify the time limits for actions under the Acts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court may extend time, set aside, amend, etc.* 12. The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting approval for something?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/833ac759-d6d5-446d-9645-02e736dd0bb0/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act, 1987 section 14 (6) No. 96.1.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the warrant to enter premises specified in Form 96.2?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of warrant* (3) A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/621b859c-730e-4948-9a51-9531bb7a22f4/Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act 1987 section 14(6) No. 96.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used when issuing a notice before an application can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of, service and lodgment of notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bc6e99d6-bc5d-4161-b3de-f92395301595/Notice Of Application For AnOrder Under Section 28a(1) - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.3.docx/docx/1), upon the respondent in a manner prescribed in section 15 of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), and shall be served at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the form for the court''s order specified?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"[Form 96. 4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- order of the Court on* (3) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 96. 4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4acb8965-52dd-49c3-8964-be16ab8e36da/Order Under Section 28a (1) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the transfer of an application from one court to another governed by a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the order so transferring shall be in the Form 96.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *transfer to Circuit Court or High Court* (4) Where, pursuant to the provisions of section 28A (1) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), the Court transfers an application made under the said subsection (1) to the Circuit Court or the High Court, the order so transferring shall be in the [Form 96.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d0549e9f-fc83-46fc-902c-fb879996b208/Order Transferring An Application To The Circuit Court High Court - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.5.docx/docx/1), and the Clerk shall forthwith transmit a certified copy of the said order and any other order made in the proceedings, the notice of application and any other document or exhibit handed into court in relation to that application, to the appropriate County Registrar or, as the case may be, Registrar of the High Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 96.6 required before an application can be made under section 55 (2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an order under section 55 (2) ... issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the Form 96.6"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 55 (2)* (2) An application for an order under section 55 (2) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) deeming consent to have been given and directing that required works be carried out shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e2bf300-61a3-4537-8279-f1c07b2ba9c7/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (2) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 referred to as ''the Act of 1977'' in this document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 4. In this Order - "**t****he Act of 1977**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977); "**the** **Act of 1990**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1990).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice required before submitting an application for an order under the Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/213ab9a4-3a14-41b0-9789-ef367e4837a6/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 10 (1) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977 No. 96.10.docx/docx/1), upon the person against whom the order is sought (the respondent) and, where the applicant is not a local authority or regional board, upon the local authority or regional board in whose functional area the waters concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time requirement for serving the notice if it''s done by registered prepaid post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where service is being effected by registered prepaid post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by registered prepaid post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement to lodge documents with the Clerk before a specific date?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- lodgment* When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the application for a warrant required to be made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 96.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d8ff4043-3dea-48f7-8fd0-3a0479af492e/Information (application for warrant to enter) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 section 28 (7) No. 96.12.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is this document requesting permission to do something?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a warrant to enter premises be made outside of specific sittings of the court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992] for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 7. (1) An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be used for a warrant to enter premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant to enter premises which is granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.15, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) A warrant to enter premises which is granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.15, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7a57d6db-6553-4b07-b191-79c676846eac/Warrant To Enter Premises - Environmental Protection Agency Act 1992 section 13(6) No. 96.15.docx/docx/1)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is a complaint about noise that causes reasonable annoyance allowed to be made at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A complaint to the Court under section 108 (1) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992] in relation to noise which is alleged to be so loud, so continuous, so repeated, of such duration or pitch or occurring at such times as to give reasonable cause for annoyance may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 8. (1) A complaint to the Court under section 108 (1) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) in relation to noise which is alleged to be so loud, so continuous, so repeated, of such duration or pitch or occurring at such times as to give reasonable cause for annoyance may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Is the notice of service required before making a complaint?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of service lodgment* (2) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the form prescribed in the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (Noise) Regulations, 1994 (S.I. No. 179 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/si/179/made/en/print), of the intention to make such a complaint, within such time as may be specified in the notice, upon the defendant, that is to say, the person alleged to have made or have caused or have been responsible for the noise. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 14 of that Act, and the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'Is an authorized officer mentioned in the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the expressions “**authorized officer**”, “**Authority**”, “**improvement notice**”, and “**official agency**” shall have the meanings given to each of them by the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 96A - Food Safety - Court: District # **Order 96A: Food Safety******[1]**** 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/29/enacted/en/html) (No. 45 of 1998); the expressions “**authorised officer**”, “**Authority**”, “**improvement notice**”, and “**official agency**” shall have the meanings given to each of them by the Act. 2(1). An application by or on behalf of the Authority or an official agency for an improvement order pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which are situated the premises which are the subject of an improvement notice served on a proprietor or person in charge of a premises pursuant to sub-section (1) of Section 52 of the Act. (2). Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 96A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/faf5ed3b-091e-4a6d-b1f9-446227bd8005/Notice Of Application - Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998, section 52 No. 96A.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on or given to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises by the applicant not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. Such notice may be served or given - - (a) by addressing it to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises by name and delivering it to him or her, - by leaving it at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter addressed to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises at the address at which he or she ordinarily resides or carries on business, - if an address for the service of notices has been furnished by the proprietor or person in charge of the premises, by leaving it at, or sending it by prepaid registered post addressed to him or her to that address,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'Is it possible to serve a notice by delivering it to someone over 16 years old who lives or works at the premises?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises, or - where there is a facility for receiving a facsimile of the notice by electronic means at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, by transmitting a facsimile of the notice by such means to that address, provided that the notice is also served or given in any of the other ways referred to in this sub-rule. (3). The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4). An order made pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act on such application shall be in the [Form 96A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3279a05f-9ef0-431b-a7a4-f227273726ba/Order (Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998, Section 52) No. 96A.2.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 96A inserted by [S.I. 700 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/700/made/en/print?q 700&years 2004), effective 14 November 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice of application for a prohibition order required to be served on the respondent at least seven days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 5. An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) applies) of the Court for the court district in which: the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or* any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or* *(iii) any such structure, stall or vehicle is kept when not in use.* 6. Notice of an application for a prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bee0d4e5-64ff-4945-b634-82d19c4b730d/Notice of application for prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the prohibition notice which was served in accordance with section 7 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct in accordance with section 8(2) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2bf9faa1-8cf8-414b-8224-7135236e0c97/Prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule The applicant shall serve a copy of the order on the respondent. Where a prohibition order specifies any premises to which the order relates, and the owner of the premises is not the respondent, the applicant shall, where practicable, cause a copy of the prohibition order to be served by registered post on the owner of the premises concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific content mentioned in the preliminary section?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Preliminary**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a specific form required for a civil order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A civil order may be in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _4. Form and service of civil order_ 4. (1) A civil order may be in the [Form 96C.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1644c92a-97fa-4443-b38b-aae26e085127/Civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 115 No. 96C.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The applicant must cause a copy of any civil order to be served on the respondent in accordance with Order 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judge modify the terms of a civil order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where the Court varies the terms of a civil order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the civil order and re-signed by the Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _6. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 6.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a civil order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the civil order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a civil order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the civil order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the civil order was made notice that the civil order has been discharged, or a copy of the civil order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is a copy of the notice of application required to be served on specific individuals mentioned in the 2001 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _8. Notice of application_ 8.(1) Notice of an application for a behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cadca7a-81ac-4669-9325-afdd44c98f72/Notice Of Application For Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001, section 257D.No. 96C.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or a copy of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form that must be issued before making an application to vary or discharge a behaviour order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _10. Application to vary or discharge a behaviour order_ 10.(1) An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging or varying a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99023c06-0ef4-4c8e-bc40-58193f9b66d8/Notice Of Application For Variation - Discharge Of Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001 section No. 96C.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with copies of the notice of application for a behaviour order and attachments thereto and of the behaviour order) must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application for discharge or variation and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a clerk send information about the discharge or variation of a behavior order to another clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _11. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 11.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an interim section 28 order be made through a motion on notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(12) of [the 2023 Act] for an interim section 28 order (save where made on or in the course of the hearing of an application for a section 28 order) may be made by motion on notice in the [Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _14. Interim order inter partes_ 14.(1) When a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(12) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an interim section 28 order (save where made on or in the course of the hearing of an application for a section 28 order) may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 96C.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/447149a6-8627-48f0-bacc-7a2e97745c47/Form Notice of Application for Interim Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can a summons be served less than seven days before the hearing if it''s considered urgent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _19. Service_ 19.(1) A summons issued under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) in accordance with this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) Without prejudice to the power of the Court to give such a direction of its own motion, a request for a direction under section 34(4) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be made viva voce at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), direct or deem sufficient service of a document under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court issue a direction on its own initiative?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"on its own motion and having heard the parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _20. Direction in relation to cross-examination or for evidence through television link_ 20. The Court may give a direction under section 32 or section 39 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) at any time in the course of proceedings under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)– - (a) upon a request for such a direction made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, and having heard the parties, or - on its own motion and having heard the parties, and may adjourn the proceedings for the purposes of section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for such period as it considers appropriate in the circumstances, and may make such orders and give further directions in accordance with section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) accordingly. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2007), effective 20 July 2007, substituted in entirety including title by 364 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/364/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,and Behaviour Orders) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 2 September 2024. Superseded amendments: Order title substituted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007 Order rule 7 inserted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a Supreme Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 97 - Road Traffic - Court: District # Order 97: Road Traffic**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a reference to a specific section of an act in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"section 33(3A)(b) of the [1961 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 33(3A)(b)* - pursuant to section 33(3A)(b) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [1968 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of the issuing authority to carry out a test,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a reference to section 33(5)(a) in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"pursuant to section 33(5)(a) of the [1961 Act]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 33(5)(a)* - pursuant to section 33(5)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the deferring of a decision by the issuing authority to issue a certificate of competency,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant resides?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 34(5)(a)* - pursuant to section 34(5)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the decision of the issuing authority under section 34(4) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) or the deferring of such a decision. may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for a search warrant under section 106(6)(a) of the 1961 Act made on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant under sec. 106 (6)* 6. An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule and, where the Judge of the District Court or the Peace Commissioner grants the application, the warrant may be in the [Form 97.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/76d54504-08eb-4f65-9395-646de3aa29bf/Information For Search Warrant - Road Traffic Act, 1961 section 106 (6) (a) No. 97.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule Application for disqualification under the Agreement on the Mutual Recognition of Driving Disqualifications between Ireland and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Can a licensing authority make an application for an order declaring someone disqualified for holding a license at any sitting of the Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act] for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act] Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue* 7.[2] (1) An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area: - where the person the subject of the mutual recognition application concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - in which the address which appears on the Irish driving licence or learner permit held by the respondent is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is a certificate required if one is not provided under section 40(3)(a) of the 2016 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where no certificate is given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/), copies of:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Documents to be appended to mutual recognition application* (3) There shall be appended to the original notice of application: - The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent signed by an officer of the licensing authority concerned authorised in that behalf by the chief executive of the licensing authority concerned given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) and any document identified in and attached to such certificate; - Where no certificate is given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/), copies of: - (a) the notification in writing concerning the case of the respondent received by the licensing authority in accordance with Article 3 of the Agreement and section 40(1) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/); - the information and documents specified in paragraph 1 of Article 6 of the Agreement concerning the case of the respondent, and - where appropriate, pursuant to the Agreement, the evidence referred to in paragraph 2 of that Article and the supplementary information referred to in paragraph 3 thereof concerning the case of the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for documents to be submitted in advance of a hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The original notice of application, together with all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Lodgment* (5) The original notice of application, together with all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an order for contribution be heard in any sitting of the Court where the liable relative resides or works?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for order for contribution* 2. (1) An application to the Court by a competent authority pursuant to subsection (2) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order directing the person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of that section (hereinafter referred to as the liable relative) to make a contribution towards a benefit or allowance being paid by that authority to a recipient may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Do rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) not apply to orders made under section 286 (4)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said Order 53, which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- 6 (2), 7 (4) of 0.53 not to apply to* (3) The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an attachment of earnings order be made after the initial hearing under section 286(2)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- attachment of earnings* (4) Where, in order to secure payments under an order made pursuant to the said section 286(4), application is made by a competent authority under section 287 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an attachment of earnings order such application, if not made at the time of the hearing of the application under section 286(2), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. The relevant provisions of Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) shall apply in every such case. The procedures to be followed and the forms to be used in relation to such applications are those provided in Order 56 (other than rule 2) of these Rules which are relevant, and that Order and those forms, with any necessary modifications, shall apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in the given text a District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 - Court: District # Order 99A: Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there any specific content mentioned under section GENERAL?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## GENERAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for applicants to indicate if a respondent is believed to be under the age of 18?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Definitions and requirement to identify where respondent is a child* 1. (1) In this Order— the “**1****997 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html); the “**2014 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**dwelling**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 6 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**house**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/18/enacted/en/html); “**site**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Traveller Accommodation) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/33/enacted/en/html). (2) Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under certain sections of the 1997 Act be held not in public?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act] may be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proceedings may be heard otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required when making an application for an excluding order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act] for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Excluding Orders* 4. (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/331b2936-1752-49cc-82e8-f8bb1cff527f/Application For An Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1). (3) Where an excluding order is made by the Court in accordance with the provisions of section 12(12)(a) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) on foot of a possession application under section 12 of that Act, the order shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.4 required before an application for a site excluding order is made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the court under section 3A of the [1997 Act] for a site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Site Excluding Orders* 5. (1) An application to the court under section 3A of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for a site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an interim excluding order required to include information on oath and in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act] on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim Excluding Orders/Site Excluding Orders* 6.[2] (1) An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8590fb7f-0de3-4171-a21d-356ce5134af5/Information - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.5.docx/docx/1) or on an affidavit sworn by the applicant incorporating the matter in that Form. (2) The order of the Court shall be in the [Form 99A.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c08a91c-e6c8-421e-88d9-0db1d7d5fb86/Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.6.docx/docx/1). (3) An application for confirmation under section of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) of an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made parte under the terms of section 4(3) of that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent by the applicant at least 2 days before the date fixed for such application of a notice in the [Form 99A.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c14e9af0-5f7b-4c77-a2b8-0c2515212e98/Application To Confirm An Interim Excluding - Interim Site Excluding Order Made Parte - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.14.docx/docx/1). The applicant shall also serve on the respondent the documents referred to in section 4(3)(c)(ii) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html). (4) Where, on such application, the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order is confirmed, such confirmation shall be indorsed upon the order and signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.7 required before varying an excluding order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 3(5) of the [1997 Act] to vary an excluding order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary Excluding/ Site Excluding/ Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders* 7. (1) An application to the Court under - (a) section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an excluding order, - section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, - section 3A(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary a site excluding order, or section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) and section 3A(9) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b135a660-4139-4bf7-9106-e0177cefb952/Application To Vary An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.7.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ee4a98d-c7c5-44f1-a4ed-9981fa04bbd1/Order Varying An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.9 required before an application can be made to the Court to discharge an excluding order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 9(1) of the [1997 Act] to discharge an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.9, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Discharge Excluding Site Excluding or Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders 8. (1) An application to the Court under section 9(1) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to discharge an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b98b105d-e0e2-4674-8f94-49219cc93bf1/Application To Discharge An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.9.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e9130d4-ae3e-4664-a740-0ed9bf4d754e/Order Discharging An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.10.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk required to send a certified copy of the order to the Garda Síochána by prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the member of the Garda Síochána Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Clerk to supply copies of order 10. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order, the Clerk shall give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable to- - (a) the applicant concerned, - the respondent, - the housing authority in whose functional area the house, site or dwelling in respect of which the application for the order was made is situate, and the Health Service Executive by ordinary prepaid post and - the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk required to notify the Gardaí when an interim excluding order ends?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall send notice that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Interim Excluding/Site Excluding orders ceases to have effect.* 11.[4] Where an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has been made and the application for an excluding order or site excluding order has been determined, the Clerk shall send notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1), that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is an appeal from an interim excluding order allowed to stay the operation of the order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"an appeal from an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall not stay the operation of the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeal from orders* 12.(1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 9(4) and [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) and that an appellant has entered into a recognisance for appeal, - (a) an appeal from an excluding order or a site excluding order shall, if the court that made the order or the court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination; - an appeal from an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall not stay the operation of the order. (2) - (a) An application to the District Court to stay the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under section 8 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made following the service and lodgment of a notice of appeal and lodgment of the recognisance of appeal and when made otherwise than upon the occasion of the making of that order shall be preceded by the issue of a notice in the [Form 99A.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/937d34a2-ae9f-44f7-bbd1-e0bf160a77b4/Application For A Stay On The Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.12.docx/docx/1), which shall be served upon the respondent to the application two days before the hearing of the application. - Where the Court grants a stay on the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under this rule, the order granting such stay shall be in the [Form 99A.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49fd2430-7992-4468-89ca-63ee0730271f/Order Staying Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.13.docx/docx/1). Where the Clerk has supplied the copies of the orders as directed by rule 10, the Clerk shall also send a copy of the order granting the stay, to the persons referred to, and in the manner directed, by rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Are there specific proceedings mentioned under the 2014 Act?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"PROCEEDINGS UNDER 2014 ACT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **III. PROCEEDINGS UNDER 2014 ACT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the 2014 Act be held in a different location than where the application is being made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"proceedings under the [2014 Act] may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling in relation to which an application under section 12, 13, 16 or 17 of the [2014 Act] is being made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 13. Subject to the provisions of section 12(15), section 13(12) or, as the case may be, section 17(11) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html), proceedings under the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling in relation to which an application under section 12, 13, 16 or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) is being made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under sections 12, 13, or 17 of the 2014 Act be held in private?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under section 12, 13, or 17 of the [2014 Act] may be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proceedings may be heard otherwise than in public* 14. Proceedings under section 12, 13, or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public, in accordance with the provisions of section 12(11), section 13(10) or, as the case may be, section 17(9) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.16 required before an application to the Court can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 16 of the [2014 Act] shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in the [Form 99A.16]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application to Court in respect of terminated tenancy* 16. An application to the Court under section 16 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in the [Form 99A.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fa2e86f-09d5-4fa6-8d02-1ae9dbf6986b/Application in respect of a tenancy terminated under section 15 Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 No. 99A.16.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99B - Employment Equality Act 1998 and Equal Status Act 2000', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for an application under Section 9 of the Terms of Employment (Information) Act, 1994?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. The original of every notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to the service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court. The Order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b2e23701-561f-4ecf-a414-0f6ecc0c5cce/Order - Employment Equality Act 1998 No. 99B.2.docx/docx/1). 5.[2] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to Section 9 of the [Terms of Employment (Information) Act, 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the respondent employer carries on any trade profession, business or occupation. 6.[3] Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 99B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e4ee31-e67a-4e79-a727-232520a11772/Notice Of Application - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to section 9 of the said [Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1da65de6-ec5f-445b-87e5-6783b9dd15eb/Order - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.4.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 263 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/263/made/en/print?q 263&years 2006), effective 20 June 2006 [2] Order rule 5 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003 [3] Order rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document providing an overview of court rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"# Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 - Court: District # Provisions Overview[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Will the District Court Rules continue to be referred to as the District Court Rules 1997 after amendments in 2014?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997] to [2014]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Title and citation* 1. (1) These Rules, which may be cited as the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014, shall come into operation on the day of February 2014. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) (S.I. No. 93 of 1997) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) to [2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Will the Interpretation of Terms section be replaced?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Amendments* 2. (1) The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997. (2) The following provisions shall be deleted from the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93), namely [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 3; Order 9; [Orders 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules) to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100. (3) The provisions set out in Schedule 2 shall be inserted to the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Order 38. (4) The Schedule of Costs set out in Schedule 3 shall be substituted for the [Schedule of Costs]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Schedule-of-Costs-District-Court-Solicitors-costs-Rules) and the Schedule of Counsel’s Fees to the District Court Rules 1997. (5) Orders 10 and 12 respectively set out in Schedule 4 shall be substituted for [Orders 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) and [12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions) of the District Court Rules 1997.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Will new forms be added to Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The forms set out in Schedule 5 shall be added to Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3. Replacement of forms* 3. (1) Forms 7.1 to 7.6 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.25 inclusive and Form 99.1 shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (2) Forms 100.1 to 100.6 inclusive shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (3) The forms set out in Schedule 5 shall be added to Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Form'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Do the new rules apply to civil proceedings that were already in progress before they came into effect?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4. Application and transitional arrangements* 4. (1) The amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules apply to every civil proceeding commenced in the District Court on or after the date on which these Rules come into effect. (2) Notwithstanding the amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect. [1] Provisions Overview inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document about rules for solicitors'' costs in the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules - Court: District # District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs higher if the amount due is not paid within ten days of service of the claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1. Solicitors’ costs in civil debt claims** | | | | | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at date of issue of the claim notice | If amount due is paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 82.00 | 137.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 164.00 | 273.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 246.00 | 410.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 328.00 | 546.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 410.00 | 682.00 | The above scale of costs (1) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. If the claim notice is defended the costs of the successful party are in accordance with the contract, breach of contract and tort scale for assessment of damages.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are the solicitors'' costs listed in the table exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2. Solicitors’ costs in contract, breach of contract and tort proceedings and in claims for damages unconnected with contract** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at the date of issue of claim notice or, (as the case may be) the amount decreed for debt | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 315.00 | 525.00 | 725.00 | 975.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 630.00 | 1,050.00 | 1,450.00 | 1,950.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,175.00 | 2,725.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 1,260.00 | 2,100.00 | 2,900.00 | 3,500.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 1,575.00 | 2,625.00 | 3,625.00 | 4,275.00 | The above scale of costs (2): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - applies to actions for wrongful detention brought by virtue of section 33(3) of the Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961, according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court; - applies to actions for wrongful detention arising out of a hire-purchase transaction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are the costs fixed or at the discretion of the court for certain types of proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"does not apply to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court by summons pursuant to section 15 of the Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Act 1851; section 10 of the Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Amendment Act 1871 or sections 81, 84, 85 and 86 of the Landlord and Tenant (Ireland) Act 1860 — in such proceedings costs shall be in the discretion of the Court and shall not exceed €110 in any case unless the Court shall, for special reason, otherwise order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3. Solicitors’ costs in landlord and tenant (ejectment) proceedings** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Annual Rent | Costs if settled before without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 189.00 | 315.00 | 410.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 378.00 | 630.00 | 819.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 1,228.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 756.00 | 1,260.00 | 1,638.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,048.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (3): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - does not apply to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court by summons pursuant to [section 15](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/sec0015.html#sec15) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/index.html) ; [section 10](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/sec0010.html#sec10) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Amendment Act 1871](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/index.html) or sections 81, 84, 85 and 86 of the Landlord and Tenant (Ireland) Act 1860 — in such proceedings costs shall be in the discretion of the Court and shall not exceed €110 in any case unless the Court shall, for special reason, otherwise order; - applies to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court on civil summons pursuant to [section 82](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/sec0082.html#sec82) of the [Civil Bill Courts (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/index.html) as applied to the District Court by [section 17](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/sec0017.html#sec17) of the [Courts of Justice Act 1928](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/index.html) .'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs for proceedings under the Enforcement of Court Orders Acts 1926 to 2009 separate from any actual and necessary outlay?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The above scale of costs (4) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings under the *Enforcement of Court Orders Acts 1926 to 2009*** | | | | --- | --- | | Amount due | | | | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 157.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 315.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 630.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 788.00 | | Exceeding €15,000 | 866.00 | The above scale of costs (4) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs higher when a case is defended?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if case defended | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **5. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings for compensation under section 15 of the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982** | Amount of compensation awarded or, in case of dismiss, amount of compensation claimed | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended | | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 463.00 | 772.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 926.00 | 1,544.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 1,389.00 | 2,315.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 1,852.00 | 3,087.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 2,315.00 | 3,859.00 | The above scale of costs (5) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are the solicitors'' costs higher when the case is defended compared to when it is not defended?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 236.00 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 945.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **6. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings for recovery of possession under section 16 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*** | Annual rent | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended | Costs of judgment for respondent (dismiss) | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 119.00 | 284.00 | 472.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 236.00 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 355.00 | 850.00 | 1,418.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 472.00 | 1,134.00 | 1,890.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 591.00 | 1,418.00 | 2,362.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (6) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs listed in the table exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The above scale of costs (7) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **7. Solicitors’ costs, where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer** | Amount of compensation claimed | Costs | | --- | --- | | | € | | Exceeding €125 and not exceeding €250 | 16.00 | | Exceeding €250 and not exceeding €750 | 94.00 | | Exceeding €750 and not exceeding €1,400 | 147.00 | | Exceeding €1,400 | 242.00 | The above scale of costs (7) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can solicitors'' costs exceed €15,000 in consent proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **10. Solicitors’ costs in consent proceedings to which section of the Courts Act 1991 relates** Where proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 are brought before the District Court and: - the amount claimed in the proceedings exceeds €15,000, and, - pursuant to the proviso to section 77A of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 (inserted by section of the Courts Act 1991), the necessary parties to the proceedings sign the prescribed form of consent, and - (iii) the Court in determining the proceedings awards an amount in excess of €15,000, the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the foregoing scales 1 to 9 in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000. Where the proceedings are dismissed, the defendant may be allowed costs similarly calculated on the amount claimed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific provision regarding solicitors'' costs when an action is transferred to the District Court from the High Court or the Circuit Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an action, other than an action to which paragraph (2) relates, has been remitted or transferred to the District Court:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **11. Solicitors’ costs in actions transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court** (1) Where an action, other than an action to which paragraph (2) relates, has been remitted or transferred to the District Court: - (a) by the High Court pursuant to section 25 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924, or - by the Circuit Court pursuant to section 15(1) of the Courts Act 1991, and the Court, in determining the matter, makes an order in favour of the claimant, the claimant may not recover any greater costs than the appropriate costs as set out in the above scales which he or she would have been entitled to recover if the action had originally been commenced in the District Court. If the claimant fails to prove the claim, the respondent is entitled, in addition to any costs which may be allowed to him or her under the above scales, to a minimum sum of €100.00 or such greater sum as the Judge may in the circumstances consider proper. (2) Where an action so remitted or transferred is an action for unliquidated damages and the Court, pursuant to section 15(2) of the Courts Act 1991 (as amended by section 20 of the Courts and Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2013), makes an order awarding to a party to the action an amount in excess of €15,000 but not exceeding €30,000, the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the above scales in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000. Where such an action is dismissed, the respondent may be allowed costs similarly calculated on the amount claimed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are miscellaneous outlays such as postage and photocopying included in the schedule?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Miscellaneous outlays to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries to be allowed in accordance with [Order 53]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **12. Schedule of outlays** Miscellaneous outlays to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries to be allowed in accordance with [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), rule 2. | | | | --- | --- | | Amount due at the date of issue of claim notice | **-** | | —(in the case of debt claims) | | | —(in the case of Instalment Orders) | | | Amount awarded | **-** | | —(in cases of contract, breach of contract and tort proceedings and in claims for damages unconnected with contract) | | | Annual rent | **-** | | —(in the case of landlord and tenant (ejectment) proceedings begun by claim notice) | | | —(in proceedings for the recovery of possession under section 16 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*) | | | Amount of compensation awarded | **-** | | —(in proceedings for compensation under section 15 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*) | | | Amount of compensation claimed | **-** | | —(in cases under the *Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986*) | | | Amount sued for | **-** | | —(in summary proceedings for the recovery of rates) | | | | | | Not exceeding €5,000 | €52.50 plus VAT | | Exceeding €5,000 and not exceeding €10,000 | €105.00 plus VAT | | Exceeding €10,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | €157.50 plus VAT |'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are counsel''s fees awarded in cases related to malicious injuries?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **13. Counsel’s Fees** (1) in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract (2) in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent (3) where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are there specific fees listed for drafting a Notice of Motion?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Drafting Notice of Motion | 50.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Part 2: Additional counsel’s fees for particular work undertaken by counsel, where certified | | | | --- | --- | | | | | | € | | Drafting Claim Notice or Defence | 175.00 | | Drafting Notice of Motion | 50.00 | | Drafting Affidavit | 125.00 | | Brief on hearing of Motion | 150.00 | | Advice on Proofs | 150.00 | | Consultation | 150.00 | | Drafting Notice for Particulars | 100.00 | | Drafting Reply to Notice for Particulars | 100.00 | [1] District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules substituted in full by [S.I. 418 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/418/made/en/print) effective from 25 August 2023'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court specified as Superior in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: Superior"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Superior # **Order Defamation Act 2009 [1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit of verification required to be filed in court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 8(5) by filing the same in the Central Office."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8** 2. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form No 4 in Appendix CC](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-actions-civil-liability-and-courts-act-2004#_fri4), with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate from the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon such pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 8(5) by filing the same in the Central Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for a ruling under section 14 be made parte?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **III. Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957** 3. (1) An application for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the [Statute of Limitations 1957](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1957/act/6/enacted/en/html) shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (3) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (4) Where no defamation action has been brought in relation to a statement referred to in section 33, an application: - for an interim order under subsection (3)(a) of that section shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be made by originating motion parte, entitled in the matter of section 33, in which the person referred 3 to as plaintiff in section 33 is named as applicant and the person referred to as defendant in section 33 is named as respondent, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the applicant;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an affidavit required when making an application under section 23(1)(a) after an offer to make amends is accepted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"an application: [...] shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted** 4. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include an order allowing either party to alter or amend his pleadings) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph(c) of section 23(1). 5. (1) Where no defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned,'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific time limit mentioned for delivering a replying affidavit by the respondent?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the respondent to such originating notice of motion may deliver a replying affidavit within two weeks of the delivery to him or her of copies of the said originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication, or - (iii) for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1) shall be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 23 and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the person who made the offer shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Notice of an application under sub-rule (1) shall be given by delivering copies of the originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit and any exhibits thereto to the respondent not later than four clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion. (3) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the respondent to such originating notice of motion may deliver a replying affidavit within two weeks of the delivery to him or her of copies of the said originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit. (4) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the applicant may deliver a further affidavit within two weeks of the delivery of any replying affidavit. 6. Save in the case of an application under paragraph (a) of section 23(1), the Court may, at the hearing of an originating motion under rule 5(and in addition to any other order it may make): - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is a plenary hearing required if there is no substantial dispute of fact?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties). 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 4 and 5 shall: - identify with sufficient precision or exhibit a copy or transcript of the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. Where an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) to bring or proceed with a defamation action against another person in respect of the statement to which the offer to make amends applies shall: - where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defendant notify their intention to provide evidence of an apology in their defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24** 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the defendant allowed to provide evidence for mitigation of damages without the judge''s permission if they do not assert the truth of the statement?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation** 10. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 511 of 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/511/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 57 related to multiple acts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc. - Court: District # Order 57: Proceedings Under:**[1]** **- Section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html)** **- Section 9A of the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11)** **- Section 52A of the**[**Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010**](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 mentioned in the definitions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Definitions** 1. (1) In this Order: “**the Act of 1940**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. [23 of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/print.html)); “**the Act of 1976**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No. 11 of 1976); “**the Act of 2009**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**the Act of 2010**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (No. 24 of 2010); “**the Act of 2011**” means the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23) (No. 31 of 2011); “**Maintenance Regulation**” means [Council Regulation 4/2009](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>) of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1); “**2011 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Maintenance) Regulations 2011 ([S.I. 274 of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print)); “**2019 Regulations**” means the European Union (Hague Maintenance Convention) Regulations 2019 ([S.I. 594 of 2019](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print)). (2) References in this Order to an “**order**” shall, as the circumstances require, be construed in accordance with: - (a) sections 65 and 136 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), or - regulation 10(2) of the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print), or - the definition of “**enforceable maintenance order**” in regulation 14(1) of the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings concerning an enforceable maintenance order be brought in a different court area if the debtor does not reside in the state?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned does not reside in the State but is employed by a person residing or having a place of business in the State or by a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, the court area in which the person resides or the body has its seat."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Venue** 2.(1) Subject to sub-rule (2), proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made and, save where the context otherwise requires, any reference in this Order to the “**Clerk**” is a reference to the Clerk for that court area. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings to which this Order relates concerning an enforceable maintenance order to which the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print) or, as the case may be, the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print) apply may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for: - (a) where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State, the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned does not reside in the State but is employed by a person residing or having a place of business in the State or by a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, the court area in which the person resides or the body has its seat.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application under section 8(1) of the Act of 1940 required to be in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) for the issue of a summons shall be in writing (and may be by the lodgment with the Clerk of a completed draft form of summons)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application in writing for summons under section 8(1) of the Act of** **1940** 3. An application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) for the issue of a summons shall be in writing (and may be by the lodgment with the Clerk of a completed draft form of summons) and shall include: - (a) a copy of the antecedent order concerned and, where relevant, a copy of any enforcement order made by the Master of the High Court in respect of the maintenance order concerned or, as the case may be, a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), of the decision issued by the court of origin; - the period(s) for which the monetary amounts directed to be paid by the antecedent order have not been duly paid; - the amount of the arrears, and any amount provided by the antecedent order for costs and expenses which is unpaid; - a statement that the applicant understands that the information included in the application may have to be proved on oath at the hearing of any summons issued on foot of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the statement of means and assets required to be submitted before the court sitting?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"not less than one week before the date of the said sitting a statement of means and assets"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Issue of summons under section 8(1) of the Act of 1940** 4.(1) The summons shall be in the [Form 57.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4dde7091-171c-4c95-b51f-5402ef56bb8a/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule The summons shall, in addition to requiring the attendance of the defaulter at a sitting of the Court, also require the defaulter to complete, detach and lodge with the Clerk not less than one week before the date of the said sitting a statement of means and assets (in the Form 53.3 Schedule with the necessary modifications), which shall be attached to the summons. (2) The applicant or solicitor for the applicant shall be entitled, on payment of the prescribed fee, to inspect and take or obtain copies of the statement of means at any time after it is lodged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the warrant of distress and sale governed by a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant of distress and sale under section of the [Act of 1940] shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Distress warrant** 5. A warrant of distress and sale under section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/38749eea-3bc2-43d2-be1a-ada03602921d/Warrant of distress and sale - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Can a maintenance creditor apply for a summons using Form 57.3?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application under section 9A(3) of the [Act of 1976] (as inserted by the [Act of 2011]) or under section 52A(3) of the [Act of 2010] (as inserted by section 146 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) for the issue of a summons may be made by the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in the [Form 57.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application\*\*\***in writing for summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010\*\*\* 6.**[2]** An application under section 9A(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (as inserted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) or under section 52A(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (as inserted by section 146 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) for the issue of a summons may be made by the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in the [Form 57.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de505ada-98be-4de0-97bc-a3cd9276d517/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.3.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application from, the Clerk will issue a summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the summons for maintenance arrears required to be in a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The summons addressed to the maintenance debtor must be in the Form [57.3A Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010** 7.[3] The summons addressed to the maintenance debtor must be in the Form [57.3A Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/06eb5b14-6585-4a62-b3cb-05032e52813a/57.3A_SI_Basic_text_Summons_to_recover_Maintenance_Arrears_specified_in_Court Rules.docx/docx/1). ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Must a statutory declaration about the service of a summons and application form be filed at least two days before the hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Service of summonses, application forms and orders** 8.[4] (1) [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons and application form mentioned in rule 4. (2) [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 8(5), 8(7) and 8(8) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons mentioned in rule 7 and application form mentioned in rule 6. A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing. (3) An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) may be in the [Form 57.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3022a2b1-6ed7-4036-94c6-7ff708590ba3/Notice Of Application To Vary A Garnishee Order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such order must be sent by registered post by the Clerk to every person directed to pay monies to the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person served with an order under rule 8(3) apply to the court to set aside or vary the order if they are unable to comply?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person served with an order mentioned in rule 8(3) who is unable to comply with the order may apply to the Court by notice of application in the [Form 57.5]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Persons affected by garnishee order** 9.(1) A person served with an order mentioned in rule 8(3) who is unable to comply with the order may apply to the Court by notice of application in the [Form 57.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/537ff74b-79ab-44a4-9185-6c4ea61f9014/Notice of application to vary a garnishee order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule to set aside or vary the order. A copy of the notice shall be served on the defaulter and on the applicant not later than seven days before the hearing of the application and the original notice shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the hearing of the application. (2) Where the Court is considering making an order under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), the Court may adjourn the hearing of the summons and direct that the person who would be directed to pay monies to the Clerk under any such order be put on notice of the adjourned application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the warrant of arrest required to follow a specific form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A warrant of arrest issued under section 9A(5) of the [Act of 1976] or 52A(5) of the [Act of 2010] shall be in accordance with [Form 57.6]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Warrant of arrest** 10. A warrant of arrest issued under section 9A(5) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or 52A(5) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fa7efc1e-7516-4693-960e-e597ff6c36de/Warrant of arrest - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976, section 9A(5) (as inserted by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 31) No. 57.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is a warrant of detention issued when there is a failure by the maintenance debtor that is treated as contempt of court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a failure by the maintenance debtor is treated as constituting contempt of court and an order of imprisonment is made, the warrant of detention shall be in accordance with Form 57.7 or 57.8 Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Warrant of detention** 11. Where a failure by the maintenance debtor is treated as constituting contempt of court and an order of imprisonment is made, the warrant of detention shall be in accordance with [Form 57.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c232310a-6e21-4ab3-9e64-3238d268540d/Warrant of detention (where debtor has attended) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.7.docx/docx/1) or [57.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55796fe-ed99-4d9d-b822-009865e6013f/Warrant of detention (failure to attend) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is a person who is imprisoned for contempt notified in writing about how to purge their contempt?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application to purge contempt** 12. Where a person is imprisoned for contempt of court in accordance with section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24): - (a) the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt; - the Court may direct that, if the contempt has not previously been purged, the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is a clerk required to provide a certificate before the hearing of an application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Before the time fixed for the hearing of an application under section 8 of the Act of 1940, section 9A of the Act of 1976 or section 52A of the Act of 2010, any Clerk for another court area to whom payments under the maintenance order, variation order, interim order or enforceable maintenance order are payable shall send to the Clerk a certificate signed by him or her certifying the amount of monies outstanding on foot of such order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Clerk to provide certificate and to be available to tender evidence** 13. (1) Before the time fixed for the hearing of an application under section 8 of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), any Clerk for another court area to whom payments under the maintenance order, variation order, interim order or enforceable maintenance order are payable shall send to the Clerk a certificate signed by him or her certifying the amount of monies outstanding on foot of such order. (2) On the hearing of an application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), without prejudice to any other evidence which may be required on that hearing, there shall be tendered or cause to be tendered as evidence - - (a) the maintenance order, variation order, interim order, (as the case may be); - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order; - in the case of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), of the decision issued by the court of origin; - the application for the summons; - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court, and - any other relevant document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Will the provisions about warrants be applied to warrants issued under this order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions contained in [Order 26] regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Provisions regarding warrants to apply** 14. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order with the proviso that warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the several Sheriffs and County Registrars. [1] Order 57 substituted in full by [S.I. 202 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/202/made/en/print), effective 5 May 2021. Superseded amendments: Order 57 originally substituted by [S.I. 325 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/325/made/en/print?q 325&years 2010), re-substituted by [S.I. 306 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/si/306/made/en/print?q 306&years 2013), substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016. [2] Order 57 rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [3] Order 57 rule 7 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [4] Order 57 rule 8 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is Order 39A related to civil proceedings in the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court - Court: District # Order 39A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section primarily focused on explaining terms?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is a ''digital user'' defined as someone who can deliver and receive documents electronically from the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"which is or who is for the time being authorised to deliver to the Clerk and to receive from the Clerk by digital means any court document or other document which may be lodged or filed in or with the Court in or in connection with any proceedings or category of proceedings in the Court, in respect of which digital delivery is for the time being authorised"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**Clerk**”, where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk; “**court document**” includes any claim notice, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the Clerk in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the Clerk, - by or on behalf of the Clerk to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership, acting through a person authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person, which is or who is for the time being authorised to deliver to the Clerk and to receive from the Clerk by digital means any court document or other document which may be lodged or filed in or with the Court in or in connection with any proceedings or category of proceedings in the Court, in respect of which digital delivery is for the time being authorised in accordance with section 20 of the [Civil Law and Criminal Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 202](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/act/13/enacted/en/html)0; “**network**” means an electronic information and communications network or system maintained and supported by the Courts Service for the purposes of use by court users in civil proceedings, for the time being in use in or for the purposes of the Court, to which digital users have access, and which is used or capable of use for digital delivery;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal delivery of a court document considered non-personal delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"\"personal delivery\" means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '“**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the Clerk: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the Clerk, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**personal delivery**” means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about the form of documents and providing copies?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"## Form of documents and provision of copies"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Form of documents and provision of copies'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for all notices and notifications to be given in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Notices in writing_ 2.(1) All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally. (2) Nothing in this Order operates to require a document delivered in electronic form, including by digital delivery, to be printed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document be submitted electronically according to the rules?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a document is for the time being authorised in accordance with this Order to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by digital delivery or to be produced in digital form (in soft copy) for use in Court, such document may comprise or include:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Form of documents_ 3.(1) Any document for use in Court which is required or permitted to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by delivery in person (of a hard copy) or by delivery by post (of a hard copy) must be clearly and legibly printed or written on A4 size paper. (2) Where a document is for the time being authorised in accordance with this Order to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by digital delivery or to be produced in digital form (in soft copy) for use in Court, such document may comprise or include: - (a) information transmitted in the form of an electronic document or other electronic data to a network (including, for the avoidance of doubt, a statement of truth), and - information made available to a digital user on a network to which the digital user concerned has secure access, which is capable of being presented or reproduced in legible form, and any such document need not be provided in printed form, notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party obtain a copy of a document directly from the Clerk if the original filer does not provide it?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"if that party fails to provide a copy, the party seeking the document may obtain a copy from the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Provision of copy documents_ 4. Any party who is entitled to a copy of a document which has been filed by or on behalf of another party may request such a copy from the party who filed it, and if that party fails to provide a copy, the party seeking the document may obtain a copy from the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor provide a legible print as a copy of a digitally delivered document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the party who has filed it or his solicitor may satisfy a request for a copy by providing a legible print which corresponds entirely in its content with the digital original document"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Provision of copies_ 5. Where a document has been filed or lodged by digital delivery, the party who has filed it or his solicitor may satisfy a request for a copy by providing a legible print which corresponds entirely in its content with the digital original document, or by providing a certified copy of such a legible print.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk certify a copy of an original document?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Copy certified by Clerk_ 6. The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section discussing how to deliver documents directly to an office or authority?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents by personal delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## III. Lodgment or filing of documents by personal delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents be delivered personally to the clerk''s office during its business hours?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Personal delivery at office_ 7. Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk set specific conditions for non-personal delivery of court documents?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may stipulate conditions, to be published in such manner as the Clerk may approve, subject to which non-personal delivery in hard copy of a court document may be effected."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for non-personal delivery in hard copy_ 8.(1) The Clerk may stipulate conditions, to be published in such manner as the Clerk may approve, subject to which non-personal delivery in hard copy of a court document may be effected. (2) Such conditions referred to in sub-rule (1) may be particular or general, and may include a requirement for the discharge of the expense of returning any court document, or copy of such document, by particular means to the person who has delivered it. Where no such conditions are for the time being stipulated, the existing practice shall continue to be used. (3) Where a provision of these Rules requires or authorises a party or person to lodge or file any court document, such lodgment or filing may be effected by non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with any condition stipulated for that means of non-personal delivery in hard copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is payment of a court fee required before a court document can be used when lodging through non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where payment of a court fee is chargeable in respect of the lodgment of the court document, the court document shall not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Additional requirements for non-personal delivery in hard copy_ 9.(1) Where any court document is authorised to be lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such document, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with rule 8; - where payment of a court fee is chargeable in respect of the lodgment of the court document, the court document shall not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee; - the date of lodgment of the document is, unless the contrary is proven, deemed to be the date of lodgment recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk and such date may be endorsed on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk; - for the purpose of fixing the return date of any notice of application (or other originating document or notice of motion requiring a return date) lodged for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, a period of four days must, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - there must be delivered with any court document lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy so many copies of that document and such other documents as would be required on the personal delivery of that court document. (2) Where a court document, having been issued, has been returned to the party or person who lodged it for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, and that court document is not received by that party or person within a reasonable time after it is sent, - (a) the Clerk concerned may, at the request of that party or person, furnish to that person -'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party proceed using a copy of a court document if they have a certificate confirming its issuance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- a copy of any duplicate or copy of the court document concerned retained by the Clerk, with a certificate endorsed thereon confirming the issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates; - a certificate as to any record made of the issue of the court document concerned, and - the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i) or, where the Court so permits, a copy of the court document lodged for issue, certified by the party who lodged it or his or her solicitor to be a true copy of the court document lodged, and a certificate given in accordance with paragraph (a)(ii).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section discussing physical document submission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific clause that states one set of rules will take precedence over others when it comes to digital document delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the provision of the rule of this Order will, in respect of the digital delivery of any document, prevail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _This Part prevails where digital delivery is concerned_ 11.(1) In the event that any conflict arises between the provision of any rule of this Order and any other provision of these Rules, the provision of the rule of this Order will, in respect of the digital delivery of any document, prevail. (2) The provisions of this Order are without prejudice to the use of and permission of access to any network used for any purpose not regulated by these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the President of the Court authorize the use of digital delivery on a temporary basis?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the President of the Court may, from time to time, by Practice Direction, authorise (including on a temporary or trial basis) the use of digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Authorisation of digital delivery of court documents or documents_ 12.(1) Having consulted with the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service the President of the Court may, from time to time, by Practice Direction, authorise (including on a temporary or trial basis) the use of digital delivery by or in respect of any: - category or class of proceedings or of applications within proceedings, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - category or class of documents, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - (iii) category or class of parties, legal representatives and/or other persons interested in proceedings (in this rule a “court user”), either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally. (2) Unless otherwise expressly provided in such Practice Direction, where the use of digital delivery is authorised in accordance with sub-rule (1), such delivery will be an alternative to any other method by which such document could be filed, lodged, issued or transmitted by or to the party or person concerned. (3) A network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is, for the purposes of the delivery of any court document or document to any Clerk, deemed to be operational only during the hours during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public. (4) Any period when a network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is inoperative will be treated, for the purposes of [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), Rule as a period during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is closed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is submitting evidence of identity required for a natural person to become a digital user?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A natural person may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: ... such person has first submitted sufficient evidence of his or her identity"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for becoming digital user_ 13.(1) A natural person may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - such person has first submitted sufficient evidence of his or her identity which may, without limitation, include: - (a) production of the original or a certified copy of a relevant document (within the meaning of section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)); - provision of the personal public service number (within the meaning of section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) issued to the person; - provision of proof of the person’s residential address, and - such person has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery. (2) A firm of solicitors or legal partnership may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - the firm or partnership has first submitted sufficient evidence of its establishment and standing; - the firm or partnership has submitted sufficient evidence of the identity of each natural person authorised on behalf of the firm to transmit court documents through the network by digital delivery; - (iii) the firm or partnership has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service set additional conditions for using the network?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service may, with the approval of the President of the Court in respect of proceedings in the Court, stipulate additional conditions for use of the network."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Additional conditions for use of the network_ 14.(1) The Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service may, with the approval of the President of the Court in respect of proceedings in the Court, stipulate additional conditions for use of the network.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must a document transmitted by digital delivery include a statement about authority when submitted by someone other than the party themselves?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Documents transmitted by digital delivery_ 15.(1) Any court document transmitted by digital delivery by or on behalf of a party must: - (a) contain: - the name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the same or, as the case may be, - the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person; - include the name of the natural person transmitting the court document concerned; - where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted. (2) Any document other than a court document which is transmitted by or on behalf of a party by digital delivery as a copy in electronic form of an original document must have endorsed on or associated with such copy a certificate given by the party or by a named solicitor that the copy has been compared to, and is a true copy, of the original document. (3) Where any court document is authorised to be filed or lodged by digital delivery: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such information, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning digital delivery in accordance with rule 14; - where a court fee is chargeable in respect of the court document, the court document may not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the date of filing, lodgment, or issue of a court document be deemed to be the date recorded in any record kept by or on behalf of the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk or on the network and such date may be endorsed electronically on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk and may be notified electronically through the network to the party concerned; - for the purpose of fixing a return date for any originating document or notice of motion which requires a return date, and which is lodged for issue by digital delivery, a period of four days will, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - any obligation or entitlement arising under these Rules to lodge or, as the case may be, to file a court document shall, unless the contrary is proved, be satisfied by the digital delivery of the document to the network and the issuance by the network of confirmation of lodgment or, as the case may be, filing; - the network or the Clerk will alert digital users, prior to submission, where the filing, lodgment or issue of any court document is subject to checking by a court officer. (4) Where the Clerk is satisfied that it is necessary to do so, he or she may: - (a) retransmit a court document, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned; - deliver a printed copy of the court document concerned by delivery in hard copy, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned, and in either such case, any party or person affected may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a court document or copy of a court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a) or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can affidavits be transmitted electronically when digital delivery is authorized?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where any affidavit is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, the affidavit shall be transmitted in such electronic format as is accommodated by the network"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where any affidavit is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, the affidavit shall be transmitted in such electronic format as is accommodated by the network, and it shall be and remain the obligation of the party filing any such affidavit to retain the affidavit bearing the original manuscript signature of the deponent and any and all of the marked exhibits to the affidavit, which remain subject to the directions of any court before which such affidavit is, or may be, relied upon or opened. (6) Where any written statement of evidence or written statement outlining the essential elements of evidence is authorised or required by any Practice Direction or any order or direction of the Court to be delivered and/or filed in any proceedings in which digital delivery is for the time being authorised, such statement may be delivered and/or filed by transmission through the network, but shall, if intended to be admitted into evidence, be subject to verification on oath or affirmation at the trial of the proceedings. (7) Where any affidavit or any statement referred to in sub-rule (6) is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, [Order 50A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url statements-of-truth), rule 6 shall apply *mutatis mutandis* to any exhibits to such affidavit or statement.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can an electronic signature satisfy the signing requirement for documents transmitted through digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Signature_ 16. Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of that Act and/or that Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there information about serving documents through digital means in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service of documents using digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Service of documents using digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can digital delivery be used for serving court documents if the rules require personal service?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Sub-rule (1) does not apply in any case where these Rules or the existing practice of the Court require personal service"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Service of documents where digital delivery applies_ 17.(1) Where any provision of any enactment, of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires or permits that any court document or document be served upon any person, such requirement may be satisfied in any case where the person to be served is or becomes a digital user by the transmission by digital delivery of the court document or document through the network to the person concerned, and in any such case any record generated by or within the network of such transmission may be produced as evidence of such service in lieu of any statutory declaration of service. (Where the person to be served is not a digital user, such person shall be served with a printed copy of the court document or document in such other manner as is permitted in the circumstances by these Rules). (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply in any case where these Rules or the existing practice of the Court require personal service, but any requirement that a person being served personally with a court document be shown any original or copy of the court document shall, where the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery, be satisfied by serving the person personally with a copy of the court document concerned and, at the same time, providing the person with a written statement that the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about misuse of digital delivery network in the given text?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Misuse of digital delivery network"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## VII. Misuse of digital delivery network'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Clerk refer a matter to the Court if they believe someone has improperly used digital permissions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a Clerk is concerned that a person has improperly used permissions available to a digital user to prejudice a party in any proceedings, the Clerk may refer the matter to the Court on notice to the parties concerned, and the Court may make such order or give such directions as are just in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Reference to Court_ 18.(1) Where a party alleges that another person has improperly used permissions available to a digital user to prejudice that party in any proceedings, the party aggrieved may apply to the Court by motion on notice, grounded on an affidavit, and the Court may make such order or give such directions as are just in the circumstances. (2) Where a Clerk is concerned that a person has improperly used permissions available to a digital user to prejudice a party in any proceedings, the Clerk may refer the matter to the Court on notice to the parties concerned, and the Court may make such order or give such directions as are just in the circumstances. [1] Order 39A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing requirements for pleadings in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. - Court: Circuit # Order 11A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section primarily focused on defining terms?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Can a court document be delivered digitally according to the definitions provided?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"delivery of that document by electronic means: by a digital user to the proper officer, by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**proper officer”** are references to the Combined Court Office manager for the time being responsible for the management of the Office of the Court for the relevant county, and where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the Circuit Court for the circuit and/or county concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Combined Court Office manager; “**court document**” includes any civil bill, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the proper officer in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the proper officer: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the proper officer, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the proper officer, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the proper officer, - by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership acting through a person or persons authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under certain sections of the 1997 Act be held outside of public view?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act] may be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proceedings may be heard otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific form required for an application to the Court for an excluding order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act] for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Excluding Orders* 4. (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/331b2936-1752-49cc-82e8-f8bb1cff527f/Application For An Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1). (3) Where an excluding order is made by the Court in accordance with the provisions of section 12(12)(a) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) on foot of a possession application under section 12 of that Act, the order shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.4 required before applying for a site excluding order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the court under section 3A of the [1997 Act] for a site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Site Excluding Orders* 5. (1) An application to the court under section 3A of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for a site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an interim excluding order required to be supported by written information on oath?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act] on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim Excluding Orders/Site Excluding Orders* 6.[2] (1) An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8590fb7f-0de3-4171-a21d-356ce5134af5/Information - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.5.docx/docx/1) or on an affidavit sworn by the applicant incorporating the matter in that Form. (2) The order of the Court shall be in the [Form 99A.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c08a91c-e6c8-421e-88d9-0db1d7d5fb86/Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.6.docx/docx/1). (3) An application for confirmation under section of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) of an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made parte under the terms of section 4(3) of that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent by the applicant at least 2 days before the date fixed for such application of a notice in the [Form 99A.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c14e9af0-5f7b-4c77-a2b8-0c2515212e98/Application To Confirm An Interim Excluding - Interim Site Excluding Order Made Parte - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.14.docx/docx/1). The applicant shall also serve on the respondent the documents referred to in section 4(3)(c)(ii) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html). (4) Where, on such application, the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order is confirmed, such confirmation shall be indorsed upon the order and signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.7 required before an application to vary an excluding order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under ... shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary Excluding/ Site Excluding/ Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders* 7. (1) An application to the Court under - (a) section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an excluding order, - section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, - section 3A(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary a site excluding order, or section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) and section 3A(9) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b135a660-4139-4bf7-9106-e0177cefb952/Application To Vary An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.7.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ee4a98d-c7c5-44f1-a4ed-9981fa04bbd1/Order Varying An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is a notice in Form 99A.9 required before an application to discharge an excluding order can be made?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"An application to the Court under section 9(1) of the [1997 Act] to discharge an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.9, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Discharge Excluding Site Excluding or Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders 8. (1) An application to the Court under section 9(1) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to discharge an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b98b105d-e0e2-4674-8f94-49219cc93bf1/Application To Discharge An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.9.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e9130d4-ae3e-4664-a740-0ed9bf4d754e/Order Discharging An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.10.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the Clerk required to send a certified copy of the order to the Garda Síochána by prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the member of the Garda Síochána Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Clerk to supply copies of order 10. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order, the Clerk shall give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable to- - (a) the applicant concerned, - the respondent, - the housing authority in whose functional area the house, site or dwelling in respect of which the application for the order was made is situate, and the Health Service Executive by ordinary prepaid post and - the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Is the clerk required to inform the Gardaí when an interim excluding order ends?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the Clerk shall send notice that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Interim Excluding/Site Excluding orders ceases to have effect.* 11.[4] Where an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has been made and the application for an excluding order or site excluding order has been determined, the Clerk shall send notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1), that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can an appeal from an interim excluding order stay the operation of that order?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"an appeal from an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall not stay the operation of the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeal from orders* 12.(1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 9(4) and [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) and that an appellant has entered into a recognisance for appeal, - (a) an appeal from an excluding order or a site excluding order shall, if the court that made the order or the court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination; - an appeal from an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall not stay the operation of the order. (2) - (a) An application to the District Court to stay the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under section 8 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made following the service and lodgment of a notice of appeal and lodgment of the recognisance of appeal and when made otherwise than upon the occasion of the making of that order shall be preceded by the issue of a notice in the [Form 99A.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/937d34a2-ae9f-44f7-bbd1-e0bf160a77b4/Application For A Stay On The Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.12.docx/docx/1), which shall be served upon the respondent to the application two days before the hearing of the application. - Where the Court grants a stay on the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under this rule, the order granting such stay shall be in the [Form 99A.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49fd2430-7992-4468-89ca-63ee0730271f/Order Staying Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.13.docx/docx/1). Where the Clerk has supplied the copies of the orders as directed by rule 10, the Clerk shall also send a copy of the order granting the stay, to the persons referred to, and in the manner directed, by rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings under the 2014 Act be held in a District Court located in the same area as the dwelling related to the application?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"proceedings under the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 13. Subject to the provisions of section 12(15), section 13(12) or, as the case may be, section 17(11) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html), proceedings under the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling in relation to which an application under section 12, 13, 16 or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) is being made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99B - Employment Equality Act 1998 and Equal Status Act 2000', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a requirement for a notice of application to be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. The original of every notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to the service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court. The Order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b2e23701-561f-4ecf-a414-0f6ecc0c5cce/Order - Employment Equality Act 1998 No. 99B.2.docx/docx/1). 5.[2] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to Section 9 of the [Terms of Employment (Information) Act, 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the respondent employer carries on any trade profession, business or occupation. 6.[3] Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 99B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e4ee31-e67a-4e79-a727-232520a11772/Notice Of Application - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to section 9 of the said [Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1da65de6-ec5f-445b-87e5-6783b9dd15eb/Order - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.4.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 263 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/263/made/en/print?q 263&years 2006), effective 20 June 2006 [2] Order rule 5 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003 [3] Order rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Will the District Court Rules continue to be referred to as the District Court Rules 1997 after the amendments in 2014?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the District Court Rules 1997 to 2014."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Title and citation* 1. (1) These Rules, which may be cited as the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014, shall come into operation on the day of February 2014. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) (S.I. No. 93 of 1997) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) to [2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Will the Interpretation of Terms provisions be replaced?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “Interpretation of Terms” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Amendments* 2. (1) The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997. (2) The following provisions shall be deleted from the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93), namely [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 3; Order 9; [Orders 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules) to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100. (3) The provisions set out in Schedule 2 shall be inserted to the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Order 38. (4) The Schedule of Costs set out in Schedule 3 shall be substituted for the [Schedule of Costs]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Schedule-of-Costs-District-Court-Solicitors-costs-Rules) and the Schedule of Counsel’s Fees to the District Court Rules 1997. (5) Orders 10 and 12 respectively set out in Schedule 4 shall be substituted for [Orders 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) and [12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions) of the District Court Rules 1997.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Do ongoing cases continue under the old rules after the new ones take effect?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4. Application and transitional arrangements* 4. (1) The amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules apply to every civil proceeding commenced in the District Court on or after the date on which these Rules come into effect. (2) Notwithstanding the amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect. [1] Provisions Overview inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs higher if the amount due is not paid within ten days of the service of the claim notice?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"If the amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1. Solicitors’ costs in civil debt claims** | | | | | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at date of issue of the claim notice | If amount due is paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 82.00 | 137.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 164.00 | 273.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 246.00 | 410.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 328.00 | 546.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 410.00 | 682.00 | The above scale of costs (1) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. If the claim notice is defended the costs of the successful party are in accordance with the contract, breach of contract and tort scale for assessment of damages.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are the solicitors'' costs listed in the table exclusive of outlay?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2. Solicitors’ costs in contract, breach of contract and tort proceedings and in claims for damages unconnected with contract** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at the date of issue of claim notice or, (as the case may be) the amount decreed for debt | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 315.00 | 525.00 | 725.00 | 975.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 630.00 | 1,050.00 | 1,450.00 | 1,950.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,175.00 | 2,725.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 1,260.00 | 2,100.00 | 2,900.00 | 3,500.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 1,575.00 | 2,625.00 | 3,625.00 | 4,275.00 | The above scale of costs (2): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - applies to actions for wrongful detention brought by virtue of section 33(3) of the Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961, according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court; - applies to actions for wrongful detention arising out of a hire-purchase transaction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are the costs for ejectment proceedings brought under certain specific sections of historical Irish legislation capped at €110?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"does not apply to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court by summons pursuant to section 15 of the Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Act 1851; section 10 of the Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Amendment Act 1871 or sections 81, 84, 85 and 86 of the Landlord and Tenant (Ireland) Act 1860 — in such proceedings costs shall be in the discretion of the Court and shall not exceed €110 in any case unless the Court shall, for special reason, otherwise order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3. Solicitors’ costs in landlord and tenant (ejectment) proceedings** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Annual Rent | Costs if settled before without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 189.00 | 315.00 | 410.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 378.00 | 630.00 | 819.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 1,228.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 756.00 | 1,260.00 | 1,638.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,048.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (3): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - does not apply to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court by summons pursuant to [section 15](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/sec0015.html#sec15) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/index.html) ; [section 10](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/sec0010.html#sec10) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Amendment Act 1871](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/index.html) or sections 81, 84, 85 and 86 of the Landlord and Tenant (Ireland) Act 1860 — in such proceedings costs shall be in the discretion of the Court and shall not exceed €110 in any case unless the Court shall, for special reason, otherwise order; - applies to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court on civil summons pursuant to [section 82](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/sec0082.html#sec82) of the [Civil Bill Courts (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/index.html) as applied to the District Court by [section 17](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/sec0017.html#sec17) of the [Courts of Justice Act 1928](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/index.html) .'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs for proceedings under the Enforcement of Court Orders Acts separate from any actual and necessary outlay?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The above scale of costs (4) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings under the *Enforcement of Court Orders Acts 1926 to 2009*** | | | | --- | --- | | Amount due | | | | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 157.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 315.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 630.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 788.00 | | Exceeding €15,000 | 866.00 | The above scale of costs (4) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs higher when a case is defended compared to when it is not?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 236.00 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 945.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **6. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings for recovery of possession under section 16 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*** | Annual rent | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended | Costs of judgment for respondent (dismiss) | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 119.00 | 284.00 | 472.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 236.00 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 355.00 | 850.00 | 1,418.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 472.00 | 1,134.00 | 1,890.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 591.00 | 1,418.00 | 2,362.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (6) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs for claims over €1,400 set at 242 euros?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Exceeding €1,400 | 242.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **7. Solicitors’ costs, where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer** | Amount of compensation claimed | Costs | | --- | --- | | | € | | Exceeding €125 and not exceeding €250 | 16.00 | | Exceeding €250 and not exceeding €750 | 94.00 | | Exceeding €750 and not exceeding €1,400 | 147.00 | | Exceeding €1,400 | 242.00 | The above scale of costs (7) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are solicitors'' costs for settling cases without appearance lower than those after a hearing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Not exceeding €1,100 | 27.00 | 54.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **8. Solicitors costs in summary proceedings for the recovery of rates** | Amount sued for | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs after hearing | | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €1,100 | 27.00 | 54.00 | | Exceeding €1,100 and not exceeding €2,200 | 35.00 | 70.00 | | Exceeding €2,200 and not exceeding €3,300 | 58.00 | 116.00 | | Exceeding €3,300 and not exceeding €5,500 | 69.00 | 138.00 | | Exceeding €5,500 and not exceeding €11,000 | 92.00 | 184.00 | | Exceeding €11,000 | 115.00 | 230.00 or such other amount as the Court thinks proper | The above scale of costs (8) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are there miscellaneous additional charges listed in the table?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Request for Discovery, Review of Documentation and Preparation of Affidavit of Discovery | 500.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **9. Miscellaneous additional charges** | | | | --- | --- | | | | | | € | | Request for Discovery, Review of Documentation and Preparation of Affidavit of Discovery | 500.00 | | Request for Particulars and Replies to Particulars, where certified by the Court in accordance with [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), rule 13 | 250.00 | | Interim applications on notice (to include all Notices of Motion) | 525.00 | | Applications under section 63 of the *Civil Liability Act 1961* | 630.00 | | Rulings in respect of Injuries Board offers (e.g. minors) | 1,050.00 | | Each additional respondent (separately represented) | 525.00 |'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Can the successful party receive costs if the awarded amount exceeds €15,000?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the foregoing scales 1 to 9 in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **10. Solicitors’ costs in consent proceedings to which section of the Courts Act 1991 relates** Where proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 are brought before the District Court and: - the amount claimed in the proceedings exceeds €15,000, and, - pursuant to the proviso to section 77A of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 (inserted by section of the Courts Act 1991), the necessary parties to the proceedings sign the prescribed form of consent, and - (iii) the Court in determining the proceedings awards an amount in excess of €15,000, the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the foregoing scales 1 to 9 in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000. Where the proceedings are dismissed, the defendant may be allowed costs similarly calculated on the amount claimed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a specific provision for solicitors'' costs when an action is transferred to the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where an action, other than an action to which paragraph (2) relates, has been remitted or transferred to the District Court: ... the claimant may not recover any greater costs than the appropriate costs as set out in the above scales which he or she would have been entitled to recover if the action had originally been commenced in the District Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **11. Solicitors’ costs in actions transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court** (1) Where an action, other than an action to which paragraph (2) relates, has been remitted or transferred to the District Court: - (a) by the High Court pursuant to section 25 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924, or - by the Circuit Court pursuant to section 15(1) of the Courts Act 1991, and the Court, in determining the matter, makes an order in favour of the claimant, the claimant may not recover any greater costs than the appropriate costs as set out in the above scales which he or she would have been entitled to recover if the action had originally been commenced in the District Court. If the claimant fails to prove the claim, the respondent is entitled, in addition to any costs which may be allowed to him or her under the above scales, to a minimum sum of €100.00 or such greater sum as the Judge may in the circumstances consider proper. (2) Where an action so remitted or transferred is an action for unliquidated damages and the Court, pursuant to section 15(2) of the Courts Act 1991 (as amended by section 20 of the Courts and Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2013), makes an order awarding to a party to the action an amount in excess of €15,000 but not exceeding €30,000, the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the above scales in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000. Where such an action is dismissed, the respondent may be allowed costs similarly calculated on the amount claimed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a schedule for miscellaneous outlays?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Miscellaneous outlays to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries to be allowed in accordance with [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), rule 2."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **12. Schedule of outlays** Miscellaneous outlays to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries to be allowed in accordance with [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), rule 2. | | | | --- | --- | | Amount due at the date of issue of claim notice | **-** | | —(in the case of debt claims) | | | —(in the case of Instalment Orders) | | | Amount awarded | **-** | | —(in cases of contract, breach of contract and tort proceedings and in claims for damages unconnected with contract) | | | Annual rent | **-** | | —(in the case of landlord and tenant (ejectment) proceedings begun by claim notice) | | | —(in proceedings for the recovery of possession under section 16 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*) | | | Amount of compensation awarded | **-** | | —(in proceedings for compensation under section 15 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*) | | | Amount of compensation claimed | **-** | | —(in cases under the *Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986*) | | | Amount sued for | **-** | | —(in summary proceedings for the recovery of rates) | | | | | | Not exceeding €5,000 | €52.50 plus VAT | | Exceeding €5,000 and not exceeding €10,000 | €105.00 plus VAT | | Exceeding €10,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | €157.50 plus VAT |'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Are counsel''s fees awarded in cases of breach of contract?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **13. Counsel’s Fees** (1) in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract (2) in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent (3) where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a fee structure based on the amount claimed or recovered in cases involving contracts or torts?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"To the claimant''s counsel when the amount recovered, or to the respondent''s counsel when the amount claimed, in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract -"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Part 1: Brief fee in respect of preparation for and attending on the trial or hearing of the claim To the claimant’s counsel when the amount recovered, or to the respondent’s counsel when the amount claimed, in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract - To the claimant’s or respondent’s counsel when the annual rent in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent - When the amount of compensation claimed under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 – | | | | --- | --- | | | | | | € | | Exceeds €2,000 and does not exceed €3,000 | 525.00 | | Exceeds €3,000 and does not exceed €4,000 | 577.00 | | Exceeds €4,000 and does not exceed €5,000 | 630.00 | | Exceeds €5,000 and does not exceed €7,000 | 788.00 | | Exceeds €7,000 and does not exceed €9,000 | 840.00 | | Exceeds €9,000 and does not exceed €11,000 | 892.00 | | Exceeds €11,000 and does not exceed €13,000 | 998.00 | | Exceeds €13,000 and does not exceed €15,000 | 1,102.00 |'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the court mentioned in Order of the Defamation Act 2009 a superior court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Court: Superior"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Superior # **Order Defamation Act 2009 [1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the affidavit of verification required to be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is addressed?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8** 2. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form No 4 in Appendix CC](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-actions-civil-liability-and-courts-act-2004#_fri4), with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate from the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon such pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 8(5) by filing the same in the Central Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is an application for an order directing the party who made the offer to take certain measures made by motion when a defamation action has been brought and an offer to make amends is accepted?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: ... under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, ... shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted** 4. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include an order allowing either party to alter or amend his pleadings) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph(c) of section 23(1). 5. (1) Where no defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned,'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Can a defendant notify their intention to give evidence of an apology through their defense?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24** 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'Is the defendant required to provide details about their intended evidence for mitigation at least seven days before the trial?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation** 10. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 511 of 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/511/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Can proceedings related to enforcing a maintenance order be held in a different court area than the one specified in sub-rule (1)?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"proceedings to which this Order relates concerning an enforceable maintenance order to which the [2011 Regulations] or, as the case may be, the [2019 Regulations] apply may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Venue** 2.(1) Subject to sub-rule (2), proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made and, save where the context otherwise requires, any reference in this Order to the “**Clerk**” is a reference to the Clerk for that court area. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings to which this Order relates concerning an enforceable maintenance order to which the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print) or, as the case may be, the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print) apply may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for: - (a) where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State, the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned does not reside in the State but is employed by a person residing or having a place of business in the State or by a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, the court area in which the person resides or the body has its seat.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is a statutory declaration required for the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons and application form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Service of summonses, application forms and orders** 8.[4] (1) [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons and application form mentioned in rule 4. (2) [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 8(5), 8(7) and 8(8) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons mentioned in rule 7 and application form mentioned in rule 6. A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing. (3) An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) may be in the [Form 57.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3022a2b1-6ed7-4036-94c6-7ff708590ba3/Notice Of Application To Vary A Garnishee Order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such order must be sent by registered post by the Clerk to every person directed to pay monies to the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person who receives an order under rule 8(3) request the court to vary or set aside the order if they cannot comply?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"A person served with an order mentioned in rule 8(3) who is unable to comply with the order may apply to the Court by notice of application in the [Form 57.5]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Persons affected by garnishee order** 9.(1) A person served with an order mentioned in rule 8(3) who is unable to comply with the order may apply to the Court by notice of application in the [Form 57.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/537ff74b-79ab-44a4-9185-6c4ea61f9014/Notice of application to vary a garnishee order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule to set aside or vary the order. A copy of the notice shall be served on the defaulter and on the applicant not later than seven days before the hearing of the application and the original notice shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the hearing of the application. (2) Where the Court is considering making an order under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), the Court may adjourn the hearing of the summons and direct that the person who would be directed to pay monies to the Clerk under any such order be put on notice of the adjourned application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Is a written notice required when a person is imprisoned for contempt?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application to purge contempt** 12. Where a person is imprisoned for contempt of court in accordance with section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24): - (a) the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt; - the Court may direct that, if the contempt has not previously been purged, the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document specifying requirements for pleadings, documents, and notices in civil proceedings in the District Court?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court - Court: District # Order 39A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section primarily focused on defining terms?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a solicitor deliver court documents digitally if they are authorized?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership, acting through a person authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**Clerk**”, where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk; “**court document**” includes any claim notice, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the Clerk in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the Clerk, - by or on behalf of the Clerk to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership, acting through a person authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person, which is or who is for the time being authorised to deliver to the Clerk and to receive from the Clerk by digital means any court document or other document which may be lodged or filed in or with the Court in or in connection with any proceedings or category of proceedings in the Court, in respect of which digital delivery is for the time being authorised in accordance with section 20 of the [Civil Law and Criminal Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 202](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/act/13/enacted/en/html)0; “**network**” means an electronic information and communications network or system maintained and supported by the Courts Service for the purposes of use by court users in civil proceedings, for the time being in use in or for the purposes of the Court, to which digital users have access, and which is used or capable of use for digital delivery;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is personal delivery of a court document considered non-personal?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"\"personal delivery\" means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '“**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the Clerk: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the Clerk, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**personal delivery**” means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must all notices and notifications under these rules be given in writing?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Notices in writing_ 2.(1) All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally. (2) Nothing in this Order operates to require a document delivered in electronic form, including by digital delivery, to be printed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a document submitted digitally be in electronic form?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"information transmitted in the form of an electronic document or other electronic data to a network"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Form of documents_ 3.(1) Any document for use in Court which is required or permitted to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by delivery in person (of a hard copy) or by delivery by post (of a hard copy) must be clearly and legibly printed or written on A4 size paper. (2) Where a document is for the time being authorised in accordance with this Order to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by digital delivery or to be produced in digital form (in soft copy) for use in Court, such document may comprise or include: - (a) information transmitted in the form of an electronic document or other electronic data to a network (including, for the avoidance of doubt, a statement of truth), and - information made available to a digital user on a network to which the digital user concerned has secure access, which is capable of being presented or reproduced in legible form, and any such document need not be provided in printed form, notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Clerk certify a copy of a document that was filed through digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Copy certified by Clerk_ 6. The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents be delivered personally to the clerk''s office during business hours?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Personal delivery at office_ 7. Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section discussing how documents can be submitted electronically?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is payment of a court fee required before using a court document for non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where payment of a court fee is chargeable in respect of the lodgment of the court document, the court document shall not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Additional requirements for non-personal delivery in hard copy_ 9.(1) Where any court document is authorised to be lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such document, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with rule 8; - where payment of a court fee is chargeable in respect of the lodgment of the court document, the court document shall not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee; - the date of lodgment of the document is, unless the contrary is proven, deemed to be the date of lodgment recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk and such date may be endorsed on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk; - for the purpose of fixing the return date of any notice of application (or other originating document or notice of motion requiring a return date) lodged for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, a period of four days must, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - there must be delivered with any court document lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy so many copies of that document and such other documents as would be required on the personal delivery of that court document. (2) Where a court document, having been issued, has been returned to the party or person who lodged it for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, and that court document is not received by that party or person within a reasonable time after it is sent, - (a) the Clerk concerned may, at the request of that party or person, furnish to that person -'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party proceed on a copy of the court document if they have a certificate confirming its issuance?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- a copy of any duplicate or copy of the court document concerned retained by the Clerk, with a certificate endorsed thereon confirming the issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates; - a certificate as to any record made of the issue of the court document concerned, and - the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i) or, where the Court so permits, a copy of the court document lodged for issue, certified by the party who lodged it or his or her solicitor to be a true copy of the court document lodged, and a certificate given in accordance with paragraph (a)(ii).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is the section about physical document submission?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is submitting proof of residential address one of the requirements for a natural person to become a digital user?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"provision of proof of the person’s residential address"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for becoming digital user_ 13.(1) A natural person may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - such person has first submitted sufficient evidence of his or her identity which may, without limitation, include: - (a) production of the original or a certified copy of a relevant document (within the meaning of section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)); - provision of the personal public service number (within the meaning of section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) issued to the person; - provision of proof of the person’s residential address, and - such person has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery. (2) A firm of solicitors or legal partnership may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - the firm or partnership has first submitted sufficient evidence of its establishment and standing; - the firm or partnership has submitted sufficient evidence of the identity of each natural person authorised on behalf of the firm to transmit court documents through the network by digital delivery; - (iii) the firm or partnership has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Must a court document transmitted digitally include a statement about authority when submitted by someone other than the party themselves?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Documents transmitted by digital delivery_ 15.(1) Any court document transmitted by digital delivery by or on behalf of a party must: - (a) contain: - the name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the same or, as the case may be, - the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person; - include the name of the natural person transmitting the court document concerned; - where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted. (2) Any document other than a court document which is transmitted by or on behalf of a party by digital delivery as a copy in electronic form of an original document must have endorsed on or associated with such copy a certificate given by the party or by a named solicitor that the copy has been compared to, and is a true copy, of the original document. (3) Where any court document is authorised to be filed or lodged by digital delivery: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such information, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning digital delivery in accordance with rule 14; - where a court fee is chargeable in respect of the court document, the court document may not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can the date of filing or lodgment be considered valid if it''s recorded in a record kept by or on behalf of the Clerk?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk or on the network and such date may be endorsed electronically on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk and may be notified electronically through the network to the party concerned; - for the purpose of fixing a return date for any originating document or notice of motion which requires a return date, and which is lodged for issue by digital delivery, a period of four days will, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - any obligation or entitlement arising under these Rules to lodge or, as the case may be, to file a court document shall, unless the contrary is proved, be satisfied by the digital delivery of the document to the network and the issuance by the network of confirmation of lodgment or, as the case may be, filing; - the network or the Clerk will alert digital users, prior to submission, where the filing, lodgment or issue of any court document is subject to checking by a court officer. (4) Where the Clerk is satisfied that it is necessary to do so, he or she may: - (a) retransmit a court document, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned; - deliver a printed copy of the court document concerned by delivery in hard copy, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned, and in either such case, any party or person affected may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a court document or copy of a court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a) or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can an electronic signature satisfy the signing requirement for documents transmitted by digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Signature_ 16. Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of that Act and/or that Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a section about service of documents using digital delivery?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Service of documents using digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Service of documents using digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party apply to the Court if they believe someone has misused digital permissions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"the party aggrieved may apply to the Court by motion on notice, grounded on an affidavit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Reference to Court_ 18.(1) Where a party alleges that another person has improperly used permissions available to a digital user to prejudice that party in any proceedings, the party aggrieved may apply to the Court by motion on notice, grounded on an affidavit, and the Court may make such order or give such directions as are just in the circumstances. (2) Where a Clerk is concerned that a person has improperly used permissions available to a digital user to prejudice a party in any proceedings, the Clerk may refer the matter to the Court on notice to the parties concerned, and the Court may make such order or give such directions as are just in the circumstances. [1] Order 39A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Is the document discussing requirements for pleadings, documents, and notices in civil proceedings?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. - Court: Circuit # Order 11A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Is this section primarily focused on providing definitions?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":true,"justification":"Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'Is digital delivery of a court document included in the definition of non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'yes_no', '{"correct":false,"justification":"does not include digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**proper officer”** are references to the Combined Court Office manager for the time being responsible for the management of the Office of the Court for the relevant county, and where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the Circuit Court for the circuit and/or county concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Combined Court Office manager; “**court document**” includes any civil bill, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the proper officer in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the proper officer: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the proper officer, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the proper officer, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the proper officer, - by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership acting through a person or persons authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person,');
INSERT INTO user_flashcards (user_id, flashcard_id) SELECT u.id, f.id FROM users u CROSS JOIN flashcards f WHERE f.source_file = 'Court Rules' AND f.flashcard_type = 'yes_no' ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
